p100
aVCHAPTER I.
p101
aVTHE TWO WANDERERS.
p102
aVA man and a boy were ascending a steep street in a country town in\u000aEastern New York.
p103
aVThe man was tall and dark-complexioned, with a\u000asinister look which of itself excited distrust.
p104
aVHe wore a slouch hat,\u000awhich, coming down over his forehead, nearly concealed from view his\u000alow, receding brow.
p105
aVA pair of black, piercing eyes looked out from\u000abeneath the brim.
p106
aVThe first impression produced upon those who met him\u000awas that he was of gipsy blood, and the impression was a correct one.
p107
aVWhere he was born no one seemed to know; perhaps he did not himself\u000aknow, for all his life he had been a wanderer, but English was the\u000atongue that he spoke, and, apart from the gipsy dialect, he knew no\u000aother.
p108
aVHis companion was a boy of fourteen.
p109
aVBetween the two there was not\u000athe slightest resemblance.
p110
aVThough embrowned by exposure to the sun\u000aand the wind, it was easy to see that the boy was originally of light\u000acomplexion.
p111
aVHis hair was chestnut and his eyes blue.
p112
aVHis features were\u000aregular and strikingly handsome, though, owing to the vagrant life\u000ahe was compelled to lead, he was not able to pay that attention to\u000acleanliness which he might have done if he had had a settled home.
p113
aVIt was five o'clock in the afternoon, and the boy looked weary.
p114
aVHe\u000aseemed scarcely able to drag one foot after the other.
p115
aVHis companion\u000aturned upon him roughly.
p116
aV"What are you dawdling that way for, Tony?"
p117
aVhe demanded.
p118
aV"You creep\u000alike a boy of three."
p119
aV"I can't help it, Rudolph," said the boy, wearily; "I'm tired."
p120
aV"What business have you to be tired?"
p121
aV"I've walked far to-day."
p122
aV"You've walked no farther than I. I don't dawdle like you."
p123
aV"You're a man.
p124
aVYou're stronger than I am, Rudolph."
p125
aV"And you're a milksop," said the man contemptuously.
p126
aV"I'm nothing of the sort," said the boy, with a flash of spirit.
p127
aV"I'm\u000anot made of cast-iron, and that's why I can't stand walking all day\u000along.
p128
aVBesides, I have had no dinner."
p129
aV"That isn't my fault, is it?"
p130
aV"I didn't say it was, but it makes me weak for all that."
p131
aV"Well," said Rudolph, "perhaps you're right.
p132
aVI feel like eating\u000asomething myself.
p133
aVWe'll go to some house and ask for supper."
p134
aVTony looked dissatisfied.
p135
aV"I wish we were not obliged to beg our meals," he said; "I don't like\u000ait."
p136
aV"Oh, you're getting proud, are you?"
p137
aVsneered Rudolph.
p138
aV"If you've got\u000amoney to pay for your supper, we won't beg, as you call it."
p139
aV"Why can't we do as other people do?"
p140
aVasked Tony.
p141
aV"What's that?"
p142
aV"Live somewhere, and not go tramping round the country all the time.
p143
aVIt\u000awould be a good deal pleasanter."
p144
aV"Not for me.
p145
aVI'm a vagrant by nature.
p146
aVI can't be cooped up in one\u000aplace.
p147
aVI should die of stagnation.
p148
aVI come of a roving stock.
p149
aVMy mother\u000aand father before me were rovers, and I follow in their steps."
p150
aVThe man spoke with animation, his eye flashing as he gazed about him,\u000aand unconsciously quickened his pace.
p151
aV"Then, I'm not like you," said Tony, decidedly.
p152
aV"I don't want to be a\u000atramp.
p153
aVWere my father and mother rovers like yours?"
p154
aV"Of course they were," answered Rudolph, but not without hesitation.
p155
aV"Ain't I your uncle?"
p156
aV"I don't know.
p157
aVAre you?"
p158
aVreturned Tony, searchingly.
p159
aV"Haven't I told you so a hundred times?"
p160
aVdemanded Rudolph, impatiently.
p161
aV"Yes," said the boy, slowly, "but there's no likeness between us.
p162
aVYou're dark and I am light."
p163
aV"That proves nothing," said the elder tramp, hastily.
p164
aV"Brothers are\u000aoften as unlike.
p165
aVPerhaps you don't want to look upon me as a relation?"
p166
aVThe boy was silent.
p167
aV"Are you getting ashamed of me?"
p168
aVdemanded Rudolph, in a harsh tone.
p169
aV"I am ashamed of myself," said Tony, bitterly.
p170
aV"I'm nothing but\u000aa tramp, begging my bread from door to door, sleeping in barns,\u000aouthouses, in the fields, anywhere I can.
p171
aVI'm as ignorant as a boy of\u000aeight.
p172
aVI can just read and that's all."
p173
aV"You know as much I do."
p174
aV"That don't satisfy me.
p175
aVWhen I grow up I don't want to be----"\u000a\u000aTony hesitated.
p176
aV"You don't want to be like me.
p177
aVIs that it?"
p178
aVasked Rudolph, angrily.
p179
aV"No, I don't want to be like you," answered Tony, boldly.
p180
aV"I want to\u000ahave a home, and a business, and to live like other people."
p181
aV"Humph!"
p182
aVmuttered Rudolph, fixing his eyes thoughtfully upon his young\u000acompanion.
p183
aV"This is something new.
p184
aVYou never talked like that before."
p185
aV"But I've felt like that plenty of times.
p186
aVI'm tired of being a tramp."
p187
aV"Then you're a fool.
p188
aVThere's no life so free and independent.
p189
aVYou can\u000ago where you please, with no one to order you here nor there, the scene\u000achanging always, instead of being obliged to look always upon the same\u000apeople and the same fields."
p190
aV"What's the good of it all?
p191
aVI'm tired of it.
p192
aVI've got no home, and\u000anever had any."
p193
aV"You've got no spirit.
p194
aVYou're only fit for a farm-boy or an apprentice."
p195
aV"I wish I was either one."
p196
aV"Sit down here if you are tired," said the man, abruptly, throwing\u000ahimself down under a wide-spreading tree by the roadside.
p197
aVTony stretched himself out at a little distance, and uttered a sign of\u000arelief as he found himself permitted to rest.
p198
aV"Have you been thinking of this long?"
p199
aVasked Rudolph.
p200
aV"Of what?"
p201
aV"Of not liking to be a tramp?"
p202
aV"Yes."
p203
aV"You have not spoken of it before."
p204
aV"I've been thinking of it more lately."
p205
aV"How did that come?"
p206
aV"I'll tell you," said Tony.
p207
aV"Don't you remember last week when we\u000apassed by a school house?
p208
aVIt was recess, and the boys were out at play.
p209
aVWhile you were away a few minutes, one of the boys sat down by me and\u000atalked.
p210
aVHe told me what he was studying, and what he was going to do\u000awhen he got older, and then he asked me about myself."
p211
aV"What did you tell him?"
p212
aV"What did I tell him?"
p213
aVsaid Tony, bitterly.
p214
aV"I told him that I was a\u000atramp, and that when I got older I should be a tramp still."
p215
aV"Well," said Rudolph, sharply, "what then?"
p216
aV"The boy told me I ought to get some regular work to do, and grow into\u000aa respectable member of society.
p217
aVHe said that his father would help me,\u000ahe thought; and----"\u000a\u000a"So you want to leave me, do you?"
p218
aVdemanded Rudolph, fiercely.
p219
aV"Is that\u000awhat you're coming to, my chicken?"
p220
aV"It isn't that so much as the life you make me lead.
p221
aVI want to leave\u000athat, Rudolph."
p222
aV"Well, you can't do it," said the man, shortly.
p223
aV"Why not?"
p224
aV"I say so, and that's enough."
p225
aVTony was silent for a moment.
p226
aVHe was not greatly disappointed, for he\u000aexpected a refusal.
p227
aVHe changed the subject.
p228
aV"Rudolph," he said, "there's something else I want to ask you about."
p229
aV"Well?"
p230
aV"Who am I?"
p231
aV"Who are you?
p232
aVA young fool," muttered the tramp, but he appeared a\u000alittle uneasy at the question.
p233
aV"I want to know something about my father and mother."
p234
aV"Your mother was my sister.
p235
aVShe died soon after you were born."
p236
aV"And my father?"
p237
aV"He was put in jail for theft, and was shot in trying to make his\u000aescape.
p238
aVDoes that satisfy you?"
p239
aV"No, it doesn't, and what's more, I don't believe it," said Tony,\u000aboldly.
p240
aV"Look here," said Rudolph, sternly.
p241
aV"I've had enough of your insolence.
p242
aVDo you see this strap?"
p243
aVHe produced a long leather strap, which he drew through his fingers\u000amenacingly.
p244
aV"Yes, I see it."
p245
aV"You'll feel it if you ain't careful.
p246
aVNow get up.
p247
aVIt's time to be\u000amoving."
p248
aVCHAPTER II.
p249
aVTHE FARM-HOUSE.
p250
aV"Where are we going to stop to-night?"
p251
aVasked Tony ten minutes later.
p252
aV"There," answered Rudolph, pointing out a farm-house, a little to the\u000aleft.
p253
aV"Suppose they won't let us."
p254
aV"They will admit us into their barn, at least, if we play our cards\u000aright.
p255
aVListen to what I say.
p256
aVYou are to be my son."
p257
aV"But I am not your son."
p258
aV"Be silent!"
p259
aVsaid the other tramp, "and don't you dare to contradict\u000ame.
p260
aVYou have been sick, and are too weak to go farther."
p261
aV"That is a lie, Rudolph."
p262
aV"That doesn't matter.
p263
aVIf they believe it, they won't turn us away.
p264
aVPerhaps they will let you sleep in the house."
p265
aV"Away from you?"
p266
aV"Yes."
p267
aVTony was puzzled.
p268
aVIt seemed as if Rudolph wanted him to be more\u000acomfortably provided for than himself, but the boy knew him too well\u000anot to suspect that there was some concealed motive for this apparent\u000akindness.
p269
aV"Well, what are you thinking about?"
p270
aVdemanded Rudolph, suspiciously, as\u000ahe observed the boy's earnest gaze.
p271
aV"Why do you want me to sleep in the house?"
p272
aVhe asked.
p273
aV"I will tell you.
p274
aVWhen all the family are asleep, I want you to steal\u000adown stairs, open the back door, and let me in."
p275
aV"What for?"
p276
aVasked the boy, startled.
p277
aV"Never you mind.
p278
aVDo as I tell you!"
p279
aV"But I don't want to do it.
p280
aVYou never asked me to do that before."
p281
aV"Didn't I?
p282
aVWell, I had no occasion.
p283
aVI ask you now."
p284
aV"What are you going to do?
p285
aVAre you going to harm any one?"
p286
aV"No.
p287
aVI'll tell you what I'm going to do, but mind you, if you breathe a\u000aword to any being, I'll cut your tongue out."
p288
aVTony looked troubled, but not frightened.
p289
aV"Go on," he said.
p290
aVRudolph continued in a rapid tone.
p291
aV"I want money to carry out a plan of importance.
p292
aVThis farm belongs to a\u000afarmer who is rich, and who keeps a part of his money in the house."
p293
aV"How do you know that?"
p294
aV"A friend of mine stopped there last week, and found out.
p295
aVHe put me on\u000athe scent.
p296
aVThe old man keeps from two to three hundred dollars in his\u000adesk.
p297
aVI must have that money."
p298
aV"I don't want to help you in this, Rudolph," said Tony.
p299
aV"I won't betray\u000ayou, but you mustn't compel me to be a thief."
p300
aV"I can't get along without you, and help me you must."
p301
aV"Suppose we fail?"
p302
aV"Then we must take to our legs.
p303
aVIf we're caught we're both in the same\u000abox.
p304
aVI don't ask you to take any risk that I don't run myself."
p305
aVTony was about to remonstrate further, but it was too late.
p306
aVThey had\u000aalready reached the farm house, and caught sight of the owner standing\u000aunder a tree in the front yard.
p307
aV"Remember!"
p308
aVhissed the older tramp.
p309
aV"Follow my lead, or I'll beat you\u000atill you are half dead.
p310
aVGood evening, sir."
p311
aVThis last was said in a humble tone to the farmer, who advanced to the\u000agate.
p312
aV"Good evening," said the farmer, ingeniously.
p313
aVHe was a man of sixty, roughly dressed to suit his work, with grizzled\u000ahair, a form somewhat bowed, and a face seamed with wrinkles.
p314
aVHe had\u000abeen a hard worker, and showed abundant traces of it in his appearance.
p315
aV"We are very tired and hungry, my boy and I," whined Rudolph.
p316
aV"We've\u000atraveled many miles since morning.
p317
aVWould you kindly give us some supper\u000aand a night's lodging?"
p318
aV"My wife'll give you something to eat," said the old man.
p319
aV"Thank\u000aHeaven!
p320
aVwe've got enough for ourselves and a bit for the poor besides.
p321
aVBut I don't know about lodging.
p322
aVI don't like to take in strangers that\u000aI know nothing about."
p323
aV"I don't blame you, sir," said Rudolph, in a tone of affected humility.
p324
aV"There's many rogues going round the country, I've heard, but I'm a\u000apoor, hardworking man."
p325
aV"Then why are you not at work?"
p326
aV"Times are hard, and I can get nothing to do.
p327
aVI am in search of work.
p328
aVI\u000acan do almost anything.
p329
aVI'm a carpenter by trade."
p330
aVRudolph knew no more of the carpenter's trade than the man in the moon,\u000abut that would do as well as any other.
p331
aV"Where are you from?"
p332
aV"From Buffalo," he answered, with slight hesitation.
p333
aV"Is business dull there?"
p334
aV"Nothing doing."
p335
aV"Well, my friend, you haven't come to the right place.
p336
aVThere's nothing\u000abut farming done here."
p337
aV"I don't know anything about that," said Rudolph, hastily, for he had\u000ano disposition to be set to work in the fields.
p338
aV"I don't need any extra hands," said the farmer.
p339
aV"I am glad of that," thought the tramp.
p340
aV"Go round to the back door, and I will speak to my wife about supper,"\u000asaid the old man.
p341
aV"Come, Tony," said Rudolph, motioning to take the boy's hand, but Tony\u000adid not see fit to notice the movement, and walked in silence by his\u000aside.
p342
aVA motherly-looking old woman made her appearance at the back door.
p343
aV"Come in," she said.
p344
aV"Come right in, and sit down to the table.
p345
aVAbner,\u000amake room for the poor man and his son."
p346
aVAbner was a stalwart youth of eighteen, hard-handed and muscular.
p347
aVHe\u000awas the only permanent "hired man" employed on the farm.
p348
aVIn haying\u000atime there were others transiently employed.
p349
aVA farmer's table is plentiful, though homely.
p350
aVThe two tramps made an\u000aabundant meal, both doing justice to the homely fare.
p351
aVThe farmer's wife\u000alooked on with hospitable satisfaction.
p352
aVShe could not bear to have\u000aanybody hungry under her roof.
p353
aV"You'll excuse our appetite, ma'am," said Rudolph, "but we've had\u000anothing to eat since breakfast."
p354
aV"Eat as much as you like," said she.
p355
aV"We never stint anybody here.
p356
aVIs\u000athat your son?"
p357
aV"Yes, ma'am."
p358
aVTony bent his eyes upon his plate, and frowned slightly.
p359
aVHe wanted to\u000adeny it, but did not dare.
p360
aV"He don't look a bit like you," said the woman.
p361
aV"He's light, and you're\u000avery dark."
p362
aV"His mother was light," said Rudolph.
p363
aV"He takes after her."
p364
aV"How old is he?"
p365
aV"Tony, tell the lady how old you are."
p366
aV"Fourteen."
p367
aV"He is well grown of his age."
p368
aV"Yes; he will make a good-sized man.
p369
aVHe's been sick."
p370
aV"Has he?
p371
aVWhat has been the matter?"
p372
aV"I don't know.
p373
aVPoor folks like us can't call in a doctor."
p374
aV"He don't look sick," said the farmer's wife, thoughtfully.
p375
aV"He's delicate, though he don't look it.
p376
aVIt's sleeping out in the open\u000aair, I expect."
p377
aV"Do you have to sleep out in the open air?"
p378
aV"Yes; we can't afford to pay for lodgings, and people won't take us\u000ainto their houses.
p379
aVI don't mind myself--I'm tough--but Tony can't stand\u000ait as well as I can."
p380
aVWhile this conversation was going on, Tony fixed his eyes upon his\u000aplate.
p381
aVHe was annoyed to have such falsehoods told about him; but if he\u000ashould utter a word of objection he knew there would be an explosion of\u000awrath on the part of his guardian, and he remained silent.
p382
aVThe farmer's wife was a simple-minded, kind-hearted woman, and though\u000aTony did not look at all delicate, she never thought of questioning\u000athe statement of Rudolph.
p383
aVIndeed she was already revolving in her mind\u000ainviting the boy to sleep in the house.
p384
aVShe was rather prejudiced in\u000afavor of Rudolph by his show of parental solicitude.
p385
aVWhen supper was over, having in the meantime consulted her husband, she\u000asaid to Rudolph:\u000a\u000a"My husband says you may sleep in the barn, if you don't smoke.
p386
aVWe can\u000afind a bed for your son with Abner.
p387
aVYou won't mind taking him into your\u000aroom?"
p388
aV"He can come," said Abner, good-naturedly.
p389
aVSo it was arranged.
p390
aVAt half-past eight, for they retired at that early\u000ahour in the farm house, Rudolph left the fireside, and sought the barn.
p391
aVAs he left the room he looked suspiciously at Tony, and shook his head\u000awarningly.
p392
aVCHAPTER III.
p393
aVRUDOLPH'S DISAPPOINTMENT.
p394
aVAbner slept in a large room in the attic.
p395
aVIt had been roughly\u000apartitioned off, and was not even plastered.
p396
aVThe beams were plainly\u000avisible.
p397
aVUpon nails which had been driven into them hung Abner's\u000alimited wardrobe.
p398
aVThere were two cot-beds in the room, as a part of the\u000ayear the farmer employed more than one hired man.
p399
aV"You can sleep there, youngster," said Abner, pointing to one of the\u000abeds.
p400
aV"This is my bed."
p401
aV"Thank you," said Tony, politely.
p402
aV"I s'pose you've traveled round considerable," said Abner, with\u000acuriosity.
p403
aV"Yes, a good deal."
p404
aV"Do you like it?"
p405
aV"No; I'm tired of it."
p406
aV"How do you make your livin'?"
p407
aV"As we can.
p408
aVWe often go hungry."
p409
aV"Why don't your father settle down somewhere?"
p410
aVTony thought of disclaiming the relationship implied, but he reflected\u000athat Rudolph would be angry, and merely answered:\u000a\u000a"He prefers to travel round."
p411
aV"Was you ever in New York?"
p412
aVasked Abner.
p413
aV"Do you mean the city of New York?
p414
aVYes."
p415
aV"I'd like to see it," said Abner, regarding Tony with new respect.
p416
aV"I've heard a sight about it.
p417
aVIt's powerful big, isn't it?"
p418
aV"It's very large."
p419
aV"There's as many as a thousand houses, isn't there?"
p420
aV"There's a hundred thousand, I should think," answered Tony.
p421
aV"Sho?
p422
aVyou don't say so!"
p423
aVexclaimed Abner, awestruck.
p424
aV"I'd like to go\u000athere."
p425
aV"Didn't you ever visit the city?"
p426
aV"No; I never traveled any.
p427
aVI never was more'n fifteen miles from home.
p428
aVDad wouldn't let me.
p429
aVWhen I'm a man, I'm bound to see the world."
p430
aV"Ain't you a man now?"
p431
aVinquired Tony, surveying his Herculean\u000aproportions with astonishment.
p432
aV"No; I'm only eighteen."
p433
aV"You're as big as a man."
p434
aV"Yes, I'm pooty big," said Abner, with a complacent grin.
p435
aV"I can do a\u000aman's work."
p436
aV"I should think you might.
p437
aVI thought you were more than four years\u000aolder than me.
p438
aVI'm fourteen."
p439
aV"I guess I weigh twice as much as you."
p440
aV"I'm not small of my age," said Tony, jealously.
p441
aV"Maybe not.
p442
aVI'm a regular bouncer.
p443
aVThat's what dad says.
p444
aVWhy, I'm half\u000aas big again as he is."
p445
aV"Does he ever lick you?"
p446
aVasked Tony, smiling.
p447
aV"I'd like to see him try it," said Abner, bursting into a roar of\u000alaughter.
p448
aV"He'd have to get upon a milkin' stool.
p449
aVDoes your dad lick\u000ayou?"
p450
aV"No," answered Tony, shortly.
p451
aV"He looks as if he might sometimes.
p452
aVHe's kinder fractious-looking."
p453
aVTony did not care to say much on the subject of Rudolph.
p454
aVHe felt that\u000ait was his policy to be silent.
p455
aVIf he said anything he might say too\u000amuch, and if it got to Rudolph's ears, the man's vindictive temper\u000awould make it dangerous for him.
p456
aV"We get along pretty well," he said, guardedly.
p457
aV"Do you get up early?"
p458
aV"Four o'clock.
p459
aVYou won't have to, though."
p460
aV"What time do you get breakfast?"
p461
aV"Half-past five, after I've milked and done the chores.
p462
aVYou must be up\u000aby that time, or you won't get anything to eat."
p463
aV"That's pretty early," thought Tony.
p464
aV"I don't see the use of getting up\u000aso early."
p465
aV"I guess I'll go to sleep," said Abner.
p466
aV"I'm tuckered out."
p467
aV"Good-night, then," said Tony.
p468
aV"Good-night."
p469
aVThe young giant turned over, closed his eyes, and in five minutes was\u000aasleep.
p470
aVTony did not compose himself to sleep so readily, partly because Abner\u000abegan to snore in a boisterous manner, partly because he felt disturbed\u000aby the thought of the treachery which Rudolph required at his hands.
p471
aVTony was only a tramp, but he had an instinct of honor in him.
p472
aVIn the\u000afarm house he had been kindly treated and hospitably entertained.
p473
aVHe\u000afelt that it would be very mean to steal down in the dead of night\u000aand open the door to his companion in order that he might rob the\u000aunsuspecting farmer of his money.
p474
aVOn the other hand, if he did not do\u000athis, he knew that he would be severely beaten by Rudolph.
p475
aV"Why am I tied to this man?"
p476
aVhe thought.
p477
aV"What chance is there of my\u000aever being anything but a tramp while I stay with him?"
p478
aVHe had thought this before now, but the circumstances in which he now\u000afound himself placed made the feeling stronger.
p479
aVHe had been often\u000ahumiliated by being forced to beg from door to door, by the thought\u000athat he was a vagrant, and the companion of a vagrant, but he had not\u000abeen urged to actual crime until now.
p480
aVHe knew enough to be aware that\u000ahe ran the risk of arrest and imprisonment if he obeyed Rudolph.
p481
aVOn the\u000aother hand, if he refused, he was sure of a beating.
p482
aVWhat should he do?
p483
aVIt was certainly a difficult question to decide, and Tony debated it in\u000ahis own mind for some time.
p484
aVFinally he came to a determination.
p485
aVRudolph\u000amight beat him, but he would not be guilty of this treachery.
p486
aVHe felt better after he had come to this resolve, and the burden being\u000anow off his mind, he composed himself to sleep.
p487
aVHe did not know how long he slept, but he had a troubled dream.
p488
aVHe\u000athought that in compliance with his companion's order he rose and\u000aopened the door to him.
p489
aVWhile Rudolph was opening the farmer's desk,\u000ahe thought that heavy steps were heard, and Abner and the farmer\u000aentered the room, provided with a lantern.
p490
aVHe thought that Rudolph and\u000ahimself were overpowered and bound.
p491
aVJust as he reached this part he\u000aawaked, and was reassured by hearing Abner's heavy breathing.
p492
aV"I'm glad it's a dream," he thought, breathing a sigh of relief.
p493
aVAt this instant his attention was called by a noise upon the panes of\u000athe only window in the room.
p494
aVHe listened, and detected the cause.
p495
aVSome one was throwing gravel stones against it.
p496
aV"It's Rudolph!"
p497
aVhe thought instantly.
p498
aV"He's trying to call my\u000aattention."
p499
aVHe thought of pretending to be asleep, and taking no notice of the\u000asignal.
p500
aVBut he feared Abner would awake, and ascertain the meaning of\u000ait.
p501
aVHe decided to go to the window, show himself, and stop the noise if\u000ahe could.
p502
aVHe rose from his bed, and presented himself at the window.
p503
aVLooking\u000adown, he saw the dark figure of Rudolph leaning against the well-curb,\u000awith his eyes fixed on the window.
p504
aV"Oh, you're there at last," growled Rudolph.
p505
aV"I thought I'd never wake\u000ayou up.
p506
aVIs the man asleep?"
p507
aV"Yes," said Tony.
p508
aV"Then come down and let me in."
p509
aV"I would rather not," said Tony, uneasily.
p510
aV"What's the fool afraid of?"
p511
aVanswered Rudolph, in a low, menacing tone.
p512
aV"The man might wake up."
p513
aV"No danger.
p514
aVSuch animals always sleep heavily.
p515
aVThere's no danger, I\u000atell you."
p516
aV"I don't want to do it," said Tony.
p517
aV"It would be mean.
p518
aVThey've treated\u000ame well, and I don't want to help rob them."
p519
aV"Curse the young idiot!"
p520
aVexclaimed Rudolph, in low tones of\u000aconcentrated passion.
p521
aV"Do you mean to disobey me?"
p522
aV"I can't do as you wish, Rudolph.
p523
aVAsk me anything else."
p524
aV"I wish I could get at him!"
p525
aVmuttered Rudolph, between his teeth.
p526
aV"He\u000anever dared to disobey me before.
p527
aVOnce more!
p528
aVWill you open the door to\u000ame?"
p529
aVdemanded Rudolph.
p530
aVTony bethought himself of an expedient.
p531
aVHe might pretend that Abner was\u000awaking up.
p532
aV"Hush!"
p533
aVhe said, in feigned alarm.
p534
aV"The man is waking up.
p535
aVGet out of\u000asight quick."
p536
aVHe disappeared from the window, and Rudolph, supposing there was really\u000adanger of detection, hurriedly stole away to the barn where he had been\u000apermitted to lodge.
p537
aVHe came out half an hour later, and again made the old signal, but this\u000atime Tony did not show himself.
p538
aVHe had made up his mind not to comply\u000awith the elder tramp's demands, and it would do no good to argue the\u000apoint.
p539
aV"I wish I knew whether he was asleep, or only pretending, the young\u000arascal," muttered Rudolph.
p540
aV"I must manage to have him stay here another\u000anight.
p541
aVThat money must and shall be mine, and he shall help to get it\u000afor me."
p542
aVCHAPTER IV.
p543
aVSETTING A TRAP.
p544
aVAt half-past five Tony got up.
p545
aVHe would have liked to remain in bed\u000atwo hours longer, but there was no chance for late resting at the farm\u000ahouse.
p546
aVRudolph, too, was awakened by Abner, and the two tramps took\u000atheir seats at the breakfast table with the rest of the family.
p547
aVRudolph furtively scowled at Tony.
p548
aVTo him he attributed the failure of\u000ahis plans the night before, and he was furious against him--the more so\u000athat he did not dare to say anything in presence of the farmer's family.
p549
aV"Where are you going to-day?"
p550
aVasked the farmer, addressing Rudolph.
p551
aV"I am going to walk to Crampton.
p552
aVI may get employment there."
p553
aV"It is twelve miles away.
p554
aVThat's a good walk."
p555
aV"I don't mind it for myself.
p556
aVI mind it for my son," said Rudolph,\u000ahypocritically.
p557
aV"He can stay here till you come back," said the farmer, hospitably.
p558
aV"If you're willing to have him, I will leave him for one more night,"\u000asaid Rudolph.
p559
aV"It'll do him good to rest."
p560
aV"He can stay as well as not," said the farmer.
p561
aV"When are you coming\u000aback?"
p562
aV"Perhaps to-night, but I think not till to-morrow."
p563
aV"Don't trouble yourself about your son.
p564
aVHe will be safe here."
p565
aV"You are very kind," said the elder tramp.
p566
aV"Tony, thank these good\u000apeople for their kindness to you."
p567
aV"I do thank them," said Tony, glancing uneasily at the other.
p568
aVWhen breakfast was over, Rudolph took his hat, and said:\u000a\u000a"I'll get started early.
p569
aVI've a long walk before me."
p570
aVTony sat still, hoping that he would not be called upon to join him.
p571
aVBut he was destined to be disappointed.
p572
aV"Come and walk a piece with me, Tony," said Rudolph.
p573
aVReluctantly Tony got his hat, and set out with him.
p574
aVAs long as they were in sight and hearing, Rudolph spoke to him gently,\u000abut when they were far enough for him to throw off the mask safely, he\u000aturned furiously upon the boy.
p575
aV"Now, you young rascal," he said, roughly, "tell me why you didn't obey\u000ame last night."
p576
aV"It wasn't safe," said Tony.
p577
aV"We should both have been caught."
p578
aV"Why should we?
p579
aVWasn't the man asleep?"
p580
aV"He stirred in his sleep.
p581
aVIf I had moved about much, or opened the\u000adoor, it would have waked him up."
p582
aV"You are a coward," sneered Rudolph.
p583
aV"When I was of your age, I\u000awouldn't have given up a job so easily.
p584
aVSuch men sleep sound.
p585
aVNo matter\u000aif they do move about, they won't wake up.
p586
aVIf you had had a little more\u000acourage, we should have succeeded last night in capturing the money."
p587
aV"I wish you'd give it up, Rudolph," said Tony, earnestly.
p588
aV"You don't know what you're talking about," said the tramp, harshly.
p589
aV"You're a milksop.
p590
aVThe world owes us a living, and we must call for it."
p591
aV"I'd rather work than steal."
p592
aV"There's no work to be had, and we must have money.
p593
aVMore depends on it\u000athan you think.
p594
aVBut we've got one more night to work in."
p595
aV"What do you mean to do?"
p596
aVasked Tony, uneasily.
p597
aV"Thanks to my management, you will sleep in the same room to-night.
p598
aVLook round the house during the day; see if the key's in the desk.
p599
aVIf\u000ayou can get hold of the money, all the better.
p600
aVIn that case, come and\u000ahide it in that hollow tree, and we can secure it after the hue and cry\u000ais over.
p601
aVDo you hear?"
p602
aV"Yes."
p603
aV"But, if there is no chance of that, look out for me at midnight.
p604
aVI\u000awill throw gravel against your window as a signal.
p605
aVWhen you hear it,\u000asteal down stairs, with your shoes in your hands, and open the door to\u000ame.
p606
aVI will attend to the rest.
p607
aVAnd mind," he added, sternly, "I shall\u000atake no excuses."
p608
aV"Suppose I am caught going down stairs?"
p609
aV"Say you are taken sick.
p610
aVIt will be easy enough to make an excuse."
p611
aV"Are you going to Crampton?"
p612
aVasked Tony.
p613
aV"Of course not.
p614
aVDo you think I am such a fool as to take a long walk\u000alike that?"
p615
aV"You said you were going."
p616
aV"Only to put them off the scent.
p617
aVI shall hide in yonder wood till\u000anight.
p618
aVThen I will find my way back to the farmhouse."
p619
aV"Do you want me to go any farther with you?"
p620
aV"No; you can go back now if you want to.
p621
aVDon't forget my directions."
p622
aV"I will remember them," said Tony, quietly.
p623
aVThe two parted company, and Tony walked slowly back to the farm.
p624
aVHe was\u000atroubled and perplexed.
p625
aVHe was in a dilemma, and how to get out of it\u000ahe did not know.
p626
aVIt was not the first time that he thought over his relations to Rudolph.
p627
aVAs far back as he could remember he had been under the care of this\u000aman.
p628
aVSometimes the latter had been away for months, leaving him in\u000athe charge of a woman whose appearance indicated that she also was\u000aof Gipsy descent.
p629
aVHe had experienced hunger, cold, neglect, but had\u000alived through them all, tolerably contented.
p630
aVNow, however, he saw that\u000aRudolph intended to make a criminal of him, and he was disposed to\u000arebel.
p631
aVThat his guardian was himself a thief, he had reason to know.
p632
aVHe\u000asuspected that some of his periodical absences were spent in prison\u000awalls.
p633
aVWould he be content to follow his example?
p634
aVTony answered unhesitatingly, "No."
p635
aVWhatever the consequences might be,\u000ahe would make a stand there.
p636
aVHe had reason to fear violence, but that\u000awas better than arrest and imprisonment.
p637
aVIf matters came to the worst,\u000ahe would run away.
p638
aVWhen he had come to a decision he felt better.
p639
aVHe returned to the farm\u000aand found Abner just leaving the yard with a hoe in his hand.
p640
aV"Where are you going?"
p641
aVhe asked.
p642
aV"To the corn field."
p643
aV"May I go with you?"
p644
aV"If you want to."
p645
aVSo Tony went out to the field with the stalwart "hired man," and kept\u000ahim company through the forenoon.
p646
aV"That's easy work," said Tony, after a while.
p647
aV"Do you think you can do it?"
p648
aV"Let me try."
p649
aVTony succeeded tolerably well, but he could not get over the ground so\u000afast as Abner.
p650
aV"Why don't you hire out on a farm?"
p651
aVasked Abner, as he took back the\u000ahoe.
p652
aV"I would if I could," answered Tony.
p653
aV"Why can't you?
p654
aVWon't your father let you?"
p655
aV"He wants me to go round with him," answered Tony.
p656
aV"Wouldn't he take me instead of you?"
p657
aVasked Abner, grinning.
p658
aV"I'd like\u000ato travel round and see the world.
p659
aVYou could stay here and do farm\u000awork."
p660
aV"If he and the farmer agree to the change, I will," answered Tony, with\u000aa smile.
p661
aVAt noon they went back to the farm house to dinner.
p662
aVTony stared with\u000aastonishment at the quantity of food Abner made away with.
p663
aVHe concluded\u000athat farm work was favorable to the appetite.
p664
aVThe afternoon passed rapidly away, and night came.
p665
aVAgain Tony went up\u000ainto the attic to share Abner's room.
p666
aVHe got nervous as the night wore\u000aon.
p667
aVHe knew what was expected of him, and he shrank from Rudolph's\u000aanger.
p668
aVHe tried to go to sleep, but could not.
p669
aVAt last the expected signal came.
p670
aVThere was a rattling of gravel stones\u000aupon the window.
p671
aV"Shall I lie here and take no notice?"
p672
aVthought Tony.
p673
aVIn this case Rudolph would continue to fling gravel stones, and\u000aAbner might wake up.
p674
aVHe decided to go to the window and announce his\u000adetermination.
p675
aVWhen Rudolph saw him appear at the window, he called out:\u000a\u000a"Come down quick, and open the door."
p676
aV"I would rather not," answered Tony.
p677
aV"You must!"
p678
aVexclaimed Rudolph, with a terrible oath.
p679
aV"If you dare to\u000arefuse, I'll flay you alive."
p680
aV"I can't do it," said Tony, pale but resolute.
p681
aV"You have no right to\u000aask it of me."
p682
aVJust then Tony was startled by a voice from the bed:\u000a\u000a"Is that your father?
p683
aVWhat does he want?"
p684
aV"I would rather not tell," said Tony.
p685
aV"You must!"
p686
aVsaid Abner, sternly.
p687
aV"He wants me to open the door and let him into the house," Tony\u000aconfessed, reluctantly.
p688
aV"What for?"
p689
aV"He wants to get your master's money."
p690
aV"Ho, ho!"
p691
aVsaid Abner.
p692
aV"Well, we'll go down and let him in."
p693
aV"What!"
p694
aVexclaimed Tony, in surprise.
p695
aV"Call from the window that you will be down directly."
p696
aV"I don't want to get him into trouble."
p697
aV"You must, or I shall think you are a thief, too."
p698
aVThus constrained, Tony called out that he would come down at once.
p699
aV"I thought you'd think better of it," muttered Rudolph.
p700
aV"Hurry down,\u000aand waste no time."
p701
aVFive minutes later, Abner and Tony crept down stairs, the former armed\u000awith a tough oak stick.
p702
aVCHAPTER V.\u000a\u000aAN ATTEMPT AT BURGLARY.
p703
aVUnsuspicious of danger, Rudolph took a position on the door-step.
p704
aVHe was incensed with Tony for having given him so much unnecessary\u000atrouble, and he was resolved to give the boy a lesson.
p705
aVIt was quite dark in the shadow of the house, and when the door opened,\u000aRudolph, supposing, of course, it was Tony who had opened it, seized\u000athe person, whom he saw but dimly, by the arm, exclaiming venomously,\u000aas he tried to reach him:\u000a\u000a"I'll teach you to keep me waiting, you young rascal."
p706
aVHe was not long in finding out his mistake.
p707
aVAbner was considerably larger and more muscular than the tramp, and he\u000areturned the compliment by shaking off Rudolph's grasp, and seizing him\u000ain his own vise-like grasp.
p708
aV"You'll teach me, will you, you villain," retorted Abner.
p709
aV"I'll teach\u000ayou to come here like a thief."
p710
aV"Let go," exclaimed the tramp, as he felt himself shaken roughly.
p711
aV"Not till I've given you a good drubbing," returned Abner, and he began\u000ato use his cudgel with effect on the back and shoulders of the tramp.
p712
aV"You've come to the wrong house, you have."
p713
aVRudolph ground his teeth with ineffectual rage.
p714
aVHe lamented that he\u000ahad not a knife or pistol with him, but he had made so sure of easy\u000aentrance into the house, and no resistance, that he had not prepared\u000ahimself.
p715
aVAs to brute force, he was no match for Abner.
p716
aV"The boy betrayed me!"
p717
aVhe shrieked.
p718
aV"I'll have his life."
p719
aV"Not much," said Abner.
p720
aV"You'll be lucky to get away with your own.
p721
aVIt\u000aisn't the boy.
p722
aVI was awake, and heard you ask him to let you in.
p723
aVNow\u000atake yourself off."
p724
aVAs he said this he gave a powerful push, and Rudolph reeled a moment\u000aand sank upon the ground, striking his head with violence.
p725
aV"He won't try it again," said Abner, as he shut to the door and bolted\u000ait.
p726
aV"I guess he's got enough for once."
p727
aVTony stood by, ashamed and mortified.
p728
aVHe was afraid Abner would class\u000ahim with the tramp who had just been ignominiously expelled from the\u000ahouse.
p729
aVHe was afraid he, too, would be thrust out of doors, in which\u000acase he would be exposed to brutal treatment from Rudolph.
p730
aVBut he\u000adid not need to fear this.
p731
aVAbner had seen and heard enough to feel\u000aconvinced that Tony was all right in the matter, and he did not mean to\u000amake the innocent suffer for the guilty.
p732
aV"Now let us go to bed, Tony," he said in a friendly manner.
p733
aV"You don't\u000awant to go with him, do you?"
p734
aV"No," said Tony.
p735
aV"I never want to see him again."
p736
aV"I shouldn't think you would.
p737
aVHe's a rascal and a thief."
p738
aV"I hope you don't think I wanted to rob the house," said Tony.
p739
aV"No; I don't believe you're a bit like him; what makes you go with him?"
p740
aV"I won't any more."
p741
aV"He isn't your father?"
p742
aV"No; I don't know who my father is."
p743
aV"That's strange," said Abner, who had seen but little of the world.
p744
aVEvery one that he knew had a father, and knew who that father was.
p745
aVHe\u000acould not realize that any one could have an experience like Tony's.
p746
aV"I wish I did know my father," said Tony, thoughtfully.
p747
aV"I'm alone in\u000athe world now."
p748
aV"What do you mean to do?"
p749
aV"I'll go off by myself to-morrow, away from Rudolph.
p750
aVI never want to\u000asee him again."
p751
aV"Have you got any money?"
p752
aVThey had now got back into the chamber, and were taking off their\u000aclothes.
p753
aV"I've got five cents," answered Tony.
p754
aV"Is that all?"
p755
aV"Yes; but I don't mind; I'll get along somehow."
p756
aVTony had always got along somehow.
p757
aVHe had never--at least not for long\u000aat a time--known what it was to have a settled home or a permanent\u000ashelter.
p758
aVWhether the world owed him a living or not, he had always got\u000aone, such as it was, and though he had often been cold and hungry,\u000ahere he was at fourteen; well and strong, and with plenty of pluck\u000aand courage to carry with him into the life struggle that was opening\u000abefore him.
p759
aVAbner's training had been different, and he wondered at the\u000acoolness with which Tony contemplated the future.
p760
aVBut he was too sleepy\u000ato wonder long at anything, and with a yawn he lapsed into slumber.
p761
aVTony did not go to sleep immediately.
p762
aVHe had need to be thoughtful.
p763
aVHe had made up his mind to be his own master henceforth, but Rudolph,\u000ahe knew, would have a word to say on that point.
p764
aVIn getting away\u000athe next morning he must manage to give the tramp a wide berth.
p765
aVIt\u000awould be better for him to go to some distant place, where, free from\u000ainterference, he could make his own living.
p766
aVThere was another thought that came to him.
p767
aVSomewhere in the world he\u000amight come across a father or mother, or more distant relative--one of\u000awhom he would not be ashamed, as he was of the companion who tried to\u000adraw him into crime.
p768
aVThis was the last thought in his mind, as he sank\u000ainto a sound sleep from which he did not awaken till he was called to\u000abreakfast.
p769
aVCHAPTER VI.
p770
aVABNER'S RUSE.
p771
aVTo say that Rudolph was angry when he recovered from the temporary\u000ainsensibility occasioned by his fall, would be a very mild expression.
p772
aVHe had not only been thwarted in his designs, but suffered violence and\u000ahumiliation in presence of the boy of whom he regarded himself as the\u000aguardian.
p773
aVHe thirsted for revenge, if not on Abner, then on Tony, whom\u000ait would be safer to maltreat and abuse.
p774
aVAnger is unreasonable, and poor Tony would have fared badly, if he had\u000afallen into Rudolph's clutches just then.
p775
aVIt made no difference that\u000aAbner had exonerated Tony from any share in the unpleasant surprise he\u000ahad met.
p776
aVHe determined to give him a severe beating, nevertheless.
p777
aVThere is an old proverb: "You must catch your hare before you cook it."
p778
aVThis did not occur to the tramp.
p779
aVHe never supposed Tony would have the\u000ahardihood or courage to give him the slip.
p780
aVThe remainder of the night spent by Tony in sleeping was less\u000apleasantly spent by Rudolph in the barn.
p781
aVHe meant to be up early, as he knew he was liable to arrest on account\u000aof his last night's attempt, and lie in wait for Tony, who, he\u000asupposed, would wait for breakfast.
p782
aVHe was right there.
p783
aVTony did remain for breakfast.
p784
aVThe farmer--Mr.\u000aColeman--had already been informed of Rudolph's attempted burglary, and\u000ahe did Tony the justice to exonerate him from any share in it.
p785
aV"What are you going to do, my boy?"
p786
aVhe asked at the breakfast table.
p787
aV"I am going to set up for myself," answered Tony, cheerfully.
p788
aV"That's right.
p789
aVHave nothing more to do with that man.
p790
aVHe can only do\u000ayou harm.
p791
aVHave you got any money?"
p792
aV"I've got five cents."
p793
aV"That isn't enough to buy a farm."
p794
aV"Not a very large one," said Tony, smiling.
p795
aVAbner nearly choked with laughter.
p796
aVThis was a joke which he could\u000aappreciate.
p797
aV"I don't think I'll go to farming," continued Tony.
p798
aV"You can stay here a week or two," said the farmer, hospitably, "till\u000ayou get time to look round."
p799
aV"Thank you," said Tony.
p800
aV"You are very kind, but I don't think it will\u000abe safe.
p801
aVRudolph will be on the watch for me."
p802
aV"The man you came with?"
p803
aV"Yes."
p804
aV"Guess he won't touch you while I'm round," said Abner.
p805
aV"I don't think he'll want to tackle you again," said Tony.
p806
aV"Didn't I lay him out though?"
p807
aVsaid Abner, with a grin.
p808
aV"He thought it\u000awas you, ho!
p809
aVho!"
p810
aV"He didn't think so long," said Tony.
p811
aV"I haven't got such an arm as\u000ayou."
p812
aVAbner was pleased with this compliment to his prowess, and wouldn't\u000ahave minded another tussle with the tramp.
p813
aV"Where do you think that chap you call Rudolph is?"
p814
aVhe asked.
p815
aV"He's searching for me, I expect," said Tony.
p816
aV"If I'm not careful he'll\u000aget hold of me."
p817
aVJust then a neighbor's boy, named Joe, came to the house on an errand.
p818
aVHe was almost Tony's size.
p819
aVHe waited about, not seeming in any hurry to\u000abe gone.
p820
aV"Abner," said the farmer, "if you've got nothing else to do, you may\u000aload up the wagon with hay, and carry it to Castleton.
p821
aVWe shall have\u000amore than we want."
p822
aV"All right," said Abner.
p823
aV"May I go, too?
p824
aVMay I ride on the hay?"
p825
aVasked Joe, eagerly.
p826
aV"Will your father let you?"
p827
aVasked the farmer.
p828
aV"Oh, yes; he won't mind."
p829
aV"Then you may go," was the reply.
p830
aV"Do you want to go, too, Tony?"
p831
aVTony was about to say yes, when an idea seized him.
p832
aV"If the other boy goes, Rudolph will think it is I, and he will follow\u000athe wagon.
p833
aVThat will give me a chance of getting off in another\u000adirection."
p834
aV"So it will," said Abner.
p835
aV"What a head-piece you've got," he added,\u000aadmiringly.
p836
aV"I wouldn't have thought of that."
p837
aVAbner's head-piece was nothing to boast of.
p838
aVHe had strength of body,\u000abut to equalize matters his mind was not equally endowed.
p839
aVThe plan was disclosed to Joe, who willingly agreed to enter into it.
p840
aVThis was the more feasible because he was of about Tony's size, and\u000awore a hat just like his.
p841
aVThe hay was loaded, and the wagon started off with Abner walking\u000aalongside.
p842
aVJoe was perched on top, nearly buried in the hay, but with\u000ahis hat rising from the mass.
p843
aVThis was about all that could be seen of\u000ahim.
p844
aVThey had gone about half a mile when from the bushes by the roadside\u000aRudolph emerged.
p845
aVHe had seen the hat, and felt sure that Tony was\u000atrying to escape him in this way.
p846
aV"Well," said Abner, with a grin, as he recognized his midnight foe,\u000a"how do you feel this morning?"
p847
aV"None the better for you, curse you!"
p848
aVreturned the tramp, roughly.
p849
aVAbner laughed.
p850
aV"That's what I thought," he said, cracking his whip.
p851
aVRudolph would like to have punished him then and there for his\u000ahumiliation of the night before, but Abner looked too powerful as he\u000astrode along manfully with vigorous steps.
p852
aVBesides, he had a heavy whip\u000ain his hand, which the tramp suspected would be used unhesitatingly if\u000athere were occasion.
p853
aVThe prospect was not inviting.
p854
aVBut, at any rate,\u000aRudolph could demand that Tony be remitted to his custody.
p855
aV"Where's my boy?"
p856
aVasked the tramp, keeping at a safe distance.
p857
aV"Didn't know you had a boy," said Abner.
p858
aV"I mean that villain Tony.
p859
aVIs that he on the load of hay?"
p860
aV"Kinder looks like him," answered Abner, grinning.
p861
aVRudolph looked up and caught sight of the hat.
p862
aV"Come down here, Tony," he said sternly.
p863
aVJoe, who had been instructed what to do, answered not a word.
p864
aV"Come down here, if you know what's best for you," continued the tramp.
p865
aV"Guess he's hard of hearing," laughed Abner.
p866
aV"Stop your wagon," said Rudolph, furiously; "I want to get hold of him."
p867
aV"Couldn't do it," said Abner, coolly.
p868
aV"I'm in a hurry."
p869
aV"Will you give me the boy or not?"
p870
aVdemanded the tramp, hoarsely.
p871
aV"He can get off and go along with you if he wants to," said Abner.
p872
aV"Do\u000ayou want to get down, Tony?"
p873
aV"No!"
p874
aVanswered the supposed Tony.
p875
aV"You see, squire, he prefers to ride," said Abner.
p876
aV"Can't blame him\u000amuch.
p877
aVI'd do it in his place."
p878
aV"Where are you going?"
p879
aVdemanded the tramp, who hadn't discovered that\u000athe voice was not that of Tony.
p880
aV"I'm going to Castleton," answered Abner.
p881
aV"Are you going to leave the hay there?"
p882
aV"Yes, that's what I calc'late to do."
p883
aV"How far is it?"
p884
aV"Six miles."
p885
aV"I'll walk along, too."
p886
aV"Better not, squire, you'll get tired."
p887
aV"I'll risk that."
p888
aVOf course Rudolph's plan was manifest.
p889
aVWhen the hay was unloaded, of\u000acourse Tony would have to get down.
p890
aVThen he would get hold of him.
p891
aV"You can do just as you've a mind to," said Abner.
p892
aV"You'll be company\u000ato Tony and me, but you needn't put yourself out on our account, hey,\u000aTony?"
p893
aVThere was a smothered laugh on top of the hay, which the tramp heard.
p894
aVHis eyes snapped viciously, and he privately determined to give Tony a\u000asettlement in full for all his offenses just as soon as he got hold of\u000ahim.
p895
aVSo they jogged on, mile after mile.
p896
aVAbner walked on one side, swinging\u000ahis whip, and occasionally cracking it.
p897
aVThe tramp walked on the other\u000aside of the road, and the boy rode along luxuriously embedded in his\u000afragrant couch of hay.
p898
aVAbner from time to time kept up the tramp's\u000aillusions by calling out, "Tony, you must take keer, or you'll fall\u000aoff."
p899
aV"I'll catch him if he does," said Rudolph, grimly.
p900
aV"So you will," chuckled Abner.
p901
aV"You'd like to, wouldn't you?"
p902
aV"Certainly.
p903
aVHe is my son," said Rudolph.
p904
aV"Do you hear that, Tony?
p905
aVHe says you're his son," said Abner, grinning\u000aagain.
p906
aVThere was another laugh from the boy on the load of hay.
p907
aV"You won't find anything to laugh at when I get hold of you," muttered\u000aRudolph.
p908
aVSo they rode into Castleton.
p909
aVFrom time to time Abner, as he thought how neatly the tramp had been\u000asold, burst into a loud laugh, which was echoed from the hay wagon.
p910
aVRudolph was not only angry, but puzzled.
p911
aV"Does the boy hope to escape me?"
p912
aVhe asked himself.
p913
aV"If so, he will\u000afind himself badly mistaken.
p914
aVHe will find that I am not to be trifled\u000awith."
p915
aV"Say, squire, what makes you look so glum?"
p916
aVasked Abner.
p917
aV"Maybe it's\u000abecause I didn't let you in when you called so late last night.
p918
aVWe\u000adon't receive visitors after midnight."
p919
aVRudolph scowled, but said nothing.
p920
aV"How long has the boy been with you?"
p921
aVasked Abner, further.
p922
aV"Since he was born," answered the tramp.
p923
aV"Ain't I his father?"
p924
aV"I don't know.
p925
aVIf it's a conundrum I give it up."
p926
aV"Well, I am, and no one has a right to keep him from me," said the\u000atramp, in a surly manner.
p927
aV"I wouldn't keep him from you for a minute," said Abner, innocently.
p928
aV"You are doing it now."
p929
aV"No, I ain't."
p930
aV"I can't get at him on that hay."
p931
aV"He can come down if he wants to.
p932
aVI don't stop him.
p933
aVYou can come down\u000aif you want to, Tony," he said, looking up to where the boy's hat was\u000avisible.
p934
aVTony did not answer, and Abner continued:\u000a\u000a"You see he don't want to come.
p935
aVHe'd rather ride.
p936
aVYou know he's been\u000asick," said Abner, with a grin, "and he's too delicate to walk.
p937
aVHe\u000aain't tough, like you and me."
p938
aV"He'll need to be tough," muttered the tramp, as he thought of the\u000aflogging he intended to give Tony.
p939
aV"What did you say?"
p940
aV"Never mind."
p941
aV"Oh, I don't mind," said Abner.
p942
aV"You can say what you want to.
p943
aVThis is\u000aa free country, only you can't do what you've a mind to."
p944
aVRudolph wished that he had a double stock of strength.
p945
aVIt was very\u000aprovoking to be laughed at and derided by Abner without being able\u000ato revenge himself.
p946
aVA pistol or a knife would make him even with the\u000acountryman, but Rudolph was too much of a coward to commit such serious\u000acrimes when there was so much danger of detection and punishment.
p947
aVAt last they entered Castleton.
p948
aVThe hay was to be delivered to a speculator, who collected large\u000aquantities of it, and forwarded over the railroad to a large city.
p949
aVIt had to be weighed, and Abner drove at once to the hay scales.
p950
aV"Now," thought Rudolph, with exultation, "the boy must come down, and I\u000ashall get hold of him."
p951
aV"I guess you'd better slide down," said Abner.
p952
aV"I can't sell you for\u000ahay, Tony."
p953
aVThere was a movement, and then the boy slid down, Abner catching him as\u000ahe descended.
p954
aVRudolph's face changed ominously when he saw that it wasn't Tony who\u000amade his appearance.
p955
aV"What does this mean?"
p956
aVhe demanded furiously.
p957
aV"What's the matter?"
p958
aV"This isn't Tony."
p959
aV"Come to look at him, it isn't," said Abner, with a twinkle in his eye.
p960
aV"Didn't you say it was Tony?"
p961
aVasked the tramp, exasperated.
p962
aV"I guess I was mistaken, squire," said Abner, grinning.
p963
aV"Where is he?"
p964
aV"I don't know, I'm sure.
p965
aVIt seems he didn't come.
p966
aVGuess he must have\u000agiven us the slip."
p967
aVThe tramp, unable to control his rage, burst into a volley of\u000aexecrations.
p968
aV"Hope you feel better, squire," said Abner, when he got through.
p969
aVThe tramp strode off, vowing dire vengeance against both Abner and\u000aTony.
p970
aV[Illustration: "What does this mean?"
p971
aVdemanded the tramp furiously.
p972
aV"This isn't Tony."
p973
aV--(See page 45.)]
p974
aVCHAPTER VII.
p975
aVA STRANGE HOTEL.
p976
aVFrom the upper window in the farm house, which was situated on elevated\u000aground, Tony saw his old guardian follow Abner.
p977
aVThus the way was opened\u000afor his escape.
p978
aVHe waited, however, a short time to make sure that all\u000awas safe, and then bade farewell to the farmer and his wife, thanking\u000athem heartily for their kindness to him.
p979
aV"Won't you stay longer with us?"
p980
aVasked the farmer.
p981
aV"You can as well as\u000anot."
p982
aV"Thank you," answered Tony, "but I wouldn't dare to.
p983
aVRudolph may be\u000aback for me, and I want to get away before he has a chance."
p984
aV"Are you going to walk?"
p985
aVasked the farmer's wife.
p986
aV"Yes," said Tony.
p987
aV"I've only got five cents in my pocket, and I can't\u000aride far on that."
p988
aV"I'm afraid you will be tired," said she, sympathetically.
p989
aV"Oh, I'm used to tramping," returned Tony, lightly.
p990
aV"I don't mind that\u000aat all."
p991
aV"Can't you put up some dinner for him, wife?"
p992
aVsuggested the farmer.
p993
aV"It'll make him hungry, walking."
p994
aV"To be sure I will," she replied, and a large supply of eatables were\u000aput in a paper, sufficient to last Tony twenty-four hours, at least.
p995
aVThe farmer deliberated whether he should not offer our hero half\u000aa dollar besides, but he was naturally close, so far as money was\u000aconcerned, and he decided in the negative.
p996
aVSo Tony set out, taking a course directly opposite to that pursued\u000aby Abner.
p997
aVIn this way he thought he should best avoid the chance of\u000ameeting Rudolph.
p998
aVHe walked easily, not being in any special hurry, and whenever he felt\u000aat all tired he stopped by the way side to rest.
p999
aVEarly in the afternoon\u000ahe lay down under a tree in the pasture and fell asleep.
p1000
aVHe was roused\u000aby a cold sensation, and found that a dog had pressed his cold nose\u000aagainst his cheek.
p1001
aV"Haven't you any more manners, sir?"
p1002
aVdemanded Tony, good-naturedly.
p1003
aVThe dog wagged his tail, and looked friendly.
p1004
aV"It's a hint that I must be on my journey," he thought.
p1005
aVAbout five o'clock he felt that it was about time to look out for a\u000anight's rest.
p1006
aVA hotel was, of course, out of the question, and he\u000alooked about for a farm house.
p1007
aVThe nearest dwelling was a small one, of\u000afour rooms, setting back from the road, down a lane.
p1008
aV"Perhaps I can get in there," thought Tony.
p1009
aVAn old man, with a patriarchal beard, whose neglected and squalid dress\u000aseemed to indicate poverty, was sitting on the door-step.
p1010
aV"Good evening," said Tony.
p1011
aV"Who are you?"
p1012
aVdemanded the old man, suspiciously.
p1013
aV"I am a poor traveler," said Tony.
p1014
aV"A tramp!"
p1015
aVsaid the old man, in the same suspicious tone.
p1016
aV"Yes, I suppose so," said Tony, although he did not like the title\u000aovermuch.
p1017
aV"Well, I've got nothing for you," said the old man, roughly.
p1018
aV"I don't want anything except the chance to sleep."
p1019
aV"Don't you want any supper?"
p1020
aV"No, I've got my supper here," returned our hero, producing his paper\u000aof provisions.
p1021
aV"What have you got there?"
p1022
aVasked the old man, with an eager look.
p1023
aV"Some bread and butter and cold meat."
p1024
aV"It looks good," said the other, with what Tony thought to be a longing\u000alook.
p1025
aV"I'll share it with you, if you'll let me sleep here to-night," said\u000aTony.
p1026
aV"Will you?"
p1027
aVthe other answered.
p1028
aV"Yes; there's enough for both of us."
p1029
aVThe old man was a miser, as Tony suspected.
p1030
aVHe was able to live\u000acomfortably, but he deprived himself of the necessaries of life in\u000aorder to hoard away money.
p1031
aVHis face revealed that to Tony.
p1032
aVHe had\u000anearly starved himself, but he had not overcome his natural appetites,\u000aand the sight of Tony's supper gave him a craving for it.
p1033
aV"I don't know," he said, doubtfully.
p1034
aV"If I let you sleep here you might\u000aget up in the night and rob me."
p1035
aVTony laughed.
p1036
aV"You don't look as if you had anything worth stealing," he said,\u000acandidly.
p1037
aV"You're right, quite right," said old Ben Hayden, for this was his\u000aname.
p1038
aV"I've only saved a little money--a very little--to pay my funeral\u000aexpenses.
p1039
aVYou wouldn't want to take that?"
p1040
aV"Oh, no," said Tony.
p1041
aV"I wouldn't take it if you'd give it to me."
p1042
aV"You wouldn't?
p1043
aVwhy not?"
p1044
aV"Because you need it yourself.
p1045
aVIf you were a rich man it would be\u000adifferent."
p1046
aV"So it would," said old Hayden.
p1047
aV"You're a good boy--an excellent boy.
p1048
aVI'll trust you.
p1049
aVYou can stay."
p1050
aV"Then let us eat supper," said Tony.
p1051
aVHe sat down on the door-step, and gave the old man half of his supply\u000aof food.
p1052
aVHe was interested to see the avidity with which he ate it.
p1053
aV"Is it good?"
p1054
aVhe asked.
p1055
aV"I haven't eaten anything so good for a long time.
p1056
aVI couldn't afford to\u000abuy food."
p1057
aV"I am sorry for you."
p1058
aV"You haven't got any left for breakfast," said the old man.
p1059
aV"Oh, somebody will give me breakfast," said Tony.
p1060
aV"I always get taken\u000acare of somehow."
p1061
aV"You are young and strong."
p1062
aV"Yes."
p1063
aV"Do you travel around all the time?"
p1064
aV"Yes; but I hope to get a chance to go to work soon; I'd rather live in\u000aone place."
p1065
aV"You might live with me if I were not so poor," said the old man.
p1066
aV"Thank you," answered Tony, politely; but it did not appear to him that\u000ait was exactly such a home as he would choose.
p1067
aV"Do you live alone?"
p1068
aVhe asked.
p1069
aV"Yes."
p1070
aV"I didn't know but you might be married."
p1071
aV"I was married when I was a young man, but my wife died long ago."
p1072
aV"Why don't you marry again?"
p1073
aVinquired Tony, half in fun.
p1074
aV"I couldn't afford it," answered Hayden, frightened at the suggestion.
p1075
aV"Women have terrible appetites."
p1076
aV"Have they?"
p1077
aVreturned Tony, amused.
p1078
aV"And I can't get enough for myself to eat."
p1079
aV"Have you always lived here?"
p1080
aV"No; I lived in England when I was a young man."
p1081
aV"What made you leave it?"
p1082
aV"Why do you ask me that?"
p1083
aVdemanded old Ben, suspiciously.
p1084
aV"Oh, if it's a secret, don't tell me," said Tony, indifferently.
p1085
aV"Who said it was a secret?"
p1086
aVsaid the old man, irritably.
p1087
aV"Nobody that I know of."
p1088
aV"Then why do you ask me such questions?"
p1089
aVThe old man surveyed Tony with a look of doubt, as if he thought the\u000aboy were laying a trap for him.
p1090
aV"Don't answer anything you don't want to," said our hero.
p1091
aV"I only asked\u000afor the sake of saying something."
p1092
aV"I don't mind telling," said old Ben, more calmly.
p1093
aV"It was because I\u000awas so poor.
p1094
aVI thought I could do better in America."
p1095
aV"And didn't you?"
p1096
aV"When I was able to work.
p1097
aVNow I'm weak and poor, and can't always get\u000aenough to eat."
p1098
aV"Do you own this place?"
p1099
aV"Yes, but it's a very poor place.
p1100
aVIt isn't worth much."
p1101
aV"I shouldn't think it was," said Tony.
p1102
aV"You're a good lad--an excellent lad.
p1103
aVYou see how poor I am."
p1104
aV"Of course I do, and I'm sorry for you.
p1105
aVI would help you, only I am\u000avery poor myself."
p1106
aV"Have you got any money?"
p1107
aVasked Ben, with interest.
p1108
aV"I've got five cents," answered Tony, laughing.
p1109
aV"I hope you've got more\u000athan that."
p1110
aV"A little more--a very little more," said Ben, cautiously.
p1111
aVThe old miser began to consider whether he couldn't charge Tony five\u000acents for his lodging, but sighed at the recollection that Tony had\u000aalready paid for it in advance by giving him a supper.
p1112
aVWhen eight o'clock came the miser suggested going to bed.
p1113
aV"I haven't any lights," he said; "candles cost so much.
p1114
aVBesides, a\u000abody's better off in bed."
p1115
aV"I'm willing to go to bed," said Tony.
p1116
aV"I've walked a good deal to-day,\u000aand I'm tired."
p1117
aVThey went into the house.
p1118
aVThere was a heap of rags in the corner of the\u000aroom when they entered.
p1119
aV"That's my bed," said old Ben; "it's all I have."
p1120
aV"I can sleep on the floor," said Tony.
p1121
aVHe took off his jacket, and rolled it up for a pillow, and stretched\u000ahimself out on the bare floor.
p1122
aVHe had often slept so before.
p1123
aVCHAPTER VIII.
p1124
aVTONY HIRES OUT AS A COOK AND HOUSEKEEPER.
p1125
aVTony was not slow in going to sleep.
p1126
aVNeither his hard bed nor his\u000astrange bed-chamber troubled him.
p1127
aVHe could sleep anywhere.
p1128
aVThat was one\u000aof the advantages of his checkered life.
p1129
aVGenerally he slept all night without awaking, but to-night, for some\u000aunknown reason, he awoke about two o'clock.
p1130
aVIt was unusually light for\u000athat hour, and so he was enabled to see what at first startled him.
p1131
aVThe\u000aold man was out of bed, and on his knees in the center of the room.
p1132
aVHe\u000ahad raised a plank, forming a part of the flooring, and had raised from\u000abeneath it a canvass bag full of gold pieces.
p1133
aVHe was taking them out\u000aand counting them, apparently quite unconscious of Tony's presence.
p1134
aVTony raised himself on his elbow, and looked at him.
p1135
aVIt occurred to him\u000athat for a man so suspicious it was strange that he should expose his\u000ahoard before a stranger.
p1136
aVSomething, however, in the old man's look led\u000ahim to think that he was in a sleepwalking fit.
p1137
aV"Ninety-five, ninety-six, ninety-seven," Tony heard him count; "that\u000amakes nine hundred and seventy dollars, all gold, good, beautiful gold.
p1138
aVNobody knows the old man is so rich.
p1139
aVThere's another bag, too.
p1140
aVThere\u000aare one hundred pieces in that.
p1141
aVThree more, and this will be full, too.
p1142
aVNobody must know, nobody must know."
p1143
aVHe put back the pieces, replaced the bag in its hiding-place, and then\u000aputting back the plank, laid down once more on his heap of rags.
p1144
aV"How uneasy he would be," thought Tony, "if he knew I had seen his\u000atreasures.
p1145
aVBut I wouldn't rob him for the world, although the money\u000awould do me good, and he makes no use of it except to look at it."
p1146
aVIf Tony was honest, it was an instinctive feeling.
p1147
aVIt could not have\u000abeen expected of one reared as he had been.
p1148
aVBut, singular as it may\u000aseem, beyond a vague longing, he felt no temptation to deprive old Ben\u000aof his money.
p1149
aV"Let him get what satisfaction he can from it," he said to himself.
p1150
aV"I\u000ahope he'll keep it till he dies.
p1151
aVI am only afraid that some night some\u000aone will see him counting the gold who will want to take it."
p1152
aVTony went to bed again, and slept till six.
p1153
aVThen he was awakened by a\u000apiteous groaning, which he soon found proceeded from the other bed.
p1154
aV"What's the matter?"
p1155
aVhe asked.
p1156
aV"Who's there?"
p1157
aVdemanded Ben, terrified.
p1158
aV"It's only I.
p1159
aVDon't you remember you let me sleep here last night?"
p1160
aV"O, yes; I remember now.
p1161
aVI'm sick; very sick."
p1162
aV"How do you feel?"
p1163
aV"I'm aching and trembling all over.
p1164
aVDo you think I am going to die?"
p1165
aVhe asked, with a startled look.
p1166
aV"Oh, no, I guess not," said Tony, reassuringly.
p1167
aV"Everybody is sick now\u000aand then."
p1168
aV"I never felt so before," groaned Ben.
p1169
aV"I'm an old man.
p1170
aVDon't you\u000athink--don't you really think I shall die?"
p1171
aVHe looked appealingly at Tony, as if the fiat of life and death lay\u000awith him.
p1172
aVTony, of course, knew nothing of medicine or of diseases, but he had\u000athe sense to understand that the old man would be more likely to\u000arecover if his terror could be allayed, and he said, lightly:\u000a\u000a"Oh, it's only a trifle.
p1173
aVYou've taken cold, very likely.
p1174
aVA cup of hot\u000atea would be good for you."
p1175
aV"I haven't any tea," groaned Ben.
p1176
aV"It costs a great deal, and I'm very\u000apoor.
p1177
aVI can't afford to buy it."
p1178
aVTony smiled to himself, remembering the hoard of gold under the floor,\u000abut he would not refer to it, at least not at present.
p1179
aV"Are you sure you haven't got a little money?"
p1180
aVhe asked.
p1181
aV"If you want\u000ato get well, you must be made comfortable."
p1182
aV"It's hard to be poor," whined Ben.
p1183
aV"I guess you've got some money," said Tony.
p1184
aV"You'd better let me go to\u000athe store, and buy some tea and a fresh roll for you."
p1185
aV"How much will it cost?"
p1186
aVasked Ben.
p1187
aV"I can get some bread, and tea, and sugar for thirty or forty cents,"\u000aanswered Tony.
p1188
aV"Forty cents!
p1189
aVIt's frightful!"
p1190
aVexclaimed Ben.
p1191
aV"I--I guess I'll do\u000awithout it."
p1192
aV"Oh, well, if you prefer to lie there and die its none of my business,"\u000asaid Tony, rather provoked at the old man's perverse folly.
p1193
aV"But I don't want to die," whined Ben.
p1194
aV"Then do as I tell you."
p1195
aVTony jumped out of bed, unrolled his coat, and put it on.
p1196
aV"Now," said he, "I'm ready to go for you, if you'll give me the money."
p1197
aV"But you may take it, and not come back," said the old man,\u000asuspiciously.
p1198
aV"If you think you can't trust me, you needn't," said Tony.
p1199
aV"I've\u000aoffered to do you a favor."
p1200
aV"I think I'll go myself," said Ben.
p1201
aVHe tried to raise himself, but a twinge of pain compelled him to lie\u000adown again.
p1202
aV"No, I can't," he said.
p1203
aV"Well, do you want me to go for you?"
p1204
aV"Yes," answered Ben, reluctantly.
p1205
aV"Then give me the money."
p1206
aVStill more reluctantly Ben produced twenty-five cents from his pocket.
p1207
aV"Isn't that enough?"
p1208
aVhe asked.
p1209
aV"Better give me more," said Tony.
p1210
aVHe produced ten cents more, and vowed it was all the money he had in\u000athe world.
p1211
aVTony decided not to contradict his assertion, but to make this go as\u000afar as it would.
p1212
aVHe put on his hat and started out.
p1213
aVHe meant also to\u000acall at the doctor's, and asked him to call round, for he thought it\u000apossible that the old man might be seriously sick.
p1214
aVFirst, however, he went to the grocery store, which had only just been\u000aopened, and obtained the articles which he had mentioned to Ben as\u000alikely to do him good.
p1215
aVNext he called at the house of the village doctor, obtaining the\u000adirection from the storekeeper.
p1216
aVIn a few words he made known his errand.
p1217
aV"Old Ben sick!"
p1218
aVsaid Doctor Compton.
p1219
aV"What's the matter with him?"
p1220
aVTony explained how he appeared to be affected.
p1221
aV"How did you happen to be in his house?"
p1222
aVasked the doctor, with\u000acuriosity.
p1223
aV"You are not a relation of his, are you?"
p1224
aVTony laughed.
p1225
aV"I don't think he would let me into the house if I were," he said.
p1226
aV"He\u000awould be suspicious of me."
p1227
aV"Then how does it happen that you were with him?"
p1228
aVTony explained.
p1229
aV"He has been repaid for taking you in," said the doctor.
p1230
aV"I'll put on\u000amy hat, and go right over with you."
p1231
aVAfter Tony left the house, old Ben lay and tormented himself with the\u000athought that the boy would never come back.
p1232
aV"Just as like as not," he\u000athought, "he will go off with the money, and leave me here to die."
p1233
aVThen he tried to sit up, but without success.
p1234
aVHalf an hour later he was relieved by seeing the door open, and Tony\u000aenter.
p1235
aVBut he looked dismayed when he saw the doctor.
p1236
aV"What did you come for?"
p1237
aVhe asked, peevishly.
p1238
aV"To see what I can do for you, Mr. Hayden.
p1239
aVLet me feel your pulse."
p1240
aV"But I can't afford to have a doctor.
p1241
aVI am poor, and can't pay you,"\u000awhined old Ben.
p1242
aV"We'll talk about that afterward."
p1243
aV"You can't charge when I didn't send for you."
p1244
aV"Make your mind easy.
p1245
aVI won't charge for this visit.
p1246
aVLet me feel your\u000apulse."
p1247
aVOld Ben no longer opposed medical treatment, finding it would cost\u000anothing.
p1248
aV"Am I going to die?"
p1249
aVhe asked, with an anxious look.
p1250
aV"You need nourishing food and care, that is all," was the reply.
p1251
aV"You\u000ahave had a chill, and you are reduced by insufficient food."
p1252
aV"I have some bread and tea here," said Tony.
p1253
aV"Do you know how to make the tea?"
p1254
aVasked the doctor.
p1255
aV"Yes," said Tony.
p1256
aV"Then make a fire, and boil it at once.
p1257
aVAnd, by the way, Mr. Hayden\u000aneeds somebody to be with him for a few days.
p1258
aVCan you stay with him and\u000alook after him?"
p1259
aV"If he will give me money enough to buy what he needs," said Tony.
p1260
aV"Will you do it, Mr.
p1261
aVHayden?"
p1262
aVasked the doctor.
p1263
aVOld Ben whined that he was poor, and had no money, but the doctor\u000ainterrupted him impatiently.
p1264
aV"That's all nonsense," he said.
p1265
aV"You may not have much money, but\u000ayou've got some, and you'll die if you don't spend some on yourself.
p1266
aVIf you don't agree to it, I shall advise this boy here to leave you to\u000ayour fate.
p1267
aVThen your only resource will be to go to the poor-house."
p1268
aVThis proposal was not acceptable to Ben, who was unwilling to leave\u000athe house where his treasures were concealed.
p1269
aVHe therefore reluctantly\u000aacceded to the doctor's conditions, and Tony got his breakfast.
p1270
aVDespite\u000ahis sickness, he relished the tea and toast, and for the moment forgot\u000awhat it cost.
p1271
aV"Well," thought Tony to himself with a smile, "I've got a situation as\u000aplain cook and housekeeper.
p1272
aVI wonder how long it will last, and what'll\u000acome of it.
p1273
aVI don't believe Rudolph will look for me here."
p1274
aVBut in this Tony was mistaken.
p1275
aVCHAPTER IX.
p1276
aVTHE FACE AT THE WINDOW.
p1277
aVTony was not only cook and housekeeper, but he was sick-nurse as well.
p1278
aVNor were his duties easy.
p1279
aVThe main difficulty was about getting money\u000ato buy what was absolutely necessary.
p1280
aVThis was very aggravating,\u000aespecially since Tony knew what he did about Ben's hidden treasure.
p1281
aVMoreover, he had reason to suspect that Ben had more money concealed\u000aelsewhere.
p1282
aVOne morning Tony went to Ben for money, saying:\u000a\u000a"There isn't a scrap of food in the house, except a little tea."
p1283
aV"You can make some tea.
p1284
aVThat will do," said Ben.
p1285
aV"It may do for you, but it won't for me," said Tony, resolutely.
p1286
aV"I\u000aain't going to stay here to starve."
p1287
aV"It costs a sight to support two people," whined the old man.
p1288
aV"I don't know about that.
p1289
aVI've only spent two dollars in six days.
p1290
aVYou\u000adon't call that much, do you?"
p1291
aV"Two dollars!"
p1292
aVejaculated the old man, terrified.
p1293
aV"O, it's too much.
p1294
aVI\u000aam ruined!"
p1295
aV"Are you?"
p1296
aVsaid Tony, coolly.
p1297
aV"Then all I can say is, you're easy\u000aruined.
p1298
aVI want half a dollar."
p1299
aV"I shan't give it to you," snarled Ben.
p1300
aV"Do you mean to starve?"
p1301
aV"I won't part with all I have.
p1302
aVYou are robbing me."
p1303
aV"That won't make much difference, as you'll be dead in three days,"\u000asaid Tony.
p1304
aV"What?"
p1305
aValmost shrieked Ben, in dismay.
p1306
aV"Who told you so?
p1307
aVThe doctor?"
p1308
aV"No."
p1309
aV"You ain't goin' to murder me, are you?"
p1310
aV"No; you are going to murder yourself."
p1311
aV"What do you mean?"
p1312
aVdemanded Ben, peevishly.
p1313
aV"You're not willing to buy anything to eat," explained Tony, "and you\u000acan't live above three days on nothing."
p1314
aV"Is that all?
p1315
aVWhat made you frighten me so?"
p1316
aVcomplained Ben, angrily.
p1317
aV"I only told you the truth.
p1318
aVAre you going to give me the money?"
p1319
aV"Perhaps you'll tell me where I am to get so much money?"
p1320
aVsaid Ben, in\u000athe same tone.
p1321
aV"I will tell you if you want me to," answered Tony.
p1322
aV"Where?"
p1323
aVasked Ben, eagerly.
p1324
aV"Under the floor," returned Tony, composedly.
p1325
aV"What!"
p1326
aVscreamed Ben, in consternation.
p1327
aV"Just where I said.
p1328
aVThere's plenty of money under that plank."
p1329
aV"Who told you?"
p1330
aVgroaned the old man, livid with terror.
p1331
aV"Have--have you\u000ataken any?"
p1332
aV"Not a dollar.
p1333
aVIt's all there.
p1334
aVYou needn't be frightened."
p1335
aV"Have you been spying when I was asleep?"
p1336
aVdemanded Ben, incensed.
p1337
aV"No, I haven't.
p1338
aVThat ain't my style," answered Tony, independently.
p1339
aV"You did.
p1340
aVI know you did."
p1341
aV"Then you know too much."
p1342
aV"How could you find out, then?"
p1343
aV"If you want to know, I'll tell you.
p1344
aVThe first night I was here you got\u000aup in your sleep and took up the board.
p1345
aVThen you drew out two bags of\u000agold pieces and counted them."
p1346
aV"Oh, I'm ruined!
p1347
aVI'm undone!"
p1348
aVlamented Ben, when he found that his\u000asecret had been discovered.
p1349
aV"I don't see how you are."
p1350
aV"I shall be robbed.
p1351
aVThere's only a little there--only a few dollars to\u000abury me."
p1352
aV"I guess you mean to have a tall funeral, then," said Tony, coolly.
p1353
aV"There's as much as a thousand dollars there."
p1354
aV"No, no--only fifty," answered the old man.
p1355
aV"There's no use talking, I know better.
p1356
aVIf you don't believe it,\u000asuppose I take up the bags and count the pieces."
p1357
aV"No, no!"
p1358
aV"Just as you say.
p1359
aVAll is, you've got plenty of money, and I know it,\u000aand if you ain't willing to use some of it, I'll go off and leave you\u000aalone."
p1360
aV"Don't go," said Ben, hastily.
p1361
aV"You're a good boy.
p1362
aVYou wouldn't rob a\u000apoor old man, would you?"
p1363
aV"Nor a rich old man either; but I don't mean to starve.
p1364
aVSo give me\u000afifty cents, and I'll go over to the store and get some fresh bread and\u000abutter, and tea and sugar."
p1365
aV"No matter about the butter.
p1366
aVIt costs too much."
p1367
aV"I want butter myself.
p1368
aVMy constitution requires it," said Tony.
p1369
aV"You\u000aneedn't eat it if you don't want to."
p1370
aVBen groaned again, but he produced the money required, and Tony soon\u000areturned from the grocery store with small supplies of the articles he\u000ahad named.
p1371
aV"Now we'll have some breakfast," said Tony, cheerfully.
p1372
aV"Don't you feel\u000ahungry?"
p1373
aV"A--a little," acknowledged Ben, reluctantly.
p1374
aV"I wish I wasn't.
p1375
aVIt\u000acosts so much to live."
p1376
aV"I don't think it costs you much," said Tony.
p1377
aV"This morning I'm going\u000ato give you a boiled egg besides your tea and toast."
p1378
aV"Where did you get it?"
p1379
aV"I bought it at the store."
p1380
aV"I can't afford it," groaned the old man.
p1381
aV"You may as well eat it as it's here.
p1382
aVI bought two, one for myself."
p1383
aV"How much did you pay?"
p1384
aV"Three cents for two."
p1385
aVBen groaned again, but when breakfast was ready he showed an unusually\u000agood appetite, and did not refrain from partaking of the egg, expensive\u000aas it was.
p1386
aVDr. Compton came in the next morning, and pronounced the old man better\u000aand stronger.
p1387
aV"Shall I be able to get up soon, doctor?"
p1388
aVasked Ben.
p1389
aV"In a day or two, I think."
p1390
aVBen heaved a sigh of relief.
p1391
aV"I'm glad of it," he said.
p1392
aV"I can't afford to be sick."
p1393
aV"Has it cost you much?"
p1394
aVasked the doctor, amused.
p1395
aV"It costs a sight to live.
p1396
aVHe eats a good deal," indicating Tony.
p1397
aV"He's a growing boy; but he's worth all he costs you.
p1398
aVYou'd better\u000aask him to stay with you a few weeks, till your strength is entirely\u000arecovered."
p1399
aV"No, no; I can't afford it," said Ben, hastily.
p1400
aV"He's a good boy; but\u000ahe's very hearty--very hearty."
p1401
aVTony laughed.
p1402
aV"Don't vex him, doctor," said our hero.
p1403
aV"I'm tired of staying here.
p1404
aVI\u000awant to get out on the road again.
p1405
aVThere isn't much fun in staying shut\u000aup here."
p1406
aVBen looked relieved.
p1407
aVHe had feared that Tony would be reluctant to go.
p1408
aV"Right, boy," he said, "you're right.
p1409
aVIt's a dull place.
p1410
aVYou'll be\u000abetter off to go."
p1411
aV"You have been lucky to have him here during your sickness," said the\u000adoctor.
p1412
aV"Without his care, or that of some one else, you would probably\u000ahave died."
p1413
aV"But I won't die now?"
p1414
aVasked old Ben, anxiously, peering up into the\u000adoctor's face.
p1415
aV"Not at present, I hope.
p1416
aVBut you must live better than you have been\u000aaccustomed to do or you will fall sick again."
p1417
aV"I shall be glad to get away," said Tony, hurriedly, to the doctor,\u000aoutside of the house.
p1418
aV"I'm used to tramping, and I can't stand it much\u000alonger.
p1419
aVThere's one thing I want to tell you before I go, and I might\u000aas well do it now."
p1420
aV"Go on, my boy."
p1421
aV"I'm afraid the old man will be robbed some time."
p1422
aV"Is there anything to steal?"
p1423
aV"Yes; I think I had better tell you about it."
p1424
aVTony, in a low tone, imparted to Dr. Compton the discovery he had made\u000aof the old miser's hoards.
p1425
aV"I suspected as much," said the doctor.
p1426
aV"I will do what I can to induce\u000aBen to have the gold moved to a place of safety, but I don't feel\u000aconfident of my ability to do it.
p1427
aVSuch men generally like to have their\u000ahoards within their own reach."
p1428
aV*       *       *       *       *       *\u000a\u000aTwo nights later, Tony woke shortly after midnight.
p1429
aVIt was a bright,\u000amoonlight night, as on the first night he slept there.
p1430
aVAgain he saw Ben\u000acrouched on the floor, with the plank removed from its place, engaged\u000ain counting his hoards.
p1431
aVThe old man had recovered enough strength to\u000aget out of bed without assistance.
p1432
aVThis time, too, he was broad awake.
p1433
aVTony was not the only witness of the spectacle.
p1434
aVCasting his eyes toward\u000athe window he was startled by seeing a dark, sinister face, pressed\u000aagainst the pane, almost devouring the old man and his gold.
p1435
aVIt was a face he well knew, and he trembled not alone for Ben, but for\u000ahimself.
p1436
aV_It was the face of Rudolph, the tramp._\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCHAPTER X.
p1437
aVTHE TRAMP'S UNEXPECTED DEFEAT.
p1438
aV"Has Rudolph tracked me, or is it only accident that has brought him\u000ahere?"
p1439
aVThis was the thought which naturally suggested itself to our hero, as\u000ain a very disturbed state of mind he stared at Rudolph through the\u000auncertain light.
p1440
aVHe decided that it was accident, for as yet the tramp did not appear\u000ato have discovered him.
p1441
aVHis eyes were fastened upon old Ben with\u000aunmistakable cupidity.
p1442
aVIt was the gold that attracted him, and between\u000ahim and the possession of the gold it seemed as if there were no\u000aobstacle to intervene.
p1443
aVWhat was the old man's feeble strength, more\u000afeeble still through disease, against this powerful man?
p1444
aVTony felt the difficulties of the position.
p1445
aVNot only would the gold be\u000ataken, but as soon as Rudolph discovered him, as he would, he too would\u000afall into the power of the tramp.
p1446
aVOld Ben had not yet discovered the sinister face at the window.
p1447
aVHe was\u000atoo busily occupied with his pleasant employment of counting over his\u000agold for the hundredth time, it might be, to be aware of the dangerous\u000awitness at the window.
p1448
aVBut he was speedily aroused by the noise of the window being raised\u000afrom the outside.
p1449
aVThen he turned with a startled look which quickly deepened into\u000aastonishment and dismay as he caught the lowering look fixed upon him.
p1450
aVThere was more than this.
p1451
aVThere was recognition besides.
p1452
aV"You here?"
p1453
aVhe gasped, mechanically gathering up the gold in his\u000atrembling fingers, with the intention of replacing it in the bag.
p1454
aV"Yes, Ben, it's me," answered the tramp, with a sneer.
p1455
aV"May I come in?"
p1456
aV"No, no!"
p1457
aVejaculated the old man, hastily.
p1458
aV"I think I must," returned the tramp, in the same mocking tone.
p1459
aV"I came\u000ato see you as an old friend, but I never dreamed you were so rich.
p1460
aVThat's a pretty lot of gold you have there."
p1461
aV"Rich!"
p1462
aVrepeated Ben, with his usual whine.
p1463
aV"I'm very poor."
p1464
aV"That looks like it."
p1465
aV"It's only a few dollars--enough to bury me."
p1466
aV"Very well, Ben, I'll take charge of it, and when you need burial I'll\u000aattend to it.
p1467
aVThat's fair, isn't it?"
p1468
aVRudolph, who had paused outside, now raised the window to its full\u000aheight, and despite the old man's terrified exclamations, bounded\u000alightly into the room.
p1469
aV"Help!
p1470
aVhelp!
p1471
aVthieves!"
p1472
aVscreamed Ben, almost beside himself with terror,\u000aas he spread his feeble hands over the gold which he had so imprudently\u000aexposed.
p1473
aV"Hold your jaw, you driveling old idiot," said Rudolph, harshly, "or\u000aI'll give you something to yell about."
p1474
aV"Help, Tony, help!"
p1475
aVcontinued the old man.
p1476
aVThe tramp's eyes, following the direction of Ben's, discovered our hero\u000aon his rude bed in the corner of the room.
p1477
aVA quick gleam of exultation\u000ashot from them as he made this discovery.
p1478
aV"Ho, ho!"
p1479
aVhe laughed with a mirth that boded ill to Tony, "so I've\u000afound you at last, have I?
p1480
aVYou served me a nice trick the other day,\u000adidn't you?
p1481
aVI owe you something for that."
p1482
aV"I hoped I should never set eyes on you again," said Tony.
p1483
aV"I've no doubt you did.
p1484
aVYou undertook to run away from me, did you?
p1485
aVI\u000aknew I should come across you sooner or later."
p1486
aVWhile this conversation was going on, Ben glanced from one to the other\u000ain surprise, his attention momentarily drawn away from his own troubles.
p1487
aV"Do you know this boy, Rudolph?"
p1488
aVhe inquired.
p1489
aV"I should think I did," answered the tramp, grimly.
p1490
aV"You can ask him."
p1491
aV"_Who is he?_" asked Ben, evidently excited.
p1492
aV"What is that to you?"
p1493
aVreturned Rudolph.
p1494
aV"It's a boy I picked up, and\u000ahave taken care of, and this is his gratitude to me, and I've had a\u000along chase to find him."
p1495
aV"Is this true?"
p1496
aVasked Ben, turning to Tony.
p1497
aV"Some of it is true," said our hero.
p1498
aV"I've been with him ever since\u000aI could remember, and I ran away because he wanted me to join him in\u000arobbing a house.
p1499
aVHe calls me his son sometimes, but I know he is not my\u000afather."
p1500
aV"How do you know?"
p1501
aVdemanded the tramp sternly.
p1502
aV"Didn't you say so just now?"
p1503
aV"It was none of the old man's business, and I did not care what I told\u000ahim."
p1504
aV"There's something within me tells me that there's no relationship\u000abetween us," said Tony, boldly.
p1505
aV"Is there, indeed," sneered the tramp.
p1506
aV"Is there anything within you\u000atells you you are going to get a good flogging?"
p1507
aV"No, there isn't."
p1508
aV"Then you needn't trust it, for that is just what is going to happen."
p1509
aVHe advanced toward Tony in a threatening manner, when he was diverted\u000afrom his purpose by seeing the old man hastily gathering up the gold\u000awith the intention of putting it away.
p1510
aVPunishment could wait, he\u000athought, but the gold must be secured now.
p1511
aV"Not so fast, Ben!"
p1512
aVhe said.
p1513
aV"You must lend me some of that."
p1514
aV"I can't," said Ben, hurrying all the faster.
p1515
aV"It's all I have, and I\u000aam very poor."
p1516
aV"I am poorer still, for I haven't a red to bless myself with.
p1517
aVCome, I\u000awon't take all, but some I must have."
p1518
aVHe stooped over, and began to grasp at the gold pieces, some of which\u000awere heaped up in piles upon the floor.
p1519
aVEven the weakest are capable of harm when exasperated, and Ben, feeble\u000aas he was, was gifted with supernatural strength when he saw himself\u000alikely to lose the hoards of a lifetime, and his anger rose to fever\u000aheat against the scoundrel whom he had known years before to be utterly\u000aunprincipled.
p1520
aVWith a cry like that of a wild beast he sprang upon the tramp, who, in\u000ahis crouching position, was unable to defend himself against a sudden\u000aattack.
p1521
aVRudolph fell with violence backward, striking his head with\u000agreat force against the brick hearth.
p1522
aVStrong as he was, it was too much\u000afor him, and he lay stunned and insensible, with the blood gushing from\u000aa wound in his head.
p1523
aVThe old man stood appalled at the consequence of his sudden attack.
p1524
aV"Have I killed him?
p1525
aVShall I be hanged?"
p1526
aVhe asked, with anguish.
p1527
aV"No, he's only stunned!"
p1528
aVsaid Tony, springing over the floor with all\u000ahis wits about him.
p1529
aV"We have no time to lose."
p1530
aV"To run away?
p1531
aVI can't leave my gold," said Ben.
p1532
aV"I don't mean that.
p1533
aVWe must secure him against doing us any harm when\u000ahe recovers.
p1534
aVHave you got some stout cord?"
p1535
aV"Yes, yes," said Ben, beginning to understand our hero's design.
p1536
aV"Stay,\u000aI'll get it right away."
p1537
aV"You'd better, for he may come to any minute."
p1538
aVThe old man fumbled round until in some out-of-the-way corner, where\u000ahe had laid away a store of odds and ends, he discovered a quantity of\u000astout cord.
p1539
aV"Will that do?"
p1540
aVhe asked.
p1541
aV"Just the thing," said Tony.
p1542
aVThe boy set to work with rapid hands to tie the prostrate tramp hand\u000aand foot.
p1543
aVHe was only afraid Rudolph would rouse to consciousness while\u000athe operation was going on, but the shock was too great, and he had\u000asufficient time to do the job effectually and well.
p1544
aV"How brave you are," exclaimed the old man, admiringly.
p1545
aV"I wouldn't\u000adare to touch him."
p1546
aV"Nor I if he were awake.
p1547
aVI didn't think you were so strong.
p1548
aVHe went\u000aover as if he were shot."
p1549
aV"Did he?"
p1550
aVasked the old man, bewildered.
p1551
aV"I don't know how I did it.
p1552
aVI\u000afeel as weak as a baby now."
p1553
aV"It's lucky for us you threw yourself upon him as you did.
p1554
aVA little\u000amore cord, Mr. Hayden.
p1555
aVI want to tie him securely.
p1556
aVYou'd better be\u000agathering up that gold, and putting it away before he comes to."
p1557
aV"So I will, so I will," said Ben, hastily.
p1558
aVScarcely was the money put away in its place of concealment, when the\u000atramp recovered from his fit of unconsciousness, and looked stupidly\u000aaround him.
p1559
aVThen he tried to move, and found himself hampered by his\u000abonds.
p1560
aVLooking up, he met the terrified gaze of old Ben, and the steady\u000aglance of Tony.
p1561
aVThen the real state of the case flashed upon him, and\u000ahe was filled with an overpowering rage at the audacity of his late\u000acharge, to whom he rightly attributed his present humiliating plight.
p1562
aVCHAPTER XI.
p1563
aVTHE PRISONER.
p1564
aV"Let me up!"
p1565
aVroared Rudolph, struggling vigorously with the cords that\u000abound him.
p1566
aVBen was terrified by his demonstration, and had half a mind to comply\u000awith his demand.
p1567
aVBut Tony had his wits about him, and felt that there\u000awas no safety in such a course.
p1568
aV"Don't you do it, Mr.
p1569
aVHayden!"
p1570
aVhe exclaimed, hastily.
p1571
aV"What!
p1572
aVyoung jackanapes," said the tramp, scowling fiercely.
p1573
aV"You dare\u000ato give him this advice?"
p1574
aV"Yes, I do," said Tony, boldly.
p1575
aV"He will be a fool if he releases you."
p1576
aV"If he don't I'll kill him and you too," returned Rudolph.
p1577
aV"What shall I do?"
p1578
aVadded Ben, hopelessly.
p1579
aVHe turned for advice to the boy, who was fifty years his junior.
p1580
aVStrong\u000aand resolute spirits naturally assume the place of leading at any age.
p1581
aV"Do you know what he'll do if you untie him?"
p1582
aVasked Tony.
p1583
aV"What will I do?"
p1584
aVdemanded Rudolph.
p1585
aV"You will steal this old man's money.
p1586
aVIt was what you were about to do\u000awhen you fell over backwards."
p1587
aV"He threw me over," said the tramp, now gazing resentfully at Ben.
p1588
aV"I didn't mean to," said the terrified old man.
p1589
aV"You almost stunned me."
p1590
aV"I'm very sorry," stammered Ben.
p1591
aV"If you're very sorry, untie them cords and let me up."
p1592
aV"I didn't tie you."
p1593
aV"Who did?"
p1594
aV"The--the boy."
p1595
aV"You _dared_ to do it?"
p1596
aVexclaimed Rudolph, turning upon Tony with\u000aconcentrated fury.
p1597
aV"Yes, I did," said Tony, calmly.
p1598
aV"It was the only way to keep you out\u000aof mischief."
p1599
aV"Insolent puppy; if I only had my hands free I would strangle you both."
p1600
aV"You hear what he says?"
p1601
aVsaid Tony, turning to old Ben.
p1602
aV"Are you in\u000afavor of untying him now?"
p1603
aV"No, no!"
p1604
aVexclaimed Ben, trembling.
p1605
aV"He is a dreadful man.
p1606
aVO, why did\u000ahe come here?"
p1607
aV"I came for your gold, you fool, and I'll have it yet," said Rudolph,\u000alosing sight of all considerations of prudence.
p1608
aV"What shall I do?"
p1609
aVasked the old man, wringing his hands in the excess\u000aof his terror.
p1610
aV"Let me up, and I won't hurt you," said the tramp, finding that he must\u000acontrol his anger for the present.
p1611
aV"Just now you said you would strangle the both of us, Rudolph."
p1612
aV"I'll strangle you, you cub, but I will do no harm to the old man."
p1613
aV"You will take his gold."
p1614
aV"No."
p1615
aV"Don't you trust him, Mr. Hayden," said Tony.
p1616
aV"He will promise anything\u000ato get free, but he will forget all about it when he is unbound."
p1617
aV"I'd like to choke you!"
p1618
aVmuttered Rudolph, who meant thoroughly what he\u000asaid.
p1619
aV"But what shall I do, Tony?
p1620
aVI can't have him in here all the time."
p1621
aV"I'll go and call for help to arrest him," said Tony.
p1622
aV"And leave me alone with him?"
p1623
aVasked Ben, terrified.
p1624
aV"No; we will lock the door, and you shall go and stay outside till I\u000acome back."
p1625
aVTony's proposal was distasteful to Rudolph.
p1626
aVHe had a wholesome dread\u000aof the law, and didn't fancy the prospect of an arrest, especially as\u000ahe knew that the testimony of Tony and the old man would be sufficient\u000ato insure him a prolonged term of imprisonment.
p1627
aVHe made a fresh and\u000aviolent struggle which portended danger to his captors.
p1628
aV"Come out quick," said Tony, hastily.
p1629
aV"It is not safe for you to stay\u000ahere any longer."
p1630
aVThe old man followed him nothing loth, and Tony locked the door on the\u000aoutside.
p1631
aV"Do you think he will get free?"
p1632
aVasked Ben, nervously.
p1633
aV"He may, and if he does there is no safety for either of us till he is\u000acaught again."
p1634
aV"The door is locked."
p1635
aV"But he may get out of the window."
p1636
aV"Oh, my gold!
p1637
aVmy gold!"
p1638
aVgroaned Ben.
p1639
aV"He may get it."
p1640
aV"Yes, he may; our only hope is to secure him as soon as possible."
p1641
aV"I am so weak I can't go fast.
p1642
aVI am trembling in every limb."
p1643
aV"You must conceal yourself somewhere, and let me run on," said Tony,\u000awith decision.
p1644
aV"There is no time to be lost."
p1645
aV"I don't know of any place."
p1646
aV"Here's a place.
p1647
aVYou will be safe here till I come for you."
p1648
aVTony pointed to an old ruined shed, which they had just reached.
p1649
aV"Will you be sure and come for me."
p1650
aV"Yes; don't be alarmed.
p1651
aVOnly don't show yourself till you hear my\u000avoice."
p1652
aVBen crept into the temporary shelter, glad that in his weakened\u000acondition he should not be obliged to go any farther.
p1653
aVTo be sure he\u000atormented himself with the thought that even now the desperate tramp\u000amight be robbing him of his treasures.
p1654
aVStill he had great confidence in\u000awhat Tony had told him, and hope was mingled with his terror.
p1655
aV"He's a brave boy," he murmured.
p1656
aV"I am glad he was with me, though he\u000adoes eat a sight.
p1657
aVOh, how many wicked men there are in the world."
p1658
aVTony hurried on to the village, where he lost no time in arousing\u000aa sufficient number to effect the capture of the burglar.
p1659
aVHe no\u000alonger felt any compunction in turning against his quondam guardian,\u000arecognizing him as his own enemy and the enemy of society.
p1660
aV"I owe him nothing," thought Tony.
p1661
aV"What has he ever done for me?
p1662
aVHe is\u000anot my father.
p1663
aVProbably he kidnapped me from my real home, and has made\u000ame an outcast and a tramp like himself.
p1664
aVBut I will be so no longer.
p1665
aVI\u000awill learn a trade, or do something else to earn an honest livelihood.
p1666
aVI mean to become a respectable member of society, if I can."
p1667
aVIt took him half an hour before he could rouse the half-dozen men whom\u000ahe considered necessary to effect the arrest and get them under way.
p1668
aVMeanwhile Rudolph was not idle.
p1669
aVIt may be thought strange that he should have so much difficulty in\u000afreeing himself from the cords with which Tony had bound him.
p1670
aVBut it\u000amust be remembered that the boy had done his work well.
p1671
aVThe cord was\u000astout and strong, and he had had time to tie it in many knots, so that\u000aeven if one had been untied, the tramp would have found himself almost\u000aas far from liberty as ever.
p1672
aVAfter he had been locked in, Rudolph set about energetically to obtain\u000arelease.
p1673
aVHe succeeded in raising himself to his feet, but as his ankles\u000awere tied together this did not do him much good.
p1674
aVBy main strength he\u000atried to break the cords, but the only result was to chafe his wrists.
p1675
aV"What a fool I am," he exclaimed at length.
p1676
aV"The old man must have\u000asome table-knives about somewhere.
p1677
aVWith these I can cut the cords."
p1678
aVIt was not till some time had elapsed, however, that this very obvious\u000athought came to him.
p1679
aVFurther time was consumed in finding the knives.
p1680
aVWhen found, they--there were two--proved so dull that even if he had\u000ahad free use of one of his hands it would not have been found easy to\u000amake them of service.
p1681
aVBut when added to this was the embarrassment of\u000ahis fettered hands, it will not excite surprise that it required a long\u000atime to sever the tough cords which bound him.
p1682
aVBut success came at\u000alength.
p1683
aVHis arms were free, and he stretched them with exultation.
p1684
aVHis ankles next demanded attention, but this was a much easier task.
p1685
aV"Now for revenge!"
p1686
aVthought the tramp.
p1687
aV"The boy shall rue this night's\u000atask, or my name is not Rudolph."
p1688
aVWhatever else he might do, he must secure the miser's gold.
p1689
aVHe had seen\u000athe hiding-place.
p1690
aVHe removed the plank, and there, beneath him, visible in the moonlight,\u000alay the much-coveted bags of golden treasure.
p1691
aVHe rose from the floor, and, with the bags in his hand, jumped out of\u000athe still opened window.
p1692
aVBut he was too late.
p1693
aVTwo strong men seized him, each by an arm, and\u000asaid, sternly:\u000a\u000a"You are our prisoner."
p1694
aV[Illustration: Tony set to work with rapid hands to tie the prostrate\u000atramp hand and foot.--(See page 73.)]
p1695
aVCHAPTER XII.
p1696
aVTONY STARTS OUT ONCE MORE.
p1697
aVIt was not until after Rudolph's seizure that Ben, who had followed the\u000aextemporized police, discovered the bags of gold in the hands of the\u000atramp.
p1698
aV"Give me my money!"
p1699
aVhe shrieked, in excitement and anguish.
p1700
aV"Don't let\u000ahim carry it off."
p1701
aV"It's safe, Ben," said one of the captors.
p1702
aV"But who would have supposed\u000ayou had so much money?"
p1703
aV"It isn't much," faltered the old man.
p1704
aV"The bags are pretty heavy," was the significant rejoinder.
p1705
aV"Will you\u000atake two hundred dollars apiece for them?"
p1706
aV"No," said the old man, embarrassed.
p1707
aV"Then it seems there is considerable after all.
p1708
aVBut never mind.
p1709
aVTake\u000athem, and take better care of them hereafter."
p1710
aVBen advanced with as much alacrity as he could summon in his weakness,\u000aand stooped to pick up the bags.
p1711
aVHe had got hold of them when the\u000atramp, whose feet were unconfined, aimed a kick at him which completely\u000aupset him.
p1712
aVEven though he fell, however, he did not lose his grip of the bags, but\u000aclung to them while crying with pain.
p1713
aV"Take that, you old fool!"
p1714
aVmuttered the tramp.
p1715
aV"It's the first\u000ainstalment of the debt I owe you."
p1716
aV"Take him away, take him away!
p1717
aVHe will murder me!"
p1718
aVexclaimed old Ben,\u000ain terror.
p1719
aV"Come along.
p1720
aVYou've done mischief enough," said his captors, sternly,\u000aforcing the tramp along.
p1721
aV"I'll do more yet," muttered Rudolph.
p1722
aVHe turned to Tony, who stood at a little distance watching the fate of\u000ahis quondam companion.
p1723
aV"I've got a score to settle with you, young traitor.
p1724
aVThe day will come\u000afor that yet."
p1725
aV"I'm sorry for you, Rudolph," said Tony; "but you brought it on\u000ayourself."
p1726
aV"Bah!
p1727
aVyou hypocrite!"
p1728
aVretorted the tramp.
p1729
aV"I don't want any of your\u000asorrow.
p1730
aVIt won't save you when the day of reckoning comes."
p1731
aVHe was not allowed to say more, but was hurried away to the village\u000alockup for detention until he could be conveyed to more permanent\u000aquarters.
p1732
aVDoctor Compton was among the party who had been summoned by Tony.
p1733
aVHe\u000alingered behind, and took Ben apart.
p1734
aV"Mr. Hayden," he said, "I want to give you a piece of advice."
p1735
aV"What is it?"
p1736
aVasked the old man.
p1737
aV"Don't keep this gold in your house.
p1738
aVIt isn't safe."
p1739
aV"Who do you think will take it?"
p1740
aVasked Ben, with a scared look.
p1741
aV"None of those here this morning, unless this tramp should escape from\u000acustody."
p1742
aV"Do you think he will?"
p1743
aVasked the old man, in terror.
p1744
aV"I think not; but he may."
p1745
aV"If he don't, what danger is there?"
p1746
aV"It will get about that you have money secreted here, and I venture to\u000asay it will be stolen before three months are over."
p1747
aV"It will kill me," said Ben, piteously.
p1748
aV"Then put it out of reach of danger."
p1749
aV"Where?"
p1750
aV"I am going over to the county town, where there is a bank.
p1751
aVDeposit it\u000athere, and whenever you want any, go and get it."
p1752
aV"But banks break sometimes," said Ben, in alarm.
p1753
aV"This is an old, established institution.
p1754
aVYou need not be afraid of it.
p1755
aVEven if there is some danger, there is far less than here."
p1756
aV"But I can't see the money--I can't count it," objected Ben.
p1757
aV"You can see the deposit record in a book.
p1758
aVEven if that doesn't suit\u000ayou as well, you can sleep comfortably, knowing that you are not liable\u000ato be attacked and murdered by burglars."
p1759
