aVHe\u000aenrolled himself on the register as "Obadiah Latham, Philadelphia."
p2825
aVThis, he thought, would answer very well for a Quaker name, much\u000abetter, certainly, than Rudolph Rugg, which on other accounts also was\u000aobjectionable.
p2826
aV"Can thee give me a room, friend?"
p2827
aVhe inquired at the desk.
p2828
aV"Certainly, sir," was the polite reply.
p2829
aV"Here, Henry, show this old\u000agentleman up to No.
p2830
aV6.
p2831
aVNo.
p2832
aV6 is one of our best rooms, Mr.
p2833
aVLatham."
p2834
aV"I thank thee," said the tramp, who, by this time, was quite accustomed\u000ato the peculiar phraseology of the Friends.
p2835
aV"The Quakers are always polite," said the bookkeeper.
p2836
aV"They are good\u000apay, too, and never give any trouble.
