aV"Boys," he asked, "did thee mention the name of Tony Rugg?"
p2873
aV"Yes, sir."
p2874
aV"Does thee know such a boy?"
p2875
aV"Yes, sir.
p2876
aVHe is working at the hotel.
p2877
aVHe got my place away from me,"\u000asaid Sam.
p2878
aV"Do you know him?"
p2879
aV"I once knew such a boy.
p2880
aVBut no!
p2881
aVhis name was Charles."
p2882
aV"Perhaps he's a relation."
p2883
aV"Perhaps thee are right."
p2884
aVThis the tramp said cunningly, not wishing Tony to hear that he had\u000abeen inquiring after him.
p2885
aVCHAPTER XXII.
p2886
aVRUDOLPH FINDS TONY.
p2887
aVRudolph was very much elated at what he had heard.
p2888
aVHis object then was\u000aalready attained, and the boy was found.
p2889
aV"Well, good luck has come to me at last," he said to himself.
p2890
aV"The\u000ayoung scoundrel is found, and now I must consider how to get him into\u000amy hands once more."
p2891
aVThe Quaker, to designate him according to his present appearance, at\u000aonce made his way back to the hotel.
p2892
aVHe wanted to see Tony and verify\u000athe information he had obtained from the boys, though he saw no reason\u000ato doubt it.
p2893
aV"There can't be two Tony Ruggs in the world," he said to himself.
p2894
aV"I am\u000asure this is the boy."
p2895
aVOn reaching the hotel he sauntered out into the stable-yard in the rear\u000aof the house.
p2896
aVHis eyes lighted with pleasure, for he at once caught\u000asight of Tony, standing beside James, the hostler.
p2897
aV"There comes old Broadbrim," said James in a low voice.
p2898
aV"The barkeeper\u000atold me he took two stiff horns of brandy.
p2899
aVHe's a queer sort of Quaker\u000ain my opinion."
p2900
aVTony gave a curious glance at the disguised tramp, but entertained no\u000asuspicion of his not being what he represented.
p2901
aVThe white hair and\u000acostume made it difficult to doubt.
p2902
aV"I never saw a Quaker before," he said.
p2903
aV"Didn't you?"
p2904
aVMeantime Rudolph came nearer.
p2905
aVHis disguise had been so successful that\u000ahe felt perfectly safe from discovery.
p2906
aV"Does thee keep many horses?"
p2907
aVhe asked.
p2908
aV"Yes, sir; we have twelve."
p2909
aV"That is a large number.
p2910
aVYea, verily, it is," said the tramp.
p2911
aV"Well, it is, but we need them all.
p2912
aVThere's a good deal of carting to\u000ado for the hotel, besides Mr. Porter keeps a livery stable.
p2913
aVWas you\u000aever this way before?"
p2914
aVasked James, thinking he might as well ask a few\u000aquestions also.
p2915
aV"Nay, verily."
p2916
aV"Where might you be from?"
p2917
aV"From Philadelphia."
p2918
aV"I've heard there's a good many Quakers out that way."
p2919
aV"Yea, verily, my friend, thee is right."
p2920
aV"Are you going away to-morrow morning?"
p2921
aV"Nay, friend, I think I shall tarry a day or two.
p2922
aVIs that lad thy son?"
p2923
aV"Tony, he asks if you are my son," said James, laughing.
p2924
aV"No, his name\u000ais Tony Rugg, while mine is James Woodley."
p2925
aV"Anthony, was thee born in this town?"
p2926
aVasked the tramp, boldly defying\u000adetection.
p2927
aV"No, sir," answered Tony.
p2928
aV"I only came here a few weeks ago."
p2929
aV"Yea, verily," was the only comment Rudolph made.
p2930
aV"I'd like to choke the boy.
p2931
aVI can hardly keep my hands off him," he\u000asaid to himself.
p2932
aV"But I'd better be going.
p2933
aVHe is looking at me closely.
p2934
aVHe might suspect something."
p2935
aV"Good-night," he said, and the two responded civilly to the salutation.
p2936
aV"Well, Tony, what do you think of Broadbrim?"
p2937
aVasked James.
p2938
aV"I don't know, there's something in his voice that sounds familiar to\u000ame."
p2939
aV"Perhaps you may have met him somewhere before," suggested the hostler.
p2940
aV"No, I am sure I have not.
p2941
aVI never met any Quaker before."
p2942
aV"Well, there's strange likenesses sometimes.
p2943
aVDid I ever tell you my\u000aadventure out in Maine?"
p2944
aV"No, what was it?"
p2945
aV"I went down East to see a sister of mine that is married down near\u000aAugusta.
p2946
aVWhen, as I was goin' through Portland, a woman came up and\u000amade a great ado about my deserting her.
p2947
aVShe took me for her husband,\u000aand came near having me arrested for desertion.
p2948
aVYou see I and her\u000ahusband was as like as two peas, that's what some of her neighbors\u000asaid."
p2949
aV"How did you get off?"
p2950
aV"Luckily I had documents in my pocket showing who I was.
