aVBesides, my\u000abrother-in-law happened to be in the city, and he identified me."
p2952
aVRudolph sat in the public room of the hotel for a time, and then\u000ahe went up to his room, partly to be out of the way of possible\u000arecognition, partly to think how he could manage to get Tony into\u000ahis clutches once more, without betraying himself, or exciting any\u000ainterference.
p2953
aVHe had a back room, the window of which looked out upon the\u000astable-yard.
p2954
aVHe seated himself at this window, and in this position\u000acould easily see and hear all that passed there.
p2955
aVTony and the hostler were lounging about, the latter smoking a clay\u000apipe, their work being done for the day.
p2956
aV"Tony," said the hostler, "I almost forgot to tell you, you're to go to\u000aThornton to-morrow."
p2957
aV"What for?"
p2958
aV"There's a top-buggy Mr. Porter has sold to a man there.
p2959
aVYou're to take\u000ait over, and lead the horse back."
p2960
aV"How far is it?"
p2961
aV"About five miles."
p2962
aV"All right.
p2963
aVI'd just as leave go as stay here.
p2964
aVCan I find the road\u000aeasily?"
p2965
aV"There's no trouble about that.
p2966
aVIt's straight all the way.
p2967
aVPart of it\u000aruns through the woods--about a mile, I should say."
p2968
aV"Did Mr. Porter say when he wanted me to start?"
p2969
aV"About nine o'clock; by that time you'll be through your chores."
p2970
aV"Well, I'm willing."
p2971
aVRudolph heard this conversation with no little pleasure.
p2972
aV"It's the very chance I was waiting for," he said to himself.
p2973
aV"I'll lie\u000ain wait for him as he comes back.
p2974
aVI can easily hide in the woods."
p2975
aVCHAPTER XXIII.
p2976
aVTHE NEGLECTED WELL.
p2977
aVRudolph took care to breakfast in good season the next morning.
p2978
aVHe felt\u000athat this day was to make his fortune.
p2979
aVThe deed which would entitle him\u000ato a life support was to be perpetrated on that day.
p2980
aVHe shuddered a\u000alittle when he reflected that in order to compass this a life must be\u000asacrificed, and that the life of the boy who had been for years under\u000ahis guardianship, who had slept at his side, and borne with him the\u000aperils and privations of his adventurous career.
p2981
aVHe was a reckless man,\u000abut he had never before shed blood, or at any rate taken the life of a\u000ahuman being.
p2982
aVHe would have been less than human if the near approach of\u000asuch a crime had not made him nervous and uncomfortable.
p2983
aVBut against this feeling he fought strenuously.
p2984
aV"What's the odds?"
p2985
aVhe said to himself.
p2986
aV"The boy's got to die some time\u000aor other, and his dying now will make me comfortable for life.
p2987
aVNo\u000amore hungry tramps for me.
p2988
aVI'll settle down and be respectable.
p2989
aVEight\u000ahundred dollars a year will relieve me from all care, and I shall only\u000aneed to enjoy myself after this."
p2990
aVRudolph must have had strange notions of respectability to think it\u000acould be obtained by crime; but in fact his idea was that a man who\u000acould live on his own means was from that very power respectable, and\u000athere are plenty of persons of a higher social grade who share in this\u000adelusion.
p2991
aVAt a few minutes after nine Tony set out on his journey.
p2992
aVIt never\u000aoccurred to him that the old Quaker in suit of sober drab, who sat on\u000athe piazza and saw him depart, was a man who cherished sinister designs\u000aupon him.
p2993
aVIn fact, he had forgotten all about him, and was intent upon\u000ahis journey alone.
p2994
aVMost boys like to drive, and our friend Tony was no\u000aexception to this general rule.
p2995
aVHe thought it much better than working\u000aabout the stable-yard.
p2996
aV"Take care of yourself, Tony," said James, the hostler, in a friendly\u000atone.
p2997
aV"Oh, yes, I'll do that," said Tony, little dreaming how necessary the\u000aadmonition was likely to prove.
p2998
aV"I may as well be starting too," thought Rudolph, and some ten minutes\u000aafterward he started at a walk along the road which led to Thornton.
p2999
aV"I'll keep on as far as the woods," he thought, "and then I'll form\u000amy plans.
p3000
aVThe boy must not escape me, for I may never have as good a\u000achance to dispose of him again."
p3001
aVAbout two miles on began the woods to which reference has already been\u000amade.
p3002
aVThe tramp selected this as probably the best part of the road to\u000aaccomplish his criminal design.
p3003
aVThey extended for nearly a mile on either side of the road, and this\u000awas likely to facilitate his purpose.
p3004
aV"I'll explore a little," thought Rudolph.
p3005
aV"I shall have plenty of time\u000abefore the boy comes back."
p3006
aVSome forty rods from the road on the right hand side, the tramp\u000adiscovered a ruined hut, which had once belonged to a recluse who had\u000afor years lived apart from his kind.
p3007
aVThis had now fallen into decay,\u000afor the former occupant had been for some time dead, and no one had\u000abeen tempted to succeed him.
p3008
aVThe general appearance of the building satisfied Rudolph that it was\u000adeserted.
p3009
aVImpelled partly by curiosity, he explored the neighborhood of\u000athe house.
p3010
aVA rod to the east there was a well, open to the view, the curb having\u000adecayed, and being in a ruined condition, Rudolph looked down into it,\u000aand judged that it might be about twenty feet deep.
p3011
aVA diabolical suggestion came to him.
p3012
aVIf he could only lure Tony to this\u000awell and dispose of him forever.
p3013
aV"I'll do it," he muttered to himself, and started to return to the\u000aroad, where he hoped to intercept our hero.
p3014
aVPoor Tony!
p3015
aVhe little dreamed of the danger that menaced him.
p3016
aVCHAPTER XXIV.
p3017
aVTHE DEED IS DONE.
p3018
aVTony drove rapidly to Thornton and sought the purchaser of the buggy.
p3019
aVThere was a delay of half an hour in finding him, but at last his\u000abusiness was done, and he set out for home.
p3020
aVIt was not quite so amusing leading the horse as sitting in a buggy and\u000adriving him.
p3021
aVBut all our pleasures have to be paid for, and Tony was\u000aready to pay the price of this one.
p3022
aVAfter all, he reflected, it was\u000aquite as amusing as working about the stable yard, especially after it\u000aoccurred to him to mount the animal and thus spare himself fatigue.
p3023
aVEverything went smoothly till he entered the woody part of the road.
p3024
aV"Now I shall be home soon," he said to himself.
p3025
aV"But, hallo!
p3026
aVwho's\u000athat?"
p3027
aVas a figure stepped out from the side of the road.
p3028
aV"Oh, it's the\u000aQuaker.
p3029
aVI wonder what brought him here?"
p3030
aV"Friend, is thee in a hurry?"
p3031
aVasked the impostor.
p3032
aV"I suppose I ought to get back as soon as I can," said Tony.
p3033
aV"Why,\u000awhat's up?"
p3034
aV"Thee is the boy from the hotel, is thee not?"
p3035
aVasked Rudolph.
p3036
aV"Yes.
p3037
aVYou're the Quaker gentleman that is stopping there?"
p3038
aV"Yes."
p3039
aV"Well, what do you want of me?"
p3040
aV"There's a man in the woods that has fallen down a well, and I fear he\u000ais badly hurt."
p3041
aV"A man fallen down a well!"
p3042
aVexclaimed Tony.
p3043
aV"Yes."
p3044
aV"Where is the well?"
p3045
aV"Back in the woods."
p3046
aV"How did you find him?"
p3047
aV"I was walking for amusement when I heard groans, and looking down I\u000acould see the poor man."
p3048
aVTony never thought of doubting this statement, and said, in a tone of\u000agenuine sympathy: "Poor fellow!"
p3049
aV"Will thee go with me and help get him out?"
p3050
aVasked the Quaker.
p3051
aV"Yes," said Tony, readily, "I'll do it.
p3052
aVNever mind if I am a little\u000alate.
p3053
aVWhere shall I put the horse?"
p3054
aV"Lead him into the woods and tie him to a tree."
p3055
aV"All right.
p3056
aVI guess that'll be the best way."
p3057
aVThe horse was disposed of as had been suggested, and the two set forth\u000aon what Tony supposed to be their charitable errand.
p3058
aV"I don't see what made you go into the woods?"
p3059
aVsaid our hero, a little\u000apuzzled.
p3060
aV"I was brought up in the woods, my young friend.
p3061
aVIt reminds me of the\u000atime when I was a boy like thee."
p3062
aV"Oh, that's it.
p3063
aVWell, it was lucky for the man, that is if we can get\u000ahim out.
p3064
aVDid you speak to him?"
p3065
aV"Yes, verily."
p3066
aV"And did he answer?"
p3067
aV"He groaned.
p3068
aVI think he was insensible.
p3069
aVI saw that I should need help,\u000aand I came to the road again.
p3070
aVLuckily thee came by."
p3071
aV"Had you been waiting long?"
p3072
aV"Only five minutes," answered Rudolph.
p3073
aVIn reality he had been compelled to wait near an hour, much to his\u000adisgust.
p3074
aVIn fact, he had been led to fear that there might be some\u000aother road by which one could return from Thornton, and that Tony had\u000ataken it.
p3075
aVShould this be the case, his elaborate trap would be useless.
p3076
aVThey had come quite near the ruined dwelling, and already the curb of\u000athe well was visible.
p3077
aV"Is that the well?"
p3078
aVasked Tony.
p3079
aV"Yes," answered the Quaker.
p3080
aV"Let us hurry, then," said Tony.
p3081
aVBut the time had come when Tony was to have revealed to him the real\u000acharacter of his companion.
p3082
aVA branch, which hung unusually low, knocked\u000aoff the hat and wig of the pseudo Quaker, and Tony was petrified with\u000adismay when he saw revealed the black, cropped head and sinister face\u000aof Rudolph, the tramp.
p3083
aV"Rudolph!"
p3084
aVhe exclaimed, stopping short in his amazement.
p3085
aV"Yes," said the tramp, avowing himself, now that he saw disguise was\u000auseless; "it's Rudolph.
p3086
aVAt last I have you, you young scamp!"
p3087
aVand he\u000aseized the boy's arm as in the grip of a vise.
p3088
aVTony tried to shake off the grip, but what could a boy do against an\u000aathletic man.
p3089
aV"It's no use," said the tramp, between his teeth, "I've got you, and I\u000adon't mean to let you go."
p3090
aV"What do you mean to do, Rudolph?"
p3091
aVasked Tony, uneasily.
p3092
aV"What do I mean to do?
p3093
aVI mean to make you repent of what you've done to\u000ame, you young whelp."
p3094
aV"What have I done?"
p3095
aV"What haven't you done?
p3096
aVYou've betrayed me, and sold me to my enemies.
p3097
aVThat's what you've done."
p3098
aV"I've only done what I was obliged to do.
p3099
aVI don't want to do you any\u000amore harm.
p3100
aVLet me go, and I won't meddle with you any more, nor say a\u000aword about you at the hotel."
p3101
aV"Really," said Rudolph, with a disagreeable sneer, "I feel very much\u000aobliged to you.
p3102
aVYou are very kind, upon my soul.
