aV"You are not related to me."
p3128
aV"I felt sure of it."
p3129
aV"Oh, you did!"
p3130
aVsneered the tramp.
p3131
aV"You are glad that you are not my\u000ason!"
p3132
aV"Who am I?"
p3133
aV"I will tell you this much, that you are the heir to a fortune."
p3134
aV"I the heir to a fortune!"
p3135
aVexclaimed Tony, in natural excitement.
p3136
aV"Yes; and I could help you to secure it if I pleased."
p3137
aVTony knew not what to say or to think.
p3138
aVWas it possible that he--Tony,\u000athe tramp--was a gentleman's son, and heir to a fortune?
p3139
aVIt was almost\u000aincredible.
p3140
aVMoreover, what was the object of Rudolph in imparting this\u000asecret, and at this time, when he sought revenge upon him.
p3141
aV"Is this true?"
p3142
aVhe asked.
p3143
aV"Perfectly true."
p3144
aV"And you know my real name and family?"
p3145
aV"Yes, I do."
p3146
aV"Oh, Rudolph, tell me who I am," Tony said, imploringly.
p3147
aV"Help me to\u000athe fortune which you say I am entitled to, and I will take care that\u000ayou are rewarded."
p3148
aVRudolph surveyed the boy, whom he still held in his firm grasp, and\u000awatched his excitement with malicious satisfaction.
p3149
aV"There is one objection to my doing that, boy," he said.
p3150
aV"What is that?"
p3151
aV"I'll tell you," he hissed, as his grasp grew tighter, and his dark\u000aface grew darker yet with passion, "_I hate you!_"\u000a\u000aThis he uttered with such intensity that Tony, brave as he was, was\u000astartled and dismayed.
p3152
aV"Then why did you tell me?"
p3153
aVhe asked.
