aV"That you might know what you are going to lose--that you might repent\u000abetraying me," answered Rudolph, rapidly.
p3155
aV"You ask me what I am going\u000ato do with you?
p3156
aVI am going to throw you down that well, and leave you\u000athere--to die!"
p3157
aVThen commenced a struggle between the man and boy.
p3158
aVTony knew what he\u000ahad to expect, and he fought for dear life.
p3159
aVRudolph found that he had\u000aundertaken no light task, but he, too, was desperate.
p3160
aVHe succeeded at\u000alast in dragging Tony to the well-curb, and, raising him in his sinewy\u000aarms, he let him fall.
p3161
aVThen, without waiting to look down, he hurried out of the wood with all\u000aspeed.
p3162
aVHe reached the hotel, settled his bill, and paid to have himself\u000acarried over to the nearest railroad station.
p3163
aVNot until he was fairly seated in the cars, and was rushing through\u000athe country at the rate of thirty miles an hour, did he pause to\u000acongratulate himself.
p3164
aV"Now for an easy life!"
p3165
aVhe ejaculated.
p3166
aV"My fortune is made!
p3167
aVI shall\u000anever have to work any more."
p3168
aVCHAPTER XXV.
p3169
aV"I HOLD YOU TO THE BOND."
p3170
aVOn reaching New York, Rudolph made his way at once to the shop from\u000awhich he had obtained his Quaker dress.
p3171
aV"Has thee come back?"
p3172
aVasked the old man, in a jocular tone.
p3173
aV"Yea, verily," answered Rudolph.
p3174
aV"How do you like being a Quaker?"
p3175
aV"I've had enough of it.
p3176
aVI want you to take them back.
p3177
aVYou promised to\u000areturn me twenty-five dollars."
p3178
aV"Let me look at them," said the old man, cautiously.
p3179
aV"They've seen hard usage," he said.
p3180
aV"Look at that rip, and that spot."
p3181
aV"Humbug!"
p3182
aVanswered Rudolph.
p3183
aV"There's nothing but what you can set\u000astraight in half an hour, and five dollars is handsome pay for that."
p3184
aVBut the old man stood out for seven, and finally the tramp, though\u000agrumbling much, was obliged to come to his terms.
p3185
aV"Where have you been?"
p3186
aVasked the old man, whose curiosity was aroused\u000aas to what prompted Rudolph to obtain the disguise.
p3187
aV"That's my business," said Rudolph, who had his reasons for secrecy, as\u000awe know.
p3188
aV"I meant no offense--I only wondered if you left the city."
p3189
aV"Yes, I've been into New Jersey," answered the tramp, who thought it\u000apolitic to put the customer on the wrong scent.
p3190
aV"You see I've got an\u000aold uncle--a Quaker--living there.
p3191
aVThe old man's got plenty of money,\u000aand I thought if I could only make him think me a good Quaker, I should\u000astand a good chance of being remembered in his will."
p3192
aV"I see--a capital idea.
p3193
aVDid it work?"
p3194
aV"I can't tell yet.
p3195
aVHe gave me four dollars and his blessing for the\u000apresent," said Rudolph, carelessly.
p3196
aV"That's a lie every word of it," said the old man to himself, after\u000athe tramp went out.
p3197
aV"You must try to fix up a more probable story next\u000atime, Mr. Rudolph.
p3198
aVHe's been up to some mischief, probably.
p3199
aVHowever,\u000ait's none of my business, I've made seven dollars out of him, and that\u000apays me well--yes, it pays me well."
p3200
aVWhen Rudolph left the costumer's, it occurred to him that the tramp's\u000adress which he had resumed had better be changed, partly because he\u000athought it probable that a journey lay before him.
p3201
aVHe sought out a\u000alarge ready-made clothing establishment on Fulton street, and with the\u000amoney which had been returned to him obtained a respectable-looking\u000asuit, which quite improved his appearance.
p3202
aVHe regarded his reflection\u000ain a long mirror with considerable satisfaction.
p3203
aVHe felt that he would\u000anow be taken for a respectable citizen, and that in discarding his old\u000adress he had removed all vestiges of the tramp.
p3204
aVIn this, however, he\u000awas not wholly right.
p3205
aVHis face and general expression he could not\u000achange.
p3206
aVA careful observer could read in them something of the life he\u000ahad lead.
p3207
aVStill he was changed for the better, and it pleased him.
p3208
aV"Now," he reflected, "I had better go and see Mrs. Harvey Middleton.
p3209
aVI\u000ahave done the work, and I shall claim the reward."
p3210
aVHe hurried to the St. Nicholas, and, experienced now in the ways of\u000aobtaining access to a guest, he wrote his name on a card and sent it up.
p3211
aV"The lady will see you," was the answer brought back by the servant.
p3212
aV"Of course she will," thought Rudolph.
p3213
aV"She'll want to know whether\u000ait's all settled, and she has no further cause for fear."
p3214
aVMrs. Middleton looked up as he entered.
p3215
aV"Sit down, Mr. Rugg," she said, politely.
p3216
aVHer manner was cool and composed; but when the servant had left the\u000aroom, she rose from her chair, and in a tone which showed the anxiety\u000awhich she had till then repressed, she asked, abruptly: "Well, Mr.\u000aRugg, have you any news for me?"
p3217
aV"Yes, ma'am, I have," he answered, deliberately.
p3218
aV"What is it?
p3219
aVDon't keep me in suspense," she said, impatiently.
p3220
aV"The job's done," said Rudolph briefly.
p3221
aV"You mean that the boy--"\u000a\u000a"Accidentally fell down a well, and was killed," said the visitor,\u000afinishing the sentence.
p3222
aV"Horrible!"
p3223
aVmurmured the lady.
p3224
aV"Wasn't it?"
p3225
aVsaid Rudolph, with a grin.
p3226
aV"He must have been very\u000acareless."
p3227
aVMrs. Middleton did not immediately speak.
p3228
aVThough she was responsible\u000afor this crime, having instigated it, she was really shocked when it\u000awas brought home to her.
p3229
aV"You are sure he is dead?"
p3230
aVshe said, after a pause.
p3231
aV"When a chap pitches head-first down a well thirty feet deep, there\u000aisn't much hope for him, is there?"
p3232
aV"No, I suppose not.
p3233
aVWhere did this accident happen?"
p3234
aVasked the lady.
p3235
aV"That ain't important," answered Rudolph.
p3236
aV"It's happened--that's all\u000ayou need to know.
p3237
aVTony won't never come after that estate of his."
p3238
aV"It would have done him little good.
p3239
aVHe was not fitted by education to\u000aassume it."
p3240
aV"No; but he might have been educated.
p3241
aVBut that's all over now.
p3242
aVIt's\u000ayours.
p3243
aVNobody can take it from you."
p3244
aV"True!"
p3245
aVsaid Mrs. Middleton, and a look of pleasure succeeded the\u000amomentary horror.
p3246
aV"You will be ready to testify that the boy is dead?"
p3247
aV"There won't be any danger, will there?
p3248
aVThey won't ask too many\u000aquestions?"
p3249
aV"As to that, I think we had better decide what we will say.
p3250
aVIt won't be\u000anecessary to say how the boy died."
p3251
aV"Won't it?"
p3252
aV"No.
p3253
aVIndeed, it will be better to give a different account."
p3254
aV"Will that do just as well?"
p3255
aV"Yes.
p3256
aVYou can say, for instance, that he died of small-pox while under\u000ayour care in St. Louis, or any other place."
p3257
aV"And that I tended him to the last with the affection of a father,"\u000aadded Rudolph, grinning.
p3258
aV"To be sure.
p3259
aVYou must settle upon all the details of the story, so as\u000anot to be caught in any discrepancies."
p3260
aV"What's that?"
p3261
aVasked the tramp, rather mystified.
p3262
aV"Your story must hang together.
p3263
aVIt mustn't contradict itself."
p3264
aV"To be sure.
p3265
aVHow long are you going to stay in New York?"
p3266
aV"There is no further occasion for my staying here.
p3267
aVI shall sail to\u000aEngland in a week."
p3268
aV"Will it be all right about the money?"
p3269
aVasked Rudolph, anxiously.
p3270
aV"Certainly."
p3271
aV"How am I to be sure of that?"
p3272
aV"The word of a lady, sir," said Mrs. Middleton, haughtily, "ought to be\u000asufficient for you."
p3273
aV"That's all very well, but suppose you should get tired of paying me\u000athe money?"
p3274
aV"Then you could make it very disagreeable for me by telling all you\u000aknow about the boy.
p3275
aVHowever, there will be no occasion for that.
p3276
aVI\u000ashall keep my promise.
p3277
aVWill you be willing to sail for England next\u000aweek."
p3278
aV"Do you mean that I am to go with you?"
p3279
aV"I mean that you are to go.
p3280
aVYour testimony must be given on the other\u000aside, in order to make clear my title to the estate."
p3281
aV"I see, ma'am.
p3282
aVIf I'd known that I wouldn't have had no fears about the\u000amoney."
p3283
aV"You need have none, Mr. Rugg," said Mrs. Middleton, coldly.
p3284
aV"The fact\u000ais, we are necessary to each other.
p3285
aVEach can promote the interests of\u000athe other."
p3286
aV"That's so, ma'am.
p3287
aVLet's shake hands on that," said Rudolph, advancing\u000awith outstretched hand.
p3288
aV"No, thank you," said Mrs. Middleton, coldly.
p3289
aV"You forget yourself,\u000asir.
p3290
aVDo not forget that I am a lady, and that you are--"\u000a\u000a"We are equal, ma'am in this matter," said Rudolph, offended.
p3291
aV"You\u000aneedn't shrink from shaking hands with me."
p3292
aV"That is not in the agreement," said Mrs. Middleton, haughtily.
p3293
aV"I\u000ashall do what I have agreed, but except so far as it is necessary in\u000athe way of business, I wish you to keep yourself away from me.
p3294
aVWe\u000abelong to different grades in society."
p3295
aV"Why didn't you say that the other day, ma'am?"
p3296
aVsaid Rudolph, frowning.
p3297
aV"Because I didn't suppose it to be necessary.
p3298
aVYou did not offer to\u000ashake hands with me then.
p3299
aVBesides, at that time you had not--"\u000a\u000a"Pushed the boy down the well, if that's what you mean," said Rudolph,\u000abluntly.
p3300
aV"Hush!
p3301
aVdon't refer to that.
p3302
aVI advise you this for your own sake."
p3303
aV"And for the sake of somebody else."
p3304
aV"Mr. Rugg, all this discussion is idle.
p3305
aVIt can do no good.
p3306
aVFor whatever\u000aservice you have rendered, you shall be well paid.
p3307
aVThat you understand.
p3308
aVBut it is best that we should know as little of each other henceforth\u000aas possible.
p3309
aVIt might excite suspicion, as you can understand."
p3310
aV"Perhaps you are right, ma'am," said Rudolph, slowly.
p3311
aV"Call here day after to-morrow, and I will let you know by what\u000asteamer I take passage for England, that you may obtain a ticket.
p3312
aVGood\u000aafternoon."
p3313
aVRudolph left the lady's presence not wholly pleased.
p3314
aV"Why wouldn't she shake my hand?"
p3315
aVhe muttered to himself.
p3316
aV"She's as\u000adeep in it as I am."
p3317
aVCHAPTER XXVI.
p3318
aVTONY'S ESCAPE.
p3319
aVWe must now return to our young hero, who was certainly in a critical\u000aposition.
p3320
aVThough strong of his age, the reader will hardly be surprised\u000athat he should have been overpowered by a man like Rudolph.
p3321
aVWhen the false Quaker's hat and wig were taken off, though he was at\u000afirst surprised, he for the first time understood why the man's face\u000aand voice had seemed familiar to him from the time they first met.
p3322
aVHe struggled in vain against the fate in store for him.
p3323
aVHe felt that\u000awith him it was to be a matter of life and death, and taken by surprise\u000athough he was, he was on the alert to save his life if he could.
p3324
aVThe well curb was partially destroyed, as we have said, but the rope\u000astill hung from it.
p3325
aVAt the instant of his fall, Tony managed while in\u000atransit to grasp the rope by one hand.
p3326
aVHe swung violently from one side\u000ato the other, and slipped a few feet downward.
p3327
aVThis Rudolph did not\u000asee, for as soon as he had hurled the boy into the well he hurried away.
p3328
aVTony waited for the rope to become steady before attempting to ascend\u000ahand over hand.
p3329
aVUnfortunately for his purpose the rope was rotten, and\u000abroke just above where he grasped it, precipitating him to the bottom\u000aof the well.
p3330
aVBut he was already so far from the opening that his fall\u000awas not over ten feet.
p3331
aVLuckily also the water was not over two feet\u000ain depth.
p3332
aVTherefore, though he was jarred and startled by the sudden\u000adescent, he was not injured.
p3333
aV"Well," thought Tony, "I'm as low as I can get--that's one comfort.
p3334
aVNow\u000ais there any chance of my getting out?"
p3335
aVHe looked up, and it gave him a peculiar sensation to look up at the\u000ablue sky from the place where he stood.
p3336
aVHe feared that Rudolph was\u000astill at hand and would resist any efforts he might make to get out of\u000athe well.
p3337
aV"If he don't interfere I'm bound to get out," he said to himself,\u000apluckily.
p3338
aVHis feet were wet, of course, and this was far from comfortable.
p3339
aVHe made a brief examination of the situation, and then decided upon his\u000aplan.
p3340
aVThe well, like most in the country, was provided by a wall of\u000astones, piled one upon another.
p3341
aVIn parts it looked rather loose, and\u000aTony shuddered as he thought of the possibility of the walls falling,\u000aand his being buried in the ruins.
p3342
aV"It would be all up with me, then," he thought, "I must get out of\u000athis as soon as I can.
p3343
aVIf I can only climb up as far as the rope I can\u000aescape."
p3344
aVThis, in fact, seemed to be his only chance.
p3345
aVUsing the wall as a\u000aladder, he began cautiously to ascend.
p3346
aVMore than once he came near\u000afalling a second time, but by greatest exertion he finally reached the\u000arope.
p3347
aVHe did not dare to trust to it entirely, but contrived to ascend\u000aas before, clinging to the rope with his hands.
p3348
aVHe was in constant fear\u000athat it would break a second time, but the strain upon it was not so\u000agreat, and finally, much to his delight, he reached the top.
p3349
aVHe breathed a deep sigh of relief when he found himself once more on\u000a_terra firma_.
p3350
aVHe looked about him cautiously, under the apprehension\u000athat Rudolph might be near by, and ready to attack him again.
p3351
aVBut, as\u000awe know, his fears were groundless.
p3352
aV"He made sure that I was disposed of," thought Tony.
p3353
aV"What could have\u000ainduced him to attempt my life?
p3354
aVCan it be true, as he said, that I am\u000aheir to a fortune?
p3355
aVWhy couldn't he tell me?
p3356
aVI would have paid him well\u000afor the information when I got my money.
p3357
aVThen he said he knew who I\u000awas--I care more for that than the money."
p3358
aVBut Tony could not dwell upon these thoughts.
p3359
aVThe claims of duty were\u000aparamount.
p3360
aVHe must seek the horse, and go back to the hotel.
p3361
aVHe had\u000abeen detained already for nearly three-quarters of an hour, and they\u000awould be wondering what had become of him.
p3362
aVHe made his way as quickly as possible to where he had tied the horse.
p3363
aVBut he looked for him in vain.
p3364
aVHe had been untied and led away--perhaps\u000astolen.
p3365
aVTony felt assured that the horse of himself could not leave the\u000aspot.
p3366
aV"It must be Rudolph," he said to himself.
p3367
aV"He has made off with the\u000ahorse.
p3368
aVNow I am in trouble.
p3369
aVWhat will Mr. Porter say to me?"
p3370
aVTony was in error, as we know, in concluding that Rudolph had carried\u000aaway the horse.
p3371
aVThe tramp had no use for him.
p3372
aVBesides, he knew that\u000asuch a proceeding would have exposed him to suspicion, which it was\u000avery important for him to avoid.
p3373
aVWho, then, had taken the horse?
p3374
aVThat is a question which we are able to\u000aanswer, though Tony could not.
p3375
aVFifteen minutes before Sam Payson, whose place Tom had taken, with a\u000acompanion, Ben Hardy, while wandering through the woods had espied a\u000ahorse.
p3376
aV"Hallo!"
p3377
aVsaid Ben, "here's a horse."
p3378
aV"So it is," said Sam.
p3379
aV"It's rather odd that he should be tied here."
p3380
aV"I wonder whose it is?"
p3381
aVSam had been examining him carefully, and had recognized him.
p3382
aV"It's Mr. Porter's Bill.
p3383
aVDon't you see that white spot?
p3384
aVThat's the way\u000aI know him.
p3385
aVI have harnessed that horse fifty times."
p3386
aV"But how did he come here?
p3387
aVThat's the question?"
p3388
aV"I'll tell you," said Sam.
p3389
aV"I was at the hotel this morning, and heard\u000athat that boy Tony was to go over to Thornton with him."
p3390
aV"That don't explain why he is tied here, does it?"
p3391
aV"Tony must have tied him while he was taking a tramp in the woods.
p3392
aVWouldn't Porter be mad if he knew it?"
p3393
aV"I shouldn't wonder if Tony would get bounced."
p3394
aV"Nor I. I tell you what, Ben, I've a great mind to untie the horse, and\u000atake him back myself."
p3395
aV"What's the good?
p3396
aVIt would be an awful job.
p3397
aVWe came out here to have\u000asome fun," grumbled Ben.
p3398
aV"This would be fun to me.
p3399
aVI'll get Tony into trouble, and very likely\u000aget back the place he cheated me out of.
p3400
aVI guess it'll pay."
p3401
aV"All right, Sam.
p3402
aVI didn't think of that.
p3403
aVI'd like to see how Tony looks\u000awhen he comes back, and finds the horse gone."
p3404
aV"It'll serve him right," said Sam.
p3405
aV"What business had he to interfere\u000awith me, I'd like to know."
p3406
aV"If you're going to do it you'd better hurry up.
p3407
aVHe may go back any\u000atime."
p3408
aV"That's so.
p3409
aVHere goes, then."
p3410
aVIn a trice Bill was untied, and Sam taking the halter led him away.
p3411
aVWhen Tony came up he was not in sight.
p3412
aVThough Tony felt convinced that Rudolph had carried away the horse, he\u000afelt it to be his duty to look about for it.
p3413
aVThere was a bare chance\u000athat he might find it somewhere in the wood.
p3414
aVIn this way he lost\u000aconsiderable time.
p3415
aVHad he started for the hotel immediately he would\u000avery likely have overtaken the two boys.
p3416
aVSam kept on his way, and finally arrived at the hotel.
p3417
aVAs he led the horse into the stable-yard James, the hostler, exclaimed\u000ain surprise:\u000a\u000a"How came you by that horse, Sam Payson?"
p3418
aV"Is that the way you thank me for bringing him back?"
p3419
aVasked Sam.
p3420
aV"He left the stable under the charge of Tony Rugg this morning."
p3421
aV"Pretty care he takes of him, then."
p3422
aV"What do you mean?
p3423
aVWhere did you find him?"
p3424
aV"Down in the woods?"
p3425
aV"What woods?"
p3426
aV"Between here and Thornton."
p3427
aV"Wasn't Tony with him?"
p3428
aV"No."
p3429
aV"Are you sure of that?
p3430
aVAre you sure you two boys didn't attack Tony and\u000atake the horse away?"
p3431
aVdemanded James, suspiciously.
p3432
aV"No, we didn't.
p3433
aVIf you don't believe me, you may ask Ben."
p3434
aV"How was it, Ben?"
p3435
aVhe asked.
p3436
aV"Just as Sam has said.
p3437
aVWe found the horse alone in the woods.
p3438
aVWe\u000athought he might be stolen, and we brought him home.
p3439
aVIt was a good deal\u000aof trouble, for it's full two miles."
p3440
aVJames looked from one to the other in perplexity.
p3441
aV"I don't understand it at all," he said.
p3442
aV"It don't look like Tony to\u000aneglect his duty that way."
p3443
aV"You've got too high an opinion of that boy entirely," said Sam,\u000asneeringly.
p3444
aV[Illustration: Tony sprung forward and seized the would-be murderer by\u000athe arm.
p3445
aV(See page 182.)]
p3446
aVCHAPTER XXVII.
p3447
aVTONY IS DISCHARGED.
p3448
aVPresently Tony came into the yard.
p3449
aVHe was looking very sober.
p3450
aVHe had\u000alost the horse, and he didn't know how to excuse himself.
p3451
aVHe didn't\u000afeel that he had been to blame, but he suspected that he should be\u000ablamed nevertheless.
p3452
aV"What did you do with the horse, Tony?"
p3453
aVasked James.
p3454
aV"He was stolen from me," answered Tony.
p3455
aV"How could that be?"
p3456
aV"I expect it was the Quaker."
p3457
aV"The Quaker!"
p3458
aVrepeated James, in amazement.
p3459
aV"Are you sure you're not\u000acrazy--or drunk?"
p3460
aV"Neither one," said Tony.
p3461
aV"It's a long story and----"\u000a\u000a"You must tell it to Mr. Porter then.
p3462
aVHe wants to see you right off.
p3463
aVBut I'll tell you for your information that the horse is here."
p3464
aV"Is here?
p3465
aVWho brought it?"
p3466
aV"Sam Payson brought it a short time since."
p3467
aV"Sam Payson!
p3468
aVWhere did he say he found it?"
p3469
aV"In the woods."
p3470
aV"Then he might have left it there," said Tony, indignantly.
p3471
aV"What\u000abusiness had he to untie it, and give me all this trouble?"
p3472
aV"You can speak to Mr. Porter about that."
p3473
aV"Where is he?"
p3474
aV"In the office."
p3475
aVTony entered the office.
p3476
aVMr. Porter regarded him with a frown.
p3477
aV"How is this, Tony?"
p3478
aVhe began.
p3479
aV"You leave my horse in the woods to be\u000abrought home by another boy.
p3480
aVHe might have been stolen, do you know\u000athat?"
p3481
aV"I've been deceived, and led into a trap," said Tony.
p3482
aV"What on earth do you mean?
p3483
aVWho has deceived and trapped you?"
p3484
aV"The Quaker who was stopping here.
p3485
aVHas he come back?"
p3486
aV"He has settled his bill and left the hotel.
p3487
aVWhat cock-and-bull story\u000ais this you have hatched up?"
p3488
aV"It is a true story, Mr. Porter.
p3489
aVThis man was not a Quaker at all.
p3490
aVHe\u000awas a tramp."
p3491
aV"Take care what you say, Tony.
p3492
aVDo you take me for a fool?"
p3493
aV"He is a man I used to know.
p3494
aVWhen I was coming home he was waiting for\u000ame in the woods, only I didn't know who he really was.
p3495
