aVThe main thing is to select\u000aone who knows how to teach, and whom you will like."
p4224
aV"I wish you were a teacher, Mr.
p4225
aVSpencer."
p4226
aV"Why?"
p4227
aV"Because then I should have a teacher whom I liked."
p4228
aV"Thank you, Tony," said the young man, evidently gratified.
p4229
aV"The liking\u000ais mutual.
p4230
aVI think myself fortunate in having you for my companion."
p4231
aV"The luck is on my side, Mr. Spencer.
p4232
aVWhat would I be but for you.
p4233
aVI\u000awouldn't be a tramp any more, for I am tired enough of that, but I\u000ashould have to earn my living as a newsboy or a bootblack, and have no\u000achance of getting an education."
p4234
aVSo the relations between Tony and his new friend became daily more\u000aclose, until Mr. Spencer came to regard him as a young brother, in\u000awhose progress he was warmly interested.
p4235
aVA tutor was selected, and Tony began to study.
p4236
aVHis ambition was roused.
p4237
aVHe realized for the first time how ignorant he was, and it is not too\u000amuch to say that he learned in one month as much as most boys learn in\u000athree.
p4238
aVHe got rid of the uncouth words he had acquired in early life,\u000aand adapted his manners to the new position which he found himself\u000aoccupying in society.
p4239
aVMr. Spencer, too, was benefited by his new\u000afriend.
p4240
aVHe gave up drink and dissipation, and contented himself with\u000apleasures in which he could invite Tony to participate.
p4241
aVMeanwhile Mrs. Harvey Middleton and Rudolph had arrived in England, and\u000awe must leave our hero, for a time and join them.
p4242
aVCHAPTER XXXII.
p4243
aVHOME AGAIN.
p4244
aVWhen Mrs. Harvey Middleton reached England, she delayed but a day\u000ain London to attend to necessary business.
p4245
aVThis business was solely\u000aconnected with her mission to America.
p4246
aVRudolph Rugg accompanied her to\u000athe chambers of a well-known lawyer, and testified to having had the\u000acharge of Tony, closing with the description of his death.
p4247
aVOf course\u000anothing was said of the well, or about his having thrown him in, for\u000aRudolph was not a fool.
p4248
aVThe details of a probable story had been got\u000aup by Mrs. Middleton and Rugg in concert.
p4249
aVAccording to them and the\u000awritten testimony, Tony had been run over by a train on the Erie\u000arailway, and a newspaper paragraph describing such an accident to an\u000aunknown boy was produced in corroboration.
p4250
aVIt was an ingenious fabrication, and Mrs. Middleton plumed herself upon\u000ait.
p4251
aV"Poor boy!"
p4252
aVshe said, with a hypocritical sigh, "his was a sad fate."
p4253
aV"It was, indeed," said the lawyer; "but," he added, dryly, "you have no\u000acause to regret it, since it secures the estate."
p4254
aV"Don't mention it, Mr. Brief.
p4255
aVIt is sad to profit by such a tragedy."
p4256
aV"You don't take a business view of it, madame.
p4257
aVSuch things happen, and\u000aif we can't prevent them, we may as well profit by them."
p4258
aV"Of course I will not refuse what has fallen in my way," said Mrs.\u000aMiddleton; "but I had formed the plan, if I found the boy alive, of\u000abringing him home and educating him for his position.
p4259
aVHe would not have\u000alet me want."
p4260
aV"Don't she do it well, though?"
p4261
aVthought Rudolph, who heard all this\u000awith a cynical admiration for the ex-governess.
p4262
aV"If I was a gentleman,\u000aI'd make up to her, and make her Mrs. Rugg if she'd say the word."
p4263
aV"You think this man's evidence will substantiate my claim to the\u000aestate?"
p4264
aVshe asked, after a pause.
p4265
aV"I should say there was no doubt on that point, unless, of course, his\u000aevidence is impeached or contradicted."
p4266
aV"That is hardly likely, Mr. Brief.
p4267
aVThe poor man suffered much at the\u000adeath of the boy, to whom he was ardently attached."
p4268
aV"So you loved the boy, Mr.
p4269
aVRugg?"
p4270
aVsaid the lawyer.
p4271
aV"Oh, uncommon," said Rudolph.
p4272
aV"He was my pet, and the apple of my eye.
p4273
aVWe was always together, Tony and I."
p4274
aV"And I suppose he loved you."
p4275
aV"He couldn't bear me out of his sight; he looked upon me as a father,\u000asir."
p4276
aV"If he'd come into the estate, he would probably have provided for\u000ayou," suggested the lawyer, watching him keenly.
p4277
aV"It's likely, sir.
p4278
aVI wish he had."
p4279
aV"So it's a personal loss to you--the death of the boy."
p4280
aV"Yes, sir."
p4281
aV"Mrs. Middleton probably will not forget your services to the boy."
p4282
aV"No, sir.
p4283
aVI shall, of course, do something for Mr. Rugg, though not as\u000amuch, perhaps, as my poor cousin would have done.
p4284
aVMr. Rugg, will you\u000asee me to my carriage?"
p4285
aV"Certainly, ma'am."
p4286
aVMrs. Middleton was anxious to go away.
p4287
aVThe conversation had taken a\u000aturn which she did not like.
p4288
aVIt almost seemed as if the lawyer was\u000atrying to find out something, and she thought it best to get Rudolph\u000aaway from the influence, lest Mr. Brief should catechise him, and draw\u000aout something to her disadvantage.
p4289
aV"Mr. Rugg," she said, as they were going down stairs, "I advise you not\u000ato go near Mr. Brief again."
p4290
aV"Why not, ma'am?"
p4291
aV"These lawyers are crafty.
p4292
aVBefore you knew what he was after, he would\u000aextract the secret from you, and there would be trouble for both of us."
p4293
aV"Do you think so, ma'am?
p4294
aVI didn't see nothing of it?"
p4295
aV"I think he suspects something.
p4296
aVThat matters nothing if it does not go\u000abeyond suspicion.
p4297
aVUnless he can impeach your testimony and draw you\u000ainto contradictions, we are safe, and you are sure of an income for\u000alife."
p4298
aV"You needn't be afraid for me, ma'am.
p4299
aVWe are in the same boat."
p4300
aVShe frowned a little at the familiar tone in which he spoke.
p4301
aVIt\u000awas as if he put himself on an equality with her.
p4302
aVBut it was true,\u000anevertheless, and it was unpleasant for her to think of.
p4303
aVWas there nothing else that was unpleasant?
p4304
aVDid she not think of the\u000apoor boy who, as she thought, was killed, and at her instigation?
p4305
aVYes,\u000ashe thought often of him, but as much as she could she kept the subject\u000aaway from her thoughts.
p4306
aV"He's better off," she said to herself.
p4307
aV"He didn't know anything of the\u000aproperty, and he wasn't fit to possess it.
p4308
aVAll the troubles of life are\u000aover for him."
p4309
aV"What are your plans, Mr.
p4310
aVRugg?"
p4311
aVshe asked.
p4312
aV"I have a mind to go down to Middleton Hall with you, ma'am.
p4313
aVI used to\u000alive there years ago, and I might find some of my old cronies."
p4314
aV"For that very reason you must not go," she said, hastily.
p4315
aV"They\u000awould be asking you all sorts of questions, and you'd be letting out\u000asomething."
p4316
aV"They wouldn't get nothing out of me."
p4317
aV"If you made no answer it would be as bad.
p4318
aVThey would suspect you."
p4319
aV"And you, too."
p4320
aV"Precisely."
p4321
aV"It's rather hard, Mrs. Middleton, I can't see my old friends."
p4322
aV"You can make new ones.
p4323
aVA man with money can always find friends."
p4324
aV"That's true, ma'am," said Rudolph, brightening up.
p4325
aV"Then you'd\u000arecommend me to stay in London?"
p4326
aV"In London, or anywhere else that you like better.
p4327
aVOnly don't come\u000awithin twenty miles of Middleton Hall."
p4328
aV"Well, ma'am, you're wiser than I am, and you know better what it's\u000abest to do."
p4329
aV"Of course I do.
p4330
aVYou are safe in being guided by me."
p4331
aV"But about the money, ma'am.
p4332
aVHow am I to get that if I don't see you?"
p4333
aV"Once a quarter I will pay in forty pounds to your account at any bank\u000ayou choose.
p4334
aVYou can let me know."
p4335
aV"All right, ma'am.
p4336
aVIt's strange to me to think of having a bank\u000aaccount."
p4337
aV"It need not be strange henceforth.
p4338
aVAnd now, Mr. Rugg, we must part.
p4339
aVI must hasten down to Middleton Hall to look after the estate.
p4340
aVI have\u000abeen absent from it now for nearly three months."
p4341
aV"I suppose you are in a hurry to see your young man," said Rudolph,\u000awith a grin.
p4342
aV"Mr. Rugg," said the lady, haughtily, "I beg you will make no reference\u000ato my private affairs.
p4343
aVYou speak as if I were a nursery maid."
p4344
aV"I beg your pardon, ma'am.
p4345
aVNo offense was meant."
p4346
aV"Then none is taken.
p4347
aVBut remember my caution."
p4348
aVShe stepped into the hansom which was waiting for her, and Rudolph\u000aremained standing on the sidewalk.
p4349
aV"She's puttin' on airs," said the tramp, frowning.
p4350
aV"She forgets all\u000aabout her bein' a governess once, without five pounds in the world.
p4351
aVShe\u000aacts as if she were a lady born.
p4352
aVI don't like it.
p4353
aVShe may try her airs\u000aon others, but not on Rudolph Rugg.
p4354
aVHe knows a little too much about\u000aMrs. Harvey Middleton.
p4355
aVRich as you are, you're in his power, and if he\u000awas so inclined he could bring you down from your high place, so he\u000acould."
p4356
aVBut Rudolph's anger was only transient.
p4357
aVHe was too astute not to\u000aunderstand clearly that he could not harm Mrs. Middleton without\u000aharming himself quite as much.
p4358
aVAs things stood, he was securely\u000aprovided for.
p4359
aVNo more tramping about the country for him in all\u000aweathers.
p4360
aVHe had enough to lodge and feed him, and provide all the beer\u000aand tobacco he could use.
p4361
aVThis was certainly a comfortable reflection.
p4362
aVSo he sought out a comfortable lodging and installed himself before\u000anight, determined to get what enjoyment he could out of London and the\u000aincome he had so foully won.
p4363
aVAnd Mrs. Middleton, she, too, congratulated herself.
p4364
aVShe leaned back in the cab and gave herself up to joyful anticipations\u000aof future happiness and security.
p4365
aV"Thank Heaven, I have got rid of that low fellow," she ejaculated,\u000ainwardly.
p4366
aV"I never want to see the brute again.
p4367
aVHe was necessary to\u000amy purpose, and I employed him, but I should be glad if he would get\u000adrowned, or be run over, or end his miserable life in some way, so that\u000aI might never see or hear of him again."
p4368
aVBut the thought of Rudolph did not long trouble her.
p4369
aVShe thought rather\u000aof the handsome Captain Lovell, whom she loved, and to marry whom she\u000ahad committed this crime, and the hard woman's face softened, and a\u000asmile crept over it.
p4370
aV"I shall soon see him, my Gregory," she murmured.
p4371
aV"He will soon be\u000amine, and I shall be repaid for my long, wearisome journey."
p4372
aVCHAPTER XXXIII.
p4373
aVCAPTAIN GREGORY LOVELL.
p4374
aVA carriage drove rapidly up the avenue leading to Middleton Hall.
p4375
aVThe hall was not large, but was handsome and well proportioned, and\u000alooked singularly attractive, its gray walls forming a harmonious\u000acontrast with the bright green ivy that partially covered them, and the\u000abroad, smooth lawn that stretched out in front.
p4376
aVMrs. Middleton regarded her home with unmingled satisfaction.
p4377
aVIt was\u000ato be her home now as long as she lived.
p4378
aVNow that the boy was dead no\u000aone could wrest it from her.
p4379
aVShe would live there, but not in solitary\u000agrandeur.
p4380
aVThe news of her success would bring Captain Gregory Lovell\u000ato her side, and their marriage would follow as soon as decency would\u000apermit.
p4381
aVIf afterward he should desire to have the name of the residence\u000achanged to Lovell Hall, Mrs. Middleton decided that she would not\u000aobject.
p4382
aVWhy should she?
p4383
aVShe had no superstitious love for her present\u000aname, while Lovell had for her the charm which love always gives to the\u000aname of the loved one.
p4384
aVThe housekeeper, stout and matronly, received her mistress at the door.
p4385
aV"Welcome home, Mrs. Middleton," she said; "how long it seems since you\u000awent away."
p4386
aV"How do you do, Sarah," said her mistress, graciously.
p4387
aV"I can assure\u000ayou I am glad to be back."
p4388
aV"You will find everything in order, mum, I hope and believe," said\u000aSarah.
p4389
aV"We expected to see you sooner."
p4390
aV"I hoped to be back sooner, but the business detained me longer than I\u000adesired."
p4391
aV"And did you succeed, mum, if I may be so bold," inquired the\u000ahousekeeper, curiously.
p4392
aV"As I expected, Sarah.
p4393
aVI found that the poor boy was dead."
p4394
aV"Indeed, mum."
p4395
aV"I hoped to bring him back with me, according to my poor husband's\u000adesire, but it was ordered otherwise by an inscrutable Providence."
p4396
aVSarah coughed.
p4397
aV"It is very sad," she said, but she looked curiously at her mistress.
p4398
aVShe knew very well that this sad news rejoiced the heart of Mrs.\u000aMiddleton, and the latter knew that she could not for a moment impose\u000aupon her clear-sighted housekeeper.
p4399
aVBut the farce must be kept up for\u000athe sake of appearances.
p4400
aV"Come up to my chamber with me, Sarah.
p4401
aVI want to ask you what has been\u000agoing on since I went away?
p4402
aVHave you heard from Lady Lovell's family?
p4403
aVAre they all well?"
p4404
aVLady Lovell was the mother of Captain Gregory Lovell, and the question\u000awas earnestly put.
p4405
aV"They are all well except the captain," answered Sarah.
p4406
aV"Is he sick?"
p4407
aVdemanded her mistress, turning upon her swiftly.
p4408
aV"No, mum; I only meant to say that the captain was gone away."
p4409
aV"Gone away!
p4410
aVWhen?
p4411
aVWhere?"
p4412
aV"He's ordered to India, I believe, mum.
p4413
aVHe went away a month ago."
p4414
aVMrs. Middleton sank into her chair, quite overcome.
p4415
aVHer joy was\u000aclouded, for the reward of her long and toilsome journey was snatched\u000afrom her.
p4416
aV"Did he not leave any message?"
p4417
aVshe asked.
p4418
aV"Did he not call before he\u000awent away?"
p4419
aV"Yes, mum.
p4420
aVHe left a note."
p4421
aV"Give it to me quick.
p4422
aVWhy did you not mention it to me before?"
p4423
aV"It's the first chance I got, mum.
p4424
aVThe letter is in my own chamber.
p4425
aVI\u000atook the best care of it.
p4426
aVI will get it directly."
p4427
aV"Do go, Sarah."
p4428
aVMrs. Middleton awaited the return of Sarah with nervous impatience.
p4429
aVPerhaps the captain had thrown her over, after all, and, loving him as\u000ashe did, this would have torn the heart of the intriguing woman, who,\u000acold and selfish as she was so far as others were concerned, really\u000aloved the handsome captain.
p4430
aVSarah speedily reappeared with the letter.
p4431
aV"Here it is, mum," she said.
p4432
aV"I have taken the best care of it."
p4433
aVMrs. Middleton tore it open with nervous haste This is the way it ran:\u000a\u000a\u000a     "MY DEAR JANE--I am about to set out for India--not\u000a     willingly, but my regiment is ordered there, and I must obey or\u000a     quit the service.
p4434
aVThis, as you well know, I cannot do; for apart\u000a     from my official pay, I have but a paltry two hundred pounds a\u000a     year, and that is barely enough to pay my tailor's bill.
p4435
aVI am\u000a     sorry to go away in your absence.
p4436
aVIf I were only sure you would\u000a     bring home good news, I could afford to sell my commission and\u000a     wait.
p4437
aVBut it is so uncertain that I cannot take the risk.
p4438
aV"I need not say, my dear Jane, how anxious I am to have all the\u000a     impediments to our union removed.
p4439
aVI am compelled to be mercenary.
p4440
aVIt is, alas!
p4441
aVnecessary for me, as a younger son, to marry a woman\u000a     with money.
p4442
aVI shall be happy, indeed, if interest and love go\u000a     hand in hand, as they will if your absolute claim to your late\u000a     husband's estate is proved beyond a doubt.
p4443
aVI append my India\u000a     address, and shall anxiously expect a communication from you on\u000a     your return.
p4444
aVIf you have been successful, I will arrange to return\u000a     at once, and our union can be solemnized without delay.
p4445
aVOnce more,\u000a     farewell.
p4446
aV"Your devoted\u000a     "GREGORY LOVELL."
p4447
aVMrs. Middleton, after reading this letter, breathed a sigh of relief.
p4448
aVHe was still hers, and she had only to call him back.
p4449
aVThere would be a\u000avexatious delay, but that must be submitted to.
p4450
aVShe had feared to lose\u000ahim, and this apprehension, at least, might be laid aside.
p4451
aVTo some the letter would have seemed too mercenary.
p4452
aVEven Mrs. Middleton\u000acould not help suspecting that, between love and interest, the latter\u000awas far the most powerful in the mind of Captain Lovell.
p4453
aVBut she\u000apurposely closed her eyes to this unpleasant suspicion.
p4454
aVShe was in love\u000awith the handsome captain, and it was the great object of her life to\u000abecome his wife.
p4455
aVShe decided to answer the letter immediately.
p4456
aVHer desk was at hand, and she opened it at once, and wrote a brief\u000aletter to her absent lover:\u000a\u000a\u000a     "DEAR GREGORY--I have just returned.
p4457
aVI am deeply\u000a     disappointed to find you absent, for, my darling, I have\u000a     succeeded.
p4458
aVI have legal proof--proof that cannot be disputed--that\u000a     the boy, my husband's cousin, is dead.
p4459
aVThe poor boy was\u000a     accidentally killed.
p4460
aVI have the sworn affidavit of the man who\u000a     took him to America, and who was his constant companion there.
p4461
aV"It is a sad fate for the poor boy.
p4462
aVI sincerely deplore his\u000a     tragical end--he was run over by a train of cars--yet (is it\u000a     wicked?
p4463
aV), my grief is mitigated by the thought that it removes all\u000a     obstacle to our union.
p4464
aVI do not for an instant charge you with\u000a     interested motives.
p4465
aVI am sure of your love, but I also comprehend\u000a     the necessities of your position.
p4466
aVYou have been brought up as a\u000a     gentleman, and you have the tastes of a gentleman.
p4467
aVYou cannot\u000a     surrender your social position.
p4468
aVIt is necessary that, if you\u000a     marry, you should have an adequate income to live upon.
p4469
aVMy darling\u000a     Gregory, I am proud and happy in the thought that I can make you\u000a     such.
p4470
aVYou know my estate.
p4471
aVThe rental is two thousand pounds, and\u000a     that is enough to maintain our social rank.
p4472
aVCome home, then, as\u000a     soon, as you receive this letter.
p4473
aVI am awaiting you impatiently,\u000a     and can hardly reconcile myself to the delay that must be.
p4474
aVMake it\u000a     as short as possible, and let me hear from you at once.
p4475
aV"Your own,\u000a     "JANE MIDDLETON."
p4476
aVThere was unexpected delay in the reception of this letter.
p4477
aVIt was\u000athree months before it came into the hands of Captain Lovell.
p4478
aVWhen at\u000alength it was received, he read it with a mixture of emotions.
p4479
aV"Decidedly," he said, removing the cigar from his mouth, "the old girl\u000ais fond of me.
p4480
aVI wish I were fond of her, for I suppose I must marry\u000aher.
p4481
aVIt will be rather a bad pill to swallow, but it is well gilded.
p4482
aVTwo thousand pounds a year are not to be thrown away by a fellow in my\u000astraits.
p4483
aVThe prospect might be brighter, but I suppose I have no right\u000ato complain.
p4484
aVIt will make me comfortable for life.
p4485
aVI must take care to\u000ahave the estate settled upon me, and then the sooner the old girl dies\u000athe better."
p4486
aVSo Captain Lovell wrote at once, saying that he would return home as\u000asoon as he could make arrangements for doing so--that every day would\u000aseem a month till he could once more embrace his dear Jane.
p4487
aVThe letter\u000awas signed, "Your devoted Gregory."
p4488
aVMrs. Middleton read it with unfeigned delight.
p4489
aVHer plans had succeeded,\u000aand the reward would soon be hers.
p4490
aVBut there was fresh delay.
p4491
aVArrangements to return could not be made so\u000aeasily as Captain Lovell anticipated.
p4492
aVIt was seven months from the day\u000aMrs. Middleton reached England when Captain Lovell was driven to his\u000ahotel in London.
p4493
aVMeanwhile events had occurred which were to have an\u000aeffect upon Mrs. Middleton's plans.
p4494
aVCHAPTER XXXIV.
p4495
aVTONY ASTONISHES HIS OLD FRIENDS.
p4496
aV"Tony," said George Spencer one evening, "you have been making\u000awonderful progress in your studies.
p4497
aVIn six months you have accomplished\u000aas much as I did at boarding school in two years when at your age."
p4498
aV"Do you really mean it, Mr.
p4499
aVSpencer?"
p4500
aVsaid Tony, gratified.
p4501
aV"I am quite in earnest."
p4502
aV"I am very glad of it," said Tony.
p4503
aV"When I began I was almost\u000adiscouraged.
p4504
aVI was so much behind boys of my age."
p4505
aV"And now your attainments raise you above the average.
p4506
aVYour tutor told\u000ame so yesterday when I made inquiries."
p4507
aV"I am rejoiced to hear it, Mr. Spencer, I was very much ashamed of\u000amyself at first, and I did not like to speak before your friends for\u000afear they would find out what sort of a life I led.
p4508
aVThat is what made\u000ame work so hard."
p4509
aV"Well, Tony, you may congratulate yourself on having succeeded.
p4510
aVI think\u000ayou can venture now to take a little vacation."
p4511
aV"A vacation!
p4512
aVI don't need one."
p4513
aV"Suppose it were spent in Europe?"
p4514
aV"What!"
p4515
aVexclaimed Tony, eagerly, "you don't think of our going abroad?"
p4516
aV"Yes.
p4517
aVThe house with which I am connected wants me to go abroad on\u000abusiness.
p4518
aVIf I go you may go with me if you would like it."
p4519
aV"Like it!"
p4520
aVexclaimed Tony, impetuously.
p4521
aV"There is nothing I would like\u000abetter."
p4522
aV"So I supposed," said George Spencer, smiling.
p4523
aV"I may as well tell you\u000athat our passage is taken for next Saturday, by the Russia."
p4524
aV"And this is Monday evening.
p4525
aVHow soon it seems!"
p4526
aV"There won't be much preparation to make--merely packing your trunk."
p4527
aV"Mr. Spencer," said Tony, "I want to ask a favor."
p4528
aV"What is it?"
p4529
aV"I have told you about being employed at a country hotel, just before I\u000acame to the city and found you."
p4530
aV"Yes."
p4531
aV"I would like to go back there for a day, just to see how all my old\u000afriends are."
p4532
aV"You don't mean to apply again for your old place?"
p4533
aV"Not unless you turn me off, and I have to find work somewhere."
p4534
aV"Turn you off, Tony!
p4535
aVWhy, I shouldn't know how to get along without\u000ayou.
p4536
aVYou are like a younger brother to me," said the young man,\u000aearnestly.
p4537
aV"Thank you, Mr. Spencer.
p4538
aVYou seem like an older brother to me.
p4539
aVSometimes I can hardly believe that I was once a tramp."
p4540
aV"It was your misfortune, Tony, not your fault.
p4541
aVSo you want to go back\u000aand view your former home?"
p4542
aV"Yes, Mr.
p4543
aVSpencer."
p4544
aV"Then you had better start to-morrow morning, so as to be back in good\u000atime to prepare for the journey."
p4545
aV"Do you know, Mr. Spencer," said Tony, "I've got an idea.
p4546
aVI'll go back\u000awearing the same clothes I had on when I left there."
p4547
aV"Have you got them still?"
p4548
aV"Yes, I laid them away, just to remind me of my old life.
p4549
aVI'll take my\u000aother clothes in a bundle, and after a while I can put them on."
p4550
aV"What is your idea in doing this, Tony?"
p4551
aVasked the young man.
p4552
aV"I want to give them a surprise."
p4553
aV"Very well, do as you please.
p4554
aVOnly don't stay away too long."
p4555
aV*       *       *       *       *       *\u000a\u000aTony proceeded to carry out the plan he had proposed.
p4556
aVHe traveled by rail to a village near by, and then with his bundle\u000asuspended to a stick, took up his march to the tavern.
p4557
aVHe entered the familiar stable yard.
p4558
aVAll looked as it did the day\u000ahe left.
p4559
aVThere was only one person in the yard, and that one Tony\u000arecognized at once as his old enemy, Sam Payson, who appeared to be\u000afilling his old position, as stable boy.
p4560
aV"Hallo, Sam!"
p4561
aVsaid Tony, whose entrance had not been observed.
p4562
aVSam looked up and whistled.
p4563
aV"What, have you come back?"
p4564
aVhe said, not appearing overjoyed at the\u000asight of Tony.
p4565
aV"Yes, Sam," said Tony.
p4566
aV"Where have you been all the time?"
p4567
aV"In New York part of the time."
p4568
aV"What have you been doing for a living?"
p4569
aV"Well, I lived with a gentleman there."
p4570
aV"What did you do--black his boots?"
p4571
aV"Not exactly."
p4572
aV"Did he turn you off?"
p4573
aV"No; but he's going to Europe next Saturday."
p4574
aV"So you're out of a place?"
p4575
aV"I have no employment."
p4576
aV"What made you come back here?"
p4577
aVdemanded Sam, suspiciously.
p4578
aV"I thought I'd like to see you all again."
p4579
aV"That don't go down," said Sam roughly.
p4580
aV"I know well enough what you're\u000aafter."
p4581
aV"What am I after?"
p4582
aV"You're after my place.
p4583
aVYou're hoping Mr. Porter will take you on\u000aagain.
p4584
aVBut it's no use.
p4585
aVThere ain't any chance for you."
p4586
aV"How long have you been back again, Sam?"
p4587
aV"Three months, and I am going to stay, too.
p4588
aVYou got me turned off once,\u000abut you can't do it again."
p4589
aV"I don't want to."
p4590
aV"Oh, no, I presume not," sneered Sam.
p4591
aV"Of course, you don't.
p4592
aVYou've got\u000aon the same clothes you wore away, haven't you?"
p4593
aV"Yes, it's the same suit, but I've got some more things in my bundle."
p4594
aV"I guess you haven't made your fortune, by the looks."
p4595
aV"The fact is, Sam, I haven't earned much since I went away."
p4596
aV"I knew you wouldn't.
p4597
aVYou ain't so smart as people think."
p4598
aV"I didn't know anybody thought me smart."
p4599
aV"James, the hostler, is always talking you up to me, but I guess I can\u000arub along as well as you."
p4600
aV"You talk as if I was your enemy, Sam, instead of your friend."
p4601
aV"I don't want such a friend.
p4602
aVYou're after my place, in spite of all you\u000asay."
p4603
aVJust then James, the hostler, came out of the stable.
p4604
aV"What, is it you, Tony?"
p4605
aVhe asked, cordially.
p4606
aV"Yes, James; I hope you're well."
p4607
aV"Tip-top; and how are you?"
p4608
aVasked the hostler, examining Tony,\u000acritically.
p4609
aV"I'm well."
p4610
aV"Have you been doing well?"
p4611
aV"I haven't wanted for anything.
p4612
aVI've been with a gentleman in New York."
p4613
aVHere Mr. Porter appeared on the scene.
p4614
aVHe too, recognized Tony.
p4615
aV"What!
p4616
aVback again, Tony?"
p4617
aVhe said.
p4618
aV"I thought I'd just look in, sir."
p4619
aV"Do you want a place!"
p4620
aV"What sort of a place?"
p4621
aV"Your old place."
p4622
aVSam heard this, and looked the picture of dismay.
p4623
aVHe took it for\u000agranted that Tony would accept at once, and privately determined that\u000aif he did he would give him a flogging, if it were a possible thing.
p4624
aVHe was both relieved and surprised when Tony answered:\u000a\u000a"I am much obliged to you, Mr. Porter, but I wouldn't like to cut out\u000aSam.
p4625
aVBesides, I have a place engaged in New York."
p4626
aV"I would rather have you than Sam, any day."
p4627
aV"Thank you, sir, but I've made an arrangement, and can't break it."
p4628
aV"How long are you going to stay here?"
p4629
aV"If you've a spare room, I'll stay over till to-morrow."
p4630
aV"All right.
p4631
aVGo into the office, and they'll give you one."
p4632
aV"I say, Tony," said Sam, after the landlord had gone, "you're a better\u000afellow than I thought you were.
p4633
aVI thought you'd take my place when it\u000awas offered you."
p4634
aV"You see you were mistaken, Sam.
p4635
aVI'll see you again."
p4636
aVTony went into the hotel--went up to a small chamber that had been\u000aassigned him, changed his clothes for a handsome suit in his bundle,\u000atook a handsome gold watch and chain from his pocket and displayed\u000athem on his vest, and then came down again.
p4637
aVAs he entered the yard again, Sam stared in amazement.
p4638
aV"It can't be you, Tony!"
p4639
aVhe said.
p4640
aV"Where'd you get them clothes, and\u000athat watch?"
p4641
aV"I came by them honestly, Sam."
p4642
aV"But I can't understand it," said Sam, scratching his head.
p4643
aV"Ain't you\u000apoor, and out of work?"
p4644
aV"I'm out of work, but not poor.
p4645
aVI've been adopted by a rich gentleman,\u000aand am going to sail for Europe on Saturday."
p4646
aV"Cracky!
p4647
aVwho ever heard the like?
p4648
aVWouldn't he adopt me, too?"
p4649
aV"I believe there is no vacancy," said Tony, smiling.
p4650
aV"Was that the reason you wouldn't take my place?"
p4651
aV"One reason."
p4652
aV"James!"
p4653
aVcalled Sam, "just look at Tony now."
p4654
aVJames stared, and when an explanation was made, heartily congratulated\u000aour hero.
p4655
aV"Sam," said Tony, producing a couple of showy neck-ties, "to prove to\u000ayou that I am not your enemy, I have brought you these."
p4656
aV"They're stunning!"
p4657
aVexclaimed the enraptured Sam.
p4658
aV"I always thought you\u000awas a good fellow, Tony.
p4659
aVAre they really for me?"
p4660
aV"To be sure they are, but I'm afraid, Sam, you didn't always think\u000aquite so well of me."
p4661
aV"Well, I do now.
p4662
aVYou're a trump."
p4663
aV"And, James, I've brought you a present too."
p4664
aVHere Tony produced a\u000ahandsome silver watch with a silver chain appended.
p4665
aV"It's to remember\u000ame by."
p4666
aV"I'd remember you without it, Tony, but I'm very much obliged too.
p4667
aVIt's\u000aa real beauty."
p4668
aVWhen the landlord was told of Tony's good fortune, he was as much\u000asurprised as the rest.
p4669
aVOur hero was at once changed to the handsomest\u000aroom in the hotel, and was made quite a lion during the remainder of\u000ahis stay.
p4670
aVThere is something in success after all.
p4671
aV"Good-by, Tony," said Sam heartily, when our hero left the next day.
p4672
aV"You're a gentleman, and I always said so."
p4673
aV"Thank you, Sam.
p4674
aVGood luck to you!"
p4675
aVresponded Tony, smiling.
p4676
aV"I'm a much finer fellow than when I was a tramp," he said to himself.
p4677
aV"Sam says so, and he ought to know.
p4678
aVI suppose it's the way of the\u000aworld.
p4679
aVAnd now for Europe!"
p4680
aVCHAPTER XXXV.
p4681
aVTONY'S BAD LUCK.
p4682
aVTwo weeks later Tony and his friend were guests at a popular London\u000ahotel, not far from Charing Cross.
p4683
aV"We will postpone business till we have seen a little of London," said\u000aGeorge Spencer.
p4684
aV"Luckily my business is not of a pressing character,\u000aand it can wait."
p4685
aV"You have been in London before, Mr. Spencer," said Tony.
p4686
aV"I am afraid\u000ayou will find it a bore going round with me."
p4687
aV"Not at all.
p4688
aVI spent a week here when a boy of twelve, and saw nothing\u000athoroughly, so I am at your disposal.
p4689
aVWhere shall we go first?"
p4690
aV"I should like to see Buckingham Palace, where the queen lives."
p4691
aV"She doesn't live there much.
p4692
aVHowever, we'll go to see it, but we'll\u000atake the Parliament House and Westminster Abbey on the way."
p4693
aVIn accordance with this programme they walked--for the distance was\u000abut short--to Westminster Abbey.
p4694
aVIt would be out of place for me to\u000adescribe here that wonderful church where so much of the rank and\u000atalent of past ages lies buried.
p4695
aVIt is enough to say that Tony enjoyed\u000ait highly.
p4696
aVHe afterward visited the Parliament House.
p4697
aVThis occupied\u000aanother hour.
p4698
aVWhen they came out Mr. Spencer said:\u000a\u000a"Tony, I have got to go to my banker's.
p4699
aVDo you care to come?"
p4700
aV"No, thank you, Mr. Spencer, I would rather walk round by myself."
p4701
aV"Very well, Tony, just as you please.
p4702
aVOnly don't get lost."
p4703
aV"I'll take care of that; I'm used to cities."
p4704
aV"You are not used to London.
p4705
aVIt is one of the blindest cities in the\u000aworld; it is a complete labyrinth."
p4706
aV"I don't mean to get lost.
p4707
aVYou'll find me at the hotel at four o'clock."
p4708
aV"Very well.
p4709
aVThat will be early enough."
p4710
aVSo George Spencer went his way, and Tony set out upon his rambles.
p4711
aVHe found plenty to amuse him in the various buildings and sights of the\u000agreat metropolis.
p4712
aVBut after awhile he began to wonder where he was.
p4713
aVHe\u000ahad strayed into a narrow street, scarcely more than a lane, with a row\u000aof tumble-down dwellings on either side.
p4714
aV"There's nothing worth seeing here," said our hero.
p4715
aV"I'll inquire my\u000away to Charing Cross."
p4716
aVHe went into a small beer house, and preferred his request.
p4717
aV"Charing Cross!"
p4718
aVrepeated the publican.
p4719
aV"It's a good ways from 'ere."
p4720
aV"How far?"
p4721
aVasked Tony.
p4722
aV"A mile easy, and there's no end of turns."
p4723
aV"Just start me, then," said Tony, "and I'll reach there.
p4724
aVWhich way is\u000ait?"
p4725
aV"Turn to the left when you go out of this shop."
p4726
aV"All right, and thank you."
p4727
aVTony noticed that there were three or four men seated at tables in\u000athe back part of the shop, but he had not the curiosity to look at\u000athem.
p4728
aVIf he had, he would have been startled, for among these men was\u000aRudolph Rugg, more disreputable than ever in appearance, for he had\u000abeen drinking deeply for the last six months.
p4729
aVHe stared at Tony as one\u000adazed, for he supposed him dead long ago at the bottom of a well three\u000athousand miles away.
p4730
aV"What's the matter, Rugg?"
p4731
aVasked his companion.
p4732
aV"You look as if you'd\u000aseen a ghost."
p4733
aV"So I have," muttered Rugg, starting for the door.
p4734
aV"Where are you going?"
p4735
aV"I've got a headache," said Rudolph.
p4736
aV"You've left your drink."
p4737
aV"I don't want it."
p4738
aV"What's come over him?"
p4739
aVsaid his late companion, in surprise.
p4740
aV"No matter.
p4741
aVHe'll be back soon."
p4742
aVRudolph swiftly followed Tony.
p4743
aVHe wanted to find out whether it was\u000areally the boy whom he had sought to murder or not.
p4744
aVThen what did his\u000aappearance in London mean?
p4745
aVWas he possibly in search of him--Rugg?
p4746
aVIt\u000awas wonderful, certainly.
p4747
aVHow had he obtained the means of coming to\u000aEngland?--as a gentleman, too, for Rudolph had not failed to notice\u000ahis rich clothes.
p4748
aVHad he obtained rich and powerful friends, and was he\u000ain search of the inheritance that had been wrongfully kept from him?
p4749
aVRudolph asked himself all these questions, but he could not answer one.
p4750
aV"If I could only ask him," he thought, "but that wouldn't be safe."
p4751
aVBy this time he had come in sight of Tony, who was walking along\u000aslowly, not feeling in any particular hurry.
p4752
aVAn idea struck Rudolph.
p4753
aVA boy who had been employed in begging was standing on the sidewalk.
p4754
aV"Gi'me a penny, sir," he said.
p4755
aVRudolph paused.
p4756
aV"Walk along with me, and I'll show you how you can earn half a crown,"\u000ahe said.
p4757
aV"Will you?"
p4758
aVsaid the boy, his face brightening.
p4759
aV"Yes, I will, and you won't find it hard work, either."
p4760
aV"Go ahead, gov'nor."
p4761
aV"Do you see that boy ahead?"
p4762
aV"That young gentleman?"
p4763
aV"Yes," said Rudolph.
p4764
aV"I see him."
p4765
aV"I want you to manage to get him up to my room; it's No.
p4766
aV7 ---- street,\u000atop floor, just at the head of the stairs."
p4767
aV"Shall I tell him you want to see him?"
p4768
aV"No, he wouldn't come.
p4769
aVTell him your poor grandfather is sick in\u000abed--anything you like, only get him to come."
p4770
aV"S'posin' he won't come?"
p4771
aV"Then follow him, and find out where he is staying.
p4772
aVDo you understand?"
p4773
aV"Yes, gov'nor.
p4774
aVI'll bring him."
p4775
aV"Go ahead, and I'll hurry round to the room.
p4776
aVI'll be in bed."
p4777
aV"All right."
p4778
aVThe boy was a sharp specimen of the juvenile London beggar.
p4779
aVHe was up\u000ato the usual tricks of his class, and quite competent to the task which\u000aRudolph had engaged him to perform.
p4780
aVHe came up to Tony, and then began to whimper.
p4781
aV"What's the matter, Johnny?"
p4782
aVsaid Tony, addressing him by the usual New\u000aYork name for an unknown boy.
p4783
aV"Oh, my poor grandfather is so sick," said the boy.
p4784
aV"What's the matter with him?"
p4785
aV"I don't know.
p4786
aVI guess he's goin' to die."
p4787
aV"Why don't you send for a doctor?"
p4788
aV"He wouldn't come--we're so poor."
p4789
aV"Do you live near here?"
p4790
aV"Oh, yes, sir; only a little way."
p4791
aV"I want to go to Charing Cross--is it much out of the way?"
p4792
aV"No, sir; it's right on the way there."
p4793
aV"Then, if you'll show me the way to Charing Cross afterward, I will\u000ago round with you and look at your grandfather.
p4794
aVPerhaps I can do\u000asomething for him."
p4795
aV"Oh, sir, how kind you are!
p4796
aVI know'd you was a gentleman when I fust\u000asaw you."
p4797
aV"When was your grandfather taken sick?"
p4798
aV"Two days ago," said the boy.
p4799
aV"Is he in bed?"
p4800
aV"Yes, sir.
p4801
aVLeastways, he was when I came out.
p4802
aVWe didn't have no\u000abreakfast."
p4803
aV"I am sorry for that.
p4804
aVDon't you want to buy something to take to him?"
p4805
aV"If you'll give me a shillin', sir, I'll ask him what he can eat.
p4806
aVSick\u000afolks can't eat the same things as the rest of us."
p4807
aV"To be sure.
p4808
aVYou are right.
p4809
aVWell, here's a shilling."
p4810
aV"The boy little thinks that I have known many a time what it is to\u000abe without breakfast or money to buy any," thought Tony.
p4811
aV"I'll do\u000asomething for the poor man, if only to show how grateful I am for my\u000aown good fortune."
p4812
aVHe followed the boy for about ten minutes, until they reached rather a\u000ashabby building.
p4813
aVThis was No.
p4814
aV7.
p4815
aV"Come right up after me," said the boy.
p4816
aVThe two went up till they reached the room indicated by Rudolph.
p4817
aVThe\u000aboy pushed the door open.
p4818
aVA sound of groaning proceeded from the bed.
p4819
aV"Grandfather, I've brought a kind young gentleman," said the boy.
p4820
aV"Come here," muttered the person in bed.
p4821
aVTony came up to the bed.
p4822
aVIn an instant Rudolph had thrown off the clothes and had him seized by\u000athe arm.
p4823
aV"There's your money, boy.
p4824
aVGo!"
p4825
aVhe said to the other, flinging a\u000ahalf-crown.
p4826
aV"I've got you at last!"
p4827
aVhe shouted.
p4828
aV"Now, you young villain, I'll get\u000aeven with you!"
p4829
aVHis face was almost fiendish with rage, as he uttered these words.
p4830
aVCHAPTER XXXVI.
p4831
aV"I HATE YOU!"
p4832
aVTo say that Tony was not startled would not be true.
p4833
aVWithout a moment's\u000awarning he found himself in the power of his old enemy--completely in\u000ahis power, knowing, too, the desperate character of the man, which\u000awould let him stick at nothing.
p4834
aVRudolph enjoyed his evident surprise.
p4835
aV"I've been waiting for this," he said.
p4836
aV"It's a great joy to me to have\u000ayou here in my power."
p4837
aVBy this time Tony had collected himself, and had become composed.
p4838
aV"Rudolph," he said, "what makes you hate me so?"
p4839
aV"Haven't you tried to injure me--didn't you get me arrested?
p4840
aVDo you\u000aforget that night in the old miser's hut?"
p4841
aV"No, I don't forget it, but you forced me to act as I did.
p4842
aVBut even if\u000aI did injure you, you took your revenge."
p4843
aV"When, and how?"
p4844
aV"When you threw me into the well.
p4845
aVHow could you do such a dark deed?
p4846
aVWhat had I done that you should seek to murder me?"
p4847
aV"How did you get out?"
p4848
aVasked Rudolph, giving way to curiosity.
p4849
aV"I climbed out."
p4850
aV"How?"
p4851
aV"By means of the wall that lined the well.
p4852
aVFinally I got hold of the\u000arope."
p4853
aV"So that was the way, was it?
p4854
aVI ought to have made surer of your fate."
p4855
aV"How could you do that?"
p4856
aV"By throwing some rocks down on you," answered the tramp, with a\u000amalignant frown.
p4857
aV"I am glad I have not such a wicked disposition as you, Rudolph," said\u000aTony, looking at him fixedly.
p4858
aV"Take care how you insult me, boy!"
p4859
aVsaid Rudolph, angrily.
p4860
aV"I have no wish to insult you.
p4861
aVNow tell me why you have lured me here?
p4862
aVI suppose you hired the boy."
p4863
aV"I did, and he did the work well," said the tramp, triumphantly.
p4864
aV"Well, now I am here, what do you want of me?"
p4865
aV"First, tell me how you happen to be in London?
p4866
aVDid you know I was\u000ahere?"
p4867
aV"I knew you crossed the Atlantic."
p4868
aV"How?"
p4869
aV"I saw you buy your ticket."
p4870
aV"What?"
p4871
aVexclaimed the tramp, in surprise.
p4872
aV"Did you reach New York so\u000asoon?"
p4873
aV"Yes.
p4874
aVI lost my situation at the inn, for they did not believe my story\u000aabout having been thrown down the well by a Quaker."
p4875
aVRudolph laughed.
p4876
aV"It was a good disguise," he said.
p4877
aV"So they discharged you?
p4878
aVThat was\u000agood."
p4879
aV"I did not think so at the time, but it proved to be the luckiest thing\u000athat could happen to me."
p4880
aV"How was that?"
p4881
aV"It led me to go to New York.
p4882
aVThere I found a rich and generous friend.
p4883
aVI have been with him ever since."
p4884
aV"As a servant?"
p4885
aV"No; as his adopted brother.
p4886
aVHe supplied me with teachers, and in\u000alittle more than six months I have acquired as much as most boys do in\u000atwo or three years."
p4887
aV"So you have gone in for education, have you?"
p4888
aVsaid Rudolph, sneering.
p4889
aV"Yes.
p4890
aVCould I go in for anything better?"
p4891
aV"And you consider yourself a young gentleman, now, do you?"
p4892
aV"That is the rank I hold in society," said Tony, calmly.
p4893
aV"And you forget that you were once Tony, the Tramp?"
p4894
aV"No, Rudolph, I have not forgotten that.
p4895
aVIt was not my fault, and I am\u000anot ashamed of it.
