aVBut we have other evidence,"\u000acontinued the lawyer.
p5255
aV"What other evidence?"
p5256
aV"The striking resemblance of my young friend to the family."
p5257
aV"Was--was he at the Haymarket Theatre last evening?"
p5258
aV"He was.
p5259
aVDid you see him?"
p5260
aV"I saw the boy I suppose you mean.
p5261
aVHe had a slight look like Mr.
p5262
aVMiddleton."
p5263
aV"He is his image."
p5264
aV"Suppose--suppose this story to be true, what do you offer me?"
p5265
aVasked\u000aMrs. Middleton, sullenly.
p5266
aV"An income of three hundred pounds from the estate," said the lawyer.
p5267
aV"If the matter comes to court, this Rugg, I am bound to tell you, has\u000aan ugly story to tell, in which you are implicated."
p5268
aVMrs. Middleton knew well enough what it meant.
p5269
aVIf the conspiracy should\u000abe disclosed, she would be ostracised socially.
p5270
aVShe rapidly made up her\u000amind.
p5271
aV"Mr. Barry," she said, "I will accept your terms, on a single\u000acondition."
p5272
aV"Name it, madame."
p5273
aV"That you will give me six weeks' undisturbed possession of the estate,\u000akeeping this matter secret meanwhile."
p5274
aV"If I knew your motive, I might consent."
p5275
aV"I will tell you in confidence.
p5276
aVWithin that time I am to be married.
p5277
aVThe abrupt disclosure of this matter might break off the marriage."
p5278
aV"May I ask the name of the bridegroom?"
p5279
aV"Captain Gregory Lovell."
p5280
aVThe lawyer smiled.
p5281
aVHe knew of Captain Lovell, and owed him a grudge.
p5282
aVHe\u000asuspected that the captain was mercenary in his wooing, and he thought\u000athat it would be a fitting revenge to let matters go on.
p5283
aV"I consent, upon my own responsibility," he said.
p5284
aV"Thank you," said Mrs. Middleton, with real gratitude.
p5285
aVShe would not lose the man she loved, after all.
p5286
aV*       *       *       *       *       *       *\u000a\u000aA month later the marriage of Captain Gregory Lovell, of Her Majesty's\u000aservice, and Mrs. Harvey Middleton, of Middleton Hall, was celebrated.
p5287
aVThere was a long paragraph in the Morning "Post," and Mrs. Lovell was\u000ahappy.
p5288
aVWhen, a week later, at Paris, the gallant captain was informed of the\u000atrick that had been played upon him, there was a terrible scene.
p5289
aVHe\u000acursed his wife, and threatened to leave her.
p5290
aV"But, Gregory, I have three hundred pounds income," she pleaded.
p5291
aV"We\u000acan live abroad."
p5292
aV"And I have sold myself for that paltry sum!"
p5293
aVhe said, bitterly.
p5294
aVBut he concluded to make the best of a bad bargain.
p5295
aVBetween them they\u000ahad an income of five hundred pounds, and on this they made shift\u000aabroad, where living is cheap.
p5296
aVBut the marriage was not happy.
p5297
aVHe was\u000abrutal at times, and his wife realized sadly that he had never loved\u000aher.
p5298
aVBut she has all the happiness she deserves, and so has he.
p5299
aVRudolph drank himself to death in six months.
p5300
aVSo the income which he\u000awas to receive made but a slight draft upon the Middleton estate.
p5301
aVAnd Tony!--no longer Tony the Tramp, but the Hon.
p5302
aVAnthony Middleton,\u000aof Middleton Hall--he has just completed a course at Oxford, and is\u000anow the possessor of an education which will help fit him for the\u000aresponsibilities he is to assume.
p5303
aVHis frank, off-hand manner makes him\u000aan immense favorite with the circle to which he now belongs.
p5304
aVHe says\u000alittle of his early history, and it is seldom thought of now.
p5305
aVHe has\u000amade a promise to his good friend, George Spencer, to visit the United\u000aStates, and will doubtless do so.
p5306
aVHe means at that time to visit once\u000amore the scenes with which he became familiar when he was A POOR\u000aBOY.
p5307
aVWHITMARSH'S REVENGE.
p5308
aVRoger Blake and Belcher Whitmarsh were both called quite good boys,\u000abut for different reasons.
p5309
aVAs their friends used sometimes to put it,\u000aBelcher was liked _because_ of his temper, and Roger was liked _in\u000aspite of_ his temper.
p5310
aVRoger was quick to fly into a passion, and as quick to get over it,\u000awhile Belcher was almost always good natured, but when once really\u000aoffended remembered the offense like an Indian.
p5311
aVThe broad play-green in front of the country schoolhouse, where the\u000aboys spent their term times together, was surrounded by trees and rocky\u000apasture lots.
p5312
aVA pretty brook ran through it.
p5313
aVOn the sides of the brook\u000aand in the rain-gulleys there were plenty of pebbles and small stones.
p5314
aVOne noon, when the boys had begun a trial of skill in firing stones at\u000aa mark, an unlucky turn was given to this small "artillery practice" by\u000athe thoughtless challenge of one of the youngsters to a playmate:\u000a\u000a"I stump you to hit _me_."
p5315
aVThe stones soon began to fly promiscuously, and the play grew more\u000alively than safe.
p5316
aVThe boys became excited and ran in all directions,\u000aexclaiming "Hit _me_, hit _me_!"
p5317
aVThe missiles were dodged with exultant\u000alaughter, and the shots returned with interest.
p5318
aVAs must be supposed, some of the players were really hit, and sore\u000aheads, and backs, and limbs made the sham skirmish before long a good\u000adeal like a real battle.
p5319
aVBelcher Whitmarsh was about the only really cool fellow on the ground.
p5320
aV"Come, fellows," he remonstrated, "this is getting dangerous.
p5321
aVWhat's\u000athe good of throwing stones when you're mad?
p5322
aVIt's poor play, any way."
p5323
aV"Ho, you're afraid," shouted Roger Blake, and in this he was joined by\u000aseveral others.
p5324
aVRoger had received one rather hard thump, and feeling quite fiery about\u000ait determined to be "even with somebody."
p5325
aVHe kept on hurling right and\u000aleft reckless of consequences.
p5326
aVBelcher paid no attention to the derision with which his words were\u000atreated.
p5327
aVHe was preparing, with one or two companions, to leave the\u000aplayground when he saw Roger near him with a heavy stone in his hand\u000adrawing back for a furious throw.
p5328
aVPartly in sport and partly out of regard for the lad aimed at, he\u000astepped behind the excited boy and caught his arm.
p5329
aVRoger whirled about instantly in a great heat.
p5330
aVAs Belcher stepped\u000aquickly backward, laughing, he let fly the stone at him with all his\u000aforce, crying:\u000a\u000a"Take it yourself, then!"
p5331
aVThe stone struck Belcher full in the face, breaking two of his front\u000ateeth and knocking him down.
p5332
aVSeeing what he had done, Blake sobered in an instant and ran to the aid\u000aof his fallen schoolfellow.
p5333
aV"I didn't mean to, Belcher," said Roger, bending over him remorsefully,\u000aand evidently afraid he had killed him.
p5334
aVThe boys began to express their indignation quite loudly, but Blake\u000amade no attempt to defend himself, only hanging over the injured lad,\u000aand declaring how sorry he was.
p5335
aV"Come," pleaded he, "try to get up, and let me help you down to the\u000aschoolhouse--I'll pay the doctor anything in the world to make you well\u000aagain."
p5336
aVBut Whitmarsh, as soon as he recovered a little, showed that he\u000aresented his sympathy as bitterly as he did his blow.
p5337
aVPushing away his hand spitefully, he staggered to his feet with the\u000ahelp of another boy, and holding his handkerchief to his bloody face\u000amoved off the green, sobbing with pain and revengeful rage.
p5338
aVBy the time school commenced he had been assisted to wash and bind up\u000ahis bleeding mouth, when he started for home, giving Roger a look which\u000awas very seldom seen on his face, but which meant plainly enough:\u000a\u000a"I'll have the worth of this out of your skin some day, see if I don't!"
p5339
aVThat afternoon the boys received a sound lecture from the teacher on\u000athe evil of throwing stones, and a penalty was imposed upon the leaders\u000ain the reckless sport, Roger among them, who, however, in consideration\u000aof his penitence, was only charged with a message to his parents,\u000amaking full confession and submitting his case entirely to their\u000ajudgment.
p5340
aVDays passed, and everything went on much as before at the school, save\u000athat Belcher Whitmarsh was missed, being at home healing his wound.
p5341
aVEvery day that his absence was noticed was to Roger's quick feelings\u000alike a new condemnation.
p5342
aVNo one was more pleased, then, than Roger Blake to see Belcher, after a\u000alittle more than a week had passed, back at his place in school.
p5343
aVHe soon found, however, that bygones were not to be bygones between\u000athem.
p5344
aVBelcher not only refused to respond to his hearty congratulations, but\u000ashowed by his manner and words (hissed through his broken teeth) that\u000aso far from forgiving Roger's offense he meant to lay it up against him.
p5345
aVSeveral times when thrown in close company with him Blake tried to\u000adisarm his dislike.
p5346
aV"Come," he would say, "now, Belch, shake hands and say quits."
p5347
aVBut Whitmarsh would only answer with a surly half threat, or grin\u000asignificantly, to expose the notch in his gums where the teeth were\u000agone.
p5348
aVThe boys saw this unreasonable dislike, and gradually transferred their\u000asympathy to Roger.
p5349
aVAt last the school closed, and though Belcher was not cordial the\u000awhole affair between the two lads seemed likely to be soon forgotten.
p5350
aVOne day during vacation, as Roger was picking whortleberries with two\u000aother boys in a lonely pasture, he was unexpectedly joined by Belcher,\u000awho had come thither on the same errand.
p5351
aVIt was not noticed that they greeted each other very differently from\u000athe usual manner of boys, and during the whole time they were together\u000aBelcher behaved himself in a way that made neither Blake nor his\u000acompanions feel any the less at ease for his company.
p5352
aVLeast of all had\u000athey any reason to suspect that he still harbored his old revenge.
p5353
aVA ruined house, many years deserted, stood in sight of the spot where\u000athe boys were picking, and growing tired of their work they agreed to\u000ago and examine the old building, and perhaps take a game of "hi spy"\u000athere.
p5354
aVAs they went over the house they found a trap-door opening into\u000aa small vault, which had evidently once been used for the family\u000acellar--for the ancient dwelling was rather cramped in size and\u000aaccommodations--and, boy-like, they all went down into the moldy hole.
p5355
aVAs the last boy was descending the rotten ladder tumbled to pieces\u000aunder his weight, and the adventurous youngsters found themselves\u000acaught like the fox and goat in the well.
p5356
aVPhilip Granger, however, being a lad of quick resources, soon hit upon\u000athe fox's plan of getting out, which was that each should climb the\u000ashoulders of a comrade, and when all but one were safely above ground\u000athese should join in pulling out the last.
p5357
aVThe plan was varied a little in practice, as it was awkward business to\u000adecide who of them should be the "goat."
p5358
aVPhil got up first, climbing over Frank Staples, and then aided his\u000ahelper out.
p5359
aVBelcher, who had made a ladder of Roger Blake, was performing the\u000apulling of his generous companion toward the opening, when a sudden\u000ayell was heard outside, and crying out "There come Dirk Avery and Ben\u000aTrench!"
p5360
aVFrank and Phil darted away, running as if for their lives.
p5361
aVSeized with their panic, Belcher instantly dropped Roger, and\u000aregardless of his terrified calls rushed from the hut in a twinkling.
p5362
aVThe jar of the hurried departure of the boys over the rickety floor\u000abrought down the trap-door with a bang, and Roger was left a prisoner\u000aindeed.
p5363
aVDirk Avery and Ben Trench were two bad characters who lived a sort of\u000ahalf-vagabond life, rarely doing any honest work, and whose savage\u000alooks and cruel natures made them the terror of all the children of the\u000aneighborhood.
p5364
aVTheir appearance in any place was the signal for a general stampede of\u000athe young people who happened to be about.
p5365
aVThere was not one in our\u000alittle whortleberry party who was not as much afraid of them as if they\u000ahad actually worn horns and hoofs.
p5366
aVOn this occasion they were out on a fishing tramp, and the contents\u000aof a bottle of cheap rum that each of them carried had made them more\u000awicked than usual.
p5367
aVAccordingly, they were in just the mood to take all possible advantage\u000aof the fright they had caused, and when the boys fled so precipitately\u000afrom the ruined house they pursued them with horrible threats and\u000ashouts of hoarse laughter.
p5368
aVFrank and Phil ran toward the lot where they had hidden their baskets,\u000athe loud voice of Dirk crying, "Skin the rascals!
p5369
aVWring their necks!"
p5370
aVDirk, however, soon overdid himself, for the two boys were fleet of\u000afoot, and saved their breath.
p5371
aVThey finally got away, with their berries.
p5372
aVBelcher struck a bee-line for home, forgetting his basket, and though\u000aBen gave him a hot chase he succeeded in distancing him.
p5373
aVPoor Roger!
p5374
aVFor some minutes after he found himself shut fast in the\u000avault his mortal fear of being found by the two roughs left him no\u000acourage to cry out, and gave him no time to think whether he ought to\u000ablame Belcher or not.
p5375
aVJudging his act by his own feelings then, he could not say but he\u000ashould have done the same.
p5376
aVBut the immediate fright soon passed, and he began to feel the real\u000amisery of his situation.
p5377
aVNobody but Whitmarsh knew where he was.
p5378
aVWhat if he _should_ leave him\u000athere, for the old grudge?
p5379
aVAnd then it came to him how singular it\u000awas that the one on whom he depended to help him out should be just\u000a_he_--the boy who had threatened him.
p5380
aVWearily enough passed the time to Roger down there in the dismal hole.
p5381
aVNeither shout nor scream would help him.
p5382
aVNo one lived within half a\u000amile of the house; or if his cries should chance to be heard it might\u000abe Avery and Trench, and they would certainly bring him more hurt than\u000agood.
p5383
aVSuddenly he heard footsteps.
p5384
aVA hand seized the trap-door and lifted it.
p5385
aVBelcher Whitmarsh's face looked into the vault.
p5386
aV"Hollo," said Roger joyfully, "I thought you'd be back before long.
p5387
aVNow\u000alet's get out of this--I've had enough of it, I'm sure."
p5388
aVBut Belcher only grinned, showing the vacancy in his front teeth, and\u000areplied coolly:\u000a\u000a"Want me to help you out?"
p5389
aV"Of course.
p5390
aVDon't be fooling now," pleaded Roger.
p5391
aV"Well," said Belcher, "I've thought it over, and seeing you're in there\u000aso nicely _I've concluded I won't_.
p5392
aVI've an old score against you.
p5393
aVPerhaps you'd like to pay it now."
p5394
aVWith that he dropped the trap-door, and made off.
p5395
aVHe had come after his basket of berries.
p5396
aVWould he be heartless enough\u000ato go home now and leave his schoolmate in that damp hole, pestilent\u000awith mildew and haunted, perhaps, by sliding adders and loathsome\u000acreatures?
p5397
aVMeantime the parents of Roger, when the hour passed at which he was\u000aexpected home, began to make inquiries for him.
p5398
aVFrank Staples and\u000aPhilip Granger, who both supposed he had climbed out of the vault and\u000aran away with Belcher from the hut, were much surprised when asked\u000awhere he was, and told that he had not returned.
p5399
aVTheir story of the encounter with Dirk Avery and Ben Trench made the\u000aparents still more anxious.
p5400
aVPossibly their boy had come to some harm at the hands of those drunken\u000aruffians.
p5401
aVWould Philip mind going over to the pasture again and showing\u000ajust where it all happened?
p5402
aVPhilip gladly consented, and getting leave from home accompanied Mr.\u000aBlake to the lot where they had gathered their berries.
p5403
aVRoger's basket was found untouched, precisely where he had been seen to\u000ahide it.
p5404
aVMr. Blake looked pale and Phil began to feel frightened.
p5405
aV"Let's go down to Mr. Whitmarsh's," said Mr. Blake, "and see Belcher."
p5406
aVIt was now about sundown, but as the old house lay not far out of the\u000away it was decided to visit it.
p5407
aVNo sooner had they reached it and looked in than Phil exclaimed, "The\u000atrap-door is shut.
p5408
aVI'm sure 'twas open when we left it."
p5409
aVIn a moment more they had uncovered the vault and found poor Roger.
p5410
aVOverjoyed, they helped him out, a good deal the worse for the hunger\u000aand fear he had undergone.
p5411
aVThe story of Belcher's mean revenge was soon noised abroad.
p5412
aVHe excused\u000ahimself by saying he meant to leave Roger only a little while for a\u000ajoke, but his father made him go to Mr. Blake's and apologize for his\u000awanton trick.
p5413
aVWe must do Belcher the justice to say that he performed the duty\u000apromptly and with apparent frankness and sincerity.
p5414
aVThere is no\u000adoubt, however, that he meant harm--not such serious harm as might\u000ahave occurred--but sufficient injury to his playfellow to satisfy his\u000amalignant feelings and glut his revenge.
p5415
aVThe spirit he exhibited was\u000athe same in kind, although not in degree, as that which makes a man a\u000amurderer.
p5416
aVA true man never allows anger to get the permanent control of his\u000afeelings.
p5417
aVHe knows its mean and dangerous tendencies, and remembers the\u000awords of Him who spake as never man spake: "If ye forgive not men their\u000atrespasses, neither will your Father forgive your trespasses."
p5418
aVTHE BOY IN THE BUSH.
p5419
aV"The impudent scoundrel!
p5420
aVJust look at this, mamma.
p5421
aVI should like to see\u000ahim at it," exclaimed Sydney Lawson in great wrath, as he handed his\u000amother a very dirty note which a shepherd had brought home.
p5422
aVOn coarse,\u000acrumpled grocer's paper these words were written in pencil:\u000a\u000a\u000a     "Master Sidney i Want your Mare the chesnit with the white starr,\u000a     soe You Send her to 3 Mile flat first thing Tomorrer Or i Shall\u000a     Have to cum an Fetch Her.
p5423
aV"WARRIGAL."
p5424
aV"Sam says," Sydney went on to say, "that the fellow was coward enough\u000ato give it him just down by the slip-panels.
p5425
aVHe wouldn't have dared to\u000atalk about sticking us up if he hadn't known father was away.
p5426
aVSend him\u000amy mare Venus!
p5427
aVI seem to see myself doing it!"
p5428
aVSidney Lawson, who made this indignant speech, was a tall, slim lad\u000aof fourteen.
p5429
aVHe and his mother had been left in charge of the station\u000awhile his father took some cattle to Port Philip.
p5430
aVSydney was very proud of his charge; he thought himself a man now, and\u000awas very angry that Warrigal, a well-known desperado, should think he\u000acould be frightened "like a baby."
p5431
aVWarrigal was a bushranger who with one or two companions wandered about\u000ain that part of New South Wales, doing pretty much as he liked.
p5432
aVThey\u000astopped the mail, and robbed draymen and horsemen on the road by the\u000atwo and three dozen together.
p5433
aVThe police couldn't get hold of them.
p5434
aVThe note that Sydney had received caused a great deal of excitement in\u000athe little station.
p5435
aVMiss Smith, who helped Mrs. Lawson in the house, and taught Sydney's\u000asisters and his brother Harry, was in a great fright.
p5436
aV"Oh!
p5437
aVpray send him the horse, Master Sydney," she cried, "or we\u000ashall all be murdered.
p5438
aVYou've got so many horses one can't make any\u000adifference."
p5439
aVMrs. Lawson was as little disposed as Sydney to let Mr. Warrigal do\u000aas he liked.
p5440
aVShe knew that her husband would have run the risk of\u000abeing "nabbed," if he had been at home, rather than have obeyed the\u000abushranger's orders; and that he would be very pleased if they could\u000amanage to defy the rascal.
p5441
aVStill it was a serious matter to provoke Messrs. Warrigal & Co. to pay\u000athe house a visit.
p5442
aVShe felt sure that Sydney would fight and she meant\u000ato fire at the robbers herself if they came; but would she and Sydney\u000abe able to stand against three armed men?
p5443
aVNot a shepherd, or stockman, or horse-breaker about the place was to\u000abe depended on; and Ki Li, the Chinaman cook, though a very good kind\u000aof fellow, would certainly go to bed in his hut if the robbers came\u000aby day, and stay in bed if the robbers came by night.
p5444
aVJohn Jones, the\u000aplowman, whose wife was Mrs. Lawson's servant, slept in the house, and\u000ahe was too honest to band with the bushrangers in any way; "but then,\u000ahe's such a _sheep_, you know, mamma," said Sydney.
p5445
aVThere was time to send word to the police in Jerry's Town; but who was\u000ato go?
p5446
aVKi Li would be afraid to go out in the dark, and John Jones would be\u000aafraid to ride anything but one of the plow horses, and that only at an\u000aamble.
p5447
aVIt wouldn't do for Sydney to leave the place, since he was the\u000aonly male on it who was to be depended upon, so what was to be done?
p5448
aVLittle Harry had heard his mother and brother talking; and as soon as\u000ahe made out their difficulty he looked up and said:\u000a\u000a"Why, mamma, _I_ can go.
p5449
aVSyd, lend me your stock-whip and let me have\u000aGuardsman."
p5450
aVNeither mother nor brother had any fear about Harry's horsemanship, but\u000athey scarcely liked to turn the little fellow out for a long ride by\u000anight.
p5451
aVHowever, he knew the way well enough, and if he did not fall in with\u000aany of the Warrigal gang nobody would harm him.
p5452
aVSo Sydney put the saddle and bridle on Guardsman and brought him\u000around to the garden-gate, where Harry stood flicking about Sydney's\u000astock-whip very impatiently, while his mamma kissed him and tied a\u000acomforter round his neck.
p5453
aVHarry shouted "Good-night," gave Guardsman his head, and was off like a\u000awild boy.
p5454
aVSydney stabled Venus, his favorite mare, and--an unusual\u000aprecaution--turned the key in the rusty padlock; and when he had given\u000aa look about the outbuildings it was time for him to go in to supper\u000aand family prayers.
p5455
aVHe read the chapter and Mrs. Lawson read the prayers.
p5456
aVShe was a brave\u000awoman, but with her little girls about her and her little boy away she\u000acouldn't keep her voice from trembling a little when she said, "Lighten\u000aour darkness, we beseech thee, O Lord; and by Thy great mercy defend us\u000afrom all perils and dangers of this night."
p5457
aVSydney went into his mother's bedroom and looked at the blunderbuss\u000athat stood by the bedhead (Mrs. Lawson had selected the blunderbuss as\u000aher weapon, because she thought she "must be sure to hit with that big\u000athing") and he showed her once more how to pull the trigger.
p5458
aVThen he bade her "good-night," and went along the veranda to his own\u000alittle room at one end, where he locked himself in, and drew the charge\u000aof his rifle and loaded it again, and looked at the chambers of his\u000arevolver, and put the caps on, and laid it down on a chair, ready to\u000ahis hand.
p5459
aVWhen his preparations were completed he said his prayers and tumbled\u000ainto bed with his clothes on.
p5460
aVHarry wasn't expected home until the next day.
p5461
aVHe had been told to\u000asleep at the tavern in Jerry's Town, when he had left his message at\u000athe barracks, and come home at his leisure in the morning.
p5462
aVAbout four miles from Wonga-Wonga, the dreariest part of the road to\u000aJerry's Town, begins a two-mile stretch of dismal scrub.
p5463
aVHarry put his\u000aheels into Guardsman's sides to make him go even faster than he was\u000agoing when they got into the scrub, and was pleased to hear a horse's\u000ahoofs coming toward him from the other end.
p5464
aVHe thought it was a neighbor riding home to the next station; but it\u000awas Warrigal.
p5465
aVAs soon as Harry pulled up Guardsman to chat a minute,\u000aWarrigal laid hold of the bridle and pulled Harry on to the saddle\u000abefore him.
p5466
aV"Let's see, you're one of the Wonga-Wonga" (that was the name of his\u000afather's station) "kids, ain't you?"
p5467
aVsaid the robber.
p5468
aV"And where are\u000ayou off to this time of night?
p5469
aVOh, oh, to fetch the traps, I guess; but\u000aI'll put a stop to that little game."
p5470
aVJust then Harry gave a _coo-ey_.
p5471
aVHe couldn't give a very loud one, for\u000ahe was lying on a sack on the robber's horse; but it made Warrigal very\u000asavage.
p5472
aVHe put the cold muzzle of a pistol against Harry's face and said, "You\u000ascreech again, youngster, and you won't do it no more."
p5473
aVAnd then Warrigal took Harry and the horses into the scrub, and gagged\u000aHarry with a bit of iron he took out of his pocket, and tied him up to\u000aa crooked old honeysuckle-tree with a long piece of rope he carried in\u000ahis saddle-bags.
p5474
aV"Don't frighten yourself, I'll tell yer mar where you are, and you'll\u000abe back by breakfast," said Warrigal, as he got on Guardsman and rode\u000aoff, driving his own tired horse before him.
p5475
aVNext morning, just as the day was breaking, Warrigal and his two mates,\u000awith crape masks on, rode up to Wonga-Wonga.
p5476
aVThey made as little noise as they could; but the dogs began to bark and\u000awoke Sydney.
p5477
aVWhen he woke, however, Warrigal had got his little window open, and was\u000acovering him with a pistol.
p5478
aVSydney put out his hand for his revolver, and though Warrigal shouted,\u000a"Throw up your hands, boy, or I'll shoot you through the head," he\u000ajumped out of bed and fired.
p5479
aVHe missed Warrigal, and Warrigal missed him; but Warrigal's bullet\u000aknocked Sydney's revolver out of his hand, and one of Warrigal's\u000amates made a butt against the bedroom door and smashed it; and he and\u000aWarrigal rushed into the room, and threw Sydney down on the bed, and\u000apinioned his arms with a sheet.
p5480
aVThe other bushranger was watching the horses.
p5481
aVBy this time the whole station was aroused.
p5482
aVThe men peeped out of their\u000ahuts, half frightened, half amused; not one of them came near the\u000ahouse.
p5483
aVJohn Jones and his wife piled their boxes against their room\u000adoor, and then crept under the bed.
p5484
aVMiss Smith went into hysterics; and Gertrude and her sisters couldn't\u000ahelp looking as white as their night-dresses.
p5485
aVMrs. Lawson had fired off her blunderbuss, but it had only broken\u000atwo panes of the parlor window, and riddled the veranda posts; so\u000aWonga-Wonga was at the bushrangers' mercy.
p5486
aVThey ransacked the house, and took possession of any little plate, and\u000ajewelry, and other portable property they could find.
p5487
aVWhen the robbers\u000ahad packed up what they called the "swag," and put it on one of their\u000ahorses, they pulled Ki Li out of bed, and made him light a fire, and\u000acook some chops and boil some tea.
p5488
aVThen they marched Mrs. Lawson, and Miss Smith, and Sydney, and his\u000asisters, and Mr. and Mrs. Jones, and Ki Li, into the keeping-room, and\u000asat down to breakfast, with pistols in their belts, and pistols laid,\u000alike knives and forks, on the table.
p5489
aVThe bushrangers tried to be funny, and pressed Mrs. Lawson and the\u000aother ladies to make themselves at home, and take a good meal.
p5490
aVOne of\u000athe robbers was going to kiss Miss Smith; but Sydney, pinioned as he\u000awas, ran at him, and butted him like a ram.
p5491
aVHe was going to strike Sydney; but Gertrude ran between them, calling\u000aout, "Oh, you great coward!"
p5492
aVand Warrigal felt ashamed, and told the\u000aman to sit down.
p5493
aV"We call him Politeful Bill," Warrigal remarked, in apology; "but he\u000aain't much used to ladies' serciety."
p5494
aVWhen breakfast was over, Warrigal asked Sydney where the mare was.
p5495
aV"Find her yourself," said Sydney.
p5496
aV"Well, there won't be much trouble about that," answered Warrigal.
p5497
aV"She's in the stable, I know; and you've locked her in, for I tried\u000athe door.
p5498
aVI suppose you are too game to give up the key, my young\u000afighting-cock?
p5499
aVBut since you're so sarcy, Master Sydney, you shall see\u000ame take your mare.
p5500
aVYou might as well ha' sent her instead of sending\u000afor the police, and then I shouldn't ha' got the bay horse too;" and he\u000apointed to Guardsman, hung up on the veranda.
p5501
aVThere was no time to ask what had become of Harry.
p5502
aVWarrigal hurried Sydney by the collar to the stable, while the other\u000amen mounted their horses, and unhooked Guardsman, to be ready for their\u000acaptain.
p5503
aVWarrigal blew off the padlock with his pistol; but Venus was fractious,\u000aand wouldn't let him put on her halter.
p5504
aVWhile he was dodging about the\u000astable with her, Sydney heard hoofs in the distance.
p5505
aVNearer and nearer\u000acame the _tan-ta-ta-tan-ta-ta-tan-ta-ta_.
p5506
aVFour bluecoats galloped up to the slip-panels, three troopers and a\u000asergeant; the sergeant with Harry on his saddlebow.
p5507
aVIn a second Harry was down, and in three seconds the slip-panels were\u000adown too.
p5508
aVThe waiting bushrangers saw the morning sun gleaming on their carbines,\u000aas the police dashed between the aloes and the prickly pears, and\u000aletting Guardsman go, were off like a shot.
p5509
aVSydney banged to the stable door; and, setting his back against it,\u000ashouted for help.
p5510
aVHis mother, Gertrude, and even John Jones, as the\u000apolice were close at hand, ran to his aid; and up galloped the troopers.
p5511
aVWarrigal fired a bullet or two through the door, and talked very big\u000aabout not being taken alive; but he thought better of it, and in an\u000ahour's time he was jogging off to Jerry's Town with handcuffs on, and\u000ahis legs tied under his horse's belly.
p5512
aVIf Warrigal had not taken up little Harry, most likely he would not\u000ahave been caught; for when Harry had got to Jerry's Town, he would have\u000afound all the troopers away except one.
p5513
aVIn the scrub, however, Harry\u000aheard the sergeant and his men returning from a wild-goose chase they\u000ahad been sent on by the bush telegraphs; and managing at last to spit\u000athe gag out of his mouth, he had given a great _co-oo-oo-oo-oo-ey_.
p5514
aVAfter that night Miss Smith always called Sydney _Mr._ Sydney; and\u000aSydney let Harry ride Venus as often as he liked.
p5515
aVTHE MIDNIGHT RIDE.
p5516
aVIt was half-a-dozen years before the war that Godfrey Brooks made a\u000avisit to his Cousin Sydney in Virginia.
p5517
aVIt was his first glimpse of\u000aplantation life, and he was not sparing of his questions or comments.
p5518
aVBoys in a strange place find it hard to carry about with them the\u000apoliteness or reticence which are such easy fitting garments at home.
p5519
aVThe two boys were standing on the piazza one sunny morning looking down\u000ato the distant swamp.
p5520
aV"You mean to tell me," said Godfrey hotly, "that gentlemen hunted their\u000arunaway slaves out of the swamp with bloodhounds?
p5521
aVBloodhounds?"
p5522
aV"No, I don't.
p5523
aVGentlemen, of course, do no such dirty work.
p5524
aVIn the\u000afirst place, our people (we don't call them slaves) never run away.
p5525
aVWhy, bless you, old Uncle Peter there, was a boy with my grandfather,\u000aand I'm sure I like him a deal better.
p5526
aVOf all the hundreds of men and\u000awomen my father owns, there's not one that don't respect and love him.
p5527
aVBut there's a class of whites who are not so respected, and when their\u000apeople escape they bring them back--that's all."
p5528
aV"It's brutal," muttered Godfrey.
p5529
aV"A man has a right to reclaim his property," said Syd coolly.
p5530
aVNow neither of the boys knew much of the intrinsic merits of the\u000aquestion.
p5531
aVThey only echoed the words and arguments their elders threw\u000aback and forth unceasingly.
p5532
aVWhen Syd began to give the details of\u000athe late hunt after a runaway horse-thief in the swamp, therefore,\u000aGodfrey's moral indignation cooled in the borrowed ardor of the chase.
p5533
aV"You see," Syd said in conclusion, "Boosey was really a criminal of\u000athe worst sort, as well as a slave, and he belonged to old Johnson.
p5534
aVJohnson's the man that owns the hounds.
p5535
aVThat's his place beyond the\u000ahill.
p5536
aVHe's a whiskey distiller, and raises slaves for the market.
p5537
aVOh,\u000aof course he's tabooed.
p5538
aVEven a decent laborer looks down on a man that\u000araises slaves for the market."
p5539
aVThe boys went out fishing presently, and Godfrey looked with a thrill\u000aof horror into the dark thicket of laurel and poisonous ivy as they\u000apassed where Boosey was still hidden.
p5540
aVDown in his secret soul there\u000awas an idea of the fierce and terrible zest of hunting anything--even\u000aa man--with a bloodhound, through that tragic dusk and quagmire.
p5541
aVIt\u000awould be akin to the gladiatorial combats between man and beast of old\u000aRome, or the bull-fights of the plaza, which his gentle Cousin Anne had\u000alearned to relish in Madrid.
p5542
aV"What do you say to riding over to Col.
p5543
aVPage's to-night?"
p5544
aVsaid Syd at\u000asupper.
p5545
aV"The girls want to practice some new music before the next\u000aparty.
p5546
aVIt's only six now.
p5547
aVWe can ride over in an hour."
p5548
aV"All right," said Godfrey.
p5549
aV"Remember, boys," said Dr. Brooks, "you are to be at home and in bed by\u000aten."
p5550
aVFor Syd's father, while he bestowed horses, guns, every accessory\u000ato pleasure upon his son with an unstinting hand, yet held a tight rein\u000aon him and never allowed him to fancy that he was a man and not in\u000areality a child.
p5551
aV"We'll be home by ten, sir," the boys said promptly.
p5552
aVNow Godfrey was but a schoolboy, and at home only snubbed and kept\u000ain place by a half-dozen grown brothers and sisters.
p5553
aVThis riding out\u000aat night, therefore, on a pony, which for the time was his own; this\u000acalling on young ladies to whom he was known as Mr. Brooks, of New\u000aYork, was an ecstatic taste of adult freedom which almost intoxicated\u000athe boy.
p5554
aVWhen nine o'clock came, and Syd beckoned him from the sofa,\u000awhere he was reading "Locksley Hall" to Miss Amelia Page, he rose so\u000aunwillingly as to cause Joe Page to look from his game of backgammon.
p5555
aV"It's too bad in the doctor to put your cousin into strict prison\u000aregulations, Syd," he said.
p5556
aV"I'll go, however, and see about your\u000ahorses."
p5557
aVHe came back with a queer twinkle in his eye.
p5558
aV"Sam declares he hitched\u000athem securely; but they're gone now.
p5559
aVSit down, boys, sit down.
p5560
aVYou may\u000aas well make the best of it.
p5561
aVThe fellows are after them.
p5562
aVThey'll be\u000ahere by and by."
p5563
aVSyd looked annoyed.
p5564
aV"I believe Joe unhitched them, himself.
p5565
aVI promised\u000afather I'd be back early."
p5566
aVHowever he sat down quietly and waited.
p5567
aVGodfrey had no annoyance to hide.
p5568
aVIt wanted but ten minutes to eleven o'clock that night when the ponies\u000awere brought to the door, and the boys, after many hand-shakings and\u000acordial invitations, were allowed to depart for home.
p5569
aVThen the glow of gallantry and manhood began to cool in Godfrey's\u000abosom, and the unpleasant tremor to take its place which was wont to\u000aovercome him when he was late at school.
p5570
aV"I say, Syd, I wish we were at home," he said, mounting.
p5571
aV"I wish we were," gloomily.
p5572
aV"Will your father be very angry?"
p5573
aV"It isn't that.
p5574
aVBut I never broke my word to him before, never.
p5575
aVI know\u000awhat he thinks of a man that breaks his word.
p5576
aVThe road is heavy.
p5577
aVIt's a\u000agood ride for an hour and a half," shutting his watch with a snap.
p5578
aV"Is there no short cut?"
p5579
aV"Yes, there's one," looking at him dubiously; "but it's through\u000aJohnson's place."
p5580
aV"The dogs--they're not loose, eh?"
p5581
aV"That I don't know.
p5582
aVHe keeps them chained in daytime, of course, but\u000awhether the scoundrel looses them at night or not I never heard.
p5583
aVIt\u000awould be just like him."
p5584
aVThe boys rode on in silence.
p5585
aVSuddenly Syd drew up with a jerk.
p5586
aV"Here's\u000athe gate into Johnson's, and I tell you what it is I must go this way,\u000adogs or no dogs.
p5587
aVI'm in honor bound to try to keep my promise as nearly\u000aas I can, no matter what lies in the way.
p5588
aVYou can ride down the hill;\u000aI'll wait for you at the house."
p5589
aV"No, sir; I'm with you," feeling himself every inch a man at the\u000achance of an adventure.
p5590
aV"Open the gate, Syd.
p5591
aVNow come on!"
p5592
aVand giving\u000atheir horses the rein they struck into a gallop down the road leading\u000aclose by Johnson's house and stables.
p5593
aVIt was so heavily covered with\u000atan-bark that the sound of the hoofs was deadened, and the boys spoke\u000ain whispers, afraid to stir the midnight silence.
p5594
aVSyd nodded toward a low kennel, back of the stables.
p5595
aV"There!"
p5596
aVhe motioned with his lips.
p5597
aV"There's where they were when they\u000atook them to hunt Boosey."
p5598
aVBut kennel and stables were silent and motionless in the cold moonlight.
p5599
aVThe tan-bark was replaced by pebbles near the house.
p5600
aVThe boys took\u000atheir ponies up on the short velvet turf, on which their swift feet\u000afell with a crisp, soft thud, a noise hardly sufficient to rouse the\u000amost watchful dog, but which drove the blood from Godfrey's cheeks.
p5601
aVHis\u000ashort-lived courage had oozed out.
p5602
aV"A man one could fight," he thought.
p5603
aV"But to be throttled like a beast\u000aby a dog."
p5604
aVThe gladiatorial fights of Rome did not thrill him so much\u000anow as the thought of them had sometimes done.
p5605
aVThud--thud.
p5606
aVEvery beat of the hoofs upon the grass sounded through the\u000aboys' brains.
p5607
aVThey were up to the kennels--past them--safe.
p5608
aVTwo minutes\u000apassed and not a sound.
p5609
aVGodfrey drew a long breath, when--hark!
p5610
aVA long, deep bay, like thunder, sounded through the night.
p5611
aV"God save us!
p5612
aVThey're loose and are after us," gasped Syd.
p5613
aVGlancing back they saw two enormous black shapes darting from behind\u000athe shadow of the porch, and coming down the slope behind them.
p5614
aV"Now, Pitch and Tar!"
p5615
aVsang out Syd, "it all rests on you."
p5616
aVHe shouted\u000aas cheerily, Godfrey thought, as though he were chasing a hare.
p5617
aVChasing\u000aand being chased were different matters, both the boys thought; though\u000athere was a reckless, gay defiance about the Southern boy which his\u000acousin lacked, courageous as he was.
p5618
aVThe ponies seemed to catch the meaning of Syd's call.
p5619
aVThey looked back.
p5620
aVTheir feet scarcely touched the sward, their nostrils were red, their\u000aeyes distended.
p5621
aVAfter the first fierce howl the dogs followed in silence.
p5622
aVThey had no\u000atime to give tongue; they had work to do.
p5623
aVA long stretch of pebbly road lay before the boys, then there was a\u000athick patch of bushes, and beyond, the gate.
p5624
aVThere was no doubt of the horses keeping up their pace.
p5625
aVTerror served\u000athem for muscle and blood.
p5626
aVBut the hounds were swifter of foot at any\u000atime.
p5627
aVThey gained with every minute.
p5628
aVThe distance was about fifty yards.
p5629
aV"Can we do it?"
p5630
aVGodfrey asked.
p5631
aVHis tongue was hot and parched.
p5632
aV"Of course we'll do it, unless the gate is locked."
p5633
aVAfter this new dread came they were silent.
p5634
aVGodfrey thought of home,\u000ahis mother, and poor little Nell; wished he had not snubbed her as he\u000aused to do.
p5635
aVSyd felt desperately in his pockets, where he found only a penknife.
p5636
aVWhy would not his father let him carry firearms as the other boys?
p5637
aVSuddenly turning to Godfrey he made a gesture, and turned his horse\u000afull on the hedge of privet.
p5638
aVIt leaped boldly--Godfrey's followed.
p5639
aVBut\u000athe hounds followed, relentless as fate, and dashed through the lower\u000abranches.
p5640
aVThey were closer than before.
p5641
aV"The gate!
p5642
aVthe gate!"
p5643
aVcried Syd.
p5644
aVHe had reached it and fumbled for the\u000abolt.
p5645
aVGodfrey, a dozen paces behind, fancied he felt the tramp of the\u000apowerful beasts shake the ground.
p5646
aVHe turned, saw them coming with open\u000ajaws, closer, closer.
p5647
aVWould the gate never open?
p5648
aVThere was a creak and crash, and it rolled\u000aback on its rusty hinges.
p5649
aVThe horses darted through so violently as to\u000athrow Godfrey on the ground.
p5650
aVWhen he looked up Syd was standing beside\u000ahim, and from the other side of the iron bars came the baffled roar of\u000athe angry beasts.
p5651
aVThe boys rode home without a word.
p5652
aV"What about reclaiming property by means of bloodhounds, Syd?"
p5653
aVasked\u000aGodfrey.
p5654
aV"It's brutal," cried Syd vehemently, and then he laughed.
p5655
aV"I tell you,\u000aGodfrey, one must actually take another man's place before he can be\u000aquite just to him, eh?"
p5656
aVA THOUSAND A YEAR.
p5657
aV"I am afraid Daniel must give up his studies," Mrs. Brooks said, sadly.
p5658
aV"I've been thinking how we are to meet the expenses of another year,\u000aand it seems quite impossible to get money enough to do so."
p5659
aV"Oh, it would be such a pity, and brother so nearly through," Susan\u000asaid, looking up in a distressed way.
p5660
aV"He mustn't leave college now,\u000awhen he is so near graduating!
p5661
aVThere _must_ be a way of helping him\u000athrough."
p5662
aVMrs. Brooks stooped to kiss the pale, tender face upturned to hers.
p5663
aV"You have a wise little head, Susan, but I am afraid there is a problem\u000ahere you cannot solve," said the widow, mournfully.
p5664
aV"How much will be needed?"
p5665
aV"At least a hundred dollars besides what he will earn himself.
p5666
aVYou know\u000athere are always extra expenses for the graduating class."
p5667
aVSusan's countenance fell.
p5668
aVIt was a great sum in her estimation, and it\u000awas already difficult for them to meet their weekly expenses.
p5669
aV"Everything depends upon brother's success," Susan said, presently.
p5670
aV"We must give up everything for him."
p5671
aV"I cannot forget I have _two_ children," the mother said, kissing the\u000agirl again more tenderly than before.
p5672
aV"Two children; but only one that will be a blessing to you," Susan\u000asaid, brushing away a tear.
p5673
aV"Don't say that, Susie.
p5674
aVI am proud of Daniel, I do not deny that--but I\u000alove you, too, all the same."
p5675
aV"But you never can be proud of me, weak and deformed as I am!
p5676
aVOh,\u000amother, why are some flowers made so beautiful and fragrant, and some\u000aso dark and noisome?
p5677
aVWhy was my brother so fair, so talented, and I so\u000arepulsive?"
p5678
aV"No, no, no, not repulsive; don't say that," the widow cried, putting\u000aher arms around the girl in a sheltering way.
p5679
aV"Do you think Daniel will let me go to see him take his diploma,\u000amother?"
p5680
aV"You would not be able, dear."
p5681
aVThe girl laughed bitterly.
p5682
aV"No; brother would say I was not able, too.
p5683
aVBut I should be glad, so\u000avery glad to see him graduate.
p5684
aVI think I would be willing to die then."
p5685
aV"Hush, my darling," the mother cried, with a sharp pain in her voice.
p5686
aV"When you are gone I shall soon follow.
p5687
aVDaniel will be satisfied with\u000ahis laurels, but women--ah, my child--women must love something, and\u000ayou are all that is left me to love."
p5688
aVSusan nestled her head in her mother's bosom without speaking, and lay\u000athere so long that her mother thought she was sleeping.
p5689
aVSuddenly she\u000aopened her eyes and said:\u000a\u000a"I have thought it all out, mother.
p5690
aVDaniel can graduate, and we will go\u000asee him take his diploma.
p5691
aVMr. Green needs girls to braid straw hats.
p5692
aVYou know I am nimble with my fingers, and I could braid a thousand a\u000ayear, and that would be how much?"
p5693
aV"But it would be wicked for me to allow you to overtask yourself in\u000athat way, darling.
p5694
aVI am not sure but it might ruin your health, feeble\u000aas you are.
p5695
aVNo, no, it is not to be thought of."
p5696
aV"How many might I undertake, mother?"
p5697
aV"Not half that amount; not a third, even."
p5698
aV"Would Daniel be willing for me to braid, do you think?"
p5699
aV"I don't know.
p5700
aVWe will ask him."
p5701
aV"Mother," Susan said, looking into her eyes, "I believe this is my\u000amission, to educate Daniel.
p5702
aVYou know we have given him everything--my\u000aportion of the property and yours.
p5703
aVI think I could hold out to do this\u000alast, and you will consent when you come to reflect upon what it will\u000abe to brother, and to you, when I am gone.
p5704
aVBut he must not know it.
p5705
aVIt\u000awould wound his pride, and he would get some false notion in his head\u000athat he could not use money I had earned in that way.
p5706
aVNow, promise me,\u000athat let what will come, you will never tell him that I braided straw\u000ahats that he might complete his education."
p5707
aV"I cannot promise _never_ to tell him, darling, because I cannot\u000aforesee the future, but I should not like him to be humbled and\u000awounded, more than yourself.
p5708
aVI am too old to learn readily, but perhaps\u000aI, too, could earn something by braiding."
p5709
aVThe determination was now fully settled in the mind of each, that the\u000ayoung man must graduate, and that the bills must be met by them.
p5710
aVThe\u000apatronage of Mr. Green was solicited, and it was agreed the work should\u000abe taken home, and that a thousand hats should be braided for ten cents\u000aeach, which he assured them was more than he would think of paying to\u000aany one else, and only to Susan in consideration of her infirmity.
p5711
aVWe ought, perhaps, to explain that Susan had been early afflicted with\u000aa curvature of the spine, which had sadly deformed her.
p5712
aVShe would never\u000ahave been a beautiful girl, Daniel having inherited not only all the\u000afamily talent, but its beauty as well.
p5713
aVBut her eyes were wondrously\u000aattractive, with their loving, yearning persuasiveness, and few could\u000aremember her deformity who had felt the warmth of her generous nature.
p5714
aVIn due time, the anticipated letter of inquiry came from Daniel,\u000aasking what the prospects were for the coming year.
p5715
aVIt was full of\u000adismal forebodings and egotistical complaints of the hard fortune that\u000amade him dependent upon his mother, but there was no regret that she\u000asuffered too; no longing to be a man that he might take this lonely\u000acouple in his strong arms and bear them tenderly over the rough places\u000aof life; only vague, ambitious dreamings of what he was to be to the\u000aworld, and the world to him.
p5716
aVThe widow laid down the letter with a sigh.
p5717
aVSusan read the pages over\u000aand over again.
p5718
aVSo grounded was she in her love for this earthly idol\u000athat the selfishness was less apparent to her than to her mother.
p5719
aVIts sadness seemed like tenderness, and he could not speak too often\u000aor too much of the genius which she believed he possessed, and which\u000awould some time break upon the world like the meteor to which he rather\u000atritely compared himself.
p5720
aV"Ah, we shall be so proud of him!"
p5721
aVSusan said, folding the letter and\u000alaying it away near her heart, where it rested many and many a day,\u000awhile she wove the strands of straw in and out, thinking how ten times\u000aten made one dollar, and how the dollars would some time count up to a\u000ahundred, and that sum, which her fingers had wrought out, would save\u000aher brother from discouragement, if not from despair.
p5722
aVThe first twenty-five dollars was earned, and the money was sent the\u000abrother.
p5723
aV"He was very glad of it," he said.
p5724
aV"He had begun to fear lest they\u000awould fail him."
p5725
aVThere was no inquiry how it had been obtained;\u000ano solicitude lest those who loved him had deprived themselves of\u000aluxuries, perhaps necessities, to meet his demands.
p5726
aVThe next twenty-five dollars was earned, with greater difficulty.
p5727
aVThe\u000awidow was awkward at braiding, and her work unsatisfactory, and so\u000asome of it was returned to Susan.
p5728
aVShe sat up later nights, that her\u000amother should not see how hard the work pressed upon her; but the\u000atwenty-five dollars came at last, and was sent to the student.
p5729
aVThen\u000athere was another letter of thanks.
p5730
aV"If you would but rest, darling," the mother would say, when some look\u000amore wan than another startled her into keener anxiety.
p5731
aV"When it is done we will rest together," was all the reply the\u000asolicitude brought.
p5732
aVIt was too late to retract now, the mother thought; and Daniel so\u000anearly through!
p5733
aVSo they pinched a little from their daily meals, a\u000alittle from the store of candles, a little from the evening fire, and\u000aprayed that every penny might be multiplied like the widow's meal.
p5734
aVOne night Mrs. Brooks had gone to bed exhausted and hysterical with\u000aoverlabor.
p5735
aVSusan pressed the blankets tenderly around her mother's\u000ashoulders, and having given her the good-night kiss, and quieted her\u000awith many promises of soon following her, she went back to the kitchen\u000afire and resumed the weary braiding.
p5736
aVShe had not completed her usual task that week, and the idea occurred\u000ato her that her mother having fallen asleep, she could braid another\u000ahat before retiring.
p5737
aVSo she set up new strands and the thin fingers\u000awove them patiently in and out, until sharp pain clutched her with\u000amerciless teeth, and she leaned forward, her head falling upon the\u000atable, in a dead faint.
p5738
aVIt was long past midnight when Susan found herself in this position.
p5739
aVShivering with cold, she crept to her mother's side and lay the\u000aremainder of the night, racked by alternate fevers and chills.
p5740
aVHow could the poor child tell her mother of what she knew was creeping\u000aso steadily toward her?
p5741
aVWould she make a final effort to save her own\u000alife and let Daniel struggle with his fortunes as he best could?
p5742
aVPoor, brave little heart, with the chill of the grave stealing over\u000ait, but warmed back into life and renewed suffering by the wonderful\u000astrength of its undying love!
p5743
aVAnother twenty five dollars was forwarded to Daniel, and a few lines\u000acame flying back by the return post, for Daniel was a man of business\u000ahabits, and punctual in all things.
p5744
aVSusan looked it all over carefully for some loving message to her; some\u000asign answering to what she felt in her own heart toward him, but there\u000awas nothing there but "_With love to Susan, I remain, etc., Daniel._"\u000a\u000aA dry sob escaped the poor child as she laid it by, and took up the\u000aweary, rustling braids.
p5745
aVThe sound rasped upon her nerves now.
p5746
aVThe very\u000aodor of the strands nauseated her.
p5747
aVEvery kink in the braids fretted\u000aher; and when one hat was finished and laid aside, it seemed such a\u000amountainous task to commence another.
p5748
aVSometimes hours would pass by without a round being accomplished, then\u000aagain the nimble fingers would be inspired, and the work would grow as\u000aof old.
p5749
aV"If I could only go and see Daniel take his diploma," she would say,\u000a"I think it would make me strong again.
p5750
aVI would wear my white muslin\u000afrock, with the blue sash, and he would not be ashamed of me."
p5751
aVBut it was not to be.
p5752
aVThe one thousand hats were braided, and Susan's\u000atask was done.
p5753
aVNothing remained for her but to lie down in her modest\u000acasket and sleep with folded hands until the blessed Saviour shall bid\u000aher approach to receive His welcome--"Well done, thou good and faithful\u000aservant."
p5754
aVDaniel returned with his collegiate honors only to listen to the sad\u000astory of her labors and death.
p5755
aVHis mother told it as they stood by the\u000acoffin.
p5756
aVThere were the worn letters she had cherished, blistered all\u000aover with tears.
p5757
aVHe was conscience stricken when he looked them over, and saw how cold\u000aand egotistical they were, and how thoughtless he had always been of\u000athe treasure that death had taken.
p5758
aVHe took the thin hands in his--the\u000ahands that had braided and plaited while he slept, and wrought out\u000athe treasure-trove that molded the key to his success, and he made\u000asolemn resolutions for the future.
p5759
aVLet us hope that, in her broken\u000alife, he learned how beautiful in the sight of God and angels is the\u000aself-sacrifice of the lowly in heart: and how much better it is to\u000adie in the struggle to bless others than it is to live to a selfish,\u000aunloving, unsanctified old age.
p5760
aVTHE END.
