aV+Captain Bayley's Heir+: A Tale of the Gold Fields of California\u000a     By G. A. HENTY.
p5931
aVWith full-page Illustrations by H. M. PAGET.
p5932
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5933
aVA frank, manly lad and his cousin are rivals in the heirship of a\u000aconsiderable property.
p5934
aVThe former falls into a trap laid by the latter,\u000aand while under a false accusation of theft foolishly leaves England\u000afor America.
p5935
aVHe works his passage before the mast, joins a small band\u000aof hunters, crosses a tract of country infested with Indians to the\u000aCalifornian gold diggings, and is successful both as digger and trader.
p5936
aV"Mr. Henty is careful to mingle instruction with entertainment;\u000a     and the humorous touches, especially in the sketch of John Holl,\u000a     the Westminster dustman, Dickens himself could hardly have\u000a     excelled."
p5937
aV--_Christian Leader._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +For Name and Fame+; or, Through Afghan Passes.
p5938
aVBy G.\u000a     A. HENTY.
p5939
aVWith full-page Illustrations by GORDON BROWNE.
p5940
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5941
aVAn interesting story of the last war in Afghanistan.
p5942
aVThe hero, after\u000abeing wrecked and going through many stirring adventures among the\u000aMalays, finds his way to Calcutta and enlists in a regiment proceeding\u000ato join the army at the Afghan passes.
p5943
aVHe accompanies the force under\u000aGeneral Roberts to the Peiwar Kotal, is wounded, taken prisoner,\u000acarried to Cabul, whence he is transferred to Candahar, and takes part\u000ain the final defeat of the army of Ayoub Khan.
p5944
aV"The best feature of the book--apart from the interest of its\u000a     scenes of adventure--is its honest effort to do justice to the\u000a     patriotism of the Afghan people."
p5945
aV--_Daily News._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Captured by Apes+: The Wonderful Adventures of a Young\u000a     Animal Trainer.
p5946
aVBy HARRY PRENTICE.
p5947
aV12mo, cloth, $1.00.
p5948
aVThe scene of this tale is laid on an island in the Malay Archipelago.
p5949
aVPhilip Garland, a young animal collector and trainer, of New York, sets\u000asail for Eastern seas in quest of a new stock of living curiosities.
p5950
aVThe vessel is wrecked off the coast of Borneo and young Garland, the\u000asole survivor of the disaster, is cast ashore on a small island and\u000acaptured by the apes that overrun the place.
p5951
aVThe lad discovers that the\u000aruling spirit of the monkey tribe is a gigantic and vicious baboon,\u000awhom he identifies as Goliah, an animal at one time in his possession\u000aand with whose instruction he had been especially diligent.
p5952
aVThe brute\u000arecognizes him, and with a kind of malignant satisfaction puts his\u000aformer master through the same course of training he had himself\u000aexperienced with a faithfulness of detail which shows how astonishing\u000ais monkey recollection.
p5953
aVVery novel indeed is the way by which the young\u000aman escapes death.
p5954
aVMr. Prentice has certainly worked a new vein on\u000ajuvenile fiction, and the ability with which he handles a difficult\u000asubject stamps him as a writer of undoubted skill.
p5955
aV+The Bravest of the Brave+; or, With Peterborough in Spain.
p5956
aVBy G. A. HENTY.
p5957
aVWith full-page Illustrations by H. M. PAGET.
p5958
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5959
aVThere are few great leaders whose lives and actions have so completely\u000afallen into oblivion as those of the Earl of Peterborough.
p5960
aVThis is\u000alargely due to the fact that they were overshadowed by the glory and\u000asuccesses of Marlborough.
p5961
aVHis career as general extended over little\u000amore than a year, and yet, in that time, he showed a genius for warfare\u000awhich has never been surpassed.
p5962
aV"Mr. Henty never loses sight of the moral purpose of his work--to\u000a     enforce the doctrine of courage and truth.
p5963
aVLads will read 'The\u000a     Bravest of the Brave' with pleasure and profit; of that we are\u000a     quite sure."
p5964
aV--_Daily Telegraph._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +The Cat of Bubastes+: A Story of Ancient Egypt.
p5965
aVBy G. A.\u000a     HENTY.
p5966
aVWith full-page Illustrations.
p5967
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5968
aVA story which will give young readers an unsurpassed insight into the\u000acustoms of the Egyptian people.
p5969
aVAmuba, a prince of the Rebu nation, is\u000acarried with his charioteer Jethro into slavery.
p5970
aVThey become inmates\u000aof the house of Ameres, the Egyptian high-priest, and are happy in his\u000aservice until the priest's son accidentally kills the sacred cat of\u000aBubastes.
p5971
aVIn an outburst of popular fury Ameres is killed, and it rests\u000awith Jethro and Amuba to secure the escape of the high-priest's son and\u000adaughter.
p5972
aV"The story, from the critical moment of the killing of the sacred\u000a     cat to the perilous exodus into Asia with which it closes, is very\u000a     skillfully constructed and full of exciting adventures.
p5973
aVIt is\u000a     admirably illustrated."
p5974
aV--_Saturday Review._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +With Washington at Monmouth+: A Story of Three Philadelphia\u000a     Boys.
p5975
aVBy JAMES OTIS.
p5976
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5977
aVThree Philadelphia boys, Seth Graydon "whose mother conducted a\u000aboarding-house which was patronized by the British officers;" Enoch\u000aBall, "son of that Mrs. Ball whose dancing school was situated on\u000aLetitia Street," and little Jacob, son of "Chris, the Baker," serve\u000aas the principal characters.
p5978
aVThe story is laid during the winter when\u000aLord Howe held possession of the city, and the lads aid the cause by\u000aassisting the American spies who make regular and frequent visits from\u000aValley Forge.
p5979
aVOne reads here of home-life in the captive city when\u000abread was scarce among the people of the lower classes, and a reckless\u000aprodigality shown by the British officers, who passed the winter in\u000afeasting and merry-making while the members of the patriot army but\u000aa few miles away were suffering from both cold and hunger.
p5980
aVThe story\u000aabounds with pictures of Colonial life skillfully drawn, and the\u000aglimpses of Washington's soldiers which are given show that the work\u000ahas not been hastily done, or without considerable study.
p5981
aV+For the Temple+: A Tale of the Fall of Jerusalem.
p5982
aVBy G. A.\u000a     HENTY, With full-page Illustrations by S. J. SOLOMON.
p5983
aV12mo, cloth, price $1,00.
p5984
aVMr. Henty here weaves into the record of Josephus an admirable and\u000aattractive story.
p5985
aVThe troubles in the district of Tiberias, the\u000amarch of the legions, the sieges of Jotapata, of Gamala, and of\u000aJerusalem, form the impressive and carefully studied historic setting\u000ato the figure of the lad who passes from the vineyard to the service\u000aof Josephus, becomes the leader of a guerrilla band of patriots,\u000afights bravely for the Temple, and after a brief term of slavery at\u000aAlexandria, returns to his Galilean home with the favor of Titus.
p5986
aV"Mr. Henty's graphic prose pictures of the hopeless Jewish\u000a     resistance to Roman sway add another leaf to his record of the\u000a     famous wars of the world."
p5987
aV--_Graphic._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Facing Death+; or, The Hero of the Vaughan Pit.
p5988
aVA Tale\u000a     of the Coal Mines.
p5989
aVBy G. A. HENTY.
p5990
aVWith full-page\u000a     Illustrations by GORDON BROWNE, 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5991
aV"Facing Death" is a story with a purpose.
p5992
aVIt is intended to show that\u000aa lad who makes up his mind firmly and resolutely that he will rise\u000ain life, and who is prepared to face toil and ridicule and hardship\u000ato carry out his determination, is sure to succeed.
p5993
aVThe hero of the\u000astory is a typical British boy, dogged, earnest, generous, and though\u000a"shamefaced" to a degree, is ready to face death in the discharge of\u000aduty.
p5994
aV"The tale is well written and well illustrated, and there is\u000a     much eanty in the characters.
p5995
aVIf any father, clergyman, or\u000a     schoolmaster is on the lookout for a good book to give as a\u000a     present to a boy who is worth his salt, this is the book we would\u000a     recommend."
p5996
aV--_Standard._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Tom Temple's Career.+ By HORATIO ALGER.
p5997
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p5998
aVTom Temple, a bright, self-reliant lad, by the death of his father\u000abecomes a boarder at the home of Nathan Middleton, a penurious\u000ainsurance agent.
p5999
aVThough well paid for keeping the boy, Nathan and his\u000awife endeavor to bring Master Tom in line with their parsimonious\u000ahabits.
p6000
aVThe lad ingeniously evades their efforts and revolutionizes the\u000ahousehold.
p6001
aVAs Tom is heir to $40,000, he is regarded as a person of\u000asome importance until by an unfortunate combination of circumstances\u000ahis fortune shrinks to a few hundreds.
p6002
aVHe leaves Plympton village to\u000aseek work in New York, whence he undertakes an important mission to\u000aCalifornia, around which center the most exciting incidents of his\u000ayoung career.
p6003
aVSome of his adventures in the far west are so startling\u000athat the reader will scarcely close the book until the last page shall\u000ahave been reached.
p6004
aVThe tale is written in Mr. Alger's most fascinating\u000astyle, and is bound to please the very large class of boys who regard\u000athis popular author as a prime favorite.
p6005
aV+Maori and Settler+: A Story of the New Zealand War.
p6006
aVBy G.\u000a     A. HENTY.
p6007
aVWith full-page Illustrations by ALFRED PEARSE.
p6008
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6009
aVThe Renshaws emigrate to New Zealand during the period of the war\u000awith the natives.
p6010
aVWilfrid, a strong, self-reliant, courageous lad, is\u000athe mainstay of the household.
p6011
aVHe has for his friend Mr. Atherton, a\u000abotanist and naturalist of herculean strength and unfailing nerve and\u000ahumor.
p6012
