p6014
aV--_Schoolmaster._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Julian Mortimer+: A Brave Boy's Struggle for Home and\u000a     Fortune.
p6015
aVBy HARRY CASTLEMON.
p6016
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6017
aVHere is a story that will warm every boy's heart.
p6018
aVThere is mystery\u000aenough to keep any lad's imagination wound up to the highest pitch.
p6019
aVThe scene of the story lies west of the Mississippi river, in the days\u000awhen emigrants made their perilous way across the great plains to the\u000aland of gold.
p6020
aVOne of the startling features of the book is the attack\u000aupon the wagon train by a large party of Indians.
p6021
aVOur hero is a lad\u000aof uncommon nerve and pluck, a brave young American in every sense of\u000athe word.
p6022
aVHe enlists and holds the reader's sympathy from the outset.
p6023
aVSurrounded by an unknown and constant peril, and assisted by the\u000aunswerving fidelity of a stalwart trapper, a real rough diamond, our\u000ahero achieves the most happy results.
p6024
aVHarry Castlemon has written many\u000aentertaining stories for boys, and it would seem almost superfluous to\u000asay anything in his praise, for the youth of America regard him as a\u000afavorite author.
p6025
aV+"Carrots:"+ Just a Little Boy.
p6026
aVBy MRS. MOLESWORTH.
p6027
aVWith Illustrations by WALTER CRANE.
p6028
aV12mo, cloth, price 75 cents.
p6029
aV"One of the cleverest and most pleasing stories it has been our\u000a     good fortune to meet with for some time.
p6030
aVCarrots and his sister\u000a     are delightful little beings, whom to read about is at once to\u000a     become very fond of."
p6031
aV--_Examiner._\u000a\u000a     "A genuine children's book; we've seen 'em seize it, and read\u000a     it greedily.
p6032
aVChildren are first-rate critics, and thoroughly\u000a     appreciate Walter Crane's illustrations."
p6033
aV--_Punch._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Mopsa the Fairy.+ By JEAN INGELOW.
p6034
aVWith Eight page\u000a     Illustrations.
p6035
aV12mo, cloth, price 75 cents.
p6036
aV"Miss Ingelow is, to our mind, the most charming of all living\u000a     writers for children, and 'Mopsa' alone ought to give her a kind\u000a     of pre-emptive right to the love and gratitude of our young folks.
p6037
aVIt requires genius to conceive a purely imaginary work which must\u000a     of necessity deal with the supernatural, without running into a\u000a     mere riot of fantastic absurdity; but genius Miss Ingelow has and\u000a     the story of 'Jack' is as careless and joyous, but as delicate, as\u000a     a picture of childhood."
p6038
aV--_Eclectic._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +A Jaunt Through Java+: The Story of a Journey to the Sacred\u000a     Mountain.
p6039
aVBy EDWARD S. ELLIS.
p6040
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6041
aVThe central interest of this story is found in the thrilling adventures\u000aof two cousins, Hermon and Eustace Hadley, on their trip across the\u000aisland of Java, from Samarang to the Sacred Mountain.
p6042
aVIn a land where\u000athe Royal Bengal tiger runs at large; where the rhinoceros and other\u000afierce beasts are to be met with at unexpected moments; it is but\u000anatural that the heroes of this book should have a lively experience.
p6043
aVHermon not only distinguishes himself by killing a full grown tiger\u000aat short range, but meets with the most startling adventure of the\u000ajourney.
p6044
aVThere is much in this narrative to instruct as well as\u000aentertain the reader, and so deftly has Mr. Ellis used his material\u000athat there is not a dull page in the book.
p6045
aVThe two heroes are brave,\u000amanly young fellows, bubbling over with boyish independence.
p6046
aVThey cope\u000awith the many difficulties that arise during the trip in a fearless way\u000athat is bound to win the admiration of every lad who is so fortunate as\u000ato read their adventures.
p6047
aV+Wrecked on Spider Island+; or, How Ned Rogers Found the\u000a     Treasure.
p6048
aVBy JAMES OTIS.
p6049
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6050
aVA "down-east" plucky lad who ships as cabin boy, not from love of\u000aadventure, but because it is the only course remaining by which he\u000acan gain a livelihood.
p6051
aVWhile in his bunk, seasick, Ned Rogers hears\u000athe captain and mate discussing their plans for the willful wreck of\u000athe brig in order to gain the insurance.
p6052
aVOnce it is known he is in\u000apossession of the secret the captain maroons him on Spider Island,\u000aexplaining to the crew that the boy is afflicted with leprosy.
p6053
aVWhile\u000athus involuntarily playing the part of a Crusoe, Ned discovers a wreck\u000asubmerged in the sand, and overhauling the timbers for the purpose\u000aof gathering material with which to build a hut finds a considerable\u000aamount of treasure.
p6054
aVRaising the wreck; a voyage to Havana under sail;\u000ashipping there a crew and running for Savannah; the attempt of the crew\u000ato seize the little craft after learning of the treasure on board, and,\u000aas a matter of course, the successful ending of the journey, all serve\u000ato make as entertaining a story of sea-life as the most captious boy\u000acould desire.
p6055
aV+Geoff and Jim+: A Story of School Life.
p6056
aVBy ISMAY THORN.
p6057
aVIllustrated by A. G. WALKER.
p6058
aV12mo, cloth, price 75 cents.
p6059
aV"This is a prettily told story of the life spent by two motherless\u000a     bairns at a small preparatory school.
p6060
aVBoth Geoff and Jim are very\u000a     lovable characters, only Jim is the more so; and the scrapes he\u000a     gets into and the trials he endures will, no doubt, interest a\u000a     large circle of young readers."
p6061
aV--_Church Times._\u000a\u000a     "This is a capital children's story, the characters\u000a     well portrayed, and the book tastefully bound and well\u000a     illustrated."
p6062
aV--_Schoolmaster._\u000a\u000a     "The story can be heartily recommended as a present for\u000a     boys."
p6063
aV--_Standard._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +The Castaways+; or, On the Florida Reefs.
p6064
aVBy JAMES OTIS.
p6065
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6066
aVThis tale smacks of the salt sea.
p6067
aVIt is just the kind of story that\u000athe majority of boys yearn for.
p6068
aVFrom the moment that the Sea Queen\u000adispenses with the services of the tug in lower New York bay till the\u000abreeze leaves her becalmed off the coast of Florida, one can almost\u000ahear the whistle of the wind through her rigging, the creak of her\u000astraining cordage as she heels to the leeward, and feel her rise to\u000athe snow-capped waves which her sharp bow cuts into twin streaks of\u000afoam.
p6069
aVOff Marquesas Keys she floats in a dead calm.
p6070
aVBen Clark, the hero\u000aof the story, and Jake, the cook, spy a turtle asleep upon the glassy\u000asurface of the water.
p6071
aVThey determine to capture him, and take a boat\u000afor that purpose, and just as they succeed in catching him a thick fog\u000acuts them off from the vessel, and then their troubles begin.
p6072
aVThey\u000atake refuge on board a drifting hulk, a storm arises and they are cast\u000aashore upon a low sandy key.
p6073
aVTheir adventures from this point cannot\u000afail to charm the reader.
p6074
aVAs a writer for young people Mr. Otis is a\u000aprime favorite.
p6075
aVHis style is captivating, and never for a moment does\u000ahe allow the interest to flag.
p6076
aVIn "The Castaways" he is at his best.
p6077
aV+Tom Thatcher's Fortune.+ By HORATIO ALGER, JR.\u000a     12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6078
aVLike all of Mr. Alger's heroes, Tom Thatcher is a brave, ambitious,\u000aunselfish boy.
p6079
aVHe supports his mother and sister on meager wages earned\u000aas a shoe-pegger in John Simpson's factory.
p6080
aVThe story begins with Tom's\u000adischarge from the factory, because Mr. Simpson felt annoyed with the\u000alad for interrogating him too closely about his missing father.
p6081
aVA few\u000adays afterward Tom learns that which induces him to start overland\u000afor California with the view of probing the family mystery.
p6082
aVHe meets\u000awith many adventures.
