p6094
aVBy JAMES OTIS.
p6095
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6096
aVThe two boys are from Portsmouth, N. H., and are introduced in August,\u000a1781, when on the point of leaving home to enlist in Col. Scammell's\u000aregiment, then stationed near New York City.
p6097
aVTheir method of traveling\u000ais on horseback, and the author has given an interesting account of\u000awhat was expected from boys in the Colonial days.
p6098
aVThe lads, after no\u000aslight amount of adventure, are sent as messengers--not soldiers--into\u000athe south to find the troops under Lafayette.
p6099
aVOnce with that youthful\u000ageneral they are given employment as spies, and enter the British\u000acamp, bringing away valuable information.
p6100
aVThe pictures of camp-life\u000aare carefully drawn, and the portrayal of Lafayette's character is\u000athoroughly well done.
p6101
aVThe story is wholesome in tone, as are all of Mr.\u000aOtis' works.
p6102
aVThere is no lack of exciting incident which the youthful\u000areader craves, but it is healthful excitement brimming with facts which\u000aevery boy should be familiar with, and while the reader is following\u000athe adventures of Ben Jaffreys and Ned Allen he is acquiring a fund of\u000ahistorical lore which will remain in his memory long after that which\u000ahe has memorized from text-books has been forgotten.
p6103
aV+Lost in the Canon+: Sam Willett's Adventures on the Great\u000a     Colorado.
p6104
aVBy ALFRED R. CALHOUN.
p6105
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6106
aVThis story hinges on a fortune left to Sam Willett, the hero, and the\u000afact that it will pass to a disreputable relative if the lad dies\u000abefore he shall have reached his majority.
p6107
aVThe Vigilance Committee of\u000aHurley's Gulch arrest Sam's father and an associate for the crime of\u000amurder.
p6108
aVTheir lives depend on the production of the receipt given for\u000amoney paid.
p6109
