aV+Frank Fowler, the Cash Boy.+ By HORATIO ALGER, JR.\u000a     12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6138
aVThrown upon his own resources Frank Fowler, a poor boy, bravely\u000adetermines to make a living for himself and his foster-sister Grace.
p6139
aVGoing to New York he obtains a situation as cash boy in a dry goods\u000astore.
p6140
aVHe renders a service to a wealthy old gentleman named Wharton,\u000awho takes a fancy to the lad.
p6141
aVFrank, after losing his place as cash\u000aboy, is enticed by an enemy to a lonesome part of New Jersey and held\u000aa prisoner.
p6142
aVThis move recoils upon the plotter, for it leads to a\u000aclue that enables the lad to establish his real identity.
p6143
aVMr. Alger's\u000astories are not only unusually interesting, but they convey a useful\u000alesson of pluck and manly independence.
p6144
aV+Budd Boyd's Triumph+; or, the Boy Firm of Fox Island.
p6145
aVBy\u000a     WILLIAM P. CHIPMAN.
p6146
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6147
aVThe scene of this story is laid on the upper part of Narragansett\u000aBay, and the leading incidents have a strong salt water flavor.
p6148
aVOwing\u000ato the conviction of his father for forgery and theft, Budd Boyd is\u000acompelled to leave his home and strike out for himself.
p6149
aVChance brings\u000aBudd in contact with Judd Floyd.
p6150
aVThe two boys, being ambitious and\u000aclear sighted, form a partnership to catch and sell fish.
p6151
aVThe scheme\u000ais successfully launched, but the unexpected appearance on the scene\u000aof Thomas Bagsley, the man whom Budd believes guilty of the crimes\u000aattributed to his father, leads to several disagreeable complications\u000athat nearly caused the lad's ruin.
p6152
aVHis pluck and good sense, however,\u000acarry him through his troubles.
p6153
aVIn following the career of the\u000aboys firm of Boyd & Floyd, the youthful reader will find a useful\u000alesson--that industry and perseverance are bound to lead to ultimate\u000asuccess.
p6154
aV+The Errand Boy+; or, How Phil Brent Won Success.
p6155
aVBy HORATIO\u000a     ALGER, JR. 12 mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6156
aVThe career of "The Errand Boy" embraces the city adventures of a smart\u000acountry lad who at an early age was abandoned by his father.
p6157
aVPhilip\u000awas brought up by a kind-hearted innkeeper named Brent.
p6158
aVThe death of\u000aMrs. Brent paved the way for the hero's subsequent troubles.
p6159
aVAccident\u000aintroduces him to the notice of a retired merchant in New York, who\u000anot only secures him the situation of errand boy but thereafter stands\u000aas his friend.
p6160
aVAn unexpected turn of fortune's wheel, however, brings\u000aPhilip and his father together.
p6161
aVIn "The Errand Boy" Philip Brent is\u000apossessed of the same sterling qualities so conspicuous in all of the\u000aprevious creations of this delightful writer for our youth.
p6162
aV+The Slate Picker+: The Story of a Boy's Life in the Coal\u000a     Mines.
p6163
aVBy HARRY PRENTICE.
p6164
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6165
aVThis is a story of a boy's life in the coal mines of Pennsylvania.
p6166
aVThere are many thrilling situations, notably that of Ben Burton's\u000aleap into the "lion's mouth"--the yawning shute in the breakers--to\u000aescape a beating at the hands of the savage Spilkins, the overseer.
p6167
aVGracie Gordon is a little angel in rags, Terence O'Dowd is a manly,\u000asympathetic lad, and Enoch Evans, the miner-poet, is a big-hearted,\u000ahonest fellow, a true friend to all whose burdens seem too heavy for\u000athem to bear.
p6168
aVBen Burton, the hero, had a hard road to travel, but\u000aby grit and energy he advanced step by step until he found himself\u000acalled upon to fill the position of chief engineer of the Kohinoor Coal\u000aCompany.
p6169
aV+A Runaway Brig+; or, An Accidental Cruise.
p6170
aVBy JAMES OTIS.
p6171
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6172
aV"A Runaway Brig" is a sea tale, pure and simple, and that's where it\u000astrikes a boy's fancy.
p6173
aVThe reader can look out upon the wide shimmering\u000asea as it flashes back the sunlight, and imagine himself afloat with\u000aHarry Vandyne, Walter Morse, Jim Libby and that old shell-back, Bob\u000aBrace, on the brig Bonita, which lands on one of the Bahama keys.
p6174
aVFinally three strangers steal the craft, leaving the rightful owners\u000ato shift for themselves aboard a broken-down tug.
p6175
aVThe boys discover\u000aa mysterious document which enables them to find a buried treasure,\u000athen a storm comes on and the tug is stranded.
p6176
aVAt last a yacht comes\u000ain sight and the party with the treasure is taken off the lonely key.
p6177
aVThe most exacting youth is sure to be fascinated with this entertaining\u000astory.
p6178
aV+Fairy Tales and Stories.+ By HANS CHRISTIAN ANDERSEN.
p6179
aVProfusely Illustrated, 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6180
aV"If I were asked to select a child's library I should name these\u000a     three volumes 'English,' 'Celtic,' and 'Indian Fairy Tales,' with\u000a     Grimm and Hans Andersen's Fairy Tales."
p6181
aV--_Independent._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +The Island Treasure+; or, Harry Darrel's Fortune.
p6182
aVBy FRANK\u000a     H. CONVERSE.
p6183
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6184
aVHarry Darrel, an orphan, having received a nautical training on a\u000aschool-ship, is bent on going to sea with a boyish acquaintance named\u000aDan Plunket.
p6185
aVA runaway horse changes his prospects.
p6186
aVHarry saves Dr.\u000aGregg from drowning and the doctor presents his preserver with a bit of\u000aproperty known as Gregg's Island, and makes the lad sailing-master of\u000ahis sloop yacht.
p6187
aVA piratical hoard is supposed to be hidden somewhere\u000aon the island.
p6188
aVAfter much search and many thwarted plans, at last Dan\u000adiscovers the treasure and is the means of finding Harry's father.
p6189
aVMr.\u000aConverse's stories possess a charm of their own which is appreciated by\u000alads who delight in good healthy tales that smack of salt water.
p6190
aV+The Boy Explorers+: The Adventures of Two Boys in Alaska.
p6191
aVBy\u000a     HARRY PRENTICE.
p6192
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6193
aVTwo boys, Raymond and Spencer Manning, travel from San Francisco to\u000aAlaska to join their father in search of their uncle, who, it is\u000abelieved, was captured and detained by the inhabitants of a place\u000acalled the "Heart of Alaska."
p6194
aVOn their arrival at Sitka the boys with\u000aan Indian guide set off across the mountains.
p6195
aVThe trip is fraught\u000awith perils that test the lads' courage to the utmost.
p6196
aVReaching the\u000aYukon River they build a raft and float down the stream, entering the\u000aMysterious River, from which they barely escape with their lives, only\u000ato be captured by natives of the Heart of Alaska.
p6197
aVAll through their\u000aexciting adventures the lads demonstrate what can be accomplished\u000aby pluck and resolution, and their experience makes one of the most\u000ainteresting tales ever written.
p6198
aV+The Treasure Finders+: A Boy's Adventures in Nicaragua.
p6199
aVBy\u000a     JAMES OTIS.
p6200
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6201
aVRoy and Dean Coloney, with their guide Tongla, leave their father's\u000aindigo plantation to visit the wonderful ruins of an ancient city.
p6202
aVThe\u000aboys eagerly explore the dismantled temples of an extinct race and\u000adiscover three golden images cunningly hidden away.
p6203
aVThey escape with\u000athe greatest difficulty; by taking advantage of a festive gathering\u000athey seize a canoe and fly down the river.
p6204
aVEventually they reach safety\u000awith their golden prizes.
p6205
aVMr. Otis is the prince of story tellers, for\u000ahe handles his material with consummate skill.
p6206
aVWe doubt if he has ever\u000awritten a more entertaining story than "The Treasure Finders."
p6207
aV+Household Fairy Tales.+ By the BROTHERS GRIMM.
p6208
aVProfusely Illustrated, 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6209
aV"As a collection of fairy tales to delight children of all ages\u000a     this work ranks second to none."
p6210
aV--_Daily Graphic._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Dan the Newsboy.+ By HORATIO ALGER, JR. 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6211
aVThe reader is introduced to Dan Mordaunt and his mother living in a\u000apoor tenement, and the lad is pluckily trying to make ends meet by\u000aselling papers in the streets of New York.
p6212
aVA little heiress of six\u000ayears is confided to the care of the Mordaunts.
p6213
aVAt the same time the\u000alad obtains a position in a wholesale house.
p6214
aVHe soon demonstrates\u000ahow valuable he is to the firm by detecting the bookkeeper in a bold\u000aattempt to rob his employers.
p6215
aVThe child is kidnaped and Dan tracks the\u000achild to the house where she is hidden, and rescues her.
p6216
aVThe wealthy\u000aaunt of the little heiress is so delighted with Dan's courage and many\u000agood qualities that she adopts him as her heir, and the conclusion of\u000athe book leaves the hero on the high road to every earthly desire.
p6217
aV+Tony the Hero+: A Brave Boy's Adventure with a Tramp.
p6218
aVBy\u000a     HORATIO ALGER, JR. 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6219
aVTony, a sturdy bright-eyed boy of fourteen, is under the control of\u000aRudolph Rugg, a thorough rascal, shiftless and lazy, spending his time\u000atramping about the country.
p6220
aVAfter much abuse Tony runs away and gets a\u000ajob as stable boy in a country hotel.
p6221
aVTony is heir to a large estate\u000ain England, and certain persons find it necessary to produce proof of\u000athe lad's death.
p6222
aVRudolph for a consideration hunts up Tony and throws\u000ahim down a deep well.
p6223
aVOf course Tony escapes from the fate provided\u000afor him, and by a brave act makes a rich friend, with whom he goes\u000ato England, where he secures his rights and is prosperous.
p6224
aVThe fact\u000athat Mr. Alger is the author of this entertaining book will at once\u000arecommend it to all juvenile readers.
p6225
aV+A Young Hero+; or, Fighting to Win.
p6226
aVBy EDWARD S. ELLIS.
p6227
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6228
aVThis story tells how a valuable solid silver service was stolen from\u000athe Misses Perkinpine, two very old and simple minded ladies.
p6229
aVFred\u000aSheldon, the hero of this story and a friend of the old ladies,\u000aundertakes to discover the thieves and have them arrested.
p6230
aVAfter much\u000atime spent in detective work, he succeeds in discovering the silver\u000aplate and winning the reward for its restoration.
p6231
aVDuring the narrative\u000aa circus comes to town and a thrilling account of the escape of the\u000alion from its cage, with its recapture, is told in Mr. Ellis' most\u000afascinating style.
p6232
aVEvery boy will be glad to read this delightful book.
p6233
aV+The Days of Bruce+: A Story from Scottish History.
p6234
aVBy\u000a     GRACE AGUILAR.
p6235
aVIllustrated, 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6236
aV"There is a delightful freshness, sincerity and vivacity about all\u000a     of Grace Aguilar's stories which cannot fail to win the interest\u000a     and admiration of every lover of good reading."
p6237
aV--_Boston Beacon._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Tom the Bootblack+; or, The Road to Success.
p6238
aVBy HORATIO ALGER, JR.\u000a     12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6239
aVA bright, enterprising lad was Tom the bootblack.
p6240
aVHe was not at all\u000aashamed of his humble calling, though always on the lookout to better\u000ahimself.
p6241
aVHis guardian, old Jacob Morton, died, leaving him a small sum\u000aof money and a written confession that Tom, instead of being of humble\u000aorigin, was the son and heir of a deceased Western merchant, and had\u000abeen defrauded out of his just rights by an unscrupulous uncle.
p6242
aVThe\u000alad started for Cincinnati to look up his heritage.
p6243
aVBut three years\u000apassed away before he obtained his first clue.
p6244
aVMr. Grey, the uncle, did\u000anot hesitate to employ a ruffian to kill the lad.
p6245
aVThe plan failed, and\u000aGilbert Grey, once Tom the bootblack, came into a comfortable fortune.
p6246
aVThis is one of Mr. Alger's best stories.
p6247
aV+Captured by Zulus+: A story of Trapping in Africa.
p6248
aVBy\u000a     HARRY PRENTICE.
p6249
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6250
aVThis story details the adventures of two lads, Dick Elsworth and Bob\u000aHarvey, in the wilds of South Africa, for the purpose of obtaining a\u000asupply of zoological curiosities.
p6251
aVBy stratagem the Zulus capture Dick\u000aand Bob and take them to their principal kraal or village.
p6252
aVThe lads\u000aescape death by digging their way out of the prison hut by night.
p6253
aVThey\u000aare pursued, and after a rough experience the boys eventually rejoin\u000athe expedition and take part in several wild animal hunts.
p6254
aVThe Zulus\u000afinally give up pursuit and the expedition arrives at the coast without\u000afurther trouble.
p6255
aVMr. Prentice has a delightful method of blending\u000afact with fiction.
p6256
aVHe tells exactly how wild-beast collectors secure\u000aspecimens on their native stamping grounds, and these descriptions make\u000avery entertaining reading.
p6257
aV+Tom the Ready+; or, Up from the Lowest.
p6258
aVBy RANDOLPH HILL.
p6259
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6260
aVThis is a dramatic narrative of the unaided rise of a fearless,\u000aambitious boy from the lowest round of fortune's ladder--the gate of\u000athe poorhouse--to wealth and the governorship of his native State.
p6261
aVThomas Seacomb begins life with a purpose.
p6262
aVWhile yet a schoolboy he\u000aconceives and presents to the world the germ of the Overland Express\u000aCo. At the very outset of his career jealousy and craft seek to\u000ablast his promising future.
p6263
aVLater he sets out to obtain a charter\u000afor a railroad line in connection with the express business.
p6264
aVNow he\u000arealizes what it is to match himself against capital.
p6265
aVYet he wins\u000aand the railroad is built.
p6266
aVOnly an uncommon nature like Tom's could\u000asuccessfully oppose such a combine.
p6267
aVHow he manages to win the battle is\u000atold by Mr. Hill in a masterful way that thrills the reader and holds\u000ahis attention and sympathy to the end.
p6268
aV+Roy Gilbert's Search+: A Tale of the Great Lakes.
p6269
aVBy WM.
p6270
aVP.\u000a     CHIPMAN.
p6271
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6272
aVA deep mystery hangs over the parentage of Roy Gilbert.
p6273
aVHe arranges\u000awith two schoolmates to make a tour of the Great Lakes on a steam\u000alaunch.
p6274
aVThe three boys leave Erie on the launch and visit many points\u000aof interest on the lakes.
p6275
aVSoon afterward the lad is conspicuous in the\u000arescue of an elderly gentleman and a lady from a sinking yacht.
p6276
aVLater\u000aon the cruise of the launch is brought to a disastrous termination\u000aand the boys narrowly escape with their lives.
p6277
aVThe hero is a manly,\u000aself-reliant boy, whose adventures will be followed with interest.
p6278
aV+The Young Scout+; The Story of a West Point Lieutenant.
p6279
aVBy\u000a     EDWARD S. ELLIS.
p6280
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6281
aVThe crafty Apache chief Geronimo but a few years ago was the most\u000aterrible scourge of the southwest border.
p6282
aVThe author has woven, in a\u000atale of thrilling interest, all the incidents of Geronimo's last raid.
p6283
aVThe hero is Lieutenant James Decker, a recent graduate of West Point.
p6284
aVAmbitious to distinguish himself so as to win well-deserved promotion,\u000athe young man takes many a desperate chance against the enemy and\u000aon more than one occasion narrowly escapes with his life.
p6285
aVThe story\u000anaturally abounds in thrilling situations, and being historically\u000acorrect, it is reasonable to believe it will find great favor with the\u000aboys.
p6286
aVIn our opinion Mr. Ellis is the best writer of Indian stories now\u000abefore the public.
p6287
aV+Adrift in the Wilds+: The Adventures of Two Shipwrecked\u000a     Boys.
p6288
aVBY EDWARD S. ELLIS.
p6289
aV12mo, cloth, price, $1.00.
p6290
aVElwood Brandon and Howard Lawrence, cousins and schoolmates,\u000aaccompanied by a lively Irishman called O'Rooney, are enroute for\u000aSan Francisco.
p6291
aVOff the coast of California the steamer takes fire.
p6292
aVThe two boys and their companion reach the shore with several of the\u000apassengers.
p6293
aVWhile O'Rooney and the lads are absent inspecting the\u000aneighborhood O'Rooney has an exciting experience and young Brandon\u000abecomes separated from his party.
p6294
aVHe is captured by hostile Indians,\u000abut is rescued by an Indian whom the lads had assisted.
p6295
aVThis is a very\u000aentertaining narrative of Southern California in the days immediately\u000apreceding the construction of the Pacific railroads.
p6296
aVMr. Ellis seems to\u000abe particularly happy in this line of fiction, and the present story is\u000afully as entertaining as anything he has ever written.
p6297
aV+The Red Fairy Book.+ Edited by ANDREW LANG.
p6298
aVProfusely Illustrated, 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6299
aV"A gift-book that will charm any child, and all older folk who\u000a     have been fortunate enough to retain their taste for the old\u000a     nursery stories."
p6300
aV--_Literary World._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +The Boy Cruisers+; or, Paddling in Florida.
p6301
aVBY ST. GEORGE\u000a     RATHBORNE.
p6302
aV12mo, cloth, price, $1.00.
p6303
aVBoys who like an admixture of sport and adventure will find this book\u000ajust to their taste.
p6304
aVWe promise them that they will not go to sleep\u000aover the rattling experiences of Andrew George and Roland Carter, who\u000astart on a canoe trip along the Gulf coast, from Key West to Tampa,\u000aFlorida.
p6305
aVTheir first adventure is with a pair of rascals who steal\u000atheir boats.
p6306
aVNext they run into a gale in the Gulf and have a lively\u000aexperience while it lasts.
p6307
aVAfter that they have a lively time with\u000aalligators and divers varieties of the finny tribe.
p6308
aVAndrew gets into\u000atrouble with a band of Seminole Indians and gets away without having\u000ahis scalp raised.
p6309
aVAfter this there is no lack of fun till they reach\u000atheir destination.
p6310
aVThat Mr. Rathborne knows just how to interest the\u000aboys is apparent at a glance, and lads who are in search of a rare\u000atreat will do well to read this entertaining story.
p6311
aV+Guy Harris+: The Runaway.
p6312
aVBY HARRY CASTLEMON.
p6313
aV12mo,\u000a     cloth, price $1.00.
p6314
aVGuy Harris lived in a small city on the shore of one of the Great\u000aLakes.
p6315
aVHis head became filled with quixotic notions of going West to\u000ahunt grizzlies, in fact, Indians.
p6316
aVHe is persuaded to go to sea, and\u000agets a glimpse of the rough side of life in a sailor's boarding house.
p6317
aVHe ships on a vessel and for five months leads a hard life.
p6318
aVHe deserts\u000ahis ship at San Francisco and starts out to become a backwoodsman, but\u000arough experiences soon cure him of all desire to be a hunter.
p6319
aVAt St.\u000aLouis he becomes a clerk and for a time he yields to the temptations of\u000aa great city.
p6320
aVThe book will not only interest boys generally on account\u000aof its graphic style, but will put many facts before their eyes in a\u000anew light.
p6321
aVThis is one of Castlemon's most attractive stories.
p6322
aV+The Train Boy.+ BY HORATIO ALGER, JR. 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6323
aVPaul Palmer was a wide-awake boy of sixteen who supported his mother\u000aand sister by selling books and papers on one of the trains running\u000abetween Chicago and Milwaukee.
p6324
aVHe detects a young man named Luke\u000aDenton in the act of picking the pockets of a young lady, and also\u000aincurs the enmity of his brother Stephen, a worthless follow.
p6325
aVLuke and\u000aStephen plot to ruin Paul, but their plans are frustrated.
p6326
aVIn a railway\u000aaccident many passengers are killed, but Paul is fortunate enough to\u000aassist a Chicago merchant, who out of gratitude takes him into his\u000aemploy.
p6327
aVPaul is sent to manage a mine in Custer City and executes his\u000acommission with tact and judgment and is well started on the road to\u000abusiness prominence.
p6328
aVThis is one of Mr. Alger's most attractive stories\u000aand is sure to please all readers.
p6329
aV+Joe's Luck+: A Boy's Adventures in California.
p6330
aVBY HORATIO\u000a     ALGER, JR. 12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6331
aVWithout a doubt Joe Mason was a lucky boy, but he deserved the golden\u000achances that fell to his lot, for he had the pluck and ambition to push\u000ahimself to the front.
p6332
aVJoe had but one dollar in the world when he stood\u000adespondently on the California Mail Steamship Co.'s dock in New York\u000awatching the preparations incident to the departure of the steamer.
p6333
aVThe same dollar was still Joe's entire capital when he landed in the\u000abustling town of tents and one-story cabins--the San Francisco of '51,\u000aand inside of the week the boy was proprietor of a small restaurant\u000aearning a comfortable profit.
p6334
aVThe story is chock full of stirring\u000aincidents, while the amusing situations are furnished by Joshua\u000aBickford, from Pumpkin Hollow, and the fellow who modestly styles\u000ahimself the "Rip-tail Roarer, from Pike Co., Missouri."
p6335
aVMr. Alger never\u000awrites a poor book, and "Joe's Luck" is certainly one of his best.
p6336
aV+Three Bright Girls+: A Story of Chance and Mischance.
p6337
aVBy\u000a     ANNIE E. ARMSTRONG.
p6338
aVWith full page Illustrations by\u000a     W. PARKINSON.
p6339
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6340
aVBy a sudden turn of fortune's wheel the three heroines of this story\u000aare brought down from a household of lavish comfort to meet the\u000aincessant cares and worries of those who have to eke out a very limited\u000aincome.
p6341
aVAnd the charm of the story lies in the cheery helpfulness of\u000aspirit developed in the girls by their changed circumstances; while the\u000aauthor finds a pleasant ending to all their happy makeshifts.
p6342
aV"The story is charmingly told, and the book can be warmly\u000a     recommended as a present for girls."
p6343
aV--_Standard._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Giannetta+: A Girl's Story of Herself.
p6344
aVBy ROSA MULHOLLAND.
p6345
aVWith full-page Illustrations by LOCKHART BOGLE.
p6346
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6347
aVThe daughter of a gentleman, who had married a poor Swiss girl, was\u000astolen as an infant by some of her mother's relatives.
p6348
aVThe child having\u000adied, they afterward for the sake of gain substitute another child for\u000ait, and the changeling, after becoming a clever modeler of clay images,\u000ais suddenly transferred to the position of a rich heiress.
p6349
aVShe develops\u000ainto a good and accomplished woman, and though the imposture of her\u000aearly friends is finally discovered, she has gained too much love and\u000adevotion to be really a sufferer by the surrender of her estates.
p6350
aV"Extremely well told and full of interest.
p6351
aVGiannetta is a true\u000a     heroine--warm-hearted, self-sacrificing, and, as all good women\u000a     nowadays are, largely touched with enthusiasm of humanity.
p6352
aVThe\u000a     illustrations are unusually good.
p6353
aVOne of the most attractive gift\u000a     books of the season."
p6354
aV--_The Academy._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Margery Merton's Girlhood.+ By ALICE CORKRAN.
p6355
aVWith\u000a     full-page Illustrations by GORDON BROWNE.
p6356
aV12mo, cloth, price $1.00.
p6357
aVThe experiences of an orphan girl who in infancy is left by her\u000afather--an officer in India--to the care of an elderly aunt residing\u000anear Paris.
p6358
aVThe accounts of the various persons who have an after\u000ainfluence on the story, the school companions of Margery, the sisters\u000aof the Conventual College of Art, the professor, and the peasantry of\u000aFontainebleau, are singularly vivid.
p6359
aVThere is a subtle attraction about\u000athe book which will make it a great favorite with thoughtful girls.
p6360
aV"Another book for girls we can warmly commend.
p6361
aVThere is a\u000a     delightful piquancy in the experiences and trials of a young\u000a     English girl who studies painting in Paris."
p6362
aV--_Saturday Review._\u000a\u000a\u000a     +Under False Colors+: A Story from Two Girls' Lives.
p6363
aVBy\u000a     SARAH DOUDNEY.
p6364
