aV.
p6858
ag6858
aVFrontispiece\u000a\u000a"All I wanted was a fayah show"\u000a\u000aFagan and Patricia\u000a\u000a"_Adis_, Seor Don Augusto"\u000a\u000a"Fought with--dishes and--knives and forks"\u000a\u000a"Dolores gazed down on her little world as it went to sleep"\u000a\u000a"With loose reins rode off to his house"\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTHE LITTLE GODS\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPROLOGUE\u000a\u000aTHE LITTLE GODS\u000a\u000a_For the life of me, as I was sitting here this sunny, late-October\u000amorning, I could not write, a distressing condition, truly, for one\u000awho lives by writing._\u000a\u000a_Outside the windows of this quiet country house lay the lean fields\u000aof New England, soberly beautiful enough in their fading autumnal\u000acolorings, but somehow yielding no inspiration--forgive the\u000apretentious and convenient word--no inspiration for my pen._\u000a\u000a_All around me my neighbors were busy; soberly engaged, each man of\u000athem, in safe-guarding himself, his body, soul, and his possessions,\u000aagainst the accidents of life and death.
p6859
aVThey too, somehow, failed\u000ato inspire that sluggish bit of pointed gold.
p6860
aVNeither do your sober\u000aneighbors, friend, as I think of them.
p6861
aVIn all essentials they might\u000abe my own.
p6862
aVFor we are all a care-worn people, we of this young West,\u000amoving always circumspectly, hedging ourselves round with a tenfold\u000awall against surprises, with creeds and codes and philosophies\u000ainnumerable, all warranted Hell-proof and Heaven-kissing._\u000a\u000a_We count him wisest who lives and loves and dies most by rule.
p6863
aVAnd\u000athe rule is that rule of our Tory Grecian forbears, "Never too much."
p6864
aV"We may be a wise people and a happy people," said I to myself, "but\u000awe are quite too prudent to be counted young, in anything but years."
p6865
aVAnd so that bit of gold hung uninspired as when it left the shop.
p6866
aVIt\u000awaited for livelier, more zestful topics than the daily grind of\u000asober middle age._\u000a\u000a_Then all at once, it seemed, familiar voices called to me from that\u000aEast we deem so old, and I was back there.
p6867
aVA street stretched\u000abeneath me, such a street as only the Far East knows, and there only\u000ain one enchanted city.
p6868
aVIt was a wide street, and a long one, all\u000aaquiver with hot, stinging sunlight.
p6869
aVIt was walled with solid,\u000afour-square houses, and above them roofs and pinnacles rose in a\u000ahundred fantastic, airy shapes for which our Western architecture has\u000ano names, and the fronts of the houses flashed with decorations of\u000abarbaric red and gold.
p6870
aVThe street flamed with them.
p6871
aVAnd all down\u000athe spacious, sun-flooded length of it, filling it from brim to brim,\u000alike a river, poured a current of tumultuous life._\u000a\u000a_From out the crowd eyes met mine, just as they used to do.
p6872
aVEyes of\u000amen intent on conquest, of goods, perhaps, or power, or pleasure, the\u000aeyes of men who sought, not soberly.
p6873
aVMocking, inviting, smiling,\u000afathomless, straightforward eyes of women, who, forgetting, or\u000aunknowing Heaven and Hell, still knew that they were women,\u000amistresses of a woman's joys and sorrows.
p6874
aVEyes of losers at the\u000agame, unhopeful but uncowed.
p6875
aVThousands of eyes glanced up at me, and\u000anot one solitary pair of them were like the eyes that look out\u000asoberly from your neighbor's head, or mine._\u000a\u000a_As my eyes questioned theirs, it seemed to me again, just as it used\u000ato do, that there in the old East, where life began, it still throbs\u000amost strongly, tingles most with the hot blood of youth; that there\u000amen, eternally young, are still most unafraid, grasp with least\u000ahesitation all life offers them, and accept the outcome of their\u000achoice with most sincerity._\u000a\u000a_As I was thinking that, it seemed to me that I went down into the\u000alife and stinging sunshine of the street, and mingled with it, till\u000aat last my steps led me down an alley and across a drawbridge that\u000aspanned a green and pestilential moat, and I approached the low\u000agateway of a gray Walled City which was old when History was young.
p6876
aVI passed under the cavern of the gate--and my feet rang on the worn\u000aflagstones as I passed--and came into a narrow street between low,\u000asombre houses without windows, and so presently to a temple which in\u000athat city bears an unpleasant reputation.
p6877
aVNot that scandal hangs\u000aabout it--it takes Christian tongues to make libertines and guzzlers\u000aof Christian priests.
p6878
aVBut it is said that for some few centuries\u000aexperiments in--in Psychical Research, let us say--have been going on\u000ain that old temple of Tzin Piau, with results that are not always\u000areassuring to a lay beholder.
p6879
aVI was in too careless a mood to care\u000afor that, that morning, and the porter let me pass, barbarian that I\u000awas, and I crossed the great courtyard and came to a little cell\u000abuilt in the thickness of the walls._\u000a\u000a_Inside the cell I saw an old, old man, a priest, though but a\u000aheathen one, half reclining on a hollowed slab of stone._\u000a\u000a_He was a very gaunt old man, but a very tall and strong one, and his\u000aface was like a mask of yellow parchment, seamed with a multitude of\u000atiny wrinkles, and his eyes were two slits set slantwise in it.
p6880
aVBut\u000aas he heard my step and looked up, they widened, and the spark of a\u000asmile glimmered in them._\u000a\u000a_"It is you again, my son?"
p6881
aVsaid that old heathen priest to me in\u000agreeting, though I did not remember having seen him before that day.
p6882
aV"What is it now?
p6883
aV"_\u000a\u000a_Suddenly I knew why I had come.
p6884
aV"My father," I said, though he was\u000abut a heathen, "I want to see Life through your eyes.
p6885
aV"_\u000a\u000a_He looked into me, and through me, and beyond me into vacancy, and\u000aas he looked the spark of laughter in his eyes danced, and flickered\u000aup into a tiny fire.
p6886
aV"You are older now," said he.
p6887
aV"Sit down.
p6888
aVI\u000awill tell you first of the Game of the Little Gods, and then you\u000ashall see Life through my eyes.
p6889
aV"_\u000a\u000a_"The Little Gods?"
p6890
aVI asked, squatting on the floor.
p6891
aVIt was the only\u000aseat he had to offer me._\u000a\u000a_"The Great God," my heathen priest explained, unheeding me and\u000asmiling into vacancy, "the Great God created us men in his own\u000aimage--and soon found us, as objects of His constant contemplation,\u000adistinctly wearisome.
p6892
aVIf He could have laughed, it would not have\u000amattered much, but Amusement is beneath the ken of a Great God.
p6893
aVTherefore our inconsistencies, our pettinesses, our hopeless\u000acontradictions, quickly wearied Him, as they would us if we had to\u000atake them seriously, forever.
p6894
aVAnd so," drawled my heathen tutor,\u000a"the Great God, at last, in self-defense, created some Little Gods to\u000atake charge of the everyday affairs of men.
p6895
aVSo far as they are Gods,\u000aof course, these Little Gods are Eternal and Impartial, far raised\u000aabove Love and Aversion, Pity and Scorn, Admiration and Derision, and\u000aall our other small emotions.
p6896
aVTo them all things are equal.
p6897
aVBut so\u000afar as they are Little, and not Great, they are capable of Amusement.
p6898
aVAnd so," said he, "those lucky Little Gods while away Eternity by\u000aplaying games, wherein we men are counters.
p6899
aVBut we men too," he\u000aadded, smiling through me into vacancy, "if we are wise, can gain\u000aamusement by looking on at the games we're part of.
p6900
aV"_\u000a\u000a_"I," said I, "have never noticed anything which looked like games--"_\u000a\u000a_"No?"
p6901
aVhe said, half mockingly.
p6902
aV"You never watched a strong man\u000astrive his utmost and grasp at last what he strove for, a handful of\u000aashes and dry leaves?
p6903
aVNever saw a woman love with all her heart,\u000atill she broke it, loving?
p6904
aVNever saw Tragedy or Comedy or Farce\u000awherein the players were not actors?
p6905
aVHave all Life's\u000acontradictions--"_\u000a\u000a_"But they've always taught me," I objected, "that in those seeming\u000acontradictions, an inscrutable Wisdom was working for the ultimate\u000agood of those--"_\u000a\u000a_"My son," said my old heathen priest, stretching his old legs out on\u000ahis stony slab, "go and see for yourself.
p6906
aVThis is the hour when I\u000atake one of my naps.
p6907
aVSee for yourself.
p6908
aV"_\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCHAPTER I\u000a\u000aFAGAN\u000a\u000aI found myself "up the railroad," as we used to say, in a\u000awell-remembered town.
p6909
aVIt had not changed since I saw it last.
p6910
aVThe\u000arailroad still ran through it, straight as a pencil-stroke ruled\u000aacross the flat lands, and the rails, on their embankment, shimmered\u000ain the sun like two unending bars of white-hot metal.
p6911
aVThe cart road\u000astill wallowed into it, and out of it, for the town is set on an\u000aisland in the marshy level of the paddies.
p6912
aVThe crazy huts of nipa,\u000aand crazier, decaying houses, still stood thick on either side of the\u000aone street.
p6913
aVAnd brown women in skirts of gaudy calico still sat under the shadow\u000aof wide shutters, dispensing such goods as Poverty can buy, while\u000atheir babies and their pigs rolled comfortably together in the dust.
p6914
aVThe shaggy thatch still rustled in the sultry breeze, and a few\u000adejected palm-trees clicked their branches as of old.
p6915
aVAnd, very far\u000aaway across the waveless green sea of the half-grown rice, the same\u000adark and threatening mountains towered into the clouds.
p6916
aVIt was all\u000aunchanged.
p6917
aVThe merciless sun struck down just as hotly.
p6918
aVThe very\u000asmells were smells I had often smelled before.
p6919
aVSuddenly there was a stir of excitement in the town.
p6920
aVThe women\u000acrawled from the litter of their wares.
p6921
aVThe men, lighting fresh\u000acigarettes from the remnants of their old ones, stood up to gaze.
p6922
aVFor down the street was coming, with the curious in-toeing shuffle of\u000aa barefoot mountaineer, a squat, huge-muscled, naked man.
p6923
aVHe carried a long, broad-bladed spear in his right hand, and a\u000ahead-axe was thrust through his belt, and at his back a bag, swollen\u000aas if it held something big and round, bobbed and dangled heavily,\u000aand something dripped from it slowly, thickly, in the dust.
p6924
aVThe\u000aman's broad, sweat-streaked face was all agrin with excitement and\u000agood-nature, but the natives of the town shrank back from him as he\u000apassed.
p6925
aV"Donde 'Mericanos?"
p6926
aVhe kept asking eagerly.
p6927
aVA bystander pointed to a house, one a little taller than the others,\u000awhere a flag of dingy white, barred with dingier red and blue, hung\u000adrooping, and a group of tall, lean, sun-bronzed men dressed in\u000afrayed shirts of blue flannel, and breeches of stained and faded\u000akhaki, and battered campaign hats, were lounging in the dusty shade.
p6928
aVThe bystander pointed to them, and the naked man, his face stretching\u000ain a wider grin, broke into a clumsy trot and ran to them.
p6929
aV"Me got," he said, and pulled the heavy, bobbing bag from his\u000ashoulders, and thrust it at them.
p6930
aVThey fell back hastily.
p6931
aV"It's\u000asomething, all right," said one of them judicially.
p6932
aV"Something\u000aplenty dead.
p6933
aVSergeant," he called, "I reckon it's your deal.
p6934
aVHere's\u000aan Igaroot with another dead-head lookin' for you."
p6935
aVAnd the others\u000alaughed.
p6936
aVAt that an oldish man with a long, drooping, gray moustache, and gray\u000aeyes that were bright below their sun-burned lids, stepped from the\u000adoor.
p6937
aVThe naked man cried out again, "Me got," and held out his\u000adripping bag.
p6938
aVAnd the saturnine old sergeant fell back, as the men\u000ahad done.
p6939
aV"You open it, Johnnie," he commanded.
p6940
aV"It's too dead for me.
p6941
aV_Patay, sabe?_  Me no likum thataway.
p6942
aV_Icao abieria_."
p6943
aVSo the man undid the string that bound his bag, and opened it, and\u000athe sergeant took one peep inside.
p6944
aV"It's a big American nigger, all\u000aright," he announced.
p6945
aV"And he's sure dead.
p6946
aVIt might be him.
p6947
aVBetter\u000acall the Captain over here, some one; I don't reckon he wants _that_\u000ain his quarters.
p6948
aVWhere you catch him, hombre?"
p6949
aVThe little man jerked his chin over his shoulder at those distant\u000amountains.
p6950
aV"You buy?"
p6951
aVhe asked anxiously.
p6952
aV"You'll get the reward all right, if it's him," said the sergeant\u000areassuringly.
p6953
aV"But you'll have to wait till it's identified.
p6954
aVThere've been a lot of duplicates brought in, _sabe_."
p6955
aVPresently other men in khaki and flannel, who in spite of their\u000aundress showed, somehow, as officers, came down the street, and they,\u000aand the sergeant, and the man with the bag, went into the house.
p6956
aVAfter a long wait, an orderly came out, pale and shaken, and turned\u000atoward the military telegraph station.
p6957
aV"It's him," he said briefly,\u000ato his waiting fellows.
p6958
aV"That Contract Dentist in there knowed him\u000aby his teeth.
p6959
aVGod!
p6960
aVI'm plumb glad I ain't no kind of medico."
p6961
aVThe men looked at each other, silently, for a long minute.
p6962
aVThe\u000aspirit of jesting seemed to have left them.
p6963
aVThe judicial one spoke\u000afirst.
p6964
aV"Well, he got _his_ good and hard at last," said he.
p6965
aV"But he\u000asure got a run for his money."
p6966
aVThen I understood what it was all about.
p6967
aVI wrote of that thing in\u000athe bag once, not knowing it then for a pawn in the Game of the\u000aLittle Gods.
p6968
aVThere was a time when men called it Fagan.
p6969
aVWhile Fagan was still a kinky-haired youngster, clad only in the\u000atraditional shirt, a question forced itself on his attention.
p6970
aV"Why\u000aain't I got a pappy?"
p6971
aVhe asked his mother, and the great,\u000adeep-bosomed woman laughed the deep, melodious laugh of her race.
p6972
aV"Lawszee, honey, I raickon you has," she replied.
p6973
aV"Mos' chillen has."
p6974
aV"Who is my pappy?"
p6975
aVthe child persisted.
p6976
aVThe woman laughed again.
p6977
aV"Lawszee, chile, how you spaik me to\u000a'maimber that?
p6978
aVI'se got other things to 'maimber, I raickon."
p6979
aVWe couldn't expect much of a Fagan, born of that race and class, and\u000ahe learned not to expect much of us.
p6980
aVA bit of food, a bit of\u000aclothing, and a chance to roll around on the levee with the other\u000apickaninnies, and bask in the sunshine and sniff the sweety-sour\u000asmells from the sugar-ships, sufficed him.
p6981
aVFor many years these\u000apleasures were his for the taking.
p6982
aVAnd as he grew older they still\u000asufficed, with the addition of a little cheap tobacco and cheaper\u000agin, and he found that a modicum of labor and a care never to offend\u000aone of the heaven-born white race would procure them.
p6983
aVThe labor was\u000aeasy, for the son of the deep-bosomed, supple-limbed woman had grown,\u000aas the rank, free growth of a swamp shoots up, into a great, broad,\u000agraceful man to whom the toil of others was mere play.
p6984
aVAnd he was of\u000aa nature so easy-going and joyous and childishly obliging that the\u000aheaven-born pointed him out with approval as "a nigger like we had\u000abefore the war."
p6985
aVHe might have lived on thus indefinitely, but one day, over a lazy\u000aroll of the dice, another black man took advantage of his known good\u000anature.
p6986
aVAnd Fagan, the kindly, felt a sudden, blinding impulse to\u000astrike.
p6987
aVThe huge black fist shot out like lightning under the\u000aimpulse of the supple, writhing muscles, and the other man dropped\u000awith a broken neck.
p6988
aVThen Fagan came to the Army, and the Army received him with joy.
p6989
aVThe\u000asurgeon's eye glistened with an artist's fervor as he thumped and\u000akneaded the great, perfect animal, and a wise old recruiting sergeant\u000aguided the pen for him to sign his name.
p6990
aVThus he was made welcome in\u000athat most catholic of societies, which cares not a whit for your\u000apast, your present, or your future, so long as you have mind and body\u000asufficient to obey orders.
p6991
aVBut even this slight requirement was much for Fagan.
p6992
aVHis careless,\u000asoapless, buttonless existence was a poor training for the rigid\u000aminuti of military life.
p6993
aVAnd he was unfortunate in his immediate\u000acommander.
p6994
aVMost of the officers of the Fifty-fourth were of the\u000aSouth, able to deal firmly yet kindly with the big black children\u000acommitted to their charge.
p6995
aVBut Sharpe was new to the Army, the son\u000aof a small tradesman in the North, and had an exalted reverence for\u000athe Regulations, and his own rank.
p6996
aVSo when he saw that the buttons\u000aof Fagan's blouse were uncleaned, one morning at guard-mounting, he\u000adid not announce the fact impersonally, as an officer should.
p6997
aVAnd Fagan, in serene ignorance of any law against immediate\u000aexplanation, replied with boyish, surprised chuckle, "Lawszee,\u000aLootenant, I raickon I plumb forgot them buttons."
p6998
aV"That's enough," snapped the officer.
p6999
aV"Sergeant, put this man under\u000aarrest."
