p7251
aVSo Fagan and Patricia must needs leave the snug little house at the\u000aend of the sleepy, grass-grown street, and go out on the High Trail,\u000athe unknown of the people of the plains, a broad highway to things\u000awith hoofs and claws and wings, and to men little less wild than\u000athey, the men of the hills.
p7252
aVAt times the brown thread of the Trail\u000awas twined amid the giant roots of trees, and they wandered in a cool\u000atwilight, alone with the long creepers and the ferns and the bright\u000abirds which played about some opening in the matted roof, far above\u000atheir heads, where the sun dropped through for a brief hour.
p7253
aVSometimes it clung to the massive walls of a caon, where a river\u000aboiled so far below that the sound of its torment came to their ears\u000alike the babble of a brook.
p7254
aVSometimes it shot upward to the realm of\u000athe clouds, and from the bare, grassy heights they peered out through\u000ashifting mist wreaths over all the cities and fields of the plains to\u000athe blue hint of the distant sea.
p7255
aVFagan and Patricia followed the Trail steadily but leisurely, day\u000aafter day.
p7256
aVThere was no call for haste, no white pursuer knew that\u000aroad.
p7257
aVSo they laughed and played, and lay for hours beside some cool\u000aspring, basking in the warm sunshine and the thin, sharp air, and\u000acamped at night in little valleys under a pall of cloud.
p7258
aVOnce Fagan\u000ashot a deer, and they delayed for days, drying the meat over pungent\u000awood-smoke.
p7259
aVBut as their muscles hardened to the Trail, they\u000ainsensibly made greater progress, in spite of their dallying.
p7260
aVTwo weeks brought them to the land of the Unknown, had they but known\u000ait.
p7261
aVThe mountains were higher and wilder, the cloud-caps more\u000afrequent.
p7262
aVOften the forest on some huge hill, towering black above\u000athe Trail, was thin and pointed at the top, as if it had been torn,\u000aand there, unseen of them, was a village perched high on the trunks\u000aof trees, whence keen-eyed men watched their progress.
p7263
aVBut they were\u000achildren of the plains and could not know, so they walked undismayed.
p7264
aVAnd the keen-eyed men walked with them, unseen, frisking along above\u000athem over ground where others would have crept--short, huge-limbed\u000amen, whose stiff black hair flowed over their shoulders, and was tied\u000aout of their eyes with fillets, men who squatted naked in the mists\u000aof evening and did not shiver, men who brought their sweethearts\u000ahideous dowries of human heads.
p7265
aVThey hung about the Trail, watching\u000athese strange creatures who walked openly and undismayed in the land\u000aof Fear.
p7266
aVOften, when the camp-fire was lighted, they stole up with\u000atheir muscles twitching like a cat's before she springs, and then\u000ahalted as a great voice rang over the forest--"I'se been wo'okin' on\u000athe ra'alroad"--and they clawed their way up the slopes to the\u000along-legged villages, and took counsel together in the queer\u000afire-shadows.
p7267
aVOne evening as they camped, Patricia missed a little bundle of\u000avenison and strolled back along the Trail to look for it.
p7268
aVFagan\u000akindled the fire and then strolled back, too.
p7269
aV"Hoy, Pats," he\u000acalled.
p7270
aVThe forest was silent.
p7271
aVHe turned a bend in the Trail, and\u000athere--Fagan gazed at it stupidly.
p7272
aVThen the blind impulse of wrath\u000aswept over him again.
p7273
aVBut there was naught to strike.
p7274
aVThe long\u000ashadows of the trees lay across the Trail, the creepers swayed lazily\u000ain the evening breeze; far up, a crow called petulantly to her\u000abelated mate.
p7275
aVFagan swung his arm helplessly at the forest.
p7276
aV"Come out," he moaned, "come out wheah I can see you.
p7277
aVCome out, you\u000acowards, you sneakin' dogs that kills women from behind.
p7278
aVI'se not\u000aafraid of you.
p7279
aVOh, I'll mash _you_!
p7280
aVCome!"
p7281
aVWith a soft chug, a\u000alance stuck quivering in the tree beside him.
p7282
aVOtherwise all was\u000asilent; even the crow had ceased to scold.
p7283
aVHe looked down.
p7284
aVA darker\u000ashadow was stealing among the lengthening ones on the Trail.
p7285
aVThe\u000aspirit of the forest gripped Fagan with an icy hand, the spirit of\u000aDread.
p7286
aVHe ran blindly to the fire, seized his rifle, and took up the\u000aTrail alone.
p7287
aVFor three days and nights he hurried on.
p7288
aVThe empty pain of his\u000astomach, the dizzying, numbing lack of sleep, could not hold him\u000aagainst the dread of his unseen escort.
p7289
aVIt gave little sign, simply\u000athe rustling of a fern now and then, the swaying of one creeper when\u000aothers were still, but he felt its presence and staggered on.
p7290
aVOn the\u000aevening of the third day, he stepped suddenly from the forest into a\u000alittle theatre among the hills.
p7291
aVA clear brook bubbled over golden\u000agravel; the turf beneath a great solitary tree was thick and soft.
p7292
aVWild cocks in the wood were crowing their families to roost.
p7293
aVEverything was quiet and peaceful, and Fagan, as he gazed, became\u000apeaceful and quiet, too.
p7294
aVHe flung himself on the soft turf, and\u000adrank his fill from the little brook.
p7295
aVAs always, when he sought to\u000arest, the forest became vague with life.
p7296
aVA covey of jungle-fowl,\u000aflushed by a sudden fright, whirred across the opening.
p7297
aVA stone\u000arolled somewhere close at hand, dislodged by a purposely careless\u000afoot.
p7298
aVBut this time Fagan merely grinned, and shook off his clinging\u000acartridge-belt.
p7299
aV"You can' bluff me no moah," he said to the forest,\u000aa trick he had learned of late.
p7300
aVA fern swayed not a dozen yards\u000aaway, and he clicked a cartridge into his Krag and fired.
p7301
aV"You git\u000aout," he chuckled.
p7302
aV"I'se a gittin' tired of you' company."
p7303
aVWhen he was rested a little, he kindled a fire and toasted a bit of\u000avenison.
p7304
aVThen he lay back lazily and twisted his last bit of tobacco\u000ainto a cigarette.
p7305
aVBetween puffs he bellowed his evening song, and\u000athe rude melody took on the sweetness of a ballad.
p7306
aV"Don' you heah\u000athe bugle callin'?"
p7307
aVFagan sang, and tossed the butt of the cigarette\u000ainto the fire.
p7308
aVIt was quite dark now in the hollow, and he sat in a\u000alittle circle of dancing light.
p7309
aVHe looked at the wall of blackness\u000awith quiet, unfrightened eyes that presently began to close with the\u000apressure of a mighty drowsiness.
p7310
aV"I'se po'owful sleepy now," he announced at length, "an' I'se a gwine\u000ato bed.
p7311
aVI was hopin' to set up an' meet some of you all, but I can't\u000ado it.
p7312
aVWhen you all wants me, you all can wake me up."
p7313
aVThe fire\u000aflickered, and he pillowed his head on his arm, and watched the dance\u000aof the shadows grow shorter.
p7314
aV"Lawszee," he murmured, drowsily, as\u000athe great numbness of sleep overcame him, "I raickon Patricia'd think\u000aI was scairt again.
p7315
aVShe'd a sat up an' waited foh them, but I can't.
p7316
aVThat little girl did have the po'owf'les' lot o' ginger in her."
p7317
aVHe\u000athrew his great arm protectingly over the empty ground beside him.
p7318
aV"Good night, Pats," he murmured.
p7319
aVIn that well-remembered town among the paddies, a squat and naked\u000aman, huge-muscled, came out of the door of the quarters.
p7320
aVIn his hand\u000ahe carried a broad-bladed spear.
p7321
aVA head-axe, bright as only\u000aspeckless steel can be in sunlight, flashed in his girdle.
p7322
aVAnd at\u000ahis back a bag, plumply round, bobbed heavily, and as it bobbed it\u000agave out a dull jingle, as of coined metal.
p7323
aV"Got his money, all right," said one of the group that watched him.
p7324
aVThe savage halted, and grinned widely at each in turn.
p7325
aV"Me got," he\u000aannounced proudly.
p7326
aV"_Mucho dinero_.
p7327
aV_Mucho mucho dinero_.
p7328
aVMe got."
p7329
aVHe could scarcely contain his joy.
p7330
aVOne of the watchers growled.
p7331
aV"I'm not in favior," said he, "of\u000apayin' gu-gus for killin' white men, no matter whether they're white\u000aor black.
p7332
aVIt's a catchin' habit."
p7333
aVIt was the judicial soldier.
p7334
aVHe\u000aswung his lean bulk toward the grinning little man.
p7335
aV"Now you've got\u000ait," he commanded, "git!"
p7336
aVThe savage, half-comprehending, turned and passed down the path they\u000aopened for him, and down the sun-beaten, dusty street, where the\u000asilent people fell away before him as if he carried pestilence.
