aVThat night, when rice was eaten and the circle of darkness had shut\u000adown about our fire, Fermin Majusay, the private of Native Scouts who\u000awas my escort on the mountain, stretched out on his slim stomach and\u000agazed into the hypnotic flames.
p7359
aV"I am going to tell you about my teniente," he said suddenly, "my\u000alieutenant who is dead six months.
p7360
aVHe was a devil, that man.
p7361
aVListen!
p7362
aVYou have sat in the Caf Puerta del Sol and watched the two\u000aold Spaniards who play forever the game called chess?
p7363
aVWell, when the\u000alittle man of Don Antonio gets in front of the little horse of Don\u000aJos, does Don Jos say, 'Bad little man, go to another little\u000asquare'?
p7364
aVNo, he says 'Muerto!'--'Dead!'
p7365
aV--and takes the little man\u000aaway.
p7366
aVThat is the game, to take all the little men off the board,\u000aand it is just the same with fighting.
p7367
aVBut all the white men I have\u000aseen, except my teniente, were afraid of the end.
p7368
aVMy teniente always\u000alaughed when the end came.
p7369
aVHe was born to be a soldier, like me.
p7370
aV"I remember how he laughed at Don Augusto.
p7371
aVWe were in a very bad\u000aprovince then.
p7372
aVAll the provinces are a little bad; that is why they\u000asent me to take care of you, because the mountains are not safe for a\u000awhite man.
p7373
aVBut that was an island in the south, and it was very bad.
p7374
aVAll the middle of it was mountains where ladrones lived, and they\u000acame down to the coast and made people give them food and money, and\u000athey stole carabaos from the plantations and killed travelers, and\u000asometimes they burned a town and took the pretty girls away.
p7375
aV"We were sent there to catch them.
p7376
aVIt was very hard work.
p7377
aVWe chased\u000athem in the mountains and killed some, but that did no good.
p7378
aVWhen we\u000awere in one place they were somewhere else, and when a man guided us\u000ain a little while he was dead.
p7379
aVWe knew what was the matter.
p7380
aVIt is\u000aalways the same.
p7381
aVThe ladrones are in the mountains, but some man in\u000athe towns is their leader, and he gets so rich and strong that every\u000aone is afraid of him.
p7382
aVIn that island it was a planter named Augusto\u000ade los Reyes.
p7383
aVThree times my lieutenant arrested Augusto de los\u000aReyes and sent him down to San Pablo; and every time the judge said\u000athere was no proof and he came back, and in a little while all the\u000awitnesses against him were dead.
p7384
aVAnd the ladrones in the mountains\u000aalways knew when we were coming.
p7385
aV"If my teniente had been like other white men, he would have given up\u000athen.
p7386
aVBut he arrested Don Augusto once more.
p7387
aVI remember the morning\u000avery well.
p7388
aVI was orderly that day, and we were in the guard-room\u000alooking at some prisoners, and a guard came in, two in front and two\u000abehind, with this Don Augusto.
p7389
aVHe was a big, fat Bisayan, and we all\u000alooked at him, and he looked at us, and smiled.
p7390
aVThen we didn't feel\u000avery good, for we knew what he'd like to do to us.
p7391
aV"But my teniente laughed when he saw him.
p7392
aVHe stood up and shook\u000ahands with Don Augusto, and he said: '_Buenos dias_, Seor Don\u000aAugusto de los Reyes.'
p7393
aVLike that, making fun.
p7394
aV'It is not very long\u000asince we met,' he said, 'but I am very glad to see you again.
p7395
aVI\u000atrust you found the prison at San Pablo pleasant?'
p7396
aV"This Don Augusto knew how to play the game, too.
p7397
aVHe smiled with his\u000amouth and said: 'It is not bad, Seor Teniente.
p7398
aVBut it grows\u000atiresome to have the comedy of going there repeated so often.
p7399
aVThe\u000ajudge gets tired, too, deciding that I am not such a bad man as my\u000afriend the teniente would have him think.'
p7400
aV"My teniente laughed again.
p7401
aV'These judges!'
p7402
aVhe said.
p7403
aV'If only they\u000acould see us as we are, Seor Don Augusto de los Reyes.
p7404
aVIt is so\u000ahard to make them understand.'
p7405
aVThen he stopped smiling, and talked\u000avery slow, more as if he talked to himself.
p7406
aV'I could send him down\u000ato San Pablo again, and I could say to the judge, "Seor Juez, this\u000ais the Seor Don Augusto de los Reyes whom the Swiss Bobin accused of\u000agiving information to the enemy, so that he lay in San Pablo jail for\u000athree weeks, till you said there was no proof."
p7407
aVAnd I could say to\u000athe judge: "Last week this innocent gentleman came back from his\u000atrial, and last Sunday, as the Swiss Bobin rode on a narrow trail,\u000afour men attacked him and cut off his hand as he drew his revolver,\u000aand then killed him."
p7408
aVBut what would that amount to?'
p7409
aV"'Very little,' said Don Augusto.
p7410
aV"'Nothing,' said my teniente.
p7411
aV'And I could tell the judge: "That\u000aSunday night men came to the house of the late Swiss Bobin and took\u000ahis woman away, and her muchacha found her next morning staked by the\u000afour hands and feet to an ant-hill."
p7412
aVBut that would be no charge\u000aagainst the Seor Don Augusto de los Reyes.'
p7413
aV"'Precisely,' said Don Augusto, and he smiled.
p7414
aVOh, he was a big,\u000aproud man, and he knew what he could do so well that he did not\u000apretend not to know.
p7415
aV"'Precisely,' said my teniente.
p7416
aV'And I could tell the judge: "The\u000atwo weeks' baby of the late widow of the late Swiss Bobin died that\u000aMonday afternoon, so to-day there is not a soul alive of the family\u000aof the man who charged an innocent gentleman unjustly, as you\u000ayourself decided, Seor Juez."
p7417
aV"Don Augusto smiled and was going to speak, but my teniente only\u000amoved his hand and went on, and all of us soldiers in the guard-room\u000aheld our breaths and listened, for we knew that he spoke the truth.
p7418
aV'We could tell the judge: "The four men who killed the man and the\u000awoman and left the baby to starve live on the plantation of the\u000aprisoner and owe him much money."
p7419
aVBut what does that prove?
p7420
aVEven if\u000awe tell him that all the enemies of the Seor Don Augusto de los\u000aReyes for twenty years have gone that way, and that no one any more\u000adares to be a witness against him for fear of his revenge, the judge\u000awill not care about that.
p7421
aVThe judge wants proof, and we have no\u000aproof.
p7422
aVNo matter how well we know each other, we have no proof.
p7423
aVSo\u000aI shall not send my dear friend down to jail again.
p7424
aVI am tired of\u000ait, too.'
p7425
aV"All we soldiers looked at the ground, for we thought our teniente\u000awas a fool, like the judge, and would let Don Augusto go again.
p7426
aVAnd\u000aDon Augusto looked at us as if we were dogs--I wanted to give him my\u000abayonet--and he smiled and said: 'I thank you so much, Teniente mio,\u000afor sparing me another of the comedies.
p7427
aVIt is better for every one.
p7428
aV_Adis_, Seor.'
p7429
aV"Oh, I told you that teniente of mine was a devil!
p7430
aVHe got up and\u000ashook the hand of Don Augusto, and he smiled and said: '_Adis_,\u000aSeor Don Augusto de los Reyes.
p7431
aVWe shall not meet again for some\u000atime, I think.
