aVJiji grew still more nervous.
p9128
aV"Okimi ca," he said at last, "I--well,\u000athe Regiment sails to-morrow."
p9129
aV"Sails?"
p9130
aVOkimi repeated dully, sliding to the floor.
p9131
aV"To America," Jiji explained.
p9132
aV"The Regiment is ordered home, and I\u000amust go with it.
p9133
aVI am a soldier."
p9134
aV"Oh," said Okimi.
p9135
aVHer face, as she huddled there on the floor, was\u000ahidden under the gay pink lining of her sleeve.
p9136
aV"America?
p9137
aVIs it--is\u000ait far to America?"
p9138
aV"Very far," he answered.
p9139
aV"Oh," said Okimi.
p9140
aVThe monkey tugged at her sleeve, and she raised\u000aher head a little.
p9141
aV"It does not matter," she said sturdily.
p9142
aV"Very\u000asoon now I shall have bought myself from Mama San.
p9143
aVI shall be free,\u000aand I will come to thee.
p9144
aVI will go anywhere for thee, so it does not\u000amatter--much.
p9145
aVPut on thy kimono."
p9146
aVJiji's nails were cutting into his palms and he did not know it.
p9147
aV"Thou canst not come, Okimi.
p9148
aVIn America I--I--" there are some\u000athings it's hard to say, even to a broken plaything.
p9149
aV"I am married\u000ain America."
p9150
aV"Oh," said Okimi.
p9151
aVShe gave the monkey a little push and he went\u000ascuttling under the bed, with shrill cries of alarm.
p9152
aV"But, oh, my\u000abeloved, let me come to thee!
p9153
aVI will be her servant.
p9154
aVLet me but\u000acome.
p9155
aVShe will not care.
p9156
aVIn Nippon are many who live so."
p9157
aV"In America," said Jiji, "they do not understand.
p9158
aVYou cannot come,\u000aOkimi.
p9159
aVIt would ruin me."
p9160
aVThen Okimi did what all her sisters of the East, and some not of the\u000aEast, have learned to do.
p9161
aVShe bowed her head and said very quietly:\u000a"Thou knowest what is best for thee.
p9162
aVIt shall be so."
p9163
aVThe little monkey, in the silence, poked out his head and looked up\u000aat big Jiji with a quick, silent grin, as a frightened monkey will.
p9164
aVAnd Jiji, looking down at the gay rumpled figure at his feet, said\u000asomething that sounded like "Godamit."
p9165
aVThen he cleared his throat\u000avery harshly.
p9166
aV"_Sayonara, Okimi ca_," he muttered.
p9167
aV"_Sayonara de\u000agans_," and he laughed unsteadily as he went out.
p9168
aV"_Sayonara_, Jiji San," said Okimi.
p9169
aVFor a long time she lay quite still.
p9170
aVSo long that the frightened,\u000acurious monkey crept out to look about him.
p9171
aVHe stretched out his\u000aclaw-like hand and plucked inquiringly at the gay bundle on the\u000afloor.
p9172
aVOkimi did not stir, and he drew back his lips in a nervous\u000agrin.
p9173
aVHe made a little rush and grinned back inquiringly at the\u000abundle, another and another, and took heart.
p9174
aVThe flame attracted\u000ahim, and he scrambled to the dresser and stood face to face with\u000aBuddh.
p9175
aVHe jumped back with his grin of frightened surprise, but\u000aBuddh did not even deign to look at him.
p9176
aVAfter a moment he sidled\u000acloser, glancing with quick hard eyes now at the bundle, now at the\u000agod.
p9177
aVAt last he stretched out his tiny brown hand and touched\u000aBuddh's knee.
p9178
aVHe dipped a wee finger in Buddh's perfumed oil, and\u000atasted it.
p9179
aVThen he dipped in both hands and splattered, as you have\u000aseen a baby in its bath, and grinned up maliciously, ready to run.
p9180
aVBut Buddh gazed straight ahead, unmoved, and the monkey, bold at\u000alast, gave the orange a most tremendous little shove.
p9181
aVIt tottered,\u000aand bumped down to the floor, and went rolling under the bed, and the\u000amonkey followed it with shrill little cries of triumph.
p9182
aVThe noise startled Okimi and she raised her head.
p9183
aVThen she went\u000ablindly over to Buddh, ugly, wrinkled, good little Buddh, who sat\u000across-legged and protected her.
p9184
aVShe patted the ridiculous little\u000adough-cakes with lingering, caressing hands, and stirred the spray of\u000aflowers so that they gave out their sweetest odor.
p9185
aVShe bent very low\u000abefore the god.
p9186
aV"Mighty Buddh," she pleaded, "he is my sooeetart.
p9187
aVI am just a little\u000agirl, and I love him.
p9188
aVPlease give him back to me, dear Buddh."
p9189
aVShe looked up at him timidly, seeking assurance, but he did not smile\u000aback at her.
p9190
aVShe was going to say more, trying to make Buddh\u000aunderstand how extremely important it was, but just then Mama San\u000aknocked at the door and told her she must come down-stairs.
p9191
aVSo Okimi dabbed on the rouge, and smoothed out her gay silken kimono,\u000aand took her samisen, and hurried down as fast as she could with her\u000afunny little toed-in steps.
p9192
aVCHAPTER VIII\u000a\u000aWHERE THERE IS NO TURNING\u000a\u000aAgain the swaying lamps burned dim above us, and the priestess of\u000aLal, all trembling, looked up at me with terror-haunted eyes.
p9193
aV"Poor little child," she whispered.
p9194
aV"Poor little life-mocked child!
p9195
aVThat is the bitter fate which women fear, to be sucked dry of their\u000afresh sweetness, of their life, and then be tossed aside.
p9196
aVOh, I have\u000aseen it many times.
p9197
aVWe give our all, and it is wasted because men--"\u000a\u000a"Not all men," I said.
p9198
aV"Not all men are like Okimi's warrior\u000asweetheart."
p9199
aV"They are all alike," cried the priestess of Lal vehemently.
p9200
aV"In\u000atheir hearts they are all alike, lighter than air, unstabler than\u000awater, more fickle than nectar-seeking butterflies.
p9201
aVThey love our\u000abeauty, and when that is gone--  Look you," she cried.
p9202
aV"This is the\u000atragedy of a woman, to be beautiful, to be loved, and to grow old.
p9203
aVLook," she said.
p9204
aV"I will show you."
p9205
aVOnce again the light of the silver lamps was quenched, and silent,\u000aside by side, the priestess of Lal and I looked far down the weary\u000apath which Eastern women travel not knowing where an end shall be.
p9206
aVIn all the ride from Segovia along the beach, Hazlitt met only three\u000aliving things, three women staring at him out of the folds of dingy\u000acalico which shielded their faces from the glare of sun and sea.
p9207
aVOne\u000awas young and very graceful; another was not so young, a comely,\u000aox-like thing, laden with comfortable fat.
p9208
aVThe third was old and\u000abent, with a hideously wrinkled, hopeless face, the mask of that\u000aimpatient death which shrivels away the women of the hot Eastern\u000aworld, outside and in.
p9209
aVFor a moment they startled him.
p9210
aVThey were\u000alike phantoms risen to confront him on the lifeless beach, for the\u000ayoungest was but a memory of what the eldest had been a little time\u000abefore, and the eldest only a prophecy of what the youngest soon\u000awould be.
p9211
aVAs they stood and watched him passing by, shifting their\u000aworn feet uneasily on the blistering sand, Hazlitt felt a mild\u000astirring of pity at the familiar sight.
p9212
aV"Hoy, friends," he hailed them.
p9213
aV"Can one of you tell me the way to\u000athe plantation of Don Raymundo?"
p9214
aVThe girl looked at him shyly under lowered lids; the grandmother,\u000asquatting on her haunches, puffed at a ragged fragment of cigar she\u000acarried and gazed out to sea; but the mother clutched volubly at the\u000aopportunity of speech.
p9215
aV"Go on till you come to the mango which blew down in the typhoon of\u000aten years ago," she said, "and the road is there.
p9216
aVIt is called the\u000a'Trail that has no Turning.'
p9217
aVDon Raymundo is a Castilian of the\u000anoblest, and he is the richest _haciendero_ in the world.
p9218
aVEach year\u000ahe loads a hundred ships with sugar.
p9219
aVThe plantation is called the\u000a'Hacienda without a Name.'
p9220
aVDon Raymundo has a daughter whose name is\u000aSeorita Dolores.
p9221
aVShe is the most beautiful woman in the world.
p9222
aVHis\u000awife is Doa Ceferina."
p9223
aVFor a moment a look of dislike crossed the\u000abroad, good-natured face.
p9224
aV"They call her Doa, and she is very\u000aproud, but after all she is just a mestizo, almost a Filipina like\u000aus.
p9225
aVShe--"\u000a\u000aHazlitt broke into her chatter with his thanks, flipped a coin in the\u000aair, and jogged on till he had left them far behind, three moving\u000adots on the waste, plodding the way of Malay womenfolk.
p9226
aVHidden in the green-shrouded wilderness of the lower hills, the\u000aHacienda without a Name lay under the sunset enchanting as a lost\u000afragment of some old world, where labor next the soil was the\u000ahappiest thing in life.
p9227
aVAnd up in the _sala_ of the great house on\u000athe hill, the mistress of the _hacienda_ stared at Hazlitt over her\u000acup.
p9228
aVShe was a beautiful woman, but under the Caucasian mold of her\u000afeatures another face was beginning to show dimly, the face of a race\u000awhose very heat and strength of life fuses all lines down to mere\u000ashapelessness of flesh.
p9229
aVA part of Doa Ceferina had been overtaken\u000aby the unrelenting advance of middle age.
p9230
aV"You say my husband is a prince, Seor?"
p9231
aVDoa Ceferina echoed\u000adoubtfully over her cup, and her soft forehead wrinkled in\u000abewilderment.
p9232
aVThis strange young visitor had puzzling notions of\u000awhat constitutes conversation, a diversion of which Doa Ceferina was\u000aextremely fond.
p9233
aV"Without doubt," she said, "I think that is a\u000amistake."
p9234
aVHazlitt looked at her in mingled amusement and vexation.
p9235
aVIn all his\u000awonderful day of discovery, this talkative, commonplace woman had\u000abeen the sole jarring note.
p9236
aVBut Doa Ceferina, oblivious to his\u000aemotions, sat in the cool twilight of the big room and poised her\u000acup, like some hybrid goddess of justice about to render a decision.
p9237
aV"Beyond doubt, it is a mistake," said Doa Ceferina.
p9238
aV"Don Raymundo's\u000afamily is one of the oldest in Spain, but it has never married with\u000aroyalty.
p9239
aVThere are few princes in Spain not of the royal blood; it\u000ais not like Russia."
p9240
aVThe word gave her a clue to a topic of real\u000ainterest, and she brightened.
p9241
aV"When I was a girl, back at school, I\u000amet a Russian prince, one summer at Biarritz--"\u000a\u000aOver _his_ cup, Don Raymundo's tiny Mephistophelian moustache lifted\u000aslightly in the mocking smile which was his extremest expression of\u000aemotion, and Hazlitt rushed to the righting of his false lead.
p9242
aV"Of course I did not mean that Don Raymundo was a prince in name," he\u000aexplained, "but in fact, you know."
p9243
aVDoa Ceferina raised her cup and sipped her chocolate resignedly, but\u000aHazlitt did not heed her.
p9244
aV"The startling, the wonderful thing to an American like me is that he\u000ais not only a prince in power, but a prince of another age.
p9245
aVThe\u000apeople here on the plantation are his, belong to him personally.
p9246
aVTake that thing we saw just now, for example, all those hundreds of\u000apeople coming in to the plantation kitchen for their suppers--"\u000a\u000aDoa Ceferina rose to her opportunity.
p9247
aV"If you only knew," she said,\u000a"how much rice it takes to feed five thousand people--"\u000a\u000aHazlitt, brimming with the enthusiasm the day had brought him, swept\u000aon.
p9248
aV"Think of having a jail of your own, and putting people in it\u000awhen you like, being their law!
p9249
aVWhy, I dare say they'd follow him to\u000awar if he told them to, and--and sack the next plantation.
p9250
aVIt's--it's positively feudal, you know.
p9251
aVThat's the only word; all\u000athis doesn't belong to our day at all.
p9252
aVAnd yet they say there's no\u000aromance left in trade!"
p9253
aVHe stopped abruptly, for Doa Ceferina was gazing at him with round\u000aeyes.
p9254
aVIf one could picture the eyes of a ruminative cow, watching\u000awith mild curiosity a serpent which sought to charm her, one would\u000ahave seen the eyes of Doa Ceferina just then.
p9255
aVDon Raymundo smiled\u000ainscrutably, and the pause grew awkward.
p9256
aVSuddenly a soft voice came to Hazlitt's relief.
p9257
aV"You remember\u000a'feudal,' mama," it said reassuringly.
p9258
aV"Ever so long ago, when they\u000ahad knights and squires and--and _gens-d'armes_, and people lived in\u000acastles, and they had the Inquisition in Spain, and the friars,\u000aand--and everything.
p9259
aVThat was 'feudal.'"
p9260
aVDoa Ceferina sighed with relief and sipped: "Dolores has just come\u000aback from school, so she remembers all those things," she explained\u000ato Hazlitt.
p9261
aV"I learned them once, of course, but one forgets, out\u000ahere.
p9262
aVAnd so you think we're feudal?
p9263
aVI don't know, I'm sure.
p9264
aVOf\u000acourse there aren't any knights any more, or castles, but we _do_\u000ahave the friars.
p9265
aVListen, seor," and she set her cup on a little\u000atable, to give freedom to her hands, and plunged into the story of\u000athe latest exaction by the local representative of the hierarchy of\u000athe Philippines.
p9266
aVNo one minded her much.
p9267
aVHer husband sat with half-closed eyes and\u000apuffed at his cigarette, Dolores turned to her window and gazed down\u000aon her little world as it went to sleep, and Hazlitt's eyes persisted\u000ain wandering to the girlish figure, glowing in a belated, ruddy shaft\u000aof light.
p9268
aVDecidedly, the talkative woman on the beach had shown some\u000adiscrimination in placing Seorita Dolores on the pinnacle of beauty.
p9269
aVSuddenly Hazlitt became aware that Doa Ceferina's tale was told, and\u000athat her talk had taken a more personal turn.
p9270
aV[Illustration: "_Dolores gazed down on her little world as it went to\u000asleep._"]\u000a\u000a"It's so good to have one from our own world to talk to again," she\u000asaid enthusiastically.
p9271
aV"One gets lonely here, with only natives for\u000aneighbors.
p9272
aVI tremble to think what my existence would have been,\u000aafter I came back from school, if Don Raymundo had not been here to\u000arescue me."
p9273
aVShe smiled radiantly at her black and white spouse, as\u000aif to include him in the conversation, but he only drew long on his\u000acigarette and puffed the smoke very deliberately toward the ceiling.
p9274
aVHazlitt's eyes wandered to the window again, and Doa Ceferina's\u000afollowed them.
p9275
aV"Isn't she beautiful?"
p9276
aVshe whispered.
p9277
aV"Yes," said Hazlitt, half to himself.
p9278
aV"She's like a Madonna, a\u000aMadonna whom some great man dreamed of painting and gave up in\u000adespair."
p9279
aV"Exactly," Doa Ceferina agreed hastily.
p9280
aV"That's just it.
p9281
aVShe's\u000abeautiful as the Virgin herself, and good!
p9282
aVPoor child, after three\u000ayears of Paris and Madrid, to come back to this!"
p9283
aVShe swept an\u000aover-jeweled hand at the great, simple, dignified room.
p9284
aV"No wonder\u000ashe's lonely, poor little dear.
p9285
aVGo and talk to her, Seor Hasleet."
p9286
aVHazlitt accepted his permission with alacrity.
p9287
aVAs he approached,\u000aDoa Dolores glanced timidly at him across the gulf of sex, which\u000atradition and training had fixed between her and all male things not\u000aof her blood, and retreated into herself.
p9288
aVHer shyness was part of\u000aher attraction, Hazlitt thought, and did not find the silence awkward\u000aas he stood beside her and looked down with her on the _hacienda_.
p9289
aVIn the shaggy village clustered about the squat stone chimney of the\u000amill, groups of girls and young men were laughing and splashing about\u000athe wells; from the little groves which embowered the houses, the\u000aevening fires glowed red; the light breeze carried, even to that\u000adistance, a hint of the pungent wood-smoke.
p9290
aVAs Hazlitt watched the\u000apeaceful scene, all the love of the open which had led him wandering\u000athrough life rolled over him in a wave.
p9291
aV"Jove, it's a good old world, after all," he said.
p9292
aVThe girl glanced up at him quickly.
p9293
aV"After all?"
p9294
aVshe echoed\u000aplaintively.
p9295
aV"Tell me, seor.
p9296
aVThe Sisters always said that the\u000aworld was bad, and we must be afraid of it.
p9297
aVWhen you speak so,\u000a_saying_ that it is good, I wonder if you also do not think it is\u000abad.
p9298
aVWhy isn't it good, if we are happy in it?"
p9299
aVHazlitt smiled down into her puzzled eyes.
p9300
aVDecidedly they were\u000amatter-of-fact, these women of the _hacienda_.
p9301
aV"It is good," he\u000aassured her, with the calm philosophy of his thirty years behind him.
p9302
aV"Of course it's good."
p9303
aVStill she looked up at him, forgetting her\u000ashyness, and a gust of protectiveness and elder-brotherly affection\u000afor this tender, budding woman-thing took hold of him.
p9304
aV"It's good,"\u000ahe urged, "and you will always be happy in it."
p9305
aVBack in the dimness Doa Ceferina was sipping her third cup of\u000achocolate, while Raymundo smoked with half shut eyes and smiled\u000ainscrutably.
p9306
aVLike Dorcas or Abigail or whoever she was of old, Doa Ceferina sat\u000aamong her maidens.
p9307
aVThere were half a dozen of them on the floor,\u000asewing and spinning and chattering in subdued voices, while the\u000amistress of the _hacienda_ sat enthroned in the midst of them.
p9308
aVBut\u000aunlike whoever she was of old, Doa Ceferina had a card-table before\u000aher, and on the other side of the table Hazlitt sat, and the two\u000asmiled companionably across at each other as they sorted fat bundles\u000aof cards.
p9309
aVThey were playing _panguingui_.
p9310
aVOne plays _panguingui_ with six\u000apacks of cards and much patience.
p9311
aVDoa Ceferina and Hazlitt had\u000aplayed a good deal of it since they first met, six months before, and\u000aHazlitt's patience had never wearied.
p9312
aVNeither had the patience of\u000aSeorita Dolores, which is more to the point, for she had to stand\u000abehind Hazlitt's chair and help him with the unfamiliar cards.
p9313
aVShe\u000awas standing there now.
p9314
aV"Hazleet, it is your lead," said Doa Ceferina, gathering up her\u000ahand.
p9315
aVIt was a sign of the fellowship established between them that\u000ashe called him Hazlitt in the good, round, Spanish way, without any\u000afuss over titles.
p9316
aVIt was a stronger sign that she sat with her feet\u000atucked up in her chair, native-fashion.
p9317
aV"One gets used to it," she\u000ahad explained, the first time she ventured it in his presence, "and\u000ait's much more comfortable."
p9318
aV"Hazleet, I shall beat you again," said Doa Ceferina.
p9319
aV"Lead!"
p9320
aVHazlitt laid his finger inquiringly on a card, and looked back over\u000ahis shoulder, where a pair of interested eyes signalled approval.
p9321
aVSuddenly he spied a forgotten card down in the corner of his fistful.
p9322
aVSeorita Dolores gave a small wail of dismay as he played it, and\u000aDoa Ceferina smiled in pleasant derision.
p9323
aV"I mistook it for a King," said Hazlitt in apology.
p9324
aV"It is a mistake," said the remorseless Doa Ceferina, "which costs\u000ayou a _media peseta_.
p9325
aVNow play again."
p9326
aVHazlitt played again and again, and lost each time, and enjoyed Doa\u000aCeferina's little triumph almost as much as she did.
p9327
aVShe wasn't half\u000abad, if she was not exciting, this plump good-natured Doa Ceferina,\u000awith her eternal cigarette and her cards or novel or conversation.
p9328
aVHazlitt smiled whimsically at that last thought.
p9329
aV"What are you\u000alaughing at, Hazleet?"
p9330
aVhis opponent demanded.
p9331
aVHe had been thinking of the Frenchwoman who was famed for having such\u000aa marvellous gift for conversation, and none at all for dialogue, but\u000ahe couldn't very well tell Doa Ceferina that.
p9332
aV"At the way I'm\u000aplaying," he replied.
p9333
aV"You couldn't well play worse," said Doa Ceferina good-humoredly,\u000ataking toll of her bit of silver.
p9334
aV"Lead again."
p9335
aVHazlitt _could_ play worse, and promptly did it.
p9336
aVThere are infinite\u000apossibilities of badness, even in _panguingui_.
p9337
aVNot at all a bad\u000aperson to share a secret with, this simple, matter-of-fact Doa\u000aCeferina.
p9338
aVAnd he believed they were sharing one.
p9339
aVIn Doa Ceferina's\u000aplacidly romantic bosom, he guessed, had grown a vision of a young\u000aprince come out of the West to rescue her imprisoned princess from\u000athis tropical Castle of Indolence.
p9340
aVA vision had come to him, too, a\u000avision which made him lean back and forget his cards.
p9341
aVSix months ago\u000aa beach-comber, gilded and respectable, of course, but still a\u000abeach-comber, an adventurer, without a country; and now, perhaps, a\u000aman whom many a petty prince might envy.
p9342
aVFancy ruling undisputed\u000awith Seorita Dolores over the quiet domain of the "Hacienda without\u000aa Name!"
p9343
aVJove, what a queen she'd make.
p9344
aVA hand stole down over his and pityingly pointed out the proper card,\u000aand Hazlitt sternly repressed an impulse to fling away the cards and\u000atake the hand, and keep it.
p9345
aVThe time was drawing near when he must\u000aput his fortune to the test.
p9346
aVThe cards ran out, and Doa Ceferina glowed triumphant.
p9347
aV"Another\u000agame, Hazleet?"
p9348
aVshe asked.
p9349
aVHazlitt laughingly turned his pocket out to show that the modest sum\u000aallotted for the stakes of the day was exhausted, and Doa Ceferina\u000aswept up her little heap of silver.
p9350
aV"You play worse than ever, I\u000athink," she said frankly.
p9351
aV"Still, I may learn _panguingui_ before I die," said Hazlitt.
p9352
aVA\u000asudden impulse seized him.
p9353
aVHe leaned forward and fixed the mistress\u000aof the _hacienda_ with his eye.
p9354
aV"I rather think, Doa Ceferina," he\u000asaid, with slow emphasis, "that I shall have to stay out here till I\u000adie.
p9355
aVThere seems to be no escape.
p9356
aVI shall have to stay and--learn\u000ato play _panguingui_.
p9357
aVWhat do you think?"
p9358
aVIn the heavy eyes of Doa Ceferina a small glow kindled, as of the\u000asurviving remnants of a very tiny fire.
p9359
aVHazlitt had seen them light\u000athat way before, when Doa Ceferina reached the climax of a novel.
p9360
aVThe glow deepened, and she looked at his understandingly.
p9361
aVHer hand\u000atrembled a little on the table.
p9362
aV"Why not, Hazleet?"
p9363
aVshe said.
p9364
aV"It--it would be very pleasant for all of us.
p9365
aVI--"  She rose\u000ahastily.
p9366
aV"I shall have to leave you for a minute.
p9367
