aVAbruptly, as if a sudden thought had\u000acome to him, he rose and filled the glasses, emptying the bottle.
p10375
aV"Gentlemen," he cried, holding his glass aloft, "I ask for bottoms\u000aup.
p10376
aVTo the Seor Ess-soffti, the prince of mascots.
p10377
aVMay he live\u000along and die busy."
p10378
aVThe glasses clinked and were emptied.
p10379
aVMr. Roe\u000aset his on the table.
p10380
aV"Good night, gentlemen," he said, and departed.
p10381
aVBut his progress was soon interrupted.
p10382
aVBlinded by the sudden\u000adarkness of the deck, he lost his way, and was nearly sent sprawling\u000aby the legs of a man who sat huddled on a settee, a shabby little\u000aman, even in the dark.
p10383
aV"What the devil," Mr. Roe began, with lofty\u000adispleasure.
p10384
aVHe checked himself.
p10385
aV"I beg your pardon, I'm sure," he\u000asaid with the elaborate courtesy of one who, having the divine right\u000ato be insolent, yet chooses to be kind.
p10386
aVShrinking as at a blow, the shabby little man drew in his legs.
p10387
aVEven\u000ain the gloom the movement had an appealing humbleness about it that\u000awent to the ready sympathy of Mr. Richard Roe.
p10388
aV"It's all right, old\u000achap," he said.
p10389
aV"No harm done.
p10390
aVGood night."
p10391
aVThe shabby little man mumbled something inarticulate, and Mr. Roe,\u000aimmaculate, self-sufficient, free from care, strode on and left his\u000amascot staring blindly out at the dim, jumbled waters flashing by.
