aVCHAPTER XI\u000a\u000aMCGENNIS'S PROMOTION\u000a\u000aMy third adventurer was of still another type, a young man, a boy, if\u000ayou like, who was fresh and unsullied in body and mind and heart,\u000awith life all before him.
p10396
aVThe opponents he fought with were all\u000ainside himself, and of the worth of what he won you shall judge for\u000ayourselves.
p10397
aVWithin a minute or two of six o'clock that morning the sun rose, and\u000ait was broad, staring day.
p10398
aVOne instant the world was smothered in a\u000adamp, impenetrable, almost tangible grayness; the next, its nakedness\u000alay discovered in a glare of light.
p10399
aVThere was a sea of limpid lukewarm water heaving slowly; a ribbon of\u000abeach, metallic-white; a tangle of untended, unproductive vegetation;\u000aa village equally untended and unproductive, except of unnecessary\u000ababies, where listless brown people moved without much purpose, or,\u000alacking the ambition even to make a show of activity, lolled where\u000athey were.
p10400
aVThe tropical sun had no magic of half-lights to tinge it all with\u000aromance or stir it into fugitive beauty.
p10401
aVSuch as Sicaba was at\u000aheart, it stood revealed.
p10402
aVWhen the sun rose, John McGennis rose too, and stood for a moment,\u000aunshivering in the lukewarm air, to look down on the poverty of his\u000atown, before he turned to pour water over himself out of an old\u000atomato-can.
p10403
aVLike the morning and the sea and the air, the water had no tang in\u000ait, and McGennis, drying himself slowly and methodically, felt no\u000afresher for his bath.
p10404
aVWhen a youthful and well-tempered body fails\u000ato respond to the caress of sluicing water, there is generally\u000asomething wrong with the mind which inhabits it.
p10405
aVThere was with the\u000amind of McGennis.
p10406
aVThe trouble lay outside his window.
p10407
aVThat compound of staring sky and\u000asea and stared-at village which the day revealed had overwhelmed him.
p10408
aVAs mere geological and botanical facts, Sicaba, Pagros, the Tropics,\u000ahad proved too big for him.
p10409
aVThey made of him just a spot of life,\u000ameaningless as an ant toiling unendingly in the forest of the\u000agrass-stems.
p10410
aVTiny dot of intelligence that he found himself, in the\u000amidst of those triumphant physical forces, McGennis had come to\u000awonder whether anything he could do among them mattered much.
p10411
aVSlowly and methodically, as he had bathed, he dressed--right sock,\u000aleft sock, right shoe, left shoe, right puttee, left puttee, put the\u000astrap twice round, haul it through the buckle and tuck the end back\u000aneatly--and when he was trim in his khaki and yellow leather he stood\u000afor a moment with the irresolution of inertia on him.
p10412
aVThen he pulled\u000ahis knife from his pocket, strode across to the thick corner-post of\u000ahis room, stooped, and with elaborate care cut a notch in the tough,\u000adense wood.
p10413
aVThe post, from the upward limit of his reach to well down toward his\u000aknees, was jagged with such notches lying in groups of seven, six\u000aside by side, and another cut diagonally across them.
p10414
aVThey were a\u000acalendar of more than ordinary significance, in the mind of its\u000amaker.
p10415
aVEach of them represented a day of "Grin, gabble, gobble,"\u000aeach checked off twenty-four hours in which he had stuck by his\u000atraditions, greeting every comer with that contortion of the lips\u000awhich, conventionally at least, expresses pleasure, eating sufficient\u000afood to keep his body in repair--McGennis reverenced his body\u000aunthinkingly as an ancient Greek--and in which he had, both in his\u000aoffice and in the primitive society of Sicaba, "waggled his jaw," and\u000athereby overcome a growing disposition to speechlessness.
p10416
aVWith the fierce enthusiasm of an ascetic, he cut these records,\u000aineffaceably deep, on the mornings of the days for which they stood.
p10417
aVThus there could be no going back.
p10418
aVStaring at him from the\u000aundecaying wood, they warned him that for one more stretch, at least,\u000ahe must grin, gobble, and gabble, or be a quitter.
p10419
aVThey served a more immediately practical purpose also.
p10420
aVMcGennis had\u000afound that it was the first grimace, the first nibble at the food his\u000aOccidental stomach loathed, the first burst of inane chatter, which\u000acame hard.
p10421
aVOnce fairly started, the grin became a veritable\u000asmile--how boyish and appealing he had never guessed--the chatter\u000abecame animated question and answer, and his stomach, more\u000afundamentally human than Occidental, found even the food Sicaba\u000aafforded preferable to emptiness.
p10422
aVBut somehow the quiet of the\u000aevenings and the stillness of the long nights and the flatness of the\u000adawns brought back continually the question: "What's the use?"
p10423
aVand he\u000awould have his fight to make all over, with his notch.
p10424
aVOn this particular morning, he stood for a while staring at the\u000ajagged post which was at once a cenotaph to his departed days and an\u000aaltar prepared for the sacrifice of days to come.
p10425
aVWithout counting,\u000aMcGennis knew that his latest notch rounded out a tale of three\u000ahundred and sixty-five.
p10426
aVThe possibilities of that one post were not\u000aexhausted yet, and his house held a dozen other posts, virgin still,\u000aand smooth.
p10427
aVAnd even if he should endure to notch all the posts in\u000aall the houses of Sicaba and all the fringing palms along the beach,\u000aand all the trees in the primeval forest round about, it would result\u000ain--what?
p10428
aVMcGennis had met a man once, down in Bacolot, who made a practice of\u000agetting as drunk as possible once each month, once and no more.
p10429
aVIt\u000agave one something definite to look forward and back to, and hope for\u000aand regret, he had explained without embarrassment, and that was an\u000aachievement for a white man in the tropics.
p10430
aVMcGennis, staring glumly\u000aat the record of his featureless year, felt that perhaps that man was\u000aas reasonable as any other.
p10431
aVThen, impulsively, he stooped again and the knife-blade flashed with\u000amimic fierceness as he hacked at his post.
p10432
aVWhen he rose there were\u000afourteen new notches in it.
p10433
aVHe had mortgaged a fortnight of his new\u000ayear.
p10434
aVThere was no sense in it, very likely, but it was done, and\u000airrevocable, and therefore comforting in a way.
p10435
aVHe stood back, and\u000athe first smile of the day curled his lips.
p10436
aVThe fool part of him\u000aamused the rest, and he turned to the _sala_ and breakfast with some\u000acheerfulness.
p10437
aVHe was making his last few conscientious pecks at that meal, when the\u000aMunicipal Secretary, exalted and short-winded personage, climbed his\u000astairs puffingly and stood blinking in the door.
p10438
aVMcGennis set his\u000acup down and uttered the sound which trustful Sicaba interpreted as\u000athe outburst of uncontrollable joy.
p10439
aV"Well, Secretario!"
p10440
aVhe cried, in his atrocious and unfaltering\u000aSpanish.
p10441
aV"You're just in time for chocolate.
p10442
aVMilicio!"
p10443
aVhe shouted\u000ato his cook.
p10444
aVThe Secretary raised a pudgy hand in deprecation, the dignity of an\u000aofficial mission being on him.
p10445
aV"It iss dhe lattair, Mr. Magheenis,"\u000ahe announced, holding out a crumpled official envelope.
p10446
aV"Dhe\u000aSupervisor Provincial sends it wiv a man to running."
p10447
aVSmiling the contented smile of a fat man whose exertion is over, the\u000aSecretary sank into a chair and fanned himself with his hat.
p10448
aV"_Sena\u000amuy importante_," he explained more familiarly.
p10449
aV"The courier cost\u000atwo _pesos_.
p10450
aVI brought it over at once."
p10451
aV"A letter by courier and two _pesos_!"
p10452
aVMcGennis cried, knowing that\u000asurprise was expected.
p10453
aV"We're getting up in the world.
p10454
aVExcuse me if\u000aI read it, Secretario?"
p10455
aV"With pleasure," the Secretary murmured, but McGennis did not hear\u000ahim.
p10456
aVHe heard nothing, saw nothing, but those surprising words in\u000athe crabbed writing of his chief, which changed life in a flash and\u000asettled that tormenting question once for all.
p10457
aVTwice he read the letter through greedily, before he dropped it to\u000astare out through the open window.
p10458
aVA kaleidoscopic change had\u000aovertaken Botany and Geology.
p10459
aVThe corner of the weedy _plaza_ on\u000awhich his house fronted now lay fresh and clean under the early\u000asunshine and the salty breeze.
p10460
aVBeyond it rose a grove of\u000acocoa-palms, with brown-thatched houses nestled in their shade, and\u000abetween the tall columns of the tree-trunks shot the crisp sparkle of\u000athe blue Visayan Sea.
p10461
aVAll at once, even Sicaba was exuberant with\u000alife, youthful in beauty, friendly.
p10462
aVHalf noting the change, McGennis\u000araced along beside his thronging thoughts.
p10463
aVWhat the chief said was true.
p10464
aVHe _had_ thought he was forgotten and\u000astranded in Sicaba.
p10465
aVHastily his mind swept back over the dragging\u000ayear he was just finishing.
p10466
aVAgain he saw himself an enthusiastic\u000apilgrim with a work to do.
p10467
aVAgain he went through the disenchantment;\u000afelt the vastness and wildness of the Islands, triumphant Geology and\u000aBotany, burst upon him, reminding him for the first time that even an\u000aEngineer is only a man at bottom.
p10468
aVAnd once again he felt his\u000adisappointment in the people, the simple, childlike, obstinately\u000apliant folk who listened so interestedly, and opposed the inertia of\u000adead centuries to every improvement.
p10469
aVHow was one to teach them\u000aanything?
p10470
aVAnd why should a deputy provincial supervisor, placed in\u000acharge of the roads and bridges and harbors of the whole North Coast,\u000awith headquarters at Sicaba, try to create roads and harbors and\u000abridges to supervise?
p10471
aVThat had become the question finally.
p10472
aVBut he had kept on trying, and now a year was up and he had\u000aaccomplished something, even in hopeless Sicaba.
p10473
aVThe town was a\u000alittle cleaner for his having lived there.
p10474
aVA few people had come to\u000atrust "America."
p10475
aVAnd there _were_ roads and bridges and harbors, on\u000athe blue-prints in his office.
p10476
aVPerhaps it had paid after all.
p10477
aVAt\u000aany rate the people liked him, and he liked them.
p10478
aVThe fat old\u000aSecretario, now--\u000a\u000aJust then that patient man interrupted him with the most suppressed\u000aof coughs.
p10479
aV"Well, Secretario," said McGennis, rousing, "let's drink\u000aour chocolate.
p10480
aVI must have been dreaming.
p10481
aVI hope I haven't kept you\u000awaiting long?"
p10482
aV"Only a moment," the visitor assured him, though the Deputy\u000aSupervisor's day-dream had lasted long for any dream, "only a moment.
p10483
aVI hope," he added, curiosity struggling with courtesy, "that I did\u000anot bring bad news."
p10484
aV"Bad news!"
p10485
aVMcGennis beamed on him.
p10486
aV"You brought the best little\u000aold news _you'll_ ever tote.
p10487
aVSecretario, if you never promulgate\u000aworse news than that, you'll boost your circulation a thousand a day.
p10488
aVIt was red news with green edges."
p10489
aVThe Secretary could understand the tone, if the words were beyond\u000ahim, and his smile matched McGennis's own.
p10490
aV"I could almost believe,"\u000ahe hinted with elephantine archness, "that the Government has\u000aincreased your salary."
p10491
aV"Secretario," said McGennis approvingly, "you hit the truth in the\u000aeye that time.
p10492
aVBut that isn't the best of it."
p10493
aV"Ah," said the Secretary promptly, "then you are also to be married."
p10494
aV"Not on your life!"
p10495
aVMcGennis shouted scornfully.
p10496
aV"Not on your life,\u000aSecretario.
p10497
aVThey've raised me."
p10498
aV"Raised you," the Secretary murmured uncomprehendingly.
p10499
aVMost of\u000aMcGennis's conversation was half incomprehensible to him, and all the\u000amore entertaining just for that.
p10500
aVIt brought him into touch with\u000awords he had never heard of.
p10501
aV"Sure," McGennis repeated.
p10502
aV"Raised me.
p10503
aVShoved me up a peg.
p10504
aVPromoted me."
p10505
aV"Ah, promoted!"
p10506
aVsaid the Secretary, catching at the flying tails of a\u000aword he knew.
p10507
aV"In the eye again," McGennis applauded.
p10508
aV"Secretario," he began\u000aimpressively, smoothing out the crumpled letter, "the Old Man,"--so\u000ahe spoke of his chief, the engineer in charge of the battle with\u000aBotany and Geology in the two great provinces of _Pagros Oriental y\u000aOccidental_--"the Old Man has had his eye on me, so he says.
p10509
aVAnd I\u000areckon he means it.
p10510
aVYes, sir, the old telescope has had a sight on\u000ayours respectfully clear up here in Sicaba."
p10511
aV"Yes?"
p10512
aVmurmured the Secretary, heroically sipping his detestable,\u000alukewarm chocolate.
p10513
aV"And he says," McGennis quoted freely, "that I haven't made good so\u000aworse, and that having watered and weeded the banana tree I shall now\u000aopen my mouth and let something drop therein.
p10514
aVAnd what, Secretario,"\u000aMcGennis demanded excitedly, "_what_ do you suppose is going to drop?"
p10515
aV"Yes," the Secretary agreed placidly, "I comprehend.
p10516
aVIt is a very\u000agood idea."
p10517
aV"You bet it is," McGennis shouted.
p10518
aV"But you don't comprehend enough\u000ato notice.
p10519
aVLook here, Secretario.
p10520
aVYou know they're building a road\u000aup in the Igorrote country, and the Igarooters won't work, and\u000athey're going to put me in charge of the worst section of it and see\u000aif I can make 'em work.
p10521
aVWill I _make_ them?"
p10522
aVhe demanded,\u000arhetorically.
p10523
aV"_Will_ I?
p10524
aVI'm sorry for them already yet."
p10525
aV"Yes," murmured the Secretary.
p10526
aV"It is a very good idea.
p10527
aVI\u000acomprehend with clearness, and up to a certain point I agree--"\u000a\u000a"I don't believe it," said McGennis flatly.
p10528
aV"Listen, Secretario.
p10529
aVI'm going away, _sabe_?
p10530
aVNo more Sicaba in mine!
p10531
aVNo more bridges and\u000aharbors in a cat's eye, but some real live Igaroots and a bunch of\u000apicks and shovels and a road you can _see_!
p10532
aVAnd _dynamite_!
p10533
aVLord,\u000aSecretario, you don't know how good it'll seem to hear a real noise\u000aagain, and--"\u000a\u000aMcGennis stopped suddenly, for something in his words had at last\u000apenetrated to the Secretary's understanding.
p10534
aVSlowly the worthy\u000aofficer put down his cup.
p10535
aVSlowly he got to his feet, and over his\u000abroad, dull face a little procession of emotions made its slow way.
p10536
aVJovial interest gave place to surprise, surprise to dismay, and at\u000alast a heavy hopelessness settled on it.
p10537
aV"You go away from Sicaba,\u000aMagheenis?"
p10538
aVhe asked.
p10539
aVAnd then he plumped down into his chair again\u000aand sat there, an embodiment of chuckle-headed woe.
p10540
aV"Lord," said McGennis to himself, looking at his victim contritely,\u000a"I ought not to have tossed it out at him that way."
p10541
aVIt was a relief that just at that moment a white-clad native teacher\u000ashould come to the door of the schoolhouse on the far side of the\u000a_plaza_ and ring a bell with nervous, insistent strokes.
p10542
aVMcGennis\u000ajerked out his watch, and realized that for the first time in Sicaba\u000ahe was late in beginning his day.
p10543
aV"Stay as long as you want to,\u000aSecretario," he called back, rushing for the stairs.
p10544
aVThe Secretary\u000asat motionless, and McGennis, plunging out into the sunshine, felt a\u000asecond pang of contrition for having tossed it out so suddenly.
p10545
aVBut his regret was only momentary.
p10546
aVSomehow the morning sparkled as\u000anever morning had outside God's own country, and the Deputy\u000aSupervisor, pushing across the _plaza_ with long, boyish strides,\u000aresponded to it.
p10547
aV"Going away, going away," was the refrain his feet\u000apatted out.
p10548
aVAway from Sicaba, away from isolation and obscurity, out\u000ato the big, big chance which waited him.
p10549
aVAnd the chief had been\u000awatching him, canny old Stewart who said so little and saw so much\u000awith those narrowed gray eyes of his; hard-mouthed Stewart, who\u000ahandled his forces for the overthrow of Botany and Geology, down\u000athere in Bacolot, as a general handles his troops.
p10550
aVAnd Stewart,\u000awhose approval was a grunt, had said in so many words that he,\u000aMcGennis, had made good.
p10551
aVTruly, it paid to cut your notches and let\u000athe Stewarts look out for the meaning of them.
p10552
aVHis eager, keen face was so bright, as he cut across the angle where\u000achurch and convent wall a corner of the _plaza_, that the men who had\u000abeen puttering there with stones and cement dropped their work to\u000asing out cheery "_Maayong agas_" a dozen of them in a volley.
p10553
aV"_Maayong aga, amigos_," returned McGennis, and hesitated.
p10554
aVHe was\u000aalready late for school, but then school is not one of the duties of\u000aan engineer in charge of half a province.
p10555
aVOne of the few duties that\u000aisn't his, McGennis had thought sometimes.
p10556
aVStill, this school of\u000aSicaba, in a way--\u000a\u000aSomehow McGennis's mind was working in quick flashes, and even as he\u000ahung there on his heel he saw again just how that school had become\u000aone of his duties, and laughed grimly to think of it.
p10557
aVThere had been a Maestro in Sicaba once, a bespectacled American from\u000aan East effete beyond words, but chronic indigestion--coupled with a\u000acoldness in the feet equally chronic, thought McGennis, with light\u000ascorn--had caused his early departure.
p10558
aVAnd then the school, in the\u000ahands of four warring native teachers, male and female, had been\u000agoing to the dogs, until McGennis, with his inherent dislike for\u000aseeing anything go to the dogs uncombatted, had, with a deft jerk of\u000athe wrist, straightened those four warring pedagogues into their\u000acollars and kept them there, till a Deputy Superintendent of Schools\u000ahad come riding up from Bacolot to see what was to be done about it.
p10559
aVMcGennis still remembered that trim, slim, innocent-eyed Deputy with\u000aregretful admiration.
p10560
aV"I reckon," McGennis had remarked, with the impersonal contempt of an\u000aEngineer speaking to a Teacher, "you'll be sending up another\u000aglass-eyed Dictionary to snarl 'em all up--"\u000a\u000a"I don't know," the Deputy Superintendent had said thoughtfully.
p10561
aV"You've done surprisingly well with them yourself."
p10562
aV"That," McGennis retorted, with huge sarcasm, "is because I've got\u000anothing else to do."
p10563
aV"In that case," the Deputy had said, looking at him with smiling\u000ainnocence, "I'll let you keep the school, just to fill up the time."
p10564
aVAnd then, unexpectedly, he had swung to his saddle and flicked a\u000aspurred heel, and gone galloping away, his big Colt's swinging at his\u000atrim waist, and left McGennis wrathful yet admiring.
p10565
aV"I say, Mr. McGennis," had been his parting shot, "try to keep their\u000aaccent and vocabulary back as close to the Mississippi as you can,\u000awon't you?"
p10566
aVRather than quit, McGennis had taken the school and kept the restive\u000ateachers in line by counsel and admonition, and had even, when he was\u000ain town, taught for an hour each morning himself, smiling with lofty\u000acontempt for his womanish occupation as he revealed to his pupils an\u000aaccent and vocabulary which had never been east of the Missouri.
p10567
aVIn\u000aa way it was his school, but the work those men were doing at the\u000aangle of the _plaza_ was infinitely more his work, and, late or not,\u000ahe swung on his heel for a look at it.
p10568
aVOf all his schemes for the redemption of Sicaba, that culvert and its\u000atributary ditches was his pet.
p10569
aVIt had been a nice problem in\u000adrainage in a town whose highest ridge rose only a meter above high\u000awater, and which yet seemed to have an inexhaustible capacity for\u000agetting wet and staying wetter.
p10570
aVThe water had lain two feet deep all\u000aover the _plaza_, the last rains, and a score of men, fathers of\u000afamilies, had wrapped their faces in their clammy cotton blankets and\u000adied stolidly of fever, to say nothing of the women and the babies.
p10571
aVThe babies had been the worst of it.
p10572
aVIt made him growl out ugly\u000acurses to see the tiny coffins borne out of the church, two and three\u000aand four a day, with their tawdry draperies of pink calico draggled\u000aand beaten by wind and rain.
p10573
aVHe had made up his mind that it must\u000astop.
p10574
aVAnd it was stopped now, if Yankee ingenuity counted for\u000aanything, McGennis thought, as he looked down at the clean green\u000amortar of his culvert.
p10575
aV"Is it good?"
p10576
aVthe foreman of the masons asked anxiously.
p10577
aVThe Deputy Supervisor surveyed the work with puckered brows.
p10578
aV"Fine,\u000aMiguel," he said genially.
p10579
aV"Couldn't be better," and the workmen\u000asmiled at each other like pleased children.
p10580
aV"Two, three, four days, it will be done," Miguel said proudly.
p10581
aV"Great!"
p10582
aVcried his ruler.
p10583
aV"You're a hustler.
p10584
aVYou and I've got a\u000alittle Irish in us, I reckon, hey?"
p10585
aVAnd then, chuckling over the\u000abewilderment his speech had caused, he resumed his light-hearted way\u000ato school.
p10586
aVThe big, sunny boys' room, where blackboards were fastened\u000aincongruously and perilously to nipa walls and bright-eyed,\u000awhite-frocked Oriental youngsters sat at American desks when they\u000amust, and drew their legs up to squat comfortably at other times, was\u000avery cheerful ordinarily, far and away the homiest place in Sicaba.
p10587
aVBut as McGennis entered, he met a chilly air.
p10588
aVFor eleven months he\u000ahad been impressing the beauty of punctuality on his charges, and now\u000ahe had his reward.
p10589
aVThe children stared with round-eyed disapproval.
p10590
aVThe teachers greeted him with frosty courtesy.
p10591
aVWith twinkling eyes, McGennis marched to the desk.
p10592
aV"I am late," he\u000areported meekly, "and--I will let Alejandro Angel name my punishment."
p10593
aVThat was an inspiration.
p10594
aVThe angelic Alexander turned stiff with\u000aresponsibility.
p10595
aV"I sink," he announced at last, "we s'all all estay\u000aafter eschool an' Meestair Magheenis s'all tell dhe estory of dhe\u000aPrincesa who wass esleepy."
p10596
aVA stir of approval greeted his\u000apronouncement.
p10597
aVThe Sleeping Beauty was dear to the hearts of younger\u000aSicaba.
p10598
aVHaving made his peace, McGennis passed on to his own little room.
p10599
aVAnd there, while detachments advanced to storm under his leadership\u000athe rough terrain of English speech, he fell to thinking again of his\u000awonderful fortune.
p10600
aVHe would make those Igorrotes work, and he would\u000alearn all their legends and crafts and games, and they would be his\u000apeople.
p10601
aVJust as the people of Sicaba were.
p10602
aVMcGennis, glancing down at the long bench where a platoon of his\u000apeople sat with the impishly angelic Alexander at one end--the lower\u000aone--and the wan-faced village hunchback at the other, felt a sudden\u000apang.
p10603
aVFor the first time he realized that some professional\u000apedagogue, some glass-eyed Dictionary, some heavy-handed, solemn\u000afellow, might have those boys he had made his.
p10604
aVIf any one must come,\u000ahe hoped it might be--McGennis ransacked his fancy for the sort of\u000aman he wanted.
p10605
aVAnd he could not find one!
p10606
aVAt that he laughed\u000aoutright.
p10607
aV"You're getting green-eyed," he said to himself, in\u000ahumorous surprise.
p10608
aV"Teacher, what is green-eye?"
p10609
aVdemanded the hunchback, and McGennis\u000aknew that he had spoken his thought.
p10610
aV"Green-eyed means a gazabo that thinks he's It," he explained\u000apromptly; and "What is gazabo, Teacher?"
p10611
aVdemanded the tireless\u000apursuer after knowledge.
p10612
aV"Time's up," said McGennis laughing.
p10613
aV"Rush along the next gang,\u000aAlejandro, and if I catch you chewing _bunga_ in school again I'll\u000awring your neck, _sabe_?"
p10614
aVWhen the one hour of his unmanly work was done and the last\u000adetachment had departed, McGennis lingered for a moment in the little\u000aroom, looking out on the _plaza_, and his eyes were very thoughtful,\u000aalmost wistful.
p10615
aV"I reckon," he muttered, "a fellow'd hate to leave\u000athe Hot Place if he'd been there long enough to get acquainted," and\u000ahe seized his hat and hurried over to his office in the big,\u000ahalf-ruinous convent which served Sicaba for municipal headquarters.
p10616
aVHis step was not so wholly buoyant as it had been in the morning, and\u000athe world was not quite so youthfully exuberant.
p10617
aVNot that it was\u000adead, as he had seen it so often from his window at sunrise.
p10618
aVIt was\u000asimply--homelike.
p10619
aVAnd in his office, too, buoyancy was lacking.
p10620
aVInstead of taking up\u000athe work he had laid aside the night before, and it was work which\u000amust be finished quickly if he meant to leave his house in order, he\u000asat stupidly for a while, and then, half unconsciously, he reached up\u000ato a shelf and took down some blue-prints of work which could not be\u000adone for years.
p10621
aVNot till all those roads and bridges had some\u000ahabitation more local than a cat's eye.
p10622
aVThere was the swamp, Manapla\u000away, a hundred good square miles of rich black mud where cacao would\u000agrow like a weed, and only a thousand cubic meters of drainage canal\u000awere needed, twelve hundred at the outside--\u000a\u000aThere was the growing bar at the mouth of Cadiz Viejo river.
p10623
aVOne\u000ajetty, placed knowingly, would scoop that out, and there was an ideal\u000aplace for a dock--McGennis's short brown hand smoothed the curling\u000ablue-prints lovingly, as he fell to thinking again of an unescapable\u000asuccessor.
p10624
aVWhom could Stewart send?
p10625
aVThere was Haskins.
p10626
aVHaskins had\u000athe education, McGennis admitted reverently, and could draw like a\u000aruling-machine and figure like a comptometer.
p10627
aVBut Haskins couldn't\u000amake a monkey catch fleas, and the North Coast needed a driver, a\u000ahard-handed--and yet not too hard.
p10628
aVBrown could make 'em hustle all\u000aright, but he would have a new fight on every day.
p10629
aVWhat the North\u000aCoast needed was a jollier--like Henry?
p10630
aVNo, Henry was a good fellow\u000aall right, but he made things cost like contract work in Frisco, and\u000athe North Coast was pitifully poor.
p10631
aVWhat it needed was a contriver\u000alike--like--well, like--\u000a\u000a"Oh, hell!"
p10632
aVsaid McGennis profanely.
p10633
aVSuddenly he stood very straight\u000aabove his draughting-table, for his door had opened.
p10634
aVThe Municipal Secretary and the Municipal Presidente came in.
p10635
aVThey\u000aseemed to radiate an air of funerals, and McGennis's boisterous\u000agreeting died in his throat.
p10636
aVThe Secretary halted just inside the\u000adoor and stood looking down, a lumpish statue of grief.
p10637
aVThe\u000aPresidente, a spare, eager-faced young native, came forward to\u000aMcGennis's table.
p10638
aV"Damn!"
p10639
aVsaid McGennis softly, looking at him.
p10640
aV"Seor Magheenis," said the Presidente, "the Seor Secretario says\u000athat you will go away.
p10641
aVAssure me that he is mistaken."
p10642
aVMcGennis started a light answer, and cut it short.
p10643
aV"It's true,\u000aPresidente," he said briefly.
p10644
aV"But," said the Presidente, "where go all our plans which we made\u000atogether?
p10645
aVRemember how we talked?
p10646
aVYou shall teach me how the good\u000aPresidentes--the Mayors--in America do, and so shall even Sicaba be\u000amade American also."
p10647
aV"I'm sorry, Presidente," said McGennis, "but you see--"\u000a\u000a"I comprehend," said the Presidente.
p10648
aV"We are too little, too poor,\u000atoo worthless, to take the strength, the teaching, of a man like\u000ayou--"\u000a\u000a"Oh, cut it out!"
p10649
aVMcGennis begged.
p10650
aV"It is not to be expected, and I do not expect it, now that I\u000acomprehend."
p10651
aVThere was a simple and impressive dignity in the little\u000aPresidente.
p10652
aV"But what comes to Sicaba, and to me?
p10653
aVExcuse me,\u000a_Magheenis amigo_.
p10654
aVI can not talk more now.
p10655
aVBefore you go I shall\u000asee you and thank you, but excuse me now."
p10656
aV"Damn!"
p10657
aVsaid McGennis savagely, looking after the two silent figures\u000aas they went out.
p10658
aV"What right have they got," he demanded sharply of\u000aSome One, "to expect me to drool away my whole life up here in this\u000aGod-forsaken hole?
p10659
aVHere, you," he shouted roughly to the\u000aman-of-all-work about his office, "get my horse saddled up, quick.
p10660
aVI've got to ride out and take a look at that cut on the Segovia road."
p10661
aVAnd so he rode away and escaped a day of unwonted excitement in\u000aSicaba as the news spread.
p10662
aVPeople told it to each other as they\u000astood in twos and threes before the little _tiendas_, and the greater\u000amen of the town, gathered in the earthen-floored caf, drank cognac\u000ain unusual and dangerous quantities, three and four thimblefuls, some\u000aof them; and the school children talked of it, tearfully, and the\u000amonkeyish little constabulary soldiers in their lime-washed\u000abarrack--McGennis had given _them_ a touch of that pliant\u000amule-driver's wrist of his, once or twice, when their inspector had\u000abeen absent riding along the eighty miles of ladrone-harried coast\u000awhich was his charge.
p10663
aVIn all Sicaba only the Municipal Secretary, sitting in his office\u000awith an unlighted cigar between his pudgy fingers, and the young\u000aPresidente pacing up and down somewhere in his big house beside\u000aSicaba River, did not speak of McGennis's going.
p10664
aVIt was toward the end of the afternoon when the Deputy Supervisor\u000arode back, himself again.
p10665
aVOut there in the open, with the sun and\u000awind about him, his brain had cleared.
p10666
aVThese people had no mortgage\u000aon his future.
p10667
aVIt was a wrench breaking old ties, but not to do it\u000ain this case would be a piece\u000aof--back-beyond-the-foot-hills--sentimentality.
p10668
aVSo when he turned into the first street of the little city and a man\u000astepped out from a tienda and asked: "You go away, Seor Magheenis?"
p10669
aVMcGennis, jogging along with a smile on his face, was ready for him.
p10670
aV"Sure," he said carelessly.
p10671
aVBut he was not ready for what followed.
p10672
aVFor the man put a hand to\u000ahis mouth and called shrilly: "It is true," and from every _tienda_\u000adown the length of that long street, men and women came out and stood\u000alooking up at him, silently, sorrowfully, questioningly, as if there\u000awere something they wanted to understand, and couldn't.
p10673
aVBefore\u000aMcGennis was half-way to the _plaza_, his smile was a savage grin,\u000aand he had kicked the big horse into a thundering gallop.
p10674
aVAnd so he\u000arode down between the rows of silent people, looking straight ahead.
p10675
aVHe had reached the _plaza_, and was swinging his horse for the corner\u000awhere his house was, when the sight of the schoolhouse on the farther\u000aside checked him.
p10676
aVThis hour, just before sunset, had come to be the\u000aone playtime hour of his busy days, and he spent it at the school.
p10677
aVNot as a teacher, nor among the boys who were his unofficial pupils.
p10678
aVAt the other end of the school from the boys' room was another\u000aequally big room crowded full of girls, and it was there, oddly\u000aenough, that McGennis spent the one happy hour when he did not have\u000ato be a Deputy Supervisor.
p10679
aVOddly, for, as McGennis put it, he "had no use for skirts."
p10680
aVIn his\u000ashort, tempestuous life he had seen many good men wasted for love of\u000awomen, and far from being curious at their fate and the causes of it,\u000ahe had drawn back into himself till he regarded the softer half of\u000ahumankind with a suspicion which bordered on hatred.
p10681
aVBut there were women of another sort.
p10682
aVTiny things whose little\u000aclinging fingers could hardly circle one of his stubby ones.
p10683
aVWee\u000athings of such primal innocence that, as they stood unclad at the\u000avillage wells, with their plump little brown bodies shining in the\u000asun, and their wisps of black hair hanging all draggled about their\u000afaces, while their mothers poured water over them, they looked up\u000aunabashed if he came riding by, and smiled up friendlily, and lisped\u000a"Good-a-mornin'."
p10684
aVOf such women McGennis had no fear, and so it had come about, very\u000agradually, that after all the others were gone, these little ones\u000awaited in the big room till McGennis came with a wonderfully colored\u000abook, and then, with shining eyes and tiny gurgles of excited\u000alaughter, they closed about him and wormed their warm little selves\u000ainside his arms and balanced precariously on his shoulders, steadying\u000athemselves by his hair, and lay piled, a heap of eager heads and\u000aforgotten arms and legs, on the big table where the book was, while\u000athe Deputy Supervisor revealed to them the thrilling difference\u000abetween a peach and an apple, and the astonishing unlikeness of\u000aeither to a violet.
p10685
aVAnd any one who had come unseen on McGennis\u000athen, would hardly have known him for a Deputy Supervisor.
p10686
aVMcGennis, at the _plaza_ corner, felt suddenly that these friends of\u000ahis were waiting for him then, and he could not bear to disappoint\u000athem.
p10687
aVSo he swung the big horse and galloped across and rolled from\u000ahis saddle at the schoolhouse door and pushed it open and took one\u000astep inside, and stopped.
p10688
aVFor from the benches and the crowded table there rose a wail of\u000ainfantile despair, so shrill and queerly, pipingly minor, so very\u000amanifestly the outpouring of very tiny broken hearts, that it was\u000alike a toy wail, almost ludicrous in its imitation of the real thing.
p10689
aVBut McGennis did not smile at it.
p10690
aVFor an instant he stood, and then\u000ahe turned and closed the door with fumbling fingers, and took the few\u000asteps to his horse stumblingly, and climbed heavily into his saddle,\u000aand with loose reins rode off to his house and went up to his _ssla_\u000aand sat down there, looking blindly out on Sicaba.
p10691
aV[Illustration: "_With loose reins rode off to his house._"]\u000a\u000aThe sunset came, brightened, and faded, and passed away, and night\u000ashut down over Sicaba, and still he sat there.
p10692
aVHis muchacho came to\u000alight a lamp, and McGennis sent him away.
p10693
aVLater his cook came,\u000aspeaking authoritatively of dinner, and McGennis sent his cook away,\u000atoo, and sat on in the dark.
p10694
aVAt last it was the hour when even Sicaba, for a little while, must\u000aseem beautiful to the most hostile critic.
p10695
aVIt is the hour when the\u000afull power of night descends upon the world, when the wind dies away\u000ato the merest murmur, and the drone of the surf becomes deep and\u000asolemn, and the great yellow stars burn very steadily against the\u000asoft velvet of the sky.
p10696
aVWhen that hour came, McGennis stirred, and stood up suddenly, and\u000alaid his hands on the broad sill of his window and looked down at\u000aSicaba and up to the stars.
p10697
aV"Of course I'm going to stay," he\u000amuttered impatiently, as if Some One had asked him a question.
p10698
aV"But\u000ait's up to You.
p10699
aVYou butted into this game, and now You've got to\u000aplay the cards.
p10700
aVPedro," he called, in quite another voice, "bring a\u000alight."
p10701
aVWhen the light was brought, he sat down at his table and drew pen and\u000apaper to him and began to write.
p10702
aV"Donald G. Stewart, C.E.," he wrote, tracing the magic initials with\u000areverent care.
p10703
aVMcGennis would never write C.E.
p10704
aVafter his own name,\u000aunless some day he did the big, big thing which would lead a college\u000ato give him the right, _honoris causa_.
p10705
aVHe had not the education, he\u000aknew that.
p10706
aV"DONALD G. STEWART, C.E.
p10707
aV"_Supervisor in Charge\u000a      "Provinces Pagros Oriental y Occidental._\u000a\u000a"SIR:--I have the honor to request that I do not be transferred to\u000aLuzon, because there are some jobs here which are not done yet."
p10708
aVHis eyes lighted with whimsical amusement as he thought of those\u000a"jobs"; teaching a presidente how to be straight, teaching brown,\u000amonkeyish soldiers not to run away, teaching the children--\u000a\u000a\u000a"The fact is, Mr. Stewart," he wrote with less formality, "that I\u000acannot leave the school which the Dep.
p10709
aVSuper.
p10710
aVSchools kindly gave me\u000ato occupy my time.
p10711
aVI am the best teacher he has got now, I think.
p10712
aVYou can ask him."
p10713
aVThen formality returned:\u000a\u000a\u000a"I have the honor to thank you for the kind words you say about me\u000amaking good.
p10714
aVOf course I know they are not so.
p10715
aV"Very respectfully,\u000a    "JOHN McGENNIS."
p10716
aV"There," said McGennis, looking down thankfully at his completed\u000aletter, for he hated letter-writing, did McGennis, "I reckon that\u000acinches it.
p10717
aVWhen the Old Man reads that, he'll sabe I'm loco enough\u000ato let alone.
p10718
aVAnyway," he added, "Haskins'll never get the chance to\u000ablow about draining Manapla swamp.
p10719
aVHaskins has got the education all\u000aright, but he couldn't make a bald monkey catch his own fleas."
p10720
aVAs he entered his bedroom, holding his chimneyless lamp high that the\u000areek of it might not draw into his nostrils, his eye lighted on the\u000ajagged post in the corner.
p10721
aV"Well," said McGennis, looking at it,\u000a"she's all notched up for a couple of weeks, anyhow.
p10722
aVI'm that much\u000aahead."
p10723
aVThe boyish smile curled his firm young lips once more, as\u000athe fool part of him began to amuse the other parts.
p10724
aVAnd then,\u000acontentedly, he turned to his canvas cot, with the heavy, blue-gray\u000ablankets spread upon it.
p10725
aVIt is hard and narrow and monkish, that couch which the world\u000aprovides for so many of her fighting men and pioneers, but to\u000aMcGennis it seemed a Place of Rest.
p10726
aVSo may they find it, all my far-wandering friends, when to-night they\u000astretch themselves on the rasping canvas and draw the honest,\u000ablue-gray blankets over them.
p10727
aVEPILOGUE\u000a\u000a_That is the East which called me with all its old familiar voices,\u000awith all the glamour and color of its pulsating life.
p10728
aVAnd now,\u000ahaving relived that life for an hour, I have come back again to the\u000aold house which stands so quiet among the frost-bitten New England\u000awoods and fields where sober-living men are providing cannily against\u000athe coming winter, in full faith that their precautions will avail,\u000athat a Great God rules who permits no Little Gods to turn His world\u000atopsyturvy.
p10729
aVI am not sorry to be back.
p10730
aVThe East for the tasting of\u000alife, the West for living it._\u000a\u000a_I feel, regretfully, as you must have felt accusingly or\u000auninterestedly, that these stories are far from pleasant.
p10731
aVThat is\u000abecause they are true.
p10732
aVEach of them was taken raw from Life.
p10733
aVThe\u000apeople of the mimic dramas you have watched are no puppets of my\u000aimagination; there is no bit of tragedy or of comedy written here,\u000ahowever dingy, that some man or woman has not lived.
p10734
aVWhether you\u000aaccept that old heathen man's hypothesis of Little Gods or not, you\u000ahave looked on at Games which were played by Some One, or by blind\u000aFate.
p10735
aVThe East you have seen is the real East, stripped of its\u000aglamour and its color, a land where nothing is sacred, where there\u000aare indeed no Ten Commandments--no Commander, it seems sometimes--a\u000aland of uncertainty and empty Fatalism._\u000a\u000a_Better, it seems to me, a little less of zest and color, and a\u000alittle more of ballasting Hope._\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTHE END.
