aVThe night was mild and very still, and perhaps Janet\u2019s\u000ayouthful bosom was still a little fluttered by that sudden surprise\u000awhich had made her heart beat.
p11943
aVShe leaned a little out, listening, with\u000aa natural self-pity that she was not there, and realization of the\u000adifferent fate of Gussy, to whom music and love and all the softnesses\u000aof life were open, while she was sent away out of sight with a naughty\u000achild.
p11944
aVJanet had far too much strength to give in or permit anyone to\u000asee that she suffered from this, nor, indeed, did she suffer more than\u000athe vague and momentary sensation of being at a disadvantage.
p11945
aVBut she\u000aleaned out to listen with a little wistfulness, impatient of the\u000achildish vehemence, and as yet but little awakened to the deeper nature\u000aof her unmanageable pupil.
p11946
aVThis pensive mood, however, was soon to be\u000ainterrupted.
p11947
aVIn the very midst of the liquid notes ascending from below,\u000athere came suddenly, as if it rent the air, a wild and wailing cry--the\u000acry as of a spirit in pain.
p11948
aVIt seemed to Janet to rise almost from her\u000aside, close by.
p11949
aVShe started back from the window and turned round with a\u000ascared and terrified exclamation,\u000a\u000a\u201cWhat is that?
p11950
aVWhat is that?\u201d\u000a\u000aFor a moment it occurred to her that some terrible accident or hurt must\u000ahave happened to the girl by her side.
p11951
aV\u201cI--don\u2019t know,\u201d said Julia, stammering as if she could not get out the\u000awords.
p11952
aVBut she was not terrified as Janet was.
p11953
aVThe governess did not\u000anotice this at first in her own panic.
p11954
aVShe ran to the door of Julia\u2019s\u000aroom, from which direction the sound seemed to come, and flung it open\u000acrying, \u201cWho is there?
p11955
aVWho is there?\u201d then shut it again in terror of\u000awhat she might see.
p11956
aV\u201cOh, run and fetch some one!
p11957
aVoh, go and alarm the house, Julia!
p11958
aVthere\u000amust be something dreadful in there.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThere\u2019s nothing,\u201d said Julia.
p11959
aV\u201cWhat are you making such a fuss about?
p11960
aVIt\u2019s--a boy outside--they make such hideous noises--it\u2019s----\u201d\u000a\u000aShe stopped, for the same sound was repeated, this time lower and\u000afurther off, as it seemed--a cry of pain dropping into a low prolonged\u000awail.
p11961
aVJanet rushed to the school-room door and out upon the staircase,\u000acalling for help, for some one to come.
p11962
aVShe was wild with alarm.
p11963
aVThere\u000awas no doubt in her mind that some wretched creature, a madman,\u000aprobably, had got into the rooms.
p11964
aVBut all was quiet in the house below, the doors all shut, everybody\u000aoccupied with their own business, singing going on in the drawing-room,\u000atalk in the servants\u2019 apartments downstairs--nothing it would seem had\u000abeen disturbed but Janet alone.
p11965
aV\u201cIt\u2019s nothing,\u201d repeated Julia.
p11966
aV\u201cOh, Miss Summerhayes, come back,\u000aplease, and don\u2019t make a fuss.
p11967
aVMamma is so angry if there\u2019s any fuss\u000amade.
p11968
aVIf I go into my room and look all round, and convince you there\u2019s\u000anobody, will that do?
p11969
aVThere\u2019s nobody, I know.
p11970
aVIt\u2019s either a boy passing\u000aoutside, or it\u2019s an owl or something that lives under the ivy in the\u000awing.
p11971
aVMamma knows.
p11972
aVIf you ask her to-morrow she\u2019ll tell you; but, oh,\u000afor goodness\u2019 sake, Miss Summerhayes, don\u2019t make a fuss to-night.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cYour mother knows?
p11973
aVDo you mean that--it has been heard before?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cYou look as if you thought it was a ghost,\u201d said Julia, who, however,\u000awas very pale.
p11974
aV\u201cWe have no ghosts in our house.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIt was like the cry of a mad creature--it was----Julia, if it comes\u000aagain I can\u2019t bear it.
p11975
aVIt must be some madman who has got in.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIf it\u2019s a madman he can\u2019t get near us,\u201d cried Julia, \u201cfor he\u2019s in the\u000awing.\u201d\u000a\u000aJanet came back into the school-room, still trembling with her fright.
p11976
aVShe dropped into a chair, unable to support herself.
p11977
aV\u201cYou know--you know what it is,\u201d she said, faintly.
p11978
aV\u201cI know--it\u2019s something in the wing.
p11979
aVIt does no harm.
p11980
aVSometimes it will\u000acry like that--oh, once in a year, perhaps.
p11981
aVIt can\u2019t do any harm.
p11982
aVOh,\u000aMiss Summerhayes, do be reasonable when I tell you.
p11983
aVWhat does it matter?
p11984
aVI don\u2019t know what you mean, to be so taken up with their squalling and\u000ashouting, and in such a state when you hear a cry.
p11985
aVI don\u2019t care either\u000afor one or the other,\u201d Julia said.
p11986
aVIt cannot be said that Janet showed much interest in the \u201csqualling and\u000ashouting\u201d of which her pupil was so contemptuous after this.
p11987
aVThe two\u000achanged their _rles_ completely for the rest of the evening, during\u000awhich Julia, though not without a titter for her companion\u2019s weakness,\u000asoothed and patronized Miss Summerhayes, and addressed to her many\u000aphilosophical admonitions, which naturally were much more self-confident\u000aeven than the exhortations of Janet, in themselves by no means deficient\u000ain the certainty of youth.
p11988
aV\u201cWhat can it matter to us,\u201d said Julia, \u201cwhat a noise is?--unless you\u000ahappen to like noises which people make, squalling at the top of their\u000avoices and call music.
p11989
aVA noise can\u2019t hurt you; it can\u2019t do you any harm.
p11990
aVYou hear it, and that\u2019s all--especially when it\u2019s only like a voice.
p11991
aVI\u000aam not fond of thunder, myself, for a thunderbolt might fall on the\u000ahouse or crush you; but a cry--what does it matter?
p11992
aVPeople are always\u000acrying out, or making some nasty noise.
p11993
aVYou should pay no attention to\u000ait.
p11994
aVI never pay any attention; it is not worth while.
p11995
aVWhy, you might\u000aspend your life thinking of such things, if you were to be disturbed by\u000aevery sound you hear.\u201d\u000a\u000aThis discourse did not satisfy Janet or even calm her mind, but she\u000areflected after a while that it was not the part of a governess to put\u000avisionary terrors into the mind of her pupil, and so far recovered\u000aherself with an effort as to satisfy Julia that it was safe to go to bed\u000aand leave Miss Summerhayes.
p11996
aVPoor little Janet, when left alone, felt for\u000athe first time how terrible it was to be so young, so impressionable,\u000aand among strangers.
p11997
aVShe dared not run downstairs, as a girl at home\u000awould, to shake off her terrors by confiding them to some one who could\u000aauthoritatively calm and reassure her.
p11998
aVMrs. Harwood had been very kind\u000ato her governess, but to go down again after she had been dismissed, to\u000ameet Gussy\u2019s astonished look turning round from the piano, and the\u000amother\u2019s suspicious glance which would ask what she wanted, why she\u000acame?--was impossible to Janet.
p11999
aVShe felt to-night, for the first time,\u000awhat it was to be a governess, although to-night, for almost the first\u000atime, she had realized what she had expected when she came out into the\u000aworld, how amusing it was to watch a story going on.
p12000
aVHow soon had all\u000ainterest in the story disappeared from her mind in the face of this\u000aterror which froze her very blood!
p12001
aVWhat was it?--was it a spirit or a\u000aliving creature in pain?
p12002
aVWhere was it?--in this tranquil house, as Julia\u000aseemed to allow?
p12003
aVAnd worst and most dreadful question of all--would it\u000acome again?
p12004
aVThis last thought was the one that kept all her faculties\u000aawake.
p12005
aVMight it at any moment burst once more out of the quiet?
p12006
aVJanet\u000athought that if she had to undergo that moment of horror again she must\u000ago mad or die.
p12007
aVShe was afraid to go to bed--afraid to close her\u000aeyes--lest she should be awakened by that cry.
p12008
aVThe singing went on late\u000adownstairs, and Janet listened anxiously to the departing of the\u000avisitor, the bolting of the door behind him, the little bustle as Mrs.\u000aHarwood was wheeled to her room on the ground floor, and Gussy came\u000aupstairs.
p12009
aVBut she did not come as far as the school-room, which she\u000asometimes did to see if all was well.
p12010
aVIt was too late to disturb any\u000aone--to wake up the sleepers.
p12011
aVJanet heard Miss Harwood coming upstairs\u000asinging softly over to herself her part in one of the duets.
p12012
aVGussy was\u000ahappy; no alarm or sense of desolation was in her.
p12013
aV\u201cIf I were happy like that I would come upstairs to see how the poor\u000alittle governess, all alone, was getting on,\u201d Janet said to herself,\u000aopening her eyes in the dark.
p12014
aVBut, indeed, she would have done nothing\u000aof the kind.
p12015
aVShe would have been perhaps more indifferent than Gussy was\u000ato the governess in causeless trouble, feeling \u201cout of it\u201d--or else in a\u000avisionary panic thinking that she had heard a ghost.
p12016
aVThe night wore away gradually, and nothing happened.
p12017
aVWhen it was between\u000athree and four, Janet, worn out, fell fast asleep.
p12018
aVShe slept till the\u000abreakfast-bell rang, and had to hurry her dressing and hasten downstairs\u000awith an apology, wondering at herself and her own foolish terror in the\u000ared light of the wintry morning.
p12019
aVGussy was very ready, it was evident,\u000ato be questioned about last night.
p12020
aVShe began her self by expressing her\u000adistress that Janet had been hastened away for \u201c_that_ child,\u201d and\u000anarrated to her with subdued triumph how many \u201cthings\u201d Mr. Meredith and\u000ashe had gone through, and what good practice it was.
p12021
aV\u201cThe Harwoods generally are so unmusical,\u201d Gussy said; \u201cI never did get\u000aany encouragement at home.
p12022
aVBut fortunately mamma likes Charley, and he\u000amay do what he pleases.
p12023
aVI do enjoy a musical evening so.
p12024
aVHasn\u2019t he a\u000adelicious voice?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIt is a charming voice,\u201d said Janet.
p12025
aV\u201cAnd he is so well trained.
p12026
aVTo sing with him it is like getting a\u000alesson.
p12027
aVHe wanted to know whether you were musical, but I said I\u000afeared----\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI used to be thought pretty good for accompaniments,\u201d said Janet.
p12028
aV\u201cOh, really!\u201d but Gussy did not receive this statement with much\u000adelight.
p12029
aV\u201cPerhaps you\u2019ll help me to practise my part,\u201d she said, and\u000areturned to sound the praises of Charley.
p12030
aVJanet would not introduce the subject of her own terrors, and if she had\u000abeen ever so intent upon doing so, there was no opportunity, for Charley\u000aand his songs and his perfections left no room for any other discourse.
p12031
aVAnd when Mrs. Harwood appeared matters were not much better.
p12032
aVThe old\u000alady remarked that Janet was pale, and feared that she had not been able\u000ato sleep for the singing.
p12033
aV\u201cThe fact is that Mr. Meredith has not been in London for a long time,\u000aand I could not cut them short, could I, the first night?\u201d\u000a\u000aTo describe the impatience with which Janet heard all this would not be\u000aeasy.
p12034
aVShe said to herself, what was Mr. Meredith to her?
p12035
aVWhat were his\u000asongs, his attentions, the grief of his absence, the joy of his return?
p12036
aVShe listened with a great eagerness to interrupt, to break through this\u000aeternal burden of the self-occupied to whom their own little affairs\u000awere everything, with her own questions.
p12037
aVBut when Mrs. Harwood\u2019s voice\u000astopped Janet did not find hers.
p12038
aVWhat could she say?
p12039
aV\u201cI heard a dreadful cry last night.
p12040
aVWhat was it?
p12041
aVYou know what it was!\u201d\u000aIt seemed to her when she turned this question in her mind that it was a\u000athing impossible to say.
p12042
aV\u201cI heard--last night,\u201d she began.
p12043
aV\u201cAh, the singing!\u201d cried both ladies together.
p12044
aV\u201cI hope it did not keep\u000ayou from your sleep, my dear,\u201d said Mrs. Harwood.
p12045
aVAnd, \u201cI\u2019m sure you\u000acould not hear me, and Charley\u2019s voice is always a pleasure,\u201d cried\u000aGussy.
p12046
aVJanet\u2019s mouth was closed, and she could say no more.
p12047
aVCHAPTER XI.
p12048
aVJanet\u2019s life seemed to herself to change from this day, though no one\u000aelse seemed aware of any difference, and all its outward expressions\u000awent on as before.
p12049
aVFor a few nights she was afraid to sit alone\u000aupstairs, and hurried to bed in the hope of getting to sleep, and thus\u000aavoiding any repetition of the cry which had so rung through and through\u000aher on the night of Mr. Meredith\u2019s first appearance; but, as the days\u000aand nights passed in perfect tranquillity, this scare passed away from\u000aher mind, and she began to be able to explain to herself that it must\u000ahave been some boy in the road outside, belated and anxious to make a\u000asensation in that still neighborhood, or perhaps that fancy had\u000aexaggerated the fantastic wailings of a love-sick cat into something\u000aportentous and terrible.
p12050
aVBoth these things were possible, but that\u000aanything mysterious could exist in this comfortable, modern, respectable\u000ahouse, where everything went as on velvet by carefully kept rule and\u000aorder, was an idea too ridiculous to be entertained.
p12051
aVAt night, it is\u000atrue, Janet had various fallings back from this confidence, and reminded\u000aherself with renewed panic that Julia had heard and had not been\u000aastonished as she was, but evidently was aware of some explanation which\u000ashe did not give.
p12052
aVThese grew fainter and fainter, however, as one week\u000apassed after another, and nothing occurred.
p12053
aVThere was one thing, however, which Janet only remarked after this\u000aperiod, though she was afterwards assured that it was no secret, but\u000amight have been seen from the first day, and that was the appearance of\u000aa man-servant in the house where none but women ever waited upon the\u000afamily.
p12054
aVShe met him one day going across the hall, a respectable,\u000aserious man of middle age, just such a butler as Mrs. Harwood ought to\u000ahave had.
p12055
aVBut the ladies had no butler; they had a highly-respectable\u000aparlor-maid, just such as, failing the butler, a family in St. John\u2019s\u000aWood, entirely _comme il faut_, must have had--tall, staid,\u000agood-looking, but not too good-looking, well-dressed, and thirty-five.
p12056
aVThe man, who had all the air of perfect familiarity with the house, and\u000awho was in indoor dress, with noiseless shoes, went across the hall from\u000athe servant\u2019s quarters towards the side upon which was the wing, an\u000aapparently unoccupied part of the dwelling.
p12057
aVAfter that first meeting, which startled her, Janet saw this man again\u000aand again.
p12058
aVThere was no explanation of him, he was never seen but in\u000athese chance encounters, yet he was no secret, nor was his presence in\u000aany way concealed.
p12059
aVWhat, after all, had a stranger to do with it?
p12060
aVIt was\u000anothing to Janet.
p12061
aVBut her strong sense of spectatorship, and the\u000acuriosity of imagination which made her keen to find indications of a\u000astory anywhere or everywhere, caused a half-conscious groping on the\u000apart of the governess among unexplained incidents.
p12062
aVIt was some time,\u000ahowever, before she began to associate the mysterious man-servant with\u000athe alarming outcry which had almost, she thought, deprived her of her\u000awits, ringing as it did into the silence of the night.
p12063
aVAfter a few weeks\u000ahad passed, she asked herself if, indeed, she ever had heard it at\u000aall--whether it was not a delusion of her senses, the reverberation of\u000asome well-known and vulgar sound.
p12064
aVNeedless to say that Janet had read\u000a\u201cNorthanger Abbey,\u201d and had been taught to smile at the investigations\u000aof our dear little Catherine, and their amusing issue: though, to tell\u000athe truth, her sympathy in Catherine Morland\u2019s thirst for romantic\u000aadventure had been more strong than her amusement in the result, which\u000adisappointed her a little too.
p12065
aVHowever, not even a romantic imagination disposed towards discoveries\u000acan survive the uneventful progress of weeks in which nothing happens.
p12066
aVAnd Janet meantime had the other story going on before her eyes which\u000ashe could study at her ease.
p12067
aVMr. Charles Meredith and his visits became\u000anow the chief interest of life in the house in St. John\u2019s Wood.
p12068
aVHe dined\u000aonce or twice, but only in company with another visitor; and on those\u000aoccasions Janet did not form one of the party.
p12069
aVGussy explained that it\u000awould \u201cput out the table.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIf I were to invite gentlemen for you and Ju, it would make quite a\u000aparty, and mamma does not like parties when Dolff is away.
p12070
aVAnd then Ju\u000ais too young to dine when there is company,\u201d said Miss Harwood.
p12071
aV\u201cOh, you must not think of me!\u201d Janet would reply; but when she heard\u000athe gentlemen arrive, and the increased sound of voices as the servants\u000awent out and in of the dining-room, and the little cheerful commotion,\u000ait is undeniable that Janet remembered Mrs. Bland\u2019s little sermons about\u000athe fate of a governess.
p12072
aVShe did not like it.
p12073
aVShe had never been left out in her life before.
p12074
aVJanet was not shy; she had always been used to take a somewhat\u000aprivileged place in the little society she was acquainted with.
p12075
aVShe\u000acould talk; she was not afraid of anybody who might drift into the\u000alittle world of Clover; and she loved variety, which is a thing not\u000apermitted to governesses.
p12076
aVOn these occasions supper was brought up to\u000athe school-room for Miss Summerhayes and her pupil.
p12077
aVIt was brought late,\u000aand they had to wait and yawn on opposite sides of the table for the\u000acold and tardy meal.
p12078
aVOn such occasions it was difficult to make herself\u000aamusing to Julia, or to find Julia amusing.
p12079
aVIt was dull.
p12080
aVIt produced a\u000acertain mortification in Janet\u2019s mind to find that she cared.
p12081
aVShe said\u000ato herself, with a little bitterness of which she was ashamed, that she\u000ahad no doubt it was a very dull party, and that the two strangers were\u000anot in the least interesting.
p12082
aVShe recalled to herself her previous\u000aconviction, that to be left alone to do what she pleased, to read a\u000anovel or write a letter, would be a pleasant relief.
p12083
aVNo, it was not so;\u000ashe wanted to be in the dining-room with the rest, hearing what was\u000asaid, even if she had to remember her own position and take little part.
p12084
aVShe wanted to see how the drama was going on, and how the hero looked\u000awhen there was some one to compare him with.
p12085
aVThat scene would glide in\u000aher imagination in front of her novel, with the attraction of a pleasure\u000aout of reach.
p12086
aVAnd Julia was a dull companion on these occasions.
p12087
aVShe\u000ayawned and wondered when they would bring the supper.
p12088
aV\u201cIt\u2019s disgusting to be kept so long waiting, and all the things like\u000astones when they do come,\u201d Julia would say; \u201cI shall complain to mamma.
p12089
aVIf all the others are so busy, Vicars might bring it up, once in a way.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cWho is Vicars?\u201d said Janet.
p12090
aV\u201cOh, he is the man; he never goes into the dining-room except when Dolff\u000ais here--but he might bring up our supper if all the rest are so busy.
p12091
aVAs if there was any reason to make such a fuss!
p12092
aVTwo men to dinner!
p12093
aVYou\u000awould think there were twenty, all fine ladies and gentlemen, to see how\u000aGussy goes on.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThey are probably great friends, and more important than twenty ladies\u000aand gentlemen,\u201d said Janet, with her most correct governess air.
p12094
aV\u201cOh, you know well enough!
p12095
aVIt is Charley Meredith, and they will\u000acaterwaul afterwards till it makes me quite ill to hear them.
p12096
aVAnd Gussy\u000awill look so silly.
p12097
aVOh, why does a woman look so silly when there is\u000anonsense like that going on?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIt is generally the man who is supposed to look silly,\u201d said Janet.
p12098
aVInvoluntarily she thought of poor Dr. Harding and his proposal; and the\u000ahard-hearted young woman laughed in spite of herself.
p12099
aV\u201cWhat are you laughing at?
p12100
aVYou are remembering something.
p12101
aVTell me, tell\u000ame, Miss Summerhayes!
p12102
aVI suppose,\u201d said Julia, with deep discrimination,\u000a\u201cthat the man looks silly when it is he who wants it most.
p12103
aVNow, here it\u000ais Gussy who wants it most.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cJulia, you have no right to discuss your sister.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cOh, but you can\u2019t stop me doing it!\u201d said Julia, with composure; \u201cyou\u000acan stop me when--when I\u2019m silly myself.
p12104
aVI was a great fool, I know.
p12105
aVI\u000athought once I could drive you away--no, I didn\u2019t want to drive you\u000aaway.
p12106
aVI wanted to get the upper hand; but you\u2019ve got the upper hand of\u000ame, and I don\u2019t mind now.
p12107
aVHowever, that\u2019s quite different.
p12108
aVThis is a\u000afree country, and I can say what I please of Gussy.
p12109
aVI say that it\u2019s\u000ashe----\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cAs it is a free country, you can\u2019t compel me to listen,\u201d said Janet;\u000a\u201cbut there is one thing in which it is not a free country, and that is\u000athat you are not permitted to be ill-bred.
p12110
aVIt is not allowed to be\u000avulgar.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cOh!\u201d cried Julia, coloring to her eyes, but affecting to laugh, \u201cas if\u000athere were not hundreds and thousands?\u201d\u000a\u000aJanet shrugged her little shoulders in a manner which her pupil,\u000arebellious, but admiring, thought irresistible.
p12111
aV\u201cOut in the streets, perhaps: so are there applewomen, and people who\u000asell matches.
p12112
aVBut in good time here comes the tray, and something for\u000ayou to do.\u201d\u000a\u000aJanet, however, was not far from being of Julia\u2019s opinion.
p12113
aVMiss Harwood,\u000awho had been so calm, who had explained that the quiet family life so\u000aunbroken, the long evenings of needlework and talk, might appear dull to\u000aJanet, but were never dull to her mother and herself, now went through\u000athese evenings as in a dream.
p12114
aVMeredith came twice, sometimes three\u000atimes, in a week, after dinner, as he had done on his first appearance.
p12115
aVHe had privileges which were extended to no one else, and it was never\u000aknown on which evening he would appear.
p12116
aVHe even took pains, Janet\u000athought, to have no rule, to appear suddenly when he was not looked for.
p12117
aVBut to this spectator, whose attention was fixed upon Gussy, as on the\u000aheroine of the drama, it was very easily apparent that there was no\u000aevening on which he was not expected.
p12118
aVShe worked, she talked, she made\u000aher little disquisitions as usual, but there was a certain fixed\u000aattitude of her head, a little almost imperceptible pause now and then\u000ain the movements of her hands, which showed that she was listening for\u000athe summons at the door, the step outside.
p12119
aVIn the quietness of the\u000asemi-rural suburban road the step of the rare passenger was sometimes\u000aheard even outside the garden wall.
p12120
