aVCHAPTER XXI.
p13287
aVEvery family has a skeleton in some closet.
p13288
aVSo says the proverb; but is\u000ait true?
p13289
aVWe are all of us aware of many cases in which it is not true.
p13290
aVTo half of the world perhaps it is a foolish fiction.
p13291
aVThey have\u000atroubles, but they are above-board, straightforward troubles upon which\u000atheir neighbors can offer sympathy.
p13292
aVThackeray speaks of the wife or the\u000ahusband in their intimate domesticity going back secretly, each unknown\u000ato the other, perhaps upon a youthful past which contained another image\u000athan that of the legitimate partner of their days, but that is a gentle\u000asort of a skeleton, its bones all covered in soft rounded outlines of\u000aimagination.
p13293
aVThe real skeleton is very different: it haunts the house in\u000athe form perhaps of a ruined son, a debased and degraded brother, still\u000amore dreadful a woman disgraced.
p13294
aVOr it is an incipient madness--a\u000adreadful disease of which the miserable people never know at what moment\u000ait may blaze forth?
p13295
aVIt is always in the minds of those to whom it\u000abelongs.
p13296
aVIn the midst of laughter, in the happiest moment, it gives a\u000atug at their hearts, as if it held them in a chain, and the smile fades,\u000aand the sweetest tints grow gray.
p13297
aVBut how could there be anything like this in the house in St. John\u2019s\u000aWood?
p13298
aVThe Harwoods were people not given to excitement of any kind.
p13299
aVThey\u000awere too orderly in mind, too calm and well-balanced, for any emotion.
p13300
