aVJanet felt more and more guilty, though she did not know what she had\u000adone, nor why she could not confess frankly where she had got her\u000ainformation.
p13853
aVThe others soon recovered the momentary depression, and\u000aresumed their talk over the approaching event, but Janet stood at the\u000apiano, running over the notes of a waltz softly with one hand, and\u000awondering why she should have produced, without intending it, so great\u000aan effect.
p13854
aVPresently Mrs. Harwood called her, clapping her hands as she\u000ahad a way of doing to secure attention.
p13855
aVJanet hurried to her side.
p13856
aVThe\u000aold lady had recovered her composure, but she still looked grave.
p13857
aV\u201cMy dear,\u201d she said, \u201cyou will wonder that I was so startled.
p13858
aVThere was\u000ano reason.
p13859
aVOf course you could know nothing.
p13860
aVThat was my husband\u2019s\u000aname.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cOh, Mrs. Harwood, I am so sorry.
p13861
aVI can\u2019t think what made me ask.
p13862
aVIt was\u000abecause most people, I suppose, have more names than one: and Charles\u000awas the first that came into my head.\u201d\u000a\u000aIt will be seen that Janet told a little fib again, but she said it in a\u000ahurry, and did not mean it, or at least this was how she afterwards\u000aexplained it to herself.
p13863
aV\u201cThen it was only what people call a curious coincidence,\u201d said Mrs.\u000aHarwood, with a smile.
p13864
aVCHAPTER XXV.
p13865
aVThe night of the ball arrived at last.
p13866
aVIt was a long time in coming to\u000athe impatience of Dolff and Julia: and even to Gussy, who was not\u000aimpatient, who would rather have held it off a little when the day at\u000alast came, and to whom so many things were involved in the hours which\u000awould be but amusement to the rest.
p13867
aVNobody suspected what was going on\u000aunder Gussy\u2019s tranquil looks.
p13868
aVShe was one of those people whom many\u000athink to be incapable of feeling at all.
p13869
aVShe had a force of resolution\u000anot to expose herself, not to let anybody know what she endured, which\u000awas equal to almost any trial.
p13870
aVThere are many women who possess this\u000apower, but it is most frequently exercised to shield and cover the\u000adelinquencies of others.
p13871
aVGussy\u2019s reticence was only for herself; but\u000astrength of any kind is respectable; and if any one had known the fever\u000athat was in her breast, the chance upon which the fortune of her life\u000aseemed to turn, and the absolute tranquillity with which, to all\u000aappearance, she prepared for the evening\u2019s pleasure, no doubt she would\u000ahave earned the admiration of some and the respect of others.
p13872
aVBut our best qualities, as well as our worst, remain for the most part\u000ablank to those who surround us, and nobody suspected either the trouble\u000ain which Miss Harwood was, or the empire she exercised over her own\u000asoul.
p13873
aVJanet, perhaps, was the only member of the party who was in the\u000aleast degree cognizant of it, but even Janet was chiefly aware, with a\u000afeeling of provoked sympathy, that Gussy, as she generally did, had\u000adressed herself unbecomingly on an occasion on which the little,\u000aquick-witted governess divined she would have wished to look her best.
p13874
aVGussy was not clever in the matter of dress.
p13875
aVShe arrayed herself in the\u000alightest of tints and materials--she who was herself so colorless, who\u000awanted something solid and distinct \u201cto throw her up.\u201d\u000a\u000aJanet had done her duty in this respect by the other young woman, who\u000acould scarcely now be called her friend, so conscious were both of a\u000amist that had come between them.
p13876
aVIt was one of Janet\u2019s good qualities\u000athat she had no jealous feeling, but that unfeigned pleasure in dress\u000awhich made her so anxious to see everybody else becomingly attired, that\u000ashe was impatient of failure.
p13877
aVShe had given many hints and suggestions\u000aas to Miss Harwood\u2019s dress on this particular occasion, but they had not\u000abeen attended to.
p13878
aVAnd Gussy had enveloped herself in something that was\u000anot quite white nor yet any other color, with the persistency common to\u000apersons who are without any real instinct in the matter; and, instead of\u000alooking her best, looked more colorless than usual.
p13879
aVJanet could scarcely restrain a cry of impatience when they all met in\u000athe drawing-room, which had been cleared for dancing.
p13880
aVIf Gussy had but\u000aworn her own black gown, what a difference it would have made!
p13881
aVBut Gussy\u000awas altogether unconscious of that, as all the others were unconscious\u000aof the way in which her heart was beating under her _fade_ and foolish\u000adress.
p13882
aVJanet, for her part, had received her programme from Dolff, with his own\u000aneat little \u201cA.
p13883
aVH.\u201d written on a great many lines; but she was too wise\u000ato permit the son of the house to make himself and her remarkable.
p13884
aVJanet\u000ahad a great terror of what the opportunities of the evening might lead\u000ato, very different from that sentiment which moved Gussy.
p13885
aVShe managed to\u000aescape, if not with some other partner, then alone, anywhere, even going\u000aso far as to make a rush upstairs till some of the dances bespoken by\u000aDolff were over.
p13886
aVShe was determined not to lay herself open to any\u000acomments in that respect, or to expose herself to the chances of what\u000aDolff might say in the excitement of the evening.
p13887
aVBut she had no such\u000aterror of Meredith, who, after he had done his duty in various\u000adirections was so polite as to ask the governess for a dance.
p13888
aVNor was\u000ashe alarmed by the eagerness with which he plunged into conversation,\u000aleading her away, when half the dance was over, to a quiet corner.
p13889
aV\u201cI am sure you are tired,\u201d he said; \u201cyou have been dancing all the\u000aevening, and so have I.
p13890
aVCome and let us talk a little.
p13891
aVI never have a\u000achance of half-a-dozen words with you, Miss Summerhayes.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThat cannot matter much,\u201d said Janet, \u201cfor I don\u2019t suppose we have\u000aanything very particular to say to each other, Mr. Meredith.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cYou must, of course, speak for yourself; but you cannot for me, and I\u000ahave a hundred things I want to say to you.
p13892
aVWe have never had a good\u000atalk but once, and that was the day I walked with you from the\u000acirculating library, when you were quite afraid to be seen with me.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cNot in the least afraid to be seen with any one,\u201d said Janet; \u201cbut it\u000adid not seem suitable somehow.
p13893
aVAnd as we are talking of that, Mr.\u000aMeredith, I don\u2019t think it\u2019s very suitable----\u201d\u000a\u000aHere Janet thought better of what she was going to say, and stopped\u000ashort.
p13894
aV\u201cWhat does not seem suitable?
p13895
aVTell me, I implore you!
p13896
aVHow can I regulate\u000amy conduct according to your wishes, which is my highest ambition, if\u000ayou will not tell me what to do?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI have nothing to do with your conduct, Mr. Meredith, I don\u2019t\u000aunderstand why you should wish to sneer at me----\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI--sneer!
p13897
aVbut you know you don\u2019t mean that.
p13898
aVI sometimes try to secure\u000ayour sympathy, I allow, when I\u2019m at a particularly hard place.
p13899
aVThey say\u000athat the lookers-on see most of the game, and I soon saw in your eyes,\u000aif you\u2019ll forgive me, that you----\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI don\u2019t see any game,\u201d cried Janet, with indignation, \u201cand if you are\u000aplaying one you ought to be ashamed of yourself; and, at all events, I\u000awill not be in your confidence!\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cHush!\u201d he said, \u201cdon\u2019t be so fiery.
p13900
aVIf you get up and leave me you will\u000amake everybody ask why, and we don\u2019t want to raise any talk, do we?
p13901
aVLook\u000athere, Miss Summerhayes--for I must talk of something--look at that man\u000aVicars.
p13902
aVWhat a hang-dog face he has!
p13903
aVLike a man that is up to some\u000amischief, don\u2019t you think?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI don\u2019t like Vicars,\u201d said Janet, hastily; \u201che would like to be\u000ainsolent, if he dared.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cInsolent, the beast!
p13904
aVYou have only to give Dolff a hint,\u201d said\u000aMeredith, with a laugh, \u201cand he\u2019ll soon put a stop to that.
p13905
aVI should\u000alike, all the same, to know a little what\u2019s Vicars\u2019s mission in this\u000ahouse.
p13906
aVOh, I know he\u2019s an old servant, and all that.
p13907
aVI have my little\u000acuriosities, Miss Summerhayes; haven\u2019t you?
p13908
aVThere are some things I\u000ashould like to know.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI thought you must know everything,\u201d said Janet; \u201cyou are such a very\u000aold friend.\u201d\u000a\u000aNow Janet was bursting with desire to communicate to somebody her own\u000awonderings and the things she had seen, or had imagined herself to see.
p13909
aVShe was held back by many things--by regard for the law which forbids\u000ayou to talk to strangers of things you have observed in the house in\u000awhich you live: and also by a principle of honor, which is but feeble in\u000asuch matters in most bosoms, and by a lingering sense of loyalty\u000atowards Gussy, whose property this man was--and by a general prejudice\u000aagainst making mischief.
p13910
aVBut, on the other hand, she was impelled to\u000aspeak by her own curiosity and conviction that there was something to\u000afind out, and eagerness to communicate her discoveries.
p13911
aVAnd then\u000aMeredith was not a stranger; and if there was anything to find out he\u000ahad a right to know it; and, of course, as Gussy\u2019s husband he would know\u000aeverything.
p13912
aVJanet\u2019s heart began to beat with excitement.
p13913
aVShould she tell\u000ahim?
p13914
aVShe wanted so much to do it that she scarcely knew how to keep in\u000athe words.
p13915
aV\u201cI am an old friend,\u201d said Meredith.
p13916
aV\u201cI have known them all my life;\u000atherefore I have a kind of right, don\u2019t you think, to want to know?
p13917
aVAnd\u000aI am one of the very few men who come familiarly about the house, so if\u000athere was any way in which that fellow Vicars was taking them in, or\u000aplaying upon them, I am just the person who ought to be told, for I\u000acould take steps to put them on their guard.\u201d\u000a\u000aIt was on this argument, which seemed so unanswerable, and especially\u000aapplicable if Meredith became, as Janet assured herself was inevitable,\u000athe son of the house, that at last she spoke.
p13918
aVAfter all, it did not seem\u000aas if she had very much to tell.
p13919
aVShe confided to him her suspicions that\u000aVicars had somebody shut up in the wing whom no one knew about, and that\u000ashe herself had seen--she was certain she had seen--a face pressed\u000aagainst the window-panes, visible between the branches of the ivy; and\u000ahow, just below the same window, there had been the other day that\u000alittle shower of scraps of paper, which looked as if they had been\u000athrown out.
p13920
aVMeredith listened with the greatest eagerness.
p13921
aVHe leaned his elbow on\u000ahis knee, and his head in his hand, looking up into her face, and\u000ashielding her thus from observation in her dark corner, so that even\u000aGussy, passing by at a little distance on the arm of her partner, could\u000anot make out who the lady was to whom he was talking, though the sight\u000aincreased almost beyond bearing the agitation in her mind.
p13922
aVMeredith\u2019s\u000aeyes on Janet\u2019s face, so near, and the manner in which he surrounded\u000aher, shutting off the world, confused her and gave her a vague sort of\u000aguilt; but, after all, how could she have helped it?
p13923
aVShe could not have\u000arefused to dance with him.
p13924
aVShe could not refuse to sit down to talk, to\u000asit out the Lancers which was then being played, and which Gussy was\u000agoing in dutifully with her partner to dance.
p13925
aVAny other girl whom he had\u000aasked would have done that, and how could Janet refuse?
p13926
aVBut there was no\u000adoubt that she felt a pang as Gussy, in her pale dress which did not\u000abecome her, and with a look in her eyes dimly divined by this little\u000ainterloper, passed into the bright room beyond to perform her duty\u000adance.
p13927
aVJanet went on with her revelations after this episode.
p13928
aVShe had seen\u000aVicars crossing the hall with a heavy tray covered with dainties very\u000alate one night, after everybody was in bed.
p13929
aVShe had seen the door in the\u000ahall, which was said to lead to the wing which was believed to be\u000apermanently shut up, open to him----\u000a\u000aAt these words Meredith started up.
p13930
aVThey were quite alone in their\u000acorner--nobody was about.
p13931
aVThe dance was going on gayly--the ball-room\u000acrowded, a little hedge of men standing round the door.
p13932
aV\u201cEverything is quiet,\u201d he said, hastily; \u201clet us go and see.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cGo and see--what?\u201d\u000a\u000aHe drew her arm within his, with a smile upon her, which dazzled Janet\u000aand made her cast down her eyes.
p13933
aVShe was so startled that she was\u000ascarcely aware that he kept her hand in his as he led her along.
p13934
aV\u201cWe have five minutes,\u201d he said, \u201cand there is nobody here.
p13935
aVLet\u2019s go and\u000asee.\u201d It seemed half a schoolboy frolic, half a righteous mission.
p13936
aVHe\u000ahurried her into the hall, which was deserted, enveloping her so in his\u000ashadow that Janet felt as if she had no longer any will of her own.
p13937
aV\u201cWhich is it?\u201d he asked, bending over her so that she felt his breath on\u000aher neck.
p13938
aVThey spoke in whispers, and crowded together on their clandestine\u000aenterprise so that they seemed but one figure.
p13939
aVShe put out her hand,\u000atrembling, and touched the door.
p13940
aVJanet\u2019s heart had been beating loudly before.
p13941
aVIt jumped up now as if it\u000awould choke her when she felt the door move slightly under her hand.
p13942
aVWhen Meredith added quickly the pressure of his fingers it swung open.
p13943
aVHe drew her in, scarcely conscious of what he was doing.
p13944
aV\u201cOh-h!\u201d Janet\u000abreathed a low cry of excitement upon his shoulder.
p13945
aVWhatever the\u000adiscovery might be there was now no escape.
p13946
aVHe silenced her, pressing\u000aher against him.
p13947
aVThey were in a dark, narrow passage, which ended in\u000athick curtains closely drawn, and was lighted by the feeblest spark of\u000alight.
p13948
aV\u201cWe must follow it on now,\u201d he said, in her ear.
p13949
aV\u201cNot a word--not a\u000aword.\u201d\u000a\u000aInside the curtains was a door which opened outward, and admitted to a\u000asteep, straight staircase.
p13950
aVEverything was dark, muffled, breathless.
p13951
aVThey groped their way up this, and found before them another closed door\u000aat the top, which yielded also to pressure, moving noiselessly.
p13952
aVWithin\u000athis were curtains again, in which they both stumbled, unable at first\u000ato open or put them aside.
p13953
aVBut the circumstances were desperate, and\u000asomehow they made their way through.
p13954
aVThey found themselves then in a\u000aroom lighted only by the window, which was the very window, covered with\u000aivy, at which Janet had seen that old man\u2019s face.
p13955
aVBut the room was void\u000aand dark.
p13956
aVThey stood for a moment looking round, but, though they could\u000asee next to nothing, it was certain there was nobody there.
p13957
aVBy this time Meredith\u2019s excitement had so grown that he forgot Janet.
p13958
aVAt\u000aleast he dropped her arm involuntarily, and leaving her trembling,\u000ascarcely able to support herself, made a long step forward to where his\u000akeen eye had found out a crevice, through which came a faint ray of\u000alight.
p13959
aVOnce more he held back a curtain and pushed a door; then with a\u000asudden, quick movement, held out his hand to Janet.
p13960
aVHer eyes by this\u000atime had become accustomed to the gloom, and she perceived that he\u000acalled her.
p13961
aVHe caught her in his arm as she stole forward, and placed\u000aher before him.
p13962
aVTheir breaths came quick in the same suppressed cadence.
p13963
aVBoth were far too much excited for speech, even had they dared to speak.
p13964
aVThis was what Janet saw.
p13965
aVA room comfortably furnished, largely\u000acurtained, dark, heavy stuff, so far as she could see in her\u000ainstantaneous glance, covering the walls, a fire burning cheerfully, a\u000asmall, shaded light by the side of a large sofa, on which lay a man fast\u000aasleep--so fast asleep that the very air seemed slumbering over him.
p13966
aVShe\u000afell back upon her companion with what, had she dared to utter it, would\u000ahave been a cry.
p13967
aVThe pale old face, long and tragical, the crown of\u000awhite hair, the long white beard, half hid by the great red coverlet\u000awhich enveloped him, were the same which she had seen at the window.
p13968
aVIt\u000awas, then, no fancy, no trick of reflection.
p13969
aVJanet for a moment, in her\u000aagitation, was unconscious of all the circumstances round her.
p13970
aVShe\u000agasped dumbly, paralyzed, yet thrilling with wonder, terror, and dismay.
p13971
aVMeredith\u2019s face touched hers as he whispered \u201cCome away.\u201d He almost\u000acarried her through the anteroom, the dark staircase, the\u000afaintly-lighted passage, lingering at the door for a moment to see that\u000aall was quiet.
p13972
aVThey came out into the hall, anxious but safe.
p13973
aVThe crowd\u000awas still about the door of the dancing-room, but the music bore witness\u000athat the dance was just at its conclusion.
p13974
aVMeredith hurried Janet back\u000ato the sheltered corner which they had left for this quest.
p13975
aV\u201cOne moment; I must speak to you for one moment more,\u201d he whispered\u000abehind a bush of evergreens, which concealed them entirely.
p13976
aV\u201cYou don\u2019t\u000aknow how important this is--Janet, have you got those papers----\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThe copy-book?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI don\u2019t believe it was a copy-book.
p13977
aVTry to give them to me quietly the\u000anext time I am here, or send them--that would be the safest--United\u000aUniversities Club.
p13978
aVDearest, I can\u2019t say half I want to say to you\u000ato-night.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cTo me there is nothing to say,\u201d said Janet, drawing away from him.
p13979
aV\u201cI\u000ahave forgotten myself in the excitement--but don\u2019t think, Mr.\u000aMeredith----\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cYes, I will think,\u201d he said.
p13980
aV\u201cDon\u2019t warn me off, for you can\u2019t do it.
p13981
aVI\u000ahave thought of you since the first moment I saw you.
p13982
aVIs it my fault if\u000athey take things into their heads, Janet?\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI will not have you call me Janet,\u201d she said, with angry vehemence.
p13983
aV\u201cBut I must.
p13984
aVI never call you anything else--to myself--darling!
p13985
aVWe\u2019ll\u000ameet again before long, and be able to say everything to each other.\u201d\u000a\u000aHe let her go suddenly, and in a moment had joined the crowd of the\u000alookers-on, who had been awaiting the end of the Lancers, and now were\u000ascattering to permit the exit of the more dutiful couples who had been\u000aperforming that now somewhat despised dance.
p13986
aVJanet seized the opportunity to fly upstairs to the shelter of her own\u000aroom, which she reached breathless and agitated.
p13987
aVShe could scarcely\u000arealize what had passed in this strange evening so full of excitement.
p13988
aVMeredith\u2019s presumption--was it presumption?
p13989
aVhis unpardonable freedom of\u000aspeech--but was it unpardonable?
p13990
aVthe confidences into which he had\u000ahurried her; the extraordinary discovery they had made together; the way\u000ain which he had assumed her consent and acquiescence, taking possession\u000aof her as if she belonged to him.
p13991
aVJanet tried to be angry; she said to\u000aherself that it was detestable, unpardonable; that never more would she\u000aspeak to him again; that, if _that_ were true, then his behavior to\u000aGussy was villainous; and if it were false?
p13992
aVHer breath came hard; her\u000aveins swelled as if they would burst.
p13993
aVHow dared he speak to her--look at\u000aher--hold her so?
p13994
aVJanet saw herself in her glass, with eyes blazing,\u000alips quivering, nostrils dilating, and wondered at herself.
p13995
aVShe could\u000asee that she had never looked like that before--never so brilliant, so\u000amuch excited, or taken out of herself.
p13996
aVOh!
p13997
aVhow did he dare--he who was\u000aas good as engaged to Gussy Harwood?
p13998
aVIt was _that_ she thought of--not\u000aof the mysterious secret tenant of the wing.
p13999
aVThat strange habitation\u000awith its tenant had died out of her mind.
p14000
aVShe found herself thinking\u000aonly of Charley--of whom?
p14001
aVGood heavens!
p14002
aVwhat had she to do with his\u000aname--of Mr. Meredith and his impertinence and presumption.
p14003
aVHe had told\u000aher to tell Dolff (with a laugh) of Vicars\u2019 impertinence; but what was\u000athat of Vicars to his?
p14004
aVHe had taken possession of her against her will.
p14005
aVHe had made her a traitor to the people whose bread she was eating.
p14006
aVHe\u000ahad made her the instrument of humiliation to Gussy.
p14007
aVOh!
p14008
aVwould he go now\u000aand whisper to Gussy, and laugh with her at Dolff and the governess?
p14009
aVJanet clinched her hands and bit her lip till it almost bled.
p14010
aVWas this\u000awhat he would do?
p14011
aVTell Gussy perhaps that the governess was a silly\u000alittle thing, and believed everything that was said to her--or was it\u000aGussy that he would slight and scorn, after so long holding her in\u000asuspense?
p14012
aVJanet felt that she abhorred Charley.
p14013
aVOh!
p14014
aVto think that his\u000aname should come to her lips without any intention, when she had nothing\u000ato do with it!
p14015
aVand he had called her by hers--the insolent, the\u000ascoundrel, the deceiver!
p14016
aVJanet wrought herself up into a passion, and\u000araved at him within herself like a little fury: and then she suddenly\u000achanged her mood, and fell a-crying, soaking up the tears that would\u000acome with her handkerchief lest they should make her eyes red, and\u000asaying to herself \u201cPoor Charley!\u201d from the bottom of her heart.
p14017
aVCHAPTER XXVI.
p14018
aVMeanwhile, all was going on merrily below, dance succeeding dance.
p14019
aVThe\u000amusic was good, the floor was good.
p14020
aV\u201cDolff\u2019s men\u201d had fully made up the\u000anumber of partners necessary, and left a few over to support the doorway\u000alest it should fall.
p14021
aVDolff himself, in the midst of the gay crowd which\u000ahad been collected to give him pleasure, wandered about distractedly,\u000aseeking Janet, but unable to find her, and teasing Gussy, who had\u000acertainly enough to worry her without his constant questions, by demands\u000awhere Janet was.
p14022
aVGussy had plenty of her own affairs on hand.
p14023
aVThe hours were\u000apassing--those hours which she had felt to be so full of fate--and\u000anothing was happening; and her heart was sore with unfulfilled\u000aexpectations.
p14024
aVTo think that while her mind was thus torn asunder, while\u000ashe was almost unconsciously, but with the keenest anxiety, watching for\u000aone figure in the crowd, yet carrying on the necessary conversations,\u000alistening to what ever nonsense might be said to her, laughing at the\u000asmallest jokes, presenting generally the aspect to all around her of a\u000adisengaged and cheerful spirit, while suffering an endless torture of\u000asuspense--to think that then Dolff should assail her with his questions:\u000a\u000a\u201cWhere is Miss Summerhayes?
p14025
aVHave you seen Miss Summerhayes?
p14026
aVThis is our\u000adance.
p14027
aVWhere has she disappeared to?
p14028
